"{\n    \"[1, 4]\": [\n        [\n            115531,\n            \"- Lord Godalming and Mr. Morris arrived earlier than we expected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115592,\n            \"Of course they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has been quite \\u201cblowing my trumpet,\\u201das Mr. Morris expressed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116735,\n            \"\\u201d As I came along the corridor I saw Mr. Morris looking out of a window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116753,\n            \"He turned as he heard my footsteps.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116770,\n            \"Then noticing my red eyes, he went on: \\u201cAh, I see you have been comforting him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116826,\n            \"\\u201d He bore his own trouble so bravely that my heart bled for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116841,\n            \"I saw the manuscript in his hand, and I knew that when he read it he would realise how much I knew;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116865,\n            \"so I said to him:-\\u201cI wish I could comfort all who suffer from the heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116885,\n            \"Will you let me be your friend, and will you come to me for comfort if you need it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116906,\n            \"You will know, later on, why I speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116917,\n            \"\\u201d He saw that I was in earnest, and stooping, took my hand, and raising it to his lips, kissed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116943,\n            \"It seemed but poor comfort to so brave and unselfish a soul, and impulsively I bent over and kissed him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116982,\n            \"he said quite calmly:-\\u201cLittle girl, you will never regret that true-hearted kindness, so long as ever you live!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117024,\n            \"\\\"-the very words he had used to Lucy, and oh, but he proved himself a friend!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117056,\n            \"- I got home at five o\\u2019clock, and found that Godalming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had made and arranged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122121,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst they were talking Mr. Morris was looking steadily at the window, and he now got up quietly, and went out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134810,\n            \"He told me, however, that up to very lately there had been a notice-board of \\u201cFor Sale\\u201dup, and that perhaps Mitchell, Sons, & Candy, the house agents, could tell me something, as he thought he remembered seeing the name of that firm on the board.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134869,\n            \"I did not wish to seem too eager, or to let my informant know or guess too much, so, thanking him in the usual manner, I strolled away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134969,\n            \"Having once told me that the Piccadilly house-which throughout our interview he called a \\u201cmansion \\\"-was sold, he considered my business as concluded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134999,\n            \"When I asked who had purchased it, he opened his eyes a thought wider, and paused a few seconds before replying:-\\u201cIt is sold, sir.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135086,\n            \"\\u201cSurely,\\u201dI said, \\u201cyou do not mind letting me know so much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135135,\n            \"\\u201d This was manifestly a prig of the first water, and there was no use arguing with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135155,\n            \"I thought I had best meet him on his own ground, so I said:-\\u201cYour clients, sir, are happy in having so resolute a guardian of their confidence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135197,\n            \"\\u201d Here I handed him my card.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136542,\n            \"\\u201d This puzzled me a little, so I drew him on:-\\u201cThen you command life;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136562,\n            \"you are a god, I suppose?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136609,\n            \"If I may state my intellectual position I am, so far as concerns things purely terrestrial, somewhat in the position which Enoch occupied spiritually!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136656,\n            \"so I had to ask a simple question, though I felt that by so doing I was lowering myself in the eyes of the lunatic:-\\u201cAnd why with Enoch?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136714,\n            \"so I harked back to what he had denied:-\\u201cSo you don\\u2019t care about life and you don\\u2019t want souls.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136745,\n            \"\\u201d I put my question quickly and somewhat sternly, on purpose to disconcert him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136765,\n            \"for an instant he unconsciously relapsed into his old servile manner, bent low before me, and actually fawned upon me as he replied:-\\u201cI don\\u2019t want any souls, indeed, indeed!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149728,\n            \"It seems to me that we ought to take cabs when we go south or east;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170745,\n            \"Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172742,\n            \"Morris Quincey, you see the Vice-Consul, and get his aid with his fellow in Galatz and all he can do to make our way smooth, so that no times be lost when over the Danube.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181733,\n            \"Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris have half a dozen good horses, well appointed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182279,\n            \"Mr. Morris and Dr. Seward were off on their long ride before we started;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188100,\n            \"Oh, if only Morris and Seward were with us.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 5]\": [\n        [\n            57004,\n            \"He came on with me to Hillingham, and found that, by Lucy\\u2019s discretion, her mother was lunching out, so that we were alone with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57086,\n            \"When I told him of our friendship and how you trust to me in the matter, he said: \\u2018 You must tell him all you think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57166,\n            \"This was when we had come back to town, and he was having a cup of tea before starting on his return to Amsterdam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57239,\n            \"So I told him I would simply write an account of our visit, just as if I were doing a descriptive special article for The Daily Telegraph.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57433,\n            \"Then he began to chat of all things except ourselves and diseases and with such an infinite geniality that I could see poor Lucy\\u2019s pretense of animation merge into reality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57525,\n            \"They told me you were down in the spirit, and that you were of a ghastly pale.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57544,\n            \"To them I say: \\u201cPouf!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57552,\n            \"\\u201d\\u2019And he snapped his fingers at me and went on: \\u2018 But you and I shall show them how wrong they are.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57578,\n            \"How can he\\u2019- and he pointed at me with the same look and gesture as that with which once he pointed me out to his class, on, or rather after, a particular occasion which he never fails to remind me of-\\u2018 know anything of a young ladies?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57684,\n            \"He has no wife nor daughter, and the young do not tell themselves to the young, but to the old, like me, who have known so many sorrows and the causes of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57722,\n            \"So, my dear, we will send him away to smoke the cigarette in the garden, whiles you and I have little talk all to ourselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57826,\n            \"I have asked her to send me her maid, that I may ask just one or two question, that so I may not chance to miss nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57950,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cAs I tell you, he would not say a word more, even when we were alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsing, the great specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly with myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59400,\n            \"We are hedged in with difficulties, all of us, my poor old fellow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59789,\n            \"\\u201d He stopped and looked at me, and said:-\\u201cMy friend John, when the corn is grown, even before it has ripened-while the milk of its mother-earth is in him, and the sunshine has not yet begun to paint him with his gold, the husbandman he pull the ear and rub him between his rough hands, and blow away the green chaff, and say to you: \\u2018 Look!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59903,\n            \"For reply he reached over and took my ear in his hand and pulled it playfully, as he used long ago to do at lectures, and said: \\u201cThe good husbandman tell you so then because he knows, but not till then.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60001,\n            \"I have sown my corn, and Nature has her work to do in making it sprout;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60054,\n            \"Then he went on, and very gravely:-\\u201cYou were always a careful student, and your case-book was ever more full than the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60126,\n            \"Even if you have not kept the good practise, let me tell you that this case of our dear miss is one that may be-mind, I say may be-of such interest to us and others that all the rest may not make him kick the beam, as your peoples say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60262,\n            \"He took with him a bag in which were many instruments and drugs, \\u201cthe ghastly paraphernalia of our beneficial trade,\\u201das he once called, in one of his lectures, the equipment of a professor of the healing craft.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60646,\n            \"Then Van Helsing beckoned to me, and we went gently out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60662,\n            \"The instant we had closed the door he stepped quickly along the passage to the next door, which was open.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60787,\n            \"\\u201d I went downstairs with him, and as we were going there was a knock at the hall-door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61196,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur looked bewildered, and the Professor went on by explaining in a kindly way:-\\u201cYoung miss is bad, very bad.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61716,\n            \"\\u201d So neither of us looked whilst he bent over her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61728,\n            \"Van Helsing turning to me, said: \\u201cHe is so young and strong and of blood so pure that we need not defibrinate it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62653,\n            \"He came back a moment later and put his head inside the door and said with warning finger held up:-\\u201cRemember, she is your charge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62777,\n            \"When I told Mrs. Westenra that Dr. Van Helsing had directed that I should sit up with her she almost pooh-poohed the idea, pointing out her daughter\\u2019s renewed strength and excellent spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63272,\n            \"I sent a short wire to Van Helsing and to Arthur, telling them of the excellent result of the operation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63986,\n            \"\\u201cCome, let us see,\\u201dhe said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64248,\n            \"He wetted the poor white lips with it, and together we rubbed palm and wrist and heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64316,\n            \"I have to call on you yourself this time, friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64607,\n            \"\\u201d To which he smiled a sad sort of smile as he replied:-\\u201cHe is her lover, her fianc\\u00e9.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64652,\n            \"\\u201d When we stopped the operation, he attended to Lucy, whilst I applied digital pressure to my own incision.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65229,\n            \"Van Helsing returned in a couple of hours, and presently said to me: \\u201cNow you go home, and eat much and drink enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65278,\n            \"You and I must watch the case, and we must have none other to know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65363,\n            \"and when I said it was Dr. Van Helsing\\u2019s wish that either he or I should sit up, they asked me quite piteously to intercede with the \\u201cforeign gentleman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66208,\n            \"It is well we have no sceptic here, or he would say that you were working some spell to keep out an evil spirit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66260,\n            \"We then waited whilst Lucy made her toilet for the night, and when she was in bed he came and himself fixed the wreath of garlic round her neck.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66367,\n            \"\\u201d As we left the house in my fly, which was waiting, Van Helsing said:-\\u201cTo-night I can sleep in peace, and sleep I want-two nights of travel, much reading in the day between, and much anxiety on the day to follow, and a night to sit up, without to wink.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66433,\n            \"To-morrow in the morning early you call for me, and we come together to see our pretty miss, so much more strong for my \\u2018 spell\\u2019which I have work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67494,\n            \"\\u201cCome,\\u201dhe said, \\u201ccome, we must see and act.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67526,\n            \"we fight him all the same.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67761,\n            \"Presently he took an opportunity of telling Mrs. Westenra that she must not remove anything from Lucy\\u2019s room without consulting him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68357,\n            \"Thomas and his wife are hospitable folk, elderly, and without children, and if the specimen I enjoyed of their hospitality be of the average kind, their lives must be pretty comfortable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68393,\n            \"The keeper would not enter on what he called \\u201cbusiness\\u201duntil the supper was over, and we were all satisfied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68417,\n            \"Then when the table was cleared, and he had lit his pipe, he said:-\\u201cNow, sir, you can go on and arsk me what you want.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68451,\n            \"You\\u2019ll excoose me refoosin\\u2019to talk of perfeshunal subjects afore meals.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68609,\n            \"Mind you,\\u201dhe added philosophically, \\u201cthere\\u2019s a deal of the same nature in us as in them theer animiles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68635,\n            \"Here\\u2019s you a-comin\\u2019and arskin\\u2019of me questions about my business, and I that grumpy-like that only for your bloomin\\u2019\\u2019 arf-quid I\\u2019d\\u2019a\\u2019seen you blowed fust\\u2019fore I\\u2019d answer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68686,\n            \"Not even when you arsked me sarcastic-like if I\\u2019d like you to arsk the Superintendent if you might arsk me questions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68712,\n            \"Without offence did I tell yer to go to\\u2019ell?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69279,\n            \"He\\u2019ad white kid gloves on\\u2019is\\u2019 ands, and he pointed out the animiles to me and says: \\u2018 Keeper, these wolves seem upset at something.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69431,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cWell, it was a odd thing, but when the animiles see us a-talkin\\u2019they lay down, and when I went over to Bersicker he let me stroke his ears same as ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69593,\n            \"\\u2019 And with that he lifts his\\u2019 at as perlite as a lord, and walks away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69985,\n            \"but I don\\u2019t know as\\u2019 ow you\\u2019d be satisfied with the theory.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70107,\n            \"I couldn\\u2019t cope in badinage with the worthy Thomas, but I thought I knew a surer way to his heart, so I said:-\\u201cNow, Mr. Bilder, we\\u2019ll consider that first half-sovereign worked off, and this brother of his is waiting to be claimed when you\\u2019ve told me what you think will happen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70191,\n            \"\\u201cYe\\u2019ll excoose me, I know, for a-chaffin\\u2019of ye, but the old woman here winked at me, which was as much as telling me to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72670,\n            \"When they were there I remembered what Dr. Van Helsing had told me, but I didn\\u2019t like to remove them, and, besides, I would have some of the servants to sit up with me now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73272,\n            \"They stopped at the gate, and a few seconds later I met Van Helsing running up the avenue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73328,\n            \"\\u201d I answered as quickly and coherently as I could that I had only got his telegram early in the morning, and had not lost a minute in coming here, and that I could not make any one in the house hear me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73374,\n            \"He paused and raised his hat as he said solemnly:-\\u201cThen I fear we are too late.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73617,\n            \"Van Helsing and I looked at each other, and as we moved away he said: \\u201cWe can attend to them later.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74358,\n            \"He answered me in a way that I did not understand, but with the sternest look that his face could wear:-\\u201cIf that were all, I would stop here where we are now, and let her fade away into peace, for I see no light in life over her horizon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74473,\n            \"Van Helsing\\u2019s face almost beamed, and as we lifted her from the bath and rolled her in a hot sheet to dry her he said to me:-\\u201cThe first gain is ours!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74585,\n            \"Van Helsing called in one of the women, and told her to stay with her and not to take her eyes off her till we returned, and then beckoned me out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74622,\n            \"\\u201cWe must consult as to what is to be done,\\u201dhe said as we descended the stairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74643,\n            \"In the hall he opened the dining-room door, and we passed in, he closing the door carefully behind him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74734,\n            \"He was evidently torturing his mind about something, so I waited for an instant, and he spoke:-\\u201cWhat are we to do now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74811,\n            \"I fear to trust those women, even if they would have courage to submit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75017,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing strode forward, and took his hand, looking him straight in the eyes as he said:-\\u201cA brave man\\u2019s blood is the best thing on this earth when a woman is in trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75206,\n            \"The Professor watched whilst I went downstairs with Quincey Morris, and sent one of the maids to pay off one of the cabmen who were waiting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75340,\n            \"He handed me the paper saying only: \\u201cIt dropped from Lucy\\u2019s breast when we carried her to the bath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75566,\n            \"I know, and you know, and the other doctor who attended her knows, that Mrs. Westenra had disease of the heart, and we can certify that she died of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76053,\n            \"I can see that-said, that time you two came into the room, that you must have another transfusion of blood, and that both you and he were exhausted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76087,\n            \"Now I know well that you medical men speak in camera, and that a man must not expect to know what they consult about in private.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77530,\n            \"After dinner Mr. Hawkins said:-\\u201c\\u2018 My dears, I want to drink your health and prosperity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77742,\n            \"for, now that Jonathan is a partner, Mr. Hawkins wants to tell him all about the clients.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79835,\n            \"It was only when I told him that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79969,\n            \"You shall lie on one, and I on the other, and our sympathy will be comfort to each other, even though we do not speak, and even if we sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80847,\n            \"\\u201d When we came into Lucy\\u2019s room I could see that Van Helsing had, with his usual forethought, been putting matters straight and making everything look as pleasing as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81288,\n            \"I kept my eyes fixed on Lucy, as did Van Helsing, and we saw a spasm as of rage flit like a shadow over her face;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81989,\n            \"Under the circumstances, Van Helsing and I took it upon ourselves to examine papers, etc.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82018,\n            \"I asked him why, for I feared that he, being a foreigner, might not be quite aware of English legal requirements, and so might in ignorance make some unnecessary trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82065,\n            \"You forget that I am a lawyer as well as a doctor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82097,\n            \"I have more than him to avoid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82382,\n            \"But I have them here, and we shall for the present say nothing of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82421,\n            \"\\u201d When we had finished the work in hand, he said to me:-\\u201cAnd now, friend John, I think we may to bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82451,\n            \"We want sleep, both you and I, and rest to recuperate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83248,\n            \"Were you not amazed, nay horrified, when I would not let Arthur kiss his love-though she was dying-and snatched him away by all my strength?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83282,\n            \"And yet you saw how she thanked me, with her so beautiful dying eyes, her voice, too, so weak, and she kiss my rough old hand and bless me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83319,\n            \"And did you not hear me swear promise to her, that so she closed her eyes grateful?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83460,\n            \"\\u201d He paused a moment and went on solemnly: \\u201cFriend John, there are strange and terrible days before us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84448,\n            \"Van Helsing ordered the former arrangement to be adhered to, explaining that, as Lord Godalming was coming very soon, it would be less harrowing to his feelings to see all that was left of his fianc\\u00e9e quite alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87342,\n            \"and now a telegram from Van Helsing, whoever he may be:-\\u201cYou will be grieved to hear that Mrs. Westenra died five days ago, and that Lucy died the day before yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87770,\n            \"The moment we were alone in the carriage he gave way to a regular fit of hysterics.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87816,\n            \"He laughed till he cried, and I had to draw down the blinds lest any one should see us and misjudge;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88049,\n            \"He ask no person;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88219,\n            \"And yet when he say things that touch my husband-heart to the quick, and make my father-heart yearn to him as to no other man-not even to you, friend John, for we are more level in experiences than father and son-yet even at such moment King Laugh he come to me and shout and bellow in my ear, \\u2018 Here I am!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88530,\n            \"As he answered me his face grew stern, and he said in quite a different tone:-\\u201cOh, it was the grim irony of it all-this so lovely lady garlanded with flowers, that looked so fair as life, till one by one we wondered if she were truly dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88937,\n            \"I showed not my feeling to others when it would wound, but only to you, my old friend, whom I can trust.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91447,\n            \"In a few minutes Mary opened the door, and announced \\u201cDr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91670,\n            \"He said to me:-\\u201cMrs. Harker, is it not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91736,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cSir,\\u201dI said, \\u201cyou could have no better claim on me than that you were a friend and helper of Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92051,\n            \"\\u201d I could not resist the temptation of mystifying him a bit-I suppose it is some of the taste of the original apple that remains still in our mouths-so I handed him the shorthand diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92155,\n            \"\\u201cI knew long that Mr. Jonathan was a man of much thankfulness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92379,\n            \"\\u201d He bowed and settled himself in a chair with his back to the light, and became absorbed in the papers, whilst I went to see after lunch chiefly in order that he might not be disturbed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92419,\n            \"When I came back, I found him walking hurriedly up and down the room, his face all ablaze with excitement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92442,\n            \"He rushed up to me and took me by both hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92454,\n            \"\\u201cOh, Madam Mina,\\u201dhe said, \\u201chow can I say what I owe to you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92488,\n            \"I am daze, I am dazzle, with so much light, and yet clouds roll in behind the light every time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92522,\n            \"Oh, but I am grateful to you, you so clever woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92536,\n            \"Madam \\\"-he said this very solemnly-\\\" if ever Abraham Van Helsing can do anything for you or yours, I trust you will let me know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92567,\n            \"It will be pleasure and delight if I may serve you as a friend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92582,\n            \"as a friend, but all I have ever learned, all I can ever do, shall be for you and those you love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92644,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut, doctor, you praise me too much, and-and you do not know me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92665,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNot know you-I, who am old, and who have studied all my life men and women;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92688,\n            \"I, who have made my specialty the brain and all that belongs to him and all that follow from him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92710,\n            \"And I have read your diary that you have so goodly written for me, and which breathes out truth in every line.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92734,\n            \"I, who have read your so sweet letter to poor Lucy of your marriage and your trust, not know you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92855,\n            \"\\u201d I saw here an opening to ask him about Jonathan, so I said:-\\u201cHe was almost recovered, but he has been greatly upset by Mr. Hawkins\\u2019 s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92908,\n            \"I have read your last two letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93042,\n            \"I suppose I was hysterical, for I threw myself on my knees and held up my hands to him, and implored him to make my husband well again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93073,\n            \"He took my hands and raised me up, and made me sit on the sofa, and sat by me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93095,\n            \"he held my hand in his, and said to me with, oh, such infinite sweetness:-\\u201cMy life is a barren and lonely one, and so full of work that I have not had much time for friendships;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93140,\n            \"but since I have been summoned to here by my friend John Seward I have known so many good people and seen such nobility that I feel more than ever-and it has grown with my advancing years-the loneliness of my life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93186,\n            \"Believe, me, then, that I come here full of respect for you, and you have given me hope-hope, not in what I am seeking of, but that there are good women still left to make life happy-good women, whose lives and whose truths may make good lesson for the children that are to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93252,\n            \"I am glad, glad, that I may here be of some use to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93286,\n            \"I promise you that I will gladly do all for him that I can-all to make his life strong and manly, and your life a happy one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93367,\n            \"You have told me all about Lucy, and so now we shall not speak of it, lest it distress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93389,\n            \"I shall stay in Exeter to-night, for I want to think much over what you have told me, and when I have thought I will ask you questions, if I may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93426,\n            \"And then, too, you will tell me of husband Jonathan\\u2019s trouble so far as you can, but not yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93456,\n            \"afterwards you shall tell me all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93463,\n            \"\\u201d After lunch, when we went back to the drawing-room, he said to me:-\\u201cAnd now tell me all about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93492,\n            \"\\u201d When it came to speaking to this great learned man, I began to fear that he would think me a weak fool, and Jonathan a madman-that journal is all so strange-and I hesitated to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93536,\n            \"But he was so sweet and kind, and he had promised to help, and I trusted him, so I said:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, what I have to tell you is so queer that you must not laugh at me or at my husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93601,\n            \"you must be kind to me, and not think me foolish that I have even half believed some very strange things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93624,\n            \"\\u201d He reassured me by his manner as well as his words when he said:-\\u201cOh, my dear, if you only know how strange is the matter regarding which I am here, it is you who would laugh.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93669,\n            \"I have learned not to think little of any one\\u2019s belief, no matter how strange it be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93747,\n            \"You have taken a weight off my mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93756,\n            \"If you will let me, I shall give you a paper to read.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93782,\n            \"It will tell you my trouble and Jonathan\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93824,\n            \"And then when I see you, perhaps, you will be very kind and tell me what you think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93845,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI promise,\\u201dhe said as I gave him the papers;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93860,\n            \"\\u201cI shall in the morning, so soon as I can, come to see you and your husband, if I may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93885,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cJonathan will be here at half-past eleven, and you must come to lunch with us and see him then;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93929,\n            \"\\u201d He was surprised at my knowledge of the trains off-hand, but he does not know that I have made up all the trains to and from Exeter, so that I may help Jonathan in case he is in a hurry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93975,\n            \"So he took the papers with him and went away, and I sit here thinking-thinking I don\\u2019t know what.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94000,\n            \"Letter (by hand), Van Helsing to Mrs. Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94022,\n            \"\\u201cDear Madam Mina,-\\u201cI have read your husband\\u2019s so wonderful diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94088,\n            \"and let me tell you from experience of men, that one who would do as he did in going down that wall and to that room-ay, and going a second time-is not one to be injured in permanence by a shock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94172,\n            \"I am blessed that to-day I come to see you, for I have learn all at once so much that again I am dazzle-dazzle more than ever, and I must think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94221,\n            \"\\u201d Letter, Mrs. Harker to Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94242,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear Dr. Van Helsing,-\\u201cA thousand thanks for your kind letter, which has taken a great weight off my mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94417,\n            \"Do not answer this, as I shall take it that, if I do not hear, you will come to breakfast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94441,\n            \"\\u201cBelieve me, \\u201cYour faithful and grateful friend, \\u201cMina Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94483,\n            \"When I got home last night Mina had supper ready, and when we had supped she told me of Van Helsing\\u2019s visit, and of her having given him the two diaries copied out, and of how anxious she has been about me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94588,\n            \"But, now that I know, I am not afraid, even of the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94605,\n            \"He has succeeded after all, then, in his design in getting to London, and it was he I saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94636,\n            \"Van Helsing is the man to unmask him and hunt him out, if he is anything like what Mina says.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94668,\n            \"Mina is dressing, and I shall call at the hotel in a few minutes and bring him over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94691,\n            \"He was, I think, surprised to see me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94702,\n            \"When I came into the room where he was, and introduced myself, he took me by the shoulder, and turned my face round to the light, and said, after a sharp scrutiny:-\\u201cBut Madam Mina told me you were ill, that you had had a shock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94800,\n            \"but you have cured me already.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94958,\n            \"I am with so much pleasure coming to you to breakfast;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94970,\n            \"and, oh, sir, you will pardon praise from an old man, but you are blessed in your wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94993,\n            \"\\u201d I would listen to him go on praising Mina for a day, so I simply nodded and stood silent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95057,\n            \"So true, so sweet, so noble, so little an egoist-and that, let me tell you, is much in this age, so sceptical and selfish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95090,\n            \"And you, sir-I have read all the letters to poor Miss Lucy, and some of them speak of you, so I know you since some days from the knowing of others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95127,\n            \"but I have seen your true self since last night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95138,\n            \"You will give me your hand, will you not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95159,\n            \"\\u201d We shook hands, and he was so earnest and so kind that it made me quite choky.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95179,\n            \"\\u201cAnd now,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cmay I ask you for some more help?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95214,\n            \"You can help me here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95220,\n            \"Can you tell me what went before your going to Transylvania?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95253,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cLook here, sir,\\u201dI said, \\u201cdoes what you have to do concern the Count?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95336,\n            \"\\u201d After breakfast I saw him to the station.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95346,\n            \"When we were parting he said:-\\u201cPerhaps you will come to town if I send to you, and take Madam Mina too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95373,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe shall both come when you will,\\u201dI said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95387,\n            \"I had got him the morning papers and the London papers of the previous night, and while we were talking at the carriage window, waiting for the train to start, he was turning them over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95426,\n            \"His eyes suddenly seemed to catch something in one of them, \\u201cThe Westminster Gazette \\\"-I knew it by the colour-and he grew quite white.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95479,\n            \"\\u201d I do not think he remembered me at the moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95650,\n            \"I had a letter from Arthur, written on Sunday, and from it I gather that he is bearing up wonderfully well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95699,\n            \"Quincey wrote me a line too, and from him I hear that Arthur is beginning to recover something of his old buoyancy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95795,\n            \"I have an idea that Van Helsing thinks he knows, too, but he will only let out enough at a time to whet curiosity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95834,\n            \"To-day he came back, and almost bounded into the room at about half-past five o\\u2019clock, and thrust last night\\u2019s \\u201cWestminster Gazette\\u201dinto my hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95891,\n            \"I looked over the paper, for I really did not know what he meant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95907,\n            \"but he took it from me and pointed out a paragraph about children being decoyed away at Hampstead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96006,\n            \"\\u201d I did not quite understand his answer:-\\u201cThat is true indirectly, but not directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96039,\n            \"I was a little inclined to take his seriousness lightly-for, after all, four days of rest and freedom from burning, harrowing anxiety does help to restore one\\u2019s spirits-but when I saw his face, it sobered me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96086,\n            \"Never, even in the midst of our despair about poor Lucy, had he looked more stern.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96140,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo you mean to tell me, friend John, that you have no suspicion as to what poor Lucy died of;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96412,\n            \"I suppose now you do not believe in corporeal transference.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96468,\n            \"\\u201d He smiled as he went on: \\u201cThen you are satisfied as to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96528,\n            \"Then, friend John, am I to take it that you simply accept fact, and are satisfied to let from premise to conclusion be a blank?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96559,\n            \"Then tell me-for I am student of the brain-how you accept the hypnotism and reject the thought reading.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96582,\n            \"Let me tell you, my friend, that there are things done to-day in electrical science which would have been deemed unholy by the very men who discovered electricity-who would themselves not so long before have been burned as wizards.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96733,\n            \"Can you tell me why, when other spiders die small and soon, that one great spider lived for centuries in the tower of the old Spanish church and grew and grew, till, on descending, he could drink the oil of all the church lamps?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96783,\n            \"Can you tell me why in the Pampas, ay and elsewhere, there are bats that come at night and open the veins of cattle and horses and suck dry their veins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96934,\n            \"\\u201d He waved his hand for silence, and went on:-\\u201cCan you tell me why the tortoise lives more long than generations of men;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96993,\n            \"Can you tell me why men believe in all ages and places that there are some few who live on always if they be permit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97072,\n            \"Can you tell me how the Indian fakir can make himself to die and have been buried, and his grave sealed and corn sowed on it, and the corn reaped and be cut and sown and reaped and cut again, and then men come and take away the unbroken seal and that there lie the Indian fakir, not dead, but that rise up and walk amongst them as before?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97158,\n            \"he so crowded on my mind his list of nature\\u2019s eccentricities and possible impossibilities that my imagination was getting fired.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97181,\n            \"I had a dim idea that he was teaching me some lesson, as long ago he used to do in his study at Amsterdam;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97207,\n            \"but he used then to tell me the thing, so that I could have the object of thought in mind all the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97232,\n            \"But now I was without this help, yet I wanted to follow him, so I said:-\\u201cProfessor, let me be your pet student again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97263,\n            \"Tell me the thesis, so that I may apply your knowledge as you go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97352,\n            \"\\u201cWell, I shall tell you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97360,\n            \"My thesis is this: I want you to believe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97427,\n            \"He meant that we shall have an open mind, and not let a little bit of truth check the rush of a big truth, like a small rock does a railway truck.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97471,\n            \"We keep him, and we value him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97480,\n            \"but all the same we must not let him think himself all the truth in the universe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97498,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThen you want me not to let some previous conviction injure the receptivity of my mind with regard to some strange matter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97523,\n            \"Do I read your lesson aright?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97598,\n            \"\\u201d He stood up and said solemnly:-\\u201cThen you are wrong.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97634,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIn God\\u2019s name, Professor Van Helsing, what do you mean?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97728,\n            \"I smote the table hard and rose up as I said to him:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, are you mad?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97753,\n            \"\\u201d He raised his head and looked at me, and somehow the tenderness of his face calmed me at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97796,\n            \"Oh, my friend, why, think you, did I go so far round, why take so long to tell you so simple a thing?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97825,\n            \"Was it because I hate you and have hated you all my life?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97839,\n            \"Was it because I wished to give you pain?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97849,\n            \"Was it that I wanted, now so late, revenge for that time when you saved my life, and from a fearful death?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97887,\n            \"He went on:-\\u201cMy friend, it was because I wished to be gentle in the breaking to you, for I know you have loved that so sweet lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97921,\n            \"But even yet I do not expect you to believe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97995,\n            \"Dare you come with me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98035,\n            \"\\u201d He saw my hesitation, and spoke:-\\u201cThe logic is simple, no madman\\u2019s logic this time, jumping from tussock to tussock in a misty bog.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98117,\n            \"Come, I tell you what I propose: first, that we go off now and see that child in the hospital.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98141,\n            \"Dr. Vincent, of the North Hospital, where the papers say the child is, is friend of mine, and I think of yours since you were in class at Amsterdam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98229,\n            \"\\u201cAnd then we spend the night, you and I, in the churchyard where Lucy lies.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98344,\n            \"Dr. Vincent took the bandage from its throat, and showed us the punctures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98391,\n            \"We asked Vincent to what he attributed them, and he replied that it must have been a bite of some animal, perhaps a rat;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98634,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201c\\u201cI hope,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing, \\u201cthat when you are sending the child home you will caution its parents to keep strict watch over it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98691,\n            \"But in any case I suppose you will not let it away for some days?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98858,\n            \"The Professor had evidently noted the road we were to go, for he went on unhesitatingly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98968,\n            \"The Professor took the key, opened the creaky door, and standing back, politely, but quite unconsciously, motioned me to precede him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99016,\n            \"My companion followed me quickly, and cautiously drew the door to, after carefully ascertaining that the lock was a falling, and not a spring, one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99358,\n            \"I actually took hold of his hand to stop him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99369,\n            \"He only said: \\u201cYou shall see,\\u201dand again fumbling in his bag, took out a tiny fret-saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99394,\n            \"Striking the turnscrew through the lead with a swift downward stab, which made me wince, he made a small hole, which was, however, big enough to admit the point of the saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99507,\n            \"Taking the edge of the loose flange, he bent it back towards the foot of the coffin, and holding up the candle into the aperture, motioned to me to look.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99552,\n            \"It was certainly a surprise to me, and gave me a considerable shock, but Van Helsing was unmoved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99606,\n            \"I felt all the dogged argumentativeness of my nature awake within me as I answered him:-\\u201cI am satisfied that Lucy\\u2019s body is not in that coffin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99753,\n            \"\\u201d he said, \\u201cwe must have more proof.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99813,\n            \"Behind us he closed the door and locked it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99823,\n            \"He handed me the key, saying: \\u201cWill you keep it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99843,\n            \"\\u201d I laughed-it was not a very cheerful laugh, I am bound to say-as I motioned him to keep it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99912,\n            \"Then he told me to watch at one side of the churchyard whilst he would watch at the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99932,\n            \"I took up my place behind a yew-tree, and I saw his dark figure move until the intervening headstones and trees hid it from my sight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99991,\n            \"I was chilled and unnerved, and angry with the Professor for taking me on such an errand and with myself for coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100195,\n            \"I heard the rustle of actual movement where I had first seen the white figure, and coming over, found the Professor holding in his arms a tiny child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100226,\n            \"When he saw me he held it out to me, and said:-\\u201cAre you satisfied now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100296,\n            \"\\u201cWe shall see,\\u201dsaid the Professor, and with one impulse we took our way out of the churchyard, he carrying the sleeping child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100377,\n            \"\\u201cWe were just in time,\\u201dsaid the Professor thankfully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100590,\n            \"But I must try to get a few hours\\u2019 sleep, as Van Helsing is to call for me at noon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100613,\n            \"He insists that I shall go with him on another expedition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100704,\n            \"but the Professor told me that we should not want more than an hour at most.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100826,\n            \"I shrugged my shoulders, however, and rested silent, for Van Helsing had a way of going on his own road, no matter who remonstrated.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100855,\n            \"He took the key, opened the vault, and again courteously motioned me to precede.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100896,\n            \"Van Helsing walked over to Lucy\\u2019s coffin, and I followed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100997,\n            \"\\u201d I said to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101009,\n            \"\\u201d said the Professor in response, and as he spoke he put over his hand, and in a way that made me shudder, pulled back the dead lips and showed the white teeth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101064,\n            \"With this and this \\\"-and he touched one of the canine teeth and that below it-\\\" the little children can be bitten.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101110,\n            \"I could not accept such an overwhelming idea as he suggested;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101212,\n            \"Van Helsing did not seem to notice my silence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101265,\n            \"Then he turned to me and said:-\\u201cHere, there is one thing which is different from all recorded;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101300,\n            \"She was bitten by the vampire when she was in a trance, sleep-walking-oh, you start;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101377,\n            \"Usually when the Un-Dead sleep at home \\\"-as he spoke he made a comprehensive sweep of his arm to designate what to a vampire was \\u201chome \\\"-\\\" their face show what they are, but this so sweet that was when she not Un-Dead she go back to the nothings of the common dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101463,\n            \"\\u201d This turned my blood cold, and it began to dawn upon me that I was accepting Van Helsing\\u2019s theories;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101506,\n            \"He looked up at me, and evidently saw the change in my face, for he said almost joyously:-\\u201cAh, you believe now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101622,\n            \"I was, in fact, beginning to shudder at the presence of this being, this Un-Dead, as Van Helsing called it, and to loathe it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101667,\n            \"I waited a considerable time for Van Helsing to begin, but he stood as if wrapped in thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101798,\n            \"But then we may have to want Arthur, and how shall we tell him of this?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101949,\n            \"I know he has forgiven me because in some mistaken idea I have done things that prevent him say good-bye as he ought;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102003,\n            \"He will then argue back that it is we, mistaken ones, that have killed her by our ideas;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102076,\n            \"and again, he will think that we may be right, and that his so beloved was, after all, an Un-Dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102105,\n            \"I told him once, and since then I learn much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102117,\n            \"Now, since I know it is all true, a hundred thousand times more do I know that he must pass through the bitter waters to reach the sweet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102170,\n            \"then we can act for good all round and send him peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102248,\n            \"I shall send for Arthur to come too, and also that so fine young man of America that gave his blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102570,\n            \"He is cunning, as I know from Mr. Jonathan and from the way that all along he have fooled us when he played with us for Miss Lucy\\u2019s life, and we lost;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102631,\n            \"even we four who gave our strength to Miss Lucy it also is all to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102648,\n            \"Besides, he can summon his wolf and I know not what.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102661,\n            \"So if it be that he come thither on this night he shall find me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102878,\n            \"I wonder if his mind can have become in any way unhinged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102945,\n            \"I am loath to think it, and indeed it would be almost as great a marvel as the other to find that Van Helsing was mad;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102973,\n            \"but anyhow I shall watch him carefully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103022,\n            \"he told us all that he wanted us to do, but especially addressing himself to Arthur, as if all our wills were centred in his.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103050,\n            \"He began by saying that he hoped we would all come with him too, \\u201cfor,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cthere is a grave duty to be done there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103083,\n            \"You were doubtless surprised at my letter?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103132,\n            \"I have been curious, too, as to what you mean.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103152,\n            \"but the more we talked, the more puzzled we got, till now I can say for myself that I\\u2019m about up a tree as to any meaning about anything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103197,\n            \"\\u201cOh,\\u201dsaid the Professor, \\u201cthen you are nearer the beginning, both of you, than friend John here, who has to go a long way back before he can even get so far as to begin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103241,\n            \"\\u201d It was evident that he recognised my return to my old doubting frame of mind without my saying a word.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103263,\n            \"Then, turning to the other two, he said with intense gravity:-\\u201cI want your permission to do what I think good this night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103302,\n            \"and when you know what it is I propose to do you will know, and only then, how much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103324,\n            \"Therefore may I ask that you promise me in the dark, so that afterwards, though you may be angry with me for a time-I must not disguise from myself the possibility that such may be-you shall not blame yourselves for anything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103467,\n            \"Then Arthur spoke out:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, I don\\u2019t quite like to \\u2018 buy a pig in a poke,\\u2019as they say in Scotland, and if it be anything in which my honour as a gentleman or my faith as a Christian is concerned, I cannot make such a promise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103634,\n            \"And now that the pourparlers are over, may I ask what it is we are to do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103653,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI want you to come with me, and to come in secret, to the churchyard at Kingstead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103740,\n            \"Pardon me, I see that you are in earnest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103751,\n            \"\\u201d He sat down again, but I could see that he sat firmly and proudly, as one who is on his dignity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103950,\n            \"\\u201cAnd then you will at least know the limit of my purpose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104071,\n            \"\\u201cI did not say she was alive, my child;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104215,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing, you try me too far.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104226,\n            \"What have I done to you that you should torture me so?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104259,\n            \"Are you mad to speak such things, or am I mad to listen to them?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104288,\n            \"I shall not give my consent to anything you do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104312,\n            \"and, by God, I shall do it!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104322,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing rose up from where he had all the time been seated, and said, gravely and sternly:-\\u201cMy Lord Godalming, I, too, have a duty to do, a duty to others, a duty to you, a duty to the dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104386,\n            \"All I ask you now is that you come with me, that you look and listen;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104404,\n            \"and if when later I make the same request you do not be more eager for its fulfilment even than I am, then-then I shall do my duty, whatever it may seem to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104443,\n            \"And then, to follow of your Lordship\\u2019s wishes I shall hold myself at your disposal to render an account to you, when and where you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104542,\n            \"Believe me that if the time comes for you to change your mind towards me, one look from you will wipe away all this so sad hour, for I would do what a man can to save you from sorrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104647,\n            \"For her-I am ashamed to say so much, but I say it in kindness-I gave what you gave;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104677,\n            \"I gave it, I, who was not, like you, her lover, but only her physician and her friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104701,\n            \"I gave to her my nights and days-before death, after death;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104716,\n            \"and if my death can do her good even now, when she is the dead Un-Dead, she shall have it freely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104859,\n            \"We all kept somehow close together, with Van Helsing slightly in front as he led the way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104878,\n            \"When we had come close to the tomb I looked well at Arthur, for I feared that the proximity to a place laden with so sorrowful a memory would upset him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104917,\n            \"I took it that the very mystery of the proceeding was in some way a counteractant to his grief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104937,\n            \"The Professor unlocked the door, and seeing a natural hesitation amongst us for various reasons, solved the difficulty by entering first himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104962,\n            \"The rest of us followed, and he closed the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104991,\n            \"Van Helsing said to me:-\\u201cYou were with me here yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105021,\n            \"\\u201d The Professor turned to the rest saying:-\\u201cYou hear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105145,\n            \"Van Helsing forced back the leaden flange, and we all looked in and recoiled.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105490,\n            \"Wait you with me outside, unseen and unheard, and things much stranger are yet to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105528,\n            \"\\u201d He opened the door, and we filed out, he coming last and locking the door behind him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105666,\n            \"Arthur was silent, and was, I could see, striving to grasp the purpose and the inner meaning of the mystery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105690,\n            \"I was myself tolerably patient, and half inclined again to throw aside doubt and to accept Van Helsing\\u2019s conclusions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105873,\n            \"I was somewhat puzzled at this, and being close, asked him what it was that he was doing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105894,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey drew near also, as they too were curious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105907,\n            \"He answered:-\\u201cI am closing the tomb, so that the Un-Dead may not enter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106006,\n            \"\\u201d It was an answer that appalled the most sceptical of us, and we felt individually that in the presence of such earnest purpose as the Professor\\u2019s, a purpose which could thus use the to him most sacred of things, it was impossible to distrust.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106341,\n            \"We were starting forward, but the Professor\\u2019s warning hand, seen by us as he stood behind a yew-tree, kept us back;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106450,\n            \"Van Helsing stepped out, and, obedient to his gesture, we all advanced too;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106540,\n            \"I could see by the tremulous light that even Van Helsing\\u2019s iron nerve had failed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107258,\n            \"We could hear the click of the closing lantern as Van Helsing held it down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107298,\n            \"We all looked on in horrified amazement as we saw, when he stood back, the woman, with a corporeal body as real at that moment as our own, pass in through the interstice where scarce a knife-blade could have gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107345,\n            \"We all felt a glad sense of relief when we saw the Professor calmly restoring the strings of putty to the edges of the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107371,\n            \"When this was done, he lifted the child and said: \\u201cCome now, my friends;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107581,\n            \"Till then I shall not ask you to forgive me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107641,\n            \"- A little before twelve o\\u2019clock we three-Arthur, Quincey Morris, and myself-called for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107792,\n            \"When we were alone and had heard the last of the footsteps die out up the road, we silently, and as if by ordered intention, followed the Professor to the tomb.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107827,\n            \"He unlocked the door, and we entered, closing it behind us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107889,\n            \"When he again lifted the lid off Lucy\\u2019s coffin we all looked-Arthur trembling like an aspen-and saw that the body lay there in all its death-beauty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108267,\n            \"When all was ready, Van Helsing said:-\\u201cBefore we do anything, let me tell you this;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109093,\n            \"Van Helsing opened his missal and began to read, and Quincey and I followed as well as we could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109678,\n            \"God bless you that you have given my dear one her soul again, and me peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109696,\n            \"\\u201d He put his hands on the Professor\\u2019s shoulder, and laying his head on his breast, cried for a while silently, whilst we stood unmoving.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109836,\n            \"the Professor and I sawed the top off the stake, leaving the point of it in the body.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109966,\n            \"Before we moved away Van Helsing said:-\\u201cNow, my friends, one step of our work is done, one the most harrowing to ourselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110019,\n            \"I have clues which we can follow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110048,\n            \"Shall you not all help me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110096,\n            \"\\u201d Each in turn, we took his hand, and the promise was made.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110112,\n            \"Then said the Professor as we moved off:-\\u201cTwo nights hence you shall meet with me and dine together at seven of the clock with friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110143,\n            \"I shall entreat two others, two that you know not as yet;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110279,\n            \"SEWARD\\u2019S DIARY-continued WHEN we arrived at the Berkeley Hotel, Van Helsing found a telegram waiting for him:-\\u201cAm coming up by train.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110327,\n            \"\\u201cAh, that wonderful Madam Mina,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cpearl among women!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110445,\n            \"When I have returned you will be master of all the facts, and we can then better enter on our inquisition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110503,\n            \"What is here told,\\u201dhe laid his hand heavily and gravely on the packet of papers as he spoke, \\u201cmay be the beginning of the end to you and me and many another;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110557,\n            \"Read all, I pray you, with the open mind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110673,\n            \"and I was beginning to feel uneasy, lest I might miss my guest, when a sweet-faced, dainty-looking girl stepped up to me, and, after a quick glance, said: \\u201cDr. Seward, is it not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110916,\n            \"As yet I have not had the chance of looking at the papers which Van Helsing left with me, though they lie open before me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111002,\n            \"- After I had tidied myself, I went down to Dr. Seward\\u2019s study.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111020,\n            \"At the door I paused a moment, for I thought I heard him talking with some one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111039,\n            \"As, however, he had pressed me to be quick, I knocked at the door, and on his calling out, \\u201cCome in,\\u201dI entered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111071,\n            \"To my intense surprise, there was no one with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111083,\n            \"He was quite alone, and on the table opposite him was what I knew at once from the description to be a phonograph.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111119,\n            \"\\u201cI hope I did not keep you waiting,\\u201dI said;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111133,\n            \"\\u201cbut I stayed at the door as I heard you talking, and thought there was some one with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111179,\n            \"\\u201d I asked him in surprise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111291,\n            \"and as it is entirely-almost entirely-about my cases, it may be awkward-that is, I mean--\\u201dHe stopped, and I tried to help him out of his embarrassment:-\\u201cYou helped to attend dear Lucy at the end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111373,\n            \"\\u201d To my surprise, he answered, with a horrorstruck look in his face:-\\u201cTell you of her death?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111423,\n            \"Again he paused, and I could see that he was trying to invent an excuse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111440,\n            \"At length he stammered out:-\\u201cYou see, I do not know how to pick out any particular part of the diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111466,\n            \"\\u201d Even while he was speaking an idea dawned upon him, and he said with unconscious simplicity, in a different voice, and with the na\\u00efvet\\u00e9 of a child: \\u201cThat\\u2019s quite true, upon my honour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111536,\n            \"\\u201cBut do you know that, although I have kept the diary for months past, it never once struck me how I was going to find any particular part of it in case I wanted to look it up?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111578,\n            \"\\u201d By this time my mind was made up that the diary of a doctor who attended Lucy might have something to add to the sum of our knowledge of that terrible Being, and I said boldly:-\\u201cThen, Dr. Seward, you had better let me copy it out for you on my typewriter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111659,\n            \"For all the world, I wouldn\\u2019t let you know that terrible story!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111723,\n            \"His eyes caught the look in mine, and, without his thinking, followed their direction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111751,\n            \"\\u201cYou do not know me,\\u201dI said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111762,\n            \"\\u201cWhen you have read those papers-my own diary and my husband\\u2019s also, which I have typed-you will know me better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111807,\n            \"but, of course, you do not know me-yet;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111820,\n            \"and I must not expect you to trust me so far.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111850,\n            \"He stood up and opened a large drawer, in which were arranged in order a number of hollow cylinders of metal covered with dark wax, and said:-\\u201cYou are quite right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111887,\n            \"I did not trust you because I did not know you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111899,\n            \"But I know you now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111905,\n            \"and let me say that I should have known you long ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111918,\n            \"I know that Lucy told you of me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111944,\n            \"Take the cylinders and hear them-the first half-dozen of them are personal to me, and they will not horrify you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111970,\n            \"then you will know me better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112006,\n            \"\\u201d He carried the phonograph himself up to my sitting-room and adjusted it for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112069,\n            \"- I was so absorbed in that wonderful diary of Jonathan Harker and that other of his wife that I let the time run on without thinking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112276,\n            \"It told me, in its very tones, the anguish of your heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112320,\n            \"I have copied out the words on my typewriter, and none other need now hear your heart beat, as I did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112453,\n            \"I think that the cylinders which you gave me contained more than you intended me to know;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112471,\n            \"but I can see that there are in your record many lights to this dark mystery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112488,\n            \"You will let me help, will you not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112507,\n            \"and I see already, though your diary only took me to 7 September, how poor Lucy was beset, and how her terrible doom was being wrought out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112538,\n            \"Jonathan and I have been working day and night since Professor Van Helsing saw us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112554,\n            \"He is gone to Whitby to get more information, and he will be here to-morrow to help us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112796,\n            \"- After dinner I came with Dr. Seward to his study.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112809,\n            \"He brought back the phonograph from my room, and I took my typewriter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112824,\n            \"He placed me in a comfortable chair, and arranged the phonograph so that I could touch it without getting up, and showed me how to stop it in case I should want to pause.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112861,\n            \"Then he very thoughtfully took a chair, with his back to me, so that I might be as free as possible, and began to read.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112938,\n            \"When Dr. Seward saw me he jumped up with a horrified exclamation, and hurriedly taking a case-bottle from a cupboard, gave me some brandy, which in a few minutes somewhat restored me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113083,\n            \"I took the cover off my typewriter, and said to Dr. Seward:-\\u201cLet me write this all out now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113108,\n            \"We must be ready for Dr. Van Helsing when he comes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113174,\n            \"You tell me that Lord Godalming and Mr. Morris are coming too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113188,\n            \"Let us be able to tell him when they come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113199,\n            \"\\u201d He accordingly set the phonograph at a slow pace, and I began to typewrite from the beginning of the seventh cylinder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113246,\n            \"It was late when I got through, but Dr. Seward went about his work of going his round of the patients;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113270,\n            \"when he had finished he came back and sat near me, reading, so that I did not feel too lonely whilst I worked.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113319,\n            \"Before I left him I remembered what Jonathan put in his diary of the Professor\\u2019s perturbation at reading something in an evening paper at the station at Exeter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113350,\n            \"so, seeing that Dr. Seward keeps his newspapers, I borrowed the files of \\u201cThe Westminster Gazette\\u201dand \\u201cThe Pall Mall Gazette,\\u201dand took them to my room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113508,\n            \"If this journal be true-and judging by one\\u2019s own wonderful experiences, it must be-he is also a man of great nerve.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113553,\n            \"After reading his account of it I was prepared to meet a good specimen of manhood, but hardly the quiet, business-like gentleman who came here to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113588,\n            \"- After lunch Harker and his wife went back to their own room, and as I passed a while ago I heard the click of the typewriter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113666,\n            \"He is now reading his wife\\u2019s typescript of my diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113782,\n            \"He says that by dinner-time they will be able to show a whole connected narrative.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113800,\n            \"He thinks that in the meantime I should see Renfield, as hitherto he has been a sort of index to the coming and going of the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114183,\n            \"- When I received Mr. Billington\\u2019s courteous message that he would give me any information in his power I thought it best to go down to Whitby and make, on the spot, such inquiries as I wanted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114316,\n            \"They all knew that I was busy, and that my stay was short, and Mr. Billington had ready in his office all the papers concerning the consignment of boxes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114499,\n            \"This was all the information Mr. Billington could give me, so I went down to the port and saw the coastguards, the Customs officers and the harbour-master.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114721,\n            \"- The station-master was good enough to give me a line to his old companion the station-master at King\\u2019s Cross, so that when I arrived there in the morning I was able to ask him about the arrival of the boxes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115155,\n            \"\\u201d Having been in the house, I could well believe him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115168,\n            \"but if he knew what I know, he would, I think, have raised his terms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115592,\n            \"Of course they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has been quite \\u201cblowing my trumpet,\\u201das Mr. Morris expressed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115801,\n            \"When Lord Godalming got his and turned it over-it does make a pretty good pile-he said:-\\u201cDid you write all this, Mrs. Harker?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115834,\n            \"\\u201d I nodded, and he went on:-\\u201cI don\\u2019t quite see the drift of it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115856,\n            \"but you people are all so good and kind, and have been working so earnestly and so energetically, that all I can do is to accept your ideas blindfold and try to help you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115916,\n            \"Besides, I know you loved my poor Lucy-\\u201d Here he turned away and covered his face with his hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115939,\n            \"I could hear the tears in his voice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115976,\n            \"I suppose there is something in woman\\u2019s nature that makes a man free to break down before her and express his feelings on the tender or emotional side without feeling it derogatory to his manhood;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116014,\n            \"for when Lord Godalming found himself alone with me he sat down on the sofa and gave way utterly and openly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116036,\n            \"I sat down beside him and took his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116046,\n            \"I hope he didn\\u2019t think it forward of me, and that if he ever thinks of it afterwards he never will have such a thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116075,\n            \"There I wrong him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116080,\n            \"I know he never will-he is too true a gentleman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116093,\n            \"I said to him, for I could see that his heart was breaking:-\\u201cI loved dear Lucy, and I know what she was to you, and what you were to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116138,\n            \"and now she is gone, will you not let me be like a sister to you in your trouble?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116159,\n            \"I know what sorrows you have had, though I cannot measure the depth of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116176,\n            \"If sympathy and pity can help in your affliction, won\\u2019t you let me be of some little service-for Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116217,\n            \"It seemed to me that all that he had of late been suffering in silence found a vent at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116277,\n            \"I felt an infinite pity for him, and opened my arms unthinkingly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116291,\n            \"With a sob he laid his head on my shoulder and cried like a wearied child, whilst he shook with emotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116338,\n            \"I felt this big sorrowing man\\u2019s head resting on me, as though it were that of the baby that some day may lie on my bosom, and I stroked his hair as though he were my own child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116418,\n            \"He told me that for days and nights past-weary days and sleepless nights-he had been unable to speak with any one, as a man must speak in his time of sorrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116455,\n            \"There was no woman whose sympathy could be given to him, or with whom, owing to the terrible circumstance with which his sorrow was surrounded, he could speak freely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116488,\n            \"\\u201cI know now how I suffered,\\u201dhe said, as he dried his eyes, \\u201cbut I do not know even yet-and none other can ever know-how much your sweet sympathy has been to me to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116562,\n            \"You will let me be like a brother, will you not, for all our lives-for dear Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116604,\n            \"\\u201cAy, and for your own sake,\\u201dhe added, \\u201cfor if a man\\u2019s esteem and gratitude are ever worth the winning, you have won mine to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116641,\n            \"If ever the future should bring to you a time when you need a man\\u2019s help, believe me, you will not call in vain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116689,\n            \"but if it should ever come, promise me that you will let me know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116705,\n            \"\\u201d He was so earnest, and his sorrow was so fresh, that I felt it would comfort him, so I said:-\\u201cI promise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117056,\n            \"- I got home at five o\\u2019clock, and found that Godalming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had made and arranged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117100,\n            \"Harker had not yet returned from his visit to the carriers\\u2019 men, of whom Dr. Hennessey had written to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118334,\n            \"Looking at my watch, I saw that I should go to the station to meet Van Helsing, so I told Mrs. Harker that it was time to leave.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118438,\n            \"\\u201d When I went to the station to meet Van Helsing I left the boys behind me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118490,\n            \"Van Helsing stepped from the carriage with the eager nimbleness of a boy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118504,\n            \"He saw me at once, and rushed up to me, saying:-\\u201cAh, friend John, how goes all?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118592,\n            \"\\u201d As I drove to the house I told him of what had passed, and of how my own diary had come to be of some use through Mrs. Harker\\u2019s suggestion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118628,\n            \"at which the Professor interrupted me:-\\u201cAh, that wonderful Madam Mina!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118977,\n            \"\\u201d Then he fell into a silence that lasted till we entered my own gateway.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118993,\n            \"Before we went to prepare for dinner he said to Mrs. Harker:-\\u201cI am told, Madam Mina, by my friend John that you and your husband have put up in exact order all things that have been, up to this moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119287,\n            \"The Professor took away one copy to study after dinner, and before our meeting, which is fixed for nine o\\u2019clock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119395,\n            \"Professor Van Helsing took the head of the table, to which Dr. Seward motioned him as he came into the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119419,\n            \"He made me sit next to him on his right, and asked me to act as secretary;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119444,\n            \"Opposite us were Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, and Mr. Morris-Lord Godalming being next the Professor, and Dr. Seward in the centre.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119474,\n            \"The Professor said:-\\u201cI may, I suppose, take it that we are all acquainted with the facts that are in these papers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119502,\n            \"\\u201d We all expressed assent, and he went on:-\\u201cThen it were, I think good that I tell you something of the kind of enemy with which we have to deal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119539,\n            \"I shall then make known to you something of the history of this man, which has been ascertained for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120222,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst he was speaking, Jonathan had taken my hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120307,\n            \"When the Professor had done speaking my husband looked in my eyes, and I in his;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120418,\n            \"I took his right hand, and Lord Godalming his left;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120476,\n            \"We resumed our places, and Dr. Van Helsing went on with a sort of cheerfulness which showed that the serious work had begun.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122150,\n            \"There was a little pause, and then the Professor went on:-\\u201cAnd now we must settle what we do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122367,\n            \"As he did so we heard Mr. Morris\\u2019 s voice without:-\\u201cSorry!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122558,\n            \"\\u201d Without saying any more he took his seat, and the Professor began to resume his statement:-\\u201cWe must trace each of these boxes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123180,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cTake me with you, friend John,\\u201dsaid the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123455,\n            \"and, besides, there was a certain dignity in the man\\u2019s manner, so much of the habit of equality, that I at once made the introduction: \\u201cLord Godalming;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123567,\n            \"and in his youth was, I have heard, the inventor of a burnt rum punch, much patronised on Derby night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123662,\n            \"What shall any man say of his pleasure at meeting Van Helsing?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123725,\n            \"You, gentlemen, who by nationality, by heredity, or by the possession of natural gifts, are fitted to hold your respective places in the moving world, I take to witness that I am as sane as at least the majority of men who are in full possession of their liberties.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123781,\n            \"And I am sure that you, Dr. Seward, humanitarian and medico-jurist as well as scientist, will deem it a moral duty to deal with me as one to be considered as under exceptional circumstances.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124097,\n            \"\\u201d He looked at me keenly, and seeing the negative in my face, turned to the others, and scrutinised them closely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124145,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou have,\\u201dI said frankly, but at the same time, as I felt, brutally.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124193,\n            \"Let me ask for this concession-boon, privilege, what you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124230,\n            \"I am not at liberty to give you the whole of my reasons;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124244,\n            \"but you may, I assure you, take it from me that they are good ones, sound and unselfish, and spring from the highest sense of duty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124404,\n            \"He said to Renfield in a tone which did not surprise me at the time, but only when I thought of it afterwards-for it was as of one addressing an equal:-\\u201cCan you not tell frankly your real reason for wishing to be free to-night?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124458,\n            \"I will undertake that if you will satisfy even me-a stranger, without prejudice, and with the habit of keeping an open mind-Dr. Seward will give you, at his own risk and on his own responsibility, the privilege you seek.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124525,\n            \"The Professor went on:-\\u201cCome, sir, bethink yourself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124587,\n            \"If you will not help us in our effort to choose the wisest course, how can we perform the duty which you yourself put upon us?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124688,\n            \"I can only ask you to trust me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124853,\n            \"I glanced at Van Helsing, and saw my conviction reflected in his eyes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125392,\n            \"When I was leaving the room, last of our party, he said to me in a quiet, well-bred voice:-\\u201cYou will, I trust, Dr. Seward, do me the justice to bear in mind, later on, that I did what I could to convince you to-night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125695,\n            \"\\u201d Lord Godalming and I were silent, but Dr. Van Helsing added:-\\u201cFriend John, you know more of lunatics than I do, and I\\u2019m glad of it, for I fear that if it had been to me to decide I would before that last hysterical outburst have given him free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125756,\n            \"But we live and learn, and in our present task we must take no chance, as my friend Quincey would say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125787,\n            \"\\u201d Dr. Seward seemed to answer them both in a dreamy kind of way:-\\u201cI don\\u2019t know but that I agree with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126144,\n            \"When we got to the porch the Professor opened his bag and took out a lot of things, which he laid on the step, sorting them into four little groups, evidently one for each.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126182,\n            \"Then he spoke:-\\u201cMy friends, we are going into a terrible danger, and we need arms of many kinds.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126300,\n            \"Keep this near your heart \\\"-as he spoke he lifted a little silver crucifix and held it out to me, I being nearest to him-\\\" put these flowers round your neck \\\"-here he handed to me a wreath of withered garlic blossoms-\\\" for other enemies more mundane, this revolver and this knife;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126403,\n            \"\\u201d This was a portion of Sacred Wafer, which he put in an envelope and handed to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126541,\n            \"It was startlingly like the image conveyed to me in Dr. Seward\\u2019s diary of the opening of Miss Westenra\\u2019s tomb;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126647,\n            \"The Professor carefully tried the lock, lest we might not be able to open it from within should we be in a hurry making our exit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126935,\n            \"He turned to me and said:-\\u201cYou know this place, Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127361,\n            \"We made an accurate examination of the place, the Professor saying as we began:-\\u201cThe first thing is to see how many of the boxes are left;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127458,\n            \"Once I got a fright, for, seeing Lord Godalming suddenly turn and look out of the vaulted door into the dark passage beyond, I looked too, and for an instant my heart stood still.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127538,\n            \"It was only for a moment, for, as Lord Godalming said, \\u201cI thought I saw a face, but it was only the shadows,\\u201dand resumed his inquiry, I turned my lamp in the direction, and stepped into the passage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127710,\n            \"For a moment or two we stood appalled, all save Lord Godalming, who was seemingly prepared for such an emergency.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127733,\n            \"Rushing over to the great iron-bound oaken door, which Dr. Seward had described from the outside, and which I had seen myself, he turned the key in the lock, drew the huge bolts, and swung the door open.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128316,\n            \"\\u201cSo far,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cour night has been eminently successful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128332,\n            \"No harm has come to us such as I feared might be and yet we have ascertained how many boxes are missing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128355,\n            \"More than all do I rejoice that this, our first-and perhaps our most difficult and dangerous-step has been accomplished without the bringing thereinto our most sweet Madam Mina or troubling her waking or sleeping thoughts with sights and sounds and smells of horror which she might never forget.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129151,\n            \"- It was towards noon when I was awakened by the Professor walking into my room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129201,\n            \"After going over the adventure of the night he suddenly said:-\\u201cYour patient interests me much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129221,\n            \"May it be that with you I visit him this morning?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129233,\n            \"Or if that you are too occupy, I can go alone if it may be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129270,\n            \"\\u201d I had some work to do which pressed, so I told him that if he would go alone I would be glad, as then I should not have to keep him waiting;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129318,\n            \"Before the Professor left the room I cautioned him against getting any false impression from my patient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129336,\n            \"\\u201cBut,\\u201dhe answered, \\u201cI want him to talk of himself and of his delusion as to consuming live things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129361,\n            \"He said to Madam Mina, as I see in your diary of yesterday, that he had once had such a belief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129511,\n            \"Perhaps I may gain more knowledge out of the folly of this madman than I shall from the teaching of the most wise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129631,\n            \"I have seen him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129658,\n            \"When I entered his room he was sitting on a stool in the centre, with his elbows on his knees, and his face was the picture of sullen discontent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129690,\n            \"I spoke to him as cheerfully as I could, and with such a measure of respect as I could assume.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129718,\n            \"\\u201cDon\\u2019t you know me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129772,\n            \"\\u201d Not a word more would he say, but sat in his implacable sullenness as indifferent to me as though I had not been in the room at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129803,\n            \"Thus departed for this time my chance of much learning from this so clever lunatic;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129843,\n            \"Friend John, it does rejoice me unspeakable that she is no more to be pained, no more to be worried with our terrible things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132500,\n            \"He replied:-\\u201cWell, guv\\u2019nor, you\\u2019ve treated me wery\\u2019an\\u2019some \\\"-I had given him half a sovereign-\\\" an\\u2019I\\u2019ll tell yer all I know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132543,\n            \"I heard a man by the name of Bloxam say four nights ago in the\\u2019Are an\\u2019\\u2019 Ounds, in Pincher\\u2019s Alley, as\\u2019 ow he an\\u2019his mate\\u2019ad\\u2019ad a rare dusty job in a old\\u2019ouse at Purfect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132625,\n            \"\\u201d I asked if he could tell me where to find him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132765,\n            \"If you can give me a envelope with a stamp on it, and put yer address on it, I\\u2019ll find out where Sam is to be found and post it ye to-night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133468,\n            \"\\u201cI\\u2019m the depity,\\u201dhe answered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133824,\n            \"I asked him if he could tell me the number of the house in Piccadilly, to which he replied:-\\u201cWell, guv\\u2019nor, I forgits the number, but it was only a few doors from a big white church or somethink of the kind, not long built.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133959,\n            \"Curse me, but he was the strongest chap I ever struck, an\\u2019him a old feller, with a white moustache, one that thin you would think he couldn\\u2019t throw a shadder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134080,\n            \"He must\\u2019a\\u2019started off and got there afore me, for when I rung of the bell he kem an\\u2019opened the door\\u2019isself an\\u2019\\u2019 elped me to carry the boxes into the\\u2019all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134172,\n            \"\\u201d I interrupted him:-\\u201cWere the boxes left in the hall?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134208,\n            \"\\u201d I made one more attempt to further matters:-\\u201cYou didn\\u2019t have any key?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134411,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that with this description I could find the house, so, having paid my friend for his information, I started off for Piccadilly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135216,\n            \"I act on the part of Lord Godalming, who wishes to know something of the property which was, he understood, lately for sale.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135253,\n            \"He said:-\\u201cI would like to oblige you if I could, Mr. Harker, and especially would I like to oblige his lordship.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135282,\n            \"We once carried out a small matter of renting some chambers for him when he was the Honourable Arthur Holmwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135342,\n            \"It will be a pleasure if we can so far deviate from our rules as to give the required information to his lordship.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135732,\n            \"when I had finished Van Helsing said:-\\u201cThis has been a great day\\u2019s work, friend Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135844,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe got into the other,\\u201danswered Lord Godalming quickly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135962,\n            \"By-and-by he stopped and said, turning from one to another of us:-\\u201cQuincey\\u2019s head is level.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136024,\n            \"\\u201d As nothing could well be done before morning, and as it would be at least advisable to wait till Lord Godalming should hear from Mitchell\\u2019s, we decided not to take any active step before breakfast time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136245,\n            \"This morning, when I went to see him after his repulse of Van Helsing, his manner was that of a man commanding destiny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137072,\n            \"Van Helsing sits in my study poring over the record prepared by the Harkers;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137119,\n            \"I would have taken him with me to see the patient, only I thought that after his last repulse he might not care to go again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138477,\n            \"- I went after my round to Van Helsing and told him my suspicion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138695,\n            \"We beg, with regard to the desire of your Lordship, expressed by Mr. Harker on your behalf, to supply the following information concerning the sale and purchase of No.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139160,\n            \"The old physicians took account of things which their followers do not accept, and the Professor is searching for witch and demon cures which may be useful to us later.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139771,\n            \"\\u201d I said to him:-\\u201cGo to Dr. Van Helsing, and ask him to kindly come here at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139806,\n            \"\\u201d The man ran off, and within a few minutes the Professor, in his dressing gown and slippers, appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139851,\n            \"I think he recognised my thought in my eyes, for he said very quietly, manifestly for the ears of the attendant:-\\u201cAh, a sad accident!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139894,\n            \"I shall stay with you myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139908,\n            \"If you will remain I shall in a few minutes join you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139968,\n            \"for, almost before he looked at the patient, he whispered to me:-\\u201cSend the attendant away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140031,\n            \"You had better go your round, and Dr. Van Helsing will operate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140100,\n            \"The Professor thought a moment and said:-\\u201cWe must reduce the pressure and get back to normal conditions, as far as can be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140184,\n            \"I went over and opened it and found in the corridor without, Arthur and Quincey in pajamas and slippers: the former spoke:-\\u201cI heard your man call up Dr. Van Helsing and tell him of an accident.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140416,\n            \"\\u201cWe shall wait,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing, \\u201cjust long enough to fix the best spot for trephining, so that we may most quickly and perfectly remove the blood clot;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140961,\n            \"Then Van Helsing said in a quiet grave tone:-\\u201cTell us your dream, Mr. Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141407,\n            \"I heard the dogs bark behind our house, but not where He was!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141496,\n            \"but he was solid then-not a ghost, and his eyes were fierce like a man\\u2019s when angry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141663,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing nodded to him as he whispered to me unconsciously:-\\u201cThe Acherontia Aitetropos of the Sphinges-what you call the \\u2018 Death\\u2019s-head Moth \\u2019?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141888,\n            \"and I thought he seemed to be saying: \\u2018 All these lives will I give you, ay, and many more and greater, through countless ages, if you will fall down and worship me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141975,\n            \"\\u2019 The rats were all gone, but He slid into the room through the sash, though it was only open an inch wide-just as the Moon herself has often come in through the tiniest crack and has stood before me in all her size and splendour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142186,\n            \"He sneered at me, and his white face looked out of the mist with his red eyes gleaming, and he went on as though he owned the whole place, and I was no one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142260,\n            \"\\u201d The two men sitting on the bed stood up and came over, standing behind him so that he could not see them, but where they could hear better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142292,\n            \"They were both silent, but the Professor started and quivered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142403,\n            \"I like them with lots of blood in them, and hers had all seemed to have run out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142434,\n            \"but when she went away I began to think, and it made me mad to know that He had been taking the life out of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142563,\n            \"and I thought I was going to win, for I didn\\u2019t mean Him to take any more of her life, till I saw His eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142671,\n            \"\\u201cWe know the worst now,\\u201dhe said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142682,\n            \"\\u201cHe is here, and we know his purpose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142773,\n            \"The Professor had his ready, and as we met in the corridor he pointed to them significantly as he said:-\\u201cThey never leave me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142892,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe must,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing grimly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142937,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing said solemnly, \\u201cYou are always right;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142980,\n            \"Friend John, when I turn the handle, if the door does not open, do you put your shoulder down and shove;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143005,\n            \"and you too, my friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143176,\n            \"His face was turned from us, but the instant we saw we all recognised the Count-in every way, even to the scar on his forehead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143535,\n            \"Van Helsing, Art, and I moved forward to Mrs. Harker, who by this time had drawn her breath and with it had given a scream so wild, so ear-piercing, so despairing that it seems to me now that it will ring in my ears till my dying day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143696,\n            \"Van Helsing stepped forward and drew the coverlet gently over her body, whilst Art, after looking at her face for an instant despairingly, ran out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143728,\n            \"Van Helsing whispered to me:-\\u201cJonathan is in a stupor such as we know the Vampire can produce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143772,\n            \"\\u201d He dipped the end of a towel in cold water and with it began to flick him on the face, his wife all the while holding her face between her hands and sobbing in a way that was heart-breaking to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143939,\n            \"His wife was aroused by the quick movement, and turned to him with her arms stretched out, as though to embrace him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144139,\n            \"\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, you love Mina, I know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144291,\n            \"Van Helsing and I tried to calm them both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144822,\n            \"so on nodding acquiescence to him he asked them what they had seen or done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145344,\n            \"then Van Helsing said, placing his hand very tenderly on Mrs. Harker\\u2019s head:-\\u201cAnd now, Madam Mina-poor, dear, dear Madam Mina-tell us exactly what happened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145384,\n            \"God knows that I do not want that you be pained;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145491,\n            \"Then she raised her head proudly, and held out one hand to Van Helsing who took it in his, and, after stooping and kissing it reverently, held it fast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146923,\n            \"for Dr. Van Helsing and Dr. Seward are agreed that if we do not eat we cannot work our best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147094,\n            \"When Dr. Van Helsing and Dr. Seward had come back from seeing poor Renfield, we went gravely into what was to be done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147121,\n            \"First, Dr. Seward told us that when he and Dr. Van Helsing had gone down to the room below they had found Renfield lying on the floor, all in a heap.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147345,\n            \"Dr. Seward said to us, when we were alone, that he did not wish to go into the matter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147586,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing was looking at her fixedly as she spoke, and said, suddenly but quietly:-\\u201cBut dear Madam Mina, are you not afraid;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147805,\n            \"but now he rose and came close to her and put his hand on her head as he said solemnly: \\u201cMy child, there is such an one if it were for your good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147842,\n            \"For myself I could hold it in my account with God to find such an euthanasia for you, even at this moment if it were best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147876,\n            \"But my child--\\u201dFor a moment he seemed choked, and a great sob rose in his throat;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147898,\n            \"he gulped it down and went on:-\\u201cThere are here some who would stand between you and death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148274,\n            \"As usual Van Helsing had thought ahead of everyone else, and was prepared with an exact ordering of our work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148296,\n            \"\\u201cIt is perhaps well,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cthat at our meeting after our visit to Carfax we decided not to do anything with the earth-boxes that lay there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148862,\n            \"\\u201d The Professor did not move, but simply said:-\\u201cAnd how are we to get into that house in Piccadilly?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149132,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd your police, they would interfere, would they not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149162,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThen,\\u201dhe looked at me as keenly as he spoke, \\u201call that is in doubt is the conscience of the employer, and the belief of your policemen as to whether or no that employer has a good conscience or a bad one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149579,\n            \"Van Helsing went on:-\\u201cWhen once within that house we may find more clues;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149646,\n            \"\\u201cI shall wire to my people to have horses and carriages where they will be most convenient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149695,\n            \"but don\\u2019t you think that one of your snappy carriages with its heraldic adornments in a byway of Walworth or Mile End would attract too much attention for our purposes?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150490,\n            \"Van Helsing had not intended to recall her frightful experience.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150501,\n            \"He had simply lost sight of her and her part in the affair in his intellectual effort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150519,\n            \"When it struck him what he said, he was horrified at his thoughtlessness and tried to comfort her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150539,\n            \"\\u201cOh, Madam Mina,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cdear, dear Madam Mina, alas!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150558,\n            \"that I of all who so reverence you should have said anything so forgetful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150599,\n            \"\\u201d He bent low beside her as he spoke;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150609,\n            \"she took his hand, and looking at him through her tears, said hoarsely:-\\u201cNo, I shall not forget, for it is well that I remember;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150642,\n            \"and with it I have so much in memory of you that is sweet, that I take it all together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150719,\n            \"When it was over, Van Helsing stood up and said:-\\u201cNow, my dear friends, we go forth to our terrible enterprise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150777,\n            \"\\u201d We all assured him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150820,\n            \"But before we go let me see you armed against personal attack.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150833,\n            \"I have myself, since you came down, prepared your chamber by the placing of things of which we know, so that He may not enter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150862,\n            \"Now let me guard yourself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150868,\n            \"On your forehead I touch this piece of Sacred Wafer in the name of the Father, the Son, and--\\u201dThere was a fearful scream which almost froze our hearts to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150905,\n            \"As he had placed the Wafer on Mina\\u2019s forehead, it had seared it-had burned into the flesh as though it had been a piece of white-hot metal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151134,\n            \"so gravely that I could not help feeling that he was in some way inspired, and was stating things outside himself:-\\u201cIt may be that you may have to bear that mark till God himself see fit, as He most surely shall, on the Judgment Day, to redress all wrongs of the earth and of His children that He has placed thereon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151368,\n            \"Mina and I both felt so, and simultaneously we each took one of the old man\\u2019s hands and bent over and kissed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151674,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing said to us solemnly as we stood before them:-\\u201cAnd now, my friends, we have a duty here to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152287,\n            \"\\u201d said Van Helsing, so we said no more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154347,\n            \"By my clock it is one hour and already, if all be well, friend Arthur and Quincey are on their way to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154407,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst he was speaking we were startled by a knock at the hall door, the double postman\\u2019s knock of the telegraph boy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154434,\n            \"We all moved out to the hall with one impulse, and Van Helsing, holding up his hand to us to keep silence, stepped to the door and opened it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154536,\n            \"\\u201d There was a pause, broken by Jonathan Harker\\u2019s voice:-\\u201cNow, God be thanked, we shall soon meet!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154563,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing turned to him quickly and said:-\\u201cGod will act in His own way and time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154684,\n            \"But God is merciful and just, and knows your pain and your devotion to that dear Madam Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154704,\n            \"Think you, how her pain would be doubled, did she but hear your wild words.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154853,\n            \"It was just an ordinary knock, such as is given hourly by thousands of gentlemen, but it made the Professor\\u2019s heart and mine beat loudly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155244,\n            \"Believe me, my friends, we shall not have long to wait now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155293,\n            \"\\u201d He held up a warning hand as he spoke, for we all could hear a key softly inserted in the lock of the hall door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155394,\n            \"With a swift glance around the room, he at once laid out our plan of attack, and, without speaking a word, with a gesture, placed us each in position.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155429,\n            \"Van Helsing, Harker, and I were just behind the door, so that when it was opened the Professor could guard it whilst we two stepped between the incomer and the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157639,\n            \"Van Helsing beckoned to us and we stole out of the room, leaving the two loving hearts alone with their God.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157662,\n            \"Before they retired the Professor fixed up the room against any coming of the Vampire, and assured Mrs. Harker that she might rest in peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157733,\n            \"Van Helsing had placed at hand a bell which either of them was to sound in case of any emergency.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158501,\n            \"She said to me hurriedly:-\\u201cGo, call the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158515,\n            \"I want to see him at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158554,\n            \"He must hypnotise me before the dawn, and then I shall be able to speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158628,\n            \"\\u201cbut Mina wants to see Dr. Van Helsing at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158641,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI will go,\\u201dhe said, and hurried into the Professor\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158660,\n            \"In two or three minutes later Van Helsing was in the room in his dressing-gown, and Mr. Morris and Lord Godalming were with Dr. Seward at the door asking questions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158696,\n            \"When the Professor saw Mina smile-a positive smile ousted the anxiety of his face;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158713,\n            \"he rubbed his hands as he said:-\\u201cOh, my dear Madam Mina, this is indeed a change.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158760,\n            \"\\u201d Then turning to her, he said, cheerfully: \\u201cAnd what am I do for you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158780,\n            \"For at this hour you do not want me for nothings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158792,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI want you to hypnotise me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158834,\n            \"\\u201d Without a word he motioned her to sit up in bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158847,\n            \"Looking fixedly at her, he commenced to make passes in front of her, from over the top of her head downward, with each hand in turn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158877,\n            \"Mina gazed at him fixedly for a few minutes, during which my own heart beat like a trip hammer, for I felt that some crisis was at hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159050,\n            \"The stillness was broken by Van Helsing\\u2019s voice speaking in a low level tone which would not break the current of her thoughts:-\\u201cWhere are you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159116,\n            \"Mina sat rigid, and the Professor stood staring at her fixedly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159144,\n            \"without taking his eyes from Mina\\u2019s face, Dr. Van Helsing motioned me to pull up the blind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159196,\n            \"On the instant the Professor spoke again:-\\u201cWhere are you now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159471,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing placed his hands on Mina\\u2019s shoulders, and laid her head down softly on her pillow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159563,\n            \"The Professor repeated the conversation, and she said:-\\u201cThen there is not a moment to lose: it may not be yet too late!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159592,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Morris and Lord Godalming started for the door but the Professor\\u2019s calm voice called them back:-\\u201cStay, my friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159994,\n            \"\\u201d Mina looked at him appealingly as she asked:-\\u201cBut why need we seek him further, when he is gone away from us?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160022,\n            \"\\u201d He took her hand and patted it as he replied:-\\u201cAsk me nothings as yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160042,\n            \"When we have breakfast, then I answer all questions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160053,\n            \"\\u201d He would say no more, and we separated to dress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160073,\n            \"He looked at her gravely for a minute and then said sorrowfully:-\\u201cBecause my dear, dear Madam Mina, now more than ever must we find him even if we have to follow him to the jaws of Hell!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160130,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBecause,\\u201dhe answered solemnly, \\u201che can live for centuries, and you are but mortal woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160153,\n            \"Time is now to be dreaded-since once he put that mark upon your throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160922,\n            \"It is better to wait till we see the Professor and the others after their investigations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160986,\n            \"Present: Professor Van Helsing, Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, Mr. Quincey Morris, Jonathan Harker, Mina Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161302,\n            \"and when Quincey give him something from his pocket which crackle as he roll it up, and put it in a so small bag which he have hid deep in his clothing, he still better fellow and humble servant to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161346,\n            \"He come with us, and ask many men who are rough and hot;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161796,\n            \"Final the captain, more red than ever, and in more tongues tell him that he doesn\\u2019t want no Frenchmen-with bloom upon them and also with blood-in his ship-with blood on her also.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161863,\n            \"\\u201cNo one knew where he went \\u2018 or bloomin\\u2019well cared,\\u2019as they said, for they had something else to think of-well with blood again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162111,\n            \"My friends of the thirst and the language that was of bloom and blood laughed, as they told how the captain\\u2019s swears exceeded even his usual polyglot, and was more than ever full of picturesque, when on questioning other mariners who were on movement up and down on the river that hour, he found that few of them had seen any of fog at all, except where it lay round the wharf.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162409,\n            \"and so our merchant friend will have done his part.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162420,\n            \"When he ask if there be any wrong, for that so, he can telegraph and have inquiry made at Varna, we say \\u2018 no \\u2019;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162504,\n            \"He replied: \\u201cWe have the best proof of that: your own evidence, when in the hypnotic trance this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162528,\n            \"\\u201d I asked him again if it were really necessary that they should pursue the Count, for oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162577,\n            \"As he went on, however, he grew more angry and more forceful, till in the end we could not but see wherein was at least some of that personal dominance which made him so long a master amongst men:-\\u201cYes, it is necessary-necessary-necessary!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162722,\n            \"I have told them how the measure of leaving his own barren land-barren of peoples-and coming to a new land where life of man teems till they are like the multitude of standing corn, was the work of centuries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164270,\n            \"I have mentioned this to Van Helsing, and he and I are to talk it over when we are alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164311,\n            \"The Count had his own purposes when he gave her what Van Helsing called \\u201cthe Vampire\\u2019s baptism of blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164559,\n            \"he went on:-\\u201cMadam Mina, our poor, dear Madam Mina is changing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164592,\n            \"Van Helsing continued:-\\u201cWith the sad experience of Miss Lucy, we must this time be warned before things go too far.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164641,\n            \"I can see the characteristics of the vampire coming in her face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164812,\n            \"he went on:-\\u201cThen, what we must do is to prevent this;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164873,\n            \"When to-day we meet, I must tell her that for reason which we will not to speak she must not more be of our council, but be simply guarded by us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164909,\n            \"\\u201d He wiped his forehead, which had broken out in profuse perspiration at the thought of the pain which he might have to inflict upon the poor soul already so tortured.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165038,\n            \"- At the very outset of our meeting a great personal relief was experienced by both Van Helsing and myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165101,\n            \"The Professor and I looked at each other for an instant, and somehow we both seemed relieved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165194,\n            \"Van Helsing roughly put the facts before us first:-\\u201cThe Czarina Catherine left the Thames yesterday morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165403,\n            \"I propose that we add Winchesters to our armament.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165432,\n            \"Do you remember, Art, when we had the pack after us at Tobolsk?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165518,\n            \"and as I think that Varna is not familiar to any of us, why not go there more soon?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165583,\n            \"\\u201d said Harker interrogatively, looking from one to another of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165600,\n            \"\\u201d answered the Professor quickly, \\u201cyou must remain to take care of your so sweet wife!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165619,\n            \"\\u201d Harker was silent for awhile and then said in a hollow voice:-\\u201cLet us talk of that part of it in the morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165647,\n            \"I want to consult with Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165654,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that now was the time for Van Helsing to warn him not to disclose our plans to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166073,\n            \"You can ask Dr. Van Helsing if I am not right;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166381,\n            \"Mina woke me early, about the same time as yesterday, and asked me to bring Dr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166438,\n            \"His door was ajar, so that he could hear the opening of the door of our room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166462,\n            \"as he passed into the room, he asked Mina if the others might come, too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166496,\n            \"You can tell them just as well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166504,\n            \"I must go with you on your journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166643,\n            \"I can tell you now, whilst the sun is coming up;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166822,\n            \"\\u201d Dr. Van Helsing said very gravely:-\\u201cMadam Mina, you are, as always, most wise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166864,\n            \"\\u201d When he had spoken, Mina\\u2019s long spell of silence made me look at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166925,\n            \"We went to his room, and within a minute Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, and Mr. Morris were with us also.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167467,\n            \"I shall have all tickets and so forth for our journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168439,\n            \"perhaps he guessed better than any of us what was coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168902,\n            \"Then her husband turned to her wan-eyed and with a greenish pallor which subdued the snowy whiteness of his hair, and asked:-\\u201cAnd must I, too, make such a promise, oh, my wife?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168946,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou too, my dearest,\\u201dshe said, with infinite yearning of pity in her voice and eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169104,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing, I have not forgotten your mercy in poor Lucy\\u2019s case to him who loved \\\"-she stopped with a flying blush, and changed her phrase-\\\" to him who had best right to give her peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169151,\n            \"If that time shall come again, I look to you to make it a happy memory of my husband\\u2019s life that it was his loving hand which set me free from the awful thrall upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169964,\n            \"and it has become a habit for Van Helsing to hypnotise her at such times.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170018,\n            \"He seems to have power at these particular moments to simply will, and her thoughts obey him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170037,\n            \"He always asks her what she can see and hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170276,\n            \"Van Helsing says that our chance will be to get on the boat between sunrise and sunset.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170596,\n            \"Godalming told the shippers that he fancied that the box sent aboard might contain something stolen from a friend of his, and got a half consent that he might open it at his own risk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170633,\n            \"The owner gave him a paper telling the Captain to give him every facility in doing whatever he chose on board the ship, and also a similar authorisation to his agent at Varna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170668,\n            \"We have seen the agent, who was much impressed with Godalming\\u2019s kindly manner to him, and we are all satisfied that whatever he can do to aid our wishes will be done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170745,\n            \"Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170955,\n            \"Rufus Smith, Lloyd\\u2019s, London, to Lord Godalming, care of H.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171027,\n            \"We were all wild with excitement yesterday when Godalming got his telegram from Lloyd\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171157,\n            \"The lethargy grows upon her, and though she seems strong and well, and is getting back some of her colour, Van Helsing and I are not satisfied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171207,\n            \"It would break poor Harker\\u2019s heart-certainly his nerve-if he knew that we had even a suspicion on the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171233,\n            \"Van Helsing examines, he tells me, her teeth very carefully, whilst she is in the hypnotic condition, for he says that so long as they do not begin to sharpen there is no active danger of a change in her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171466,\n            \"We men are all in a fever of excitement, except Harker, who is calm;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171545,\n            \"Van Helsing and I were a little alarmed about Mrs. Harker to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171930,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing is terribly anxious, and told me just now that he fears the Count is escaping us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171951,\n            \"He added significantly:-\\u201cI did not like that lethargy of Madam Mina\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172250,\n            \"Van Helsing raised his hand over his head for a moment, as though in remonstrance with the Almighty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172678,\n            \"You, friend Arthur, go to the train and get the tickets and arrange that all be ready for us to go in the morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172950,\n            \"When the three men had gone out to their tasks Van Helsing asked Mrs. Harker to look up the copy of the diaries and find him the part of Harker\\u2019s journal at the Castle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172995,\n            \"when the door was shut upon her he said to me:-\\u201cWe mean the same!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173044,\n            \"Do you know why I asked her to get the manuscript?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173124,\n            \"In the moment when Madam Mina said those words that arrest both our understanding, an inspiration came to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174306,\n            \"Oh, my dear, I see that your eyes are opened, and that to you the lightning flash show all the leagues,\\u201dfor Mrs. Harker began to clap her hands and her eyes sparkled.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174692,\n            \"I do in any case, and shall tell you if you are right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175122,\n            \"At such times you go by my volition and not by his;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175419,\n            \"and after a longer and more serious effort on the part of Van Helsing than has been usually necessary, she sank into the trance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175741,\n            \"when she had gone Van Helsing said:-\\u201cYou see, my friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176046,\n            \"at last, in obedience to his will she made reply:-\\u201cAll is dark.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176431,\n            \"She said no more, even in answer to the Professor\\u2019s imperative questioning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176662,\n            \"Speak, I command you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176677,\n            \"At the same time there was despair in his eyes, for the risen sun was reddening even Mrs. Harker\\u2019s pale face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176703,\n            \"She opened her eyes, and we all started as she said, sweetly and seemingly with the utmost unconcern:-\\u201cOh, Professor, why ask me to do what you know I can\\u2019t?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176788,\n            \"I know nothing, only that I was lying here, half asleep, and heard you say go on!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176809,\n            \"speak, I command you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176815,\n            \"\\u2019 It seemed so funny to hear you order me about, as if I were a bad child!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176835,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cOh, Madam Mina,\\u201dhe said, sadly, \\u201cit is proof, if proof be needed, of how I love and honour you, when a word for your good, spoken more earnest than ever, can seem so strange because it is to order her whom I am proud to obey!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176925,\n            \"- Mr. Morris took me to the hotel where our rooms had been ordered by telegraph, he being the one who could best be spared, since he does not speak any foreign language.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176962,\n            \"The forces were distributed much as they had been at Varna, except that Lord Godalming went to the Vice-Consul, as his rank might serve as an immediate guarantee of some sort to the official, we being in extreme hurry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177007,\n            \"Jonathan and the two doctors went to the shipping agent to learn particulars of the arrival of the Czarina Catherine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177117,\n            \"They had received a wire from London, in answer to Lord Godalming\\u2019s telegraphed request, asking us to show them any civility in their power.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177251,\n            \"It\\u2019s no canny to run frae London to the Black Sea wi\\u2019a wind ahint ye, as though the Deil himself were blawin\\u2019on yer sail for his ain purpose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177403,\n            \"but whiles, I thocht that if the Deil was minded to get us into the Black Sea quick, he was like to do it whether we would or no.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177530,\n            \"\\u201d The skipper was not displeased with the compliment, and went on:-\\u201cWhen we got past the Bosphorus the men began to grumble;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177558,\n            \"some o\\u2019them, the Roumanians, came and asked me to heave overboard a big box which had been put on board by a queer lookin\\u2019old man just before we had started frae London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177996,\n            \"He had his papers a\\u2019reet, an\\u2019glad I was to be rid o\\u2019the dam\\u2019thing, for I was beginnin\\u2019masel\\u2019to feel uneasy at it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178079,\n            \"\\u201cI\\u2019ll be tellin\\u2019ye quick!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178118,\n            \"We found out that this was all the Captain knew;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178136,\n            \"We found Hildesheim in his office, a Hebrew of rather the Adelphi Theatre type, with a nose like a sheep, and a fez.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178163,\n            \"His arguments were pointed with specie-we doing the punctuation-and with a little bargaining he told us what he knew.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180190,\n            \"The others kept shaking me by both hands, and Dr. Van Helsing said:-\\u201cOur dear Madam Mina is once more our teacher.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180786,\n            \"she will be my care, if I may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180849,\n            \"And I can die, if need be, as well as younger men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181060,\n            \"\\u201d Here Jonathan interrupted him hotly:-\\u201cDo you mean to say, Professor Van Helsing, that you would bring Mina, in her sad case and tainted as she is with that devil\\u2019s illness, right into the jaws of his death-trap?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181248,\n            \"The Professor\\u2019s voice, as he spoke in clear, sweet tones, which seemed to vibrate in the air, calmed us all:-\\u201cOh, my friend, it is because I would save Madam Mina from that awful place that I would go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181299,\n            \"God forbid that I should take her into that place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181498,\n            \"If it were that any one went into that place to stay, it is I who would have to go to keep them company.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181524,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo as you will,\\u201dsaid Jonathan, with a sob that shook him all over, \\u201cwe are in the hands of God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181765,\n            \"Professor Van Helsing and I are to leave by the 11: 40 train to-night for Veresti, where we are to get a carriage to drive to the Borgo Pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181837,\n            \"The Professor knows something of a great many languages, so we shall get on all right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181972,\n            \"the Professor is looking at you keenly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182040,\n            \"He is an experienced hand at the work, as he has had for years a launch of his own on the Thames, and another on the Norfolk Broads.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182851,\n            \"God bless him for all his goodness to poor dear Mina and me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182982,\n            \"I wonder where Mina is now, and Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183373,\n            \"Godalming is an amateur fitter himself, and evidently it was he who put the launch in trim again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183528,\n            \"He says that he will later on try to buy additional horses, so that we may be able to change them on the way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183703,\n            \"The Professor encourages her, and whispers to me that it may be a week before we can get any good food again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183975,\n            \"he tells the farmers that he is hurrying to Bistritz, and pays them well to make the exchange of horses.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184279,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing is sleeping, Poor dear, he looks very tired and old and grey, but his mouth is set as firmly as a conqueror\\u2019s;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184321,\n            \"When we have well started I must make him rest whilst I drive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184582,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing says that by morning we shall reach the Borgo Pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184597,\n            \"The houses are very few here now, and the Professor says that the last horse we got will have to go on with us, as we may not be able to change.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184632,\n            \"He got two in addition to the two we changed, so that now we have a rude four-in-hand.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 6]\": [\n        [\n            113588,\n            \"- After lunch Harker and his wife went back to their own room, and as I passed a while ago I heard the click of the typewriter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113623,\n            \"Mrs. Harker says that they are knitting together in chronological order every scrap of evidence they have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113666,\n            \"He is now reading his wife\\u2019s typescript of my diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113847,\n            \"What a good thing that Mrs. Harker put my cylinders into type!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113964,\n            \"I believe that, had I not had the chat with Harker and read the letters and the dates of his outbursts, I should have been prepared to sign for him after a brief time of observation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117056,\n            \"- I got home at five o\\u2019clock, and found that Godalming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had made and arranged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117124,\n            \"Mrs. Harker gave us a cup of tea, and I can honestly say that, for the first time since I have lived in it, this old house seemed like home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117159,\n            \"When we had finished, Mrs. Harker said:-\\u201cDr. Seward, may I ask a favour?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117198,\n            \"What you have said of him in your diary interests me so much!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117212,\n            \"\\u201d She looked so appealing and so pretty that I could not refuse her, and there was no possible reason why I should;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117237,\n            \"so I took her with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117641,\n            \"I have a husband of my own, to whom I was married before I ever saw Dr. Seward, or he me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117681,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy husband and I are staying on a visit with Dr. Seward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117711,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that this style of conversation might not be pleasant to Mrs. Harker, any more than it was to me, so I joined in:-\\u201cHow did you know I wanted to marry any one?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117754,\n            \"\\u201d His reply was simply contemptuous, given in a pause in which he turned his eyes from Mrs. Harker to me, instantly turning them back again:-\\u201cWhat an asinine question!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117791,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI don\\u2019t see that at all, Mr. Renfield,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Harker, at once championing me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117817,\n            \"He replied to her with as much courtesy and respect as he had shown contempt to me:-\\u201cYou will, of course, understand, Mrs. Harker, that when a man is so loved and honoured as our host is, everything regarding him is of interest in our little community.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117993,\n            \"I wonder if it was Mrs. Harker\\u2019s presence which had touched some chord in his memory.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118047,\n            \"and, seeing that he was seemingly quite reasonable, she ventured, looking at me questioningly as she began, to lead him to his favourite topic.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118334,\n            \"Looking at my watch, I saw that I should go to the station to meet Van Helsing, so I told Mrs. Harker that it was time to leave.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118366,\n            \"She came at once, after saying pleasantly to Mr. Renfield: \\u201cGood-bye, and I hope I may see you often, under auspices pleasanter to yourself,\\u201dto which, to my astonishment, he replied:-\\u201cGood-bye, my dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118592,\n            \"\\u201d As I drove to the house I told him of what had passed, and of how my own diary had come to be of some use through Mrs. Harker\\u2019s suggestion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118993,\n            \"Before we went to prepare for dinner he said to Mrs. Harker:-\\u201cI am told, Madam Mina, by my friend John that you and your husband have put up in exact order all things that have been, up to this moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119223,\n            \"It can but make your husband love you the more, and all us, your friends, more honour you-as well as more esteem and love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129421,\n            \"\\u201cWhen our sane and learned lunatic made that very statement of how he used to consume life, his mouth was actually nauseous with the flies and spiders which he had eaten just before Mrs. Harker entered the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138695,\n            \"We beg, with regard to the desire of your Lordship, expressed by Mr. Harker on your behalf, to supply the following information concerning the sale and purchase of No.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138879,\n            \"After dinner, when we had all gathered round the fire in the study-Mrs. Harker having gone to bed-we discussed the attempts and discoveries of the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139287,\n            \"If we could only get some hint as to what passed in his mind, between the time of my argument with him to-day and his resumption of fly-catching, it might afford us a valuable clue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139359,\n            \"The attendant came bursting into my room and told me that Renfield had somehow met with some accident.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139573,\n            \"The attendant who was kneeling beside the body said to me as we turned him over:-\\u201cI think, sir, his back is broken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139771,\n            \"\\u201d I said to him:-\\u201cGo to Dr. Van Helsing, and ask him to kindly come here at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139851,\n            \"I think he recognised my thought in my eyes, for he said very quietly, manifestly for the ears of the attendant:-\\u201cAh, a sad accident!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139968,\n            \"for, almost before he looked at the patient, he whispered to me:-\\u201cSend the attendant away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140005,\n            \"\\u201d So I said:-\\u201cI think that will do now, Simmons.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140184,\n            \"I went over and opened it and found in the corridor without, Arthur and Quincey in pajamas and slippers: the former spoke:-\\u201cI heard your man call up Dr. Van Helsing and tell him of an accident.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140303,\n            \"\\u201d I nodded, and held the door open till they had entered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140363,\n            \"\\u201d I told him briefly, and added that we expected he would recover consciousness after the operation-for a short time, at all events.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140521,\n            \"but the conviction of what was coming was on me, as I have read of men who have heard the death-watch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140640,\n            \"I looked at my companions, one after another, and saw from their flushed faces and damp brows that they were enduring equal torture.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141407,\n            \"I heard the dogs bark behind our house, but not where He was!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141663,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing nodded to him as he whispered to me unconsciously:-\\u201cThe Acherontia Aitetropos of the Sphinges-what you call the \\u2018 Death\\u2019s-head Moth \\u2019?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141888,\n            \"and I thought he seemed to be saying: \\u2018 All these lives will I give you, ay, and many more and greater, through countless ages, if you will fall down and worship me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141975,\n            \"\\u2019 The rats were all gone, but He slid into the room through the sash, though it was only open an inch wide-just as the Moon herself has often come in through the tiniest crack and has stood before me in all her size and splendour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142186,\n            \"He sneered at me, and his white face looked out of the mist with his red eyes gleaming, and he went on as though he owned the whole place, and I was no one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142245,\n            \"I thought that, somehow, Mrs. Harker had come into the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142434,\n            \"but when she went away I began to think, and it made me mad to know that He had been taking the life out of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142462,\n            \"\\u201d I could feel that the rest quivered, as I did, but we remained otherwise still.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142508,\n            \"I had heard that madmen have unnatural strength;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142517,\n            \"and as I knew I was a madman-at times anyhow-I resolved to use my power.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142563,\n            \"and I thought I was going to win, for I didn\\u2019t mean Him to take any more of her life, till I saw His eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143309,\n            \"As we burst into the room, the Count turned his face, and the hellish look that I had heard described seemed to leap into it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143535,\n            \"Van Helsing, Art, and I moved forward to Mrs. Harker, who by this time had drawn her breath and with it had given a scream so wild, so ear-piercing, so despairing that it seems to me now that it will ring in my ears till my dying day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143728,\n            \"Van Helsing whispered to me:-\\u201cJonathan is in a stupor such as we know the Vampire can produce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144139,\n            \"\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, you love Mina, I know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144291,\n            \"Van Helsing and I tried to calm them both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144601,\n            \"After a while her sobs became less frequent and more faint, and then he said to me, speaking with a studied calmness which I felt tried his nervous power to the utmost:-\\u201cAnd now, Dr. Seward, tell me all about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144682,\n            \"but his nostrils twitched and his eyes blazed as I told how the ruthless hands of the Count had held his wife in that terrible and horrid position, with her mouth to the open wound in his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144789,\n            \"I understood him to mean if we were to take advantage of their coming to divert if possible the thoughts of the unhappy husband and wife from each other and from themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145316,\n            \"For a space of perhaps a couple of minutes there was silence, and I could fancy that I could hear the sound of our hearts beating;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145454,\n            \"\\u201d The poor, dear lady shivered, and I could see the tension of her nerves as she clasped her husband closer to her and bent her head lower and lower still on his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145546,\n            \"After a pause in which she was evidently ordering her thoughts, she began:-\\u201cI took the sleeping draught which you had so kindly given me, but for a long time it did not act.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145586,\n            \"I seemed to become more wakeful, and myriads of horrible fancies began to crowd in upon my mind-all of them connected with death, and vampires;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145777,\n            \"But I forget now if you know of this;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145787,\n            \"you will find it in my diary which I shall show you later.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145928,\n            \"I knew him at once from the description of the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146182,\n            \"I suppose it is a part of the horrible curse that such is, when his touch is on his victim.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146204,\n            \"And oh, my God, my God, pity me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146231,\n            \"She clasped his hand harder, and looked at him pityingly, as if he were the injured one, and went on:-\\u201cI felt my strength fading away, and I was in a half swoon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146341,\n            \"With a great effort she recovered herself and went on:-\\u201cThen he spoke to me mockingly, \\u2018 And so you, like the others, would play your brains against mine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146997,\n            \"The teaching, big or little, could not have landed Mina or me anywhere worse than we are to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147028,\n            \"Poor Mina told me just now, with the tears running down her dear cheeks, that it is in trouble and trial that our faith is tested-that we must keep on trusting;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148062,\n            \"\\u201d The poor dear grew white as death, and shock and shivered, as I have seen a quicksand shake and shiver at the incoming of the tide.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148119,\n            \"so sorrowfully, as she held out her hand:-\\u201cI promise you, my dear friend, that if God will let me live, I shall strive to do so;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148208,\n            \"I told her that she was to have all the papers in the safe, and all the papers or diaries and phonographs we might hereafter use;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148583,\n            \"\\u201d Here I started up for I could not contain myself at the thought that the minutes and seconds so preciously laden with Mina\\u2019s life and happiness were flying from us, since whilst we talked action was impossible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148839,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThen let us come at once,\\u201dI cried, \\u201cwe are wasting the precious, precious time!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149111,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI should get a respectable locksmith, and set him to work to pick the lock for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149162,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThen,\\u201dhe looked at me as keenly as he spoke, \\u201call that is in doubt is the conscience of the employer, and the belief of your policemen as to whether or no that employer has a good conscience or a bad one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149272,\n            \"and if you do it as such things are rightly done, and at the time such things are rightly done, no one will interfere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149299,\n            \"I have read of a gentleman who owned a so fine house in London, and when he went for months of summer to Switzerland and lock up his house, some burglar came and broke window at back and got in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149547,\n            \"\\u201d I could not but see how right he was and the terrible despair of Mina\\u2019s face became relaxed a thought;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149809,\n            \"\\u201d Mina took a growing interest in everything and I was rejoiced to see that the exigency of affairs was helping her to forget for a time the terrible experience of the night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149871,\n            \"I did not mention this last, lest it should give her needless pain;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149886,\n            \"but it made my blood run cold in my veins to think of what had occurred with poor Lucy when the Count had sucked her blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150033,\n            \"As to the disposal of forces, it was suggested by the Professor that, after our visit to Carfax, we should all enter the house in Piccadilly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150063,\n            \"that the two doctors and I should remain there, whilst Lord Godalming and Quincey found the lairs at Walworth and Mile End and destroyed them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150090,\n            \"It was possible, if not likely, the Professor urged, that the Count might appear in Piccadilly during the day, and that if so we might be able to cope with him then and there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150143,\n            \"To this plan I strenuously objected, and so far as my going was concerned, for I said that I intended to stay and protect Mina, I thought that my mind was made up on the subject;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150183,\n            \"but Mina would not listen to my objection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150192,\n            \"She said that there might be some law matter in which I could be useful;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150255,\n            \"I had to give in, for Mina\\u2019s resolution was fixed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150350,\n            \"\\u201d So I started up crying out: \\u201cThen in God\\u2019s name let us come at once, for we are losing time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151080,\n            \"I had thrown myself beside her in an agony of helpless grief, and putting my arms around held her tight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151134,\n            \"so gravely that I could not help feeling that he was in some way inspired, and was stating things outside himself:-\\u201cIt may be that you may have to bear that mark till God himself see fit, as He most surely shall, on the Judgment Day, to redress all wrongs of the earth and of His children that He has placed thereon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151204,\n            \"And oh, Madam Mina, my dear, my dear, may we who love you be there to see, when that red scar, the sign of God\\u2019s knowledge of what has been, shall pass away, and leave your forehead as pure as the heart we know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151368,\n            \"Mina and I both felt so, and simultaneously we each took one of the old man\\u2019s hands and bent over and kissed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151468,\n            \"So I said farewell to Mina, a parting which neither of us shall forget to our dying day;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151493,\n            \"To one thing I have made up my mind: if we find out that Mina must be a vampire in the end, then she shall not go into that unknown and terrible land alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151674,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing said to us solemnly as we stood before them:-\\u201cAnd now, my friends, we have a duty here to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151810,\n            \"but we did not somehow seem to mind, for our attention was concentrated on the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151902,\n            \"When we closed the door behind us, the Professor said solemnly:-\\u201cSo much is already done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151987,\n            \"I looked eagerly, and in the window of my own room saw Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152002,\n            \"I waved my hand to her, and nodded to tell that our work there was successfully accomplished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152031,\n            \"The last I saw, she was waving her hand in farewell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152088,\n            \"- Just before we reached Fenchurch Street Lord Godalming said to me:-\\u201cQuincey and I will find a locksmith.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152111,\n            \"You had better not come with us in case there should be any difficulty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152146,\n            \"But you are a solicitor and the Incorporated Law Society might tell you that you should have known better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152166,\n            \"\\u201d I demurred as to my not sharing any danger even of odium, but he went on: \\u201cBesides, it will attract less attention if there are not too many of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152222,\n            \"You had better go with Jack and the Professor and stay in the Green Park, somewhere in sight of the house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152245,\n            \"and when you see the door opened and the smith has gone away, do you all come across.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152265,\n            \"We shall be on the lookout for you, and shall let you in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152329,\n            \"My heart beat as I saw the house on which so much of our hope was centred, looming up grim and silent in its deserted condition amongst its more lively and spruce-looking neighbours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153337,\n            \"The Professor tried to keep our minds active by using them all the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153629,\n            \"As I learned from the researches of my friend Arminus of Buda-Pesth, he was in life a most wonderful man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153913,\n            \"for had he dared, at the first, to attempt certain things he would long ago have been beyond our power.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154043,\n            \"How he has been making use of the zo\\u00f6phagous patient to effect his entry into friend John\\u2019s home;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154064,\n            \"for your Vampire, though in all afterwards he can come when and how he will, must at the first make entry only when asked thereto by an inmate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154324,\n            \"Is there not more at stake for us than for him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154336,\n            \"Then why we not be even more careful than him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154853,\n            \"It was just an ordinary knock, such as is given hourly by thousands of gentlemen, but it made the Professor\\u2019s heart and mine beat loudly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155343,\n            \"In all our hunting parties and adventures in different parts of the world, Quincey Morris had always been the one to arrange the plan of action, and Arthur and I had been accustomed to obey him implicitly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155429,\n            \"Van Helsing, Harker, and I were just behind the door, so that when it was opened the Professor could guard it whilst we two stepped between the incomer and the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155669,\n            \"It was a pity that we had not some better organised plan of attack, for even at the moment I wondered what we were to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155697,\n            \"I did not myself know whether our lethal weapons would avail us anything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155868,\n            \"and it was without surprise that I saw the monster cower back before a similar movement made spontaneously by each one of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156579,\n            \"\\u201d I could see that he spoke as bravely as he could to comfort Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156603,\n            \"now and again he gave a low groan which he could not suppress-he was thinking of his wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156624,\n            \"With sad hearts we came back to my house, where we found Mrs. Harker waiting us, with an appearance of cheerfulness which did honour to her bravery and unselfishness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156710,\n            \"\\u201d As she spoke, she took her husband\\u2019s grey head in her hands and kissed it-\\\" Lay your poor head here and rest it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156779,\n            \"We had a sort of perfunctory supper together, and I think it cheered us all up somewhat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156866,\n            \"and although she grew snowy white at times when danger had seemed to threaten her husband, and red at others when his devotion to her was manifested, she listened bravely and with calmness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156902,\n            \"When we came to the part where Harker had rushed at the Count so recklessly, she clung to her husband\\u2019s arm, and held it tight as though her clinging could protect him from any harm that might come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156970,\n            \"Then without letting go her husband\\u2019s hand she stood up amongst us and spoke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157246,\n            \"\\u201d As she spoke I could see her husband\\u2019s face darken and draw together, as though the passion in him were shrivelling his being to its core.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157295,\n            \"She did not flinch from the pain which I knew she must have suffered, but looked at him with eyes that were more appealing than ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157612,\n            \"Her husband flung himself on his knees beside her, and putting his arms round her, hid his face in the folds of her dress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157754,\n            \"When they had retired, Quincey, Godalming, and I arranged that we should sit up, dividing the night between us, and watch over the safety of the poor stricken lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157977,\n            \"This I know: that if ever there was a woman who was all perfection, that one is my poor wronged darling.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158001,\n            \"I love her a thousand times more for her sweet pity of last night, a pity that made my own hate of the monster seem despicable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158080,\n            \"I fear what her dreams might be like, with such terrible memories to ground them in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158098,\n            \"She has not been so calm, within my seeing, since the sunset.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158136,\n            \"I thought at the time that it was the softness of the red sunset on her face, but somehow now I think it has a deeper meaning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158212,\n            \"- I must have fallen asleep, for I was awaked by Mina, who was sitting up in bed, with a startled look on her face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158241,\n            \"I could see easily, for we did not leave the room in darkness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158256,\n            \"she had placed a warning hand over my mouth, and now she whispered in my ear:-\\u201cHush!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158363,\n            \"\\u201d His look and gesture forbade discussion, so I came back and told Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158379,\n            \"She sighed and positively a shadow of a smile stole over her poor, pale face as she put her arms round me and said softly:-\\u201cOh, thank God for good brave men!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158449,\n            \"- Once again during the night I was wakened by Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158501,\n            \"She said to me hurriedly:-\\u201cGo, call the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158589,\n            \"Dr. Seward was resting on the mattress, and, seeing me, he sprang to his feet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158877,\n            \"Mina gazed at him fixedly for a few minutes, during which my own heart beat like a trip hammer, for I felt that some crisis was at hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158976,\n            \"There was a far-away look in her eyes, and her voice had a sad dreaminess which was new to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159144,\n            \"without taking his eyes from Mina\\u2019s face, Dr. Van Helsing motioned me to pull up the blind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159166,\n            \"I did so, and the day seemed just upon us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159230,\n            \"I have heard her use the same tone when reading her shorthand notes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160170,\n            \"\\u201d I was just in time to catch her as she fell forward in a faint.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160216,\n            \"We shall go to make our search-if I can call it so, for it is not search but knowing, and we seek confirmation only.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160680,\n            \"- When I read to Mina, Van Helsing\\u2019s message in the phonograph, the poor girl brightened up considerably.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160726,\n            \"For my own part, now that his horrible danger is not face to face with us, it seems almost impossible to believe in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160788,\n            \"In the midst of my thought my eye fell on the red scar on my poor darling\\u2019s white forehead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160833,\n            \"Mina and I fear to be idle, so we have been over all the diaries again and again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160901,\n            \"I shall try to think as she does.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161566,\n            \"Then the thin man go and some one tell him where horse and cart can be hired.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161796,\n            \"Final the captain, more red than ever, and in more tongues tell him that he doesn\\u2019t want no Frenchmen-with bloom upon them and also with blood-in his ship-with blood on her also.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162043,\n            \"But the thin man did not be offend, and went down with the mate and saw where it was place, and came up and stood awhile on deck in fog.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162089,\n            \"Indeed they thought not of him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162111,\n            \"My friends of the thirst and the language that was of bloom and blood laughed, as they told how the captain\\u2019s swears exceeded even his usual polyglot, and was more than ever full of picturesque, when on questioning other mariners who were on movement up and down on the river that hour, he found that few of them had seen any of fog at all, except where it lay round the wharf.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162228,\n            \"\\u201cAnd so, my dear Madam Mina, it is that we have to rest for a time, for our enemy is on the sea, with the fog at his command, on his way to the Danube mouth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162504,\n            \"He replied: \\u201cWe have the best proof of that: your own evidence, when in the hypnotic trance this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162528,\n            \"\\u201d I asked him again if it were really necessary that they should pursue the Count, for oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162697,\n            \"you, my dear Madam Mina, will learn it in the phonograph of my friend John, or in that of your husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163035,\n            \"He have infect you-oh, forgive me, my dear, that I must say such;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163054,\n            \"but it is for good of you that I speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163296,\n            \"Your man-eater, as they of India call the tiger who has once tasted blood of the human, care no more for the other prey, but prowl unceasing till he get him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163372,\n            \"In his life, his living life, he go over the Turkey frontier and attack his enemy on his own ground;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163649,\n            \"Oh, if such an one was to come from God, and not the Devil, what a force for good might he not be in this old world of ours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163732,\n            \"It would be at once his sheath and his armour, and his weapons to destroy us, his enemies, who are willing to peril even our own souls for the safety of one we love-for the good of mankind, and for the honour and glory of God.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163961,\n            \"- We all rose early, and I think that sleep did much for each and all of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164047,\n            \"More than once as we sat around the table, my eyes opened in wonder whether the whole of the past days had not been a dream.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164075,\n            \"It was only when I caught sight of the red blotch on Mrs. Harker\\u2019s forehead that I was brought back to reality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164101,\n            \"Even now, when I am gravely revolving the matter, it is almost impossible to realise that the cause of all our trouble is still existent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164167,\n            \"We are to meet here in my study in half an hour and decide on our course of action.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164187,\n            \"I see only one immediate difficulty, I know it by instinct rather than reason: we shall all have to speak frankly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164211,\n            \"and yet I fear that in some mysterious way poor Mrs. Harker\\u2019s tongue is tied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164230,\n            \"I know that she forms conclusions of her own, and from all that has been I can guess how brilliant and how true they must be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164270,\n            \"I have mentioned this to Van Helsing, and he and I are to talk it over when we are alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164292,\n            \"I suppose it is some of that horrid poison which has got into her veins beginning to work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164368,\n            \"One thing I know: that if my instinct be true regarding poor Mrs. Harker\\u2019s silences, then there is a terrible difficulty-an unknown danger-in the work before us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164423,\n            \"for so I should in my thoughts dishonour a noble woman!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165038,\n            \"- At the very outset of our meeting a great personal relief was experienced by both Van Helsing and myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165101,\n            \"The Professor and I looked at each other for an instant, and somehow we both seemed relieved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165120,\n            \"For my own part, I thought that if Mrs. Harker realised the danger herself, it was much pain as well as much danger averted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165654,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that now was the time for Van Helsing to warn him not to disclose our plans to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165714,\n            \"- For some time after our meeting this morning I could not think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165749,\n            \"Mina\\u2019s determination not to take any part in the discussion set me thinking;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165765,\n            \"and as I could not argue the matter with her, I could only guess.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165871,\n            \"I sat watching Mina\\u2019s happy sleep, and came as near to being happy myself as I suppose I shall ever be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165927,\n            \"All at once Mina opened her eyes, and looking at me tenderly, said:-\\u201cJonathan, I want you to promise me something on your word of honour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165960,\n            \"A promise made to me, but made holily in God\\u2019s hearing, and not to be broken though I should go down on my knees and implore you with bitter tears.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165995,\n            \"Quick, you must make it to me at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166006,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMina,\\u201dI said, \\u201ca promise like that, I cannot make at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166035,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut, dear one,\\u201dshe said, with such spiritual intensity that her eyes were like pole stars, \\u201cit is I who wish it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166073,\n            \"You can ask Dr. Van Helsing if I am not right;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166119,\n            \"\\u201d I said, and for a moment she looked supremely happy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166132,\n            \"though to me all happiness for her was denied by the red scar on her forehead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166149,\n            \"She said:-\\u201cPromise me that you will not tell me anything of the plans formed for the campaign against the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166203,\n            \"I saw that she was in earnest, and said solemnly:-\\u201cI promise!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166220,\n            \"\\u201d and as I said it I felt that from that instant a door had been shut between us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166275,\n            \"as a result even I myself felt as if the pall of gloom which weighs us down were somewhat lifted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166346,\n            \"Perhaps her example may affect me as her gaiety did to-night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166381,\n            \"Mina woke me early, about the same time as yesterday, and asked me to bring Dr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166702,\n            \"\\u201d God saw the look that she turned on me as she spoke, and if there be indeed a Recording Angel that look is noted to her everlasting honour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166733,\n            \"I could only clasp her hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166797,\n            \"Besides, I may be of service, since you can hypnotise me and so learn that which even I myself do not know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166864,\n            \"\\u201d When he had spoken, Mina\\u2019s long spell of silence made me look at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166892,\n            \"she did not even wake when I had pulled up the blind and let in the sunlight which flooded the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167289,\n            \"My child, believe me none of us shall lag behind or pause from any fear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167531,\n            \"Mina if she survive is my sole heir.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167569,\n            \"Mina\\u2019s uneasiness calls my attention to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167579,\n            \"I am sure that there is something on her mind which the time of exact sunset will reveal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167640,\n            \"I write all these things in the diary since my darling must not hear them now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167674,\n            \"She is calling to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167722,\n            \"I think that none of us were surprised when we were asked to see Mrs. Harker a little before the time of sunset.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167901,\n            \"I put it down myself to her making a violent effort at the earliest instant she could do so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168052,\n            \"You are going to be so good to me as to take me with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168068,\n            \"I know that all that brave earnest men can do for a poor weak woman, whose soul perhaps is lost-no, no, not yet, but is at any rate at stake-you will do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168109,\n            \"But you must remember that I am not as you are.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168138,\n            \"which must destroy me, unless some relief comes to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168150,\n            \"Oh, my friends, you know as well as I do, that my soul is at stake;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168170,\n            \"and though I know there is one way out for me, you must not and I must not take it!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168266,\n            \"I know, and you know, that were I once dead you could and would set free my immortal spirit, even as you did my poor Lucy\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168468,\n            \"\\u201d I could not but note the quaint legal phrase which she used in such a place, and with all seriousness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168499,\n            \"Your lives I know,\\u201dshe went on quickly, \\u201cthat is easy for brave men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168597,\n            \"You must promise me, one and all-even you, my beloved husband-that, should the time come, you will kill me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169104,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing, I have not forgotten your mercy in poor Lucy\\u2019s case to him who loved \\\"-she stopped with a flying blush, and changed her phrase-\\\" to him who had best right to give her peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169151,\n            \"If that time shall come again, I look to you to make it a happy memory of my husband\\u2019s life that it was his loving hand which set me free from the awful thrall upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170469,\n            \"Judge Moneybag will settle this case, I think!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170745,\n            \"Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171119,\n            \"In old days she would, I am sure, have noticed, no matter how we might have tried to conceal it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171157,\n            \"The lethargy grows upon her, and though she seems strong and well, and is getting back some of her colour, Van Helsing and I are not satisfied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171233,\n            \"Van Helsing examines, he tells me, her teeth very carefully, whilst she is in the hypnotic condition, for he says that so long as they do not begin to sharpen there is no active danger of a change in her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171545,\n            \"Van Helsing and I were a little alarmed about Mrs. Harker to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171930,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing is terribly anxious, and told me just now that he fears the Count is escaping us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172076,\n            \"- When the telegram came announcing the arrival in Galatz I do not think it was such a shock to any of us as might have been expected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172124,\n            \"but I think we all expected that something strange would happen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172179,\n            \"I suppose that nature works on such a hopeful basis that we believe against ourselves that things will be as they ought to be, not as we should know that they will be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172315,\n            \"Quincey Morris tightened his belt with that quick movement which I knew so well;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172783,\n            \"John will stay with Madam Mina and me, and we shall consult.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172995,\n            \"when the door was shut upon her he said to me:-\\u201cWe mean the same!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173024,\n            \"It is a hope that makes me sick, for it may deceive us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173044,\n            \"Do you know why I asked her to get the manuscript?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173495,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that the Professor was going to break down and have hysterics, just as he had when Lucy died, but with a great effort he controlled himself and was at perfect nervous poise when Mrs. Harker tripped into the room, bright and happy-looking and, in the doing of work, seemingly forgetful of her misery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174385,\n            \"His finger and thumb closed on her pulse, as I thought instinctively and unconsciously, as she spoke:-\\u201cThe Count is a criminal and of criminal type.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174614,\n            \"A moment later he said to me, as calmly as though we had been having a sick-room consultation:-\\u201cSeventy-two only;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174733,\n            \"fear not, you must be egotist, for it is of you that we think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175290,\n            \"\\u201d And so I have written it whilst we wait their return, and Mrs. Harker has written with her typewriter all since she brought the MS.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175632,\n            \"Quincey raised his eyebrows slightly and looked at her intently, whilst Harker\\u2019s hand instinctively closed round the hilt of his Kukri.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176239,\n            \"I am in fear that her power of reading the Count\\u2019s sensations may die away, just when we want it most.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176264,\n            \"It seems to me that her imagination is beginning to work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176304,\n            \"If I thought that the Count\\u2019s power over her would die away equally with her power of knowledge it would be a happy thought;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176510,\n            \"- We are near Galatz now, and I may not have time to write later.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176925,\n            \"- Mr. Morris took me to the hotel where our rooms had been ordered by telegraph, he being the one who could best be spared, since he does not speak any foreign language.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177597,\n            \"I had seen them speer at the fellow, and put out their twa fingers when they saw him, to guard against the evil eye.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177635,\n            \"I sent them aboot their business pretty quick;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177644,\n            \"but as just after a fog closed in on us I felt a wee bit as they did anent something, though I wouldn\\u2019t say it was agin the big box.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177678,\n            \"Well, on we went, and as the fog didn\\u2019t let up for five days I joost let the wind carry us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177783,\n            \"The Roumanians were wild, and wanted me right or wrong to take out the box and fling it in the river.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177806,\n            \"I had to argy wi\\u2019them aboot it wi\\u2019a handspike;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177820,\n            \"an\\u2019when the last o\\u2019them rose off the deck wi\\u2019his head in his hand, I had convinced them that, evil eye or no evil eye, the property and the trust of my owners were better in my hands than in the river Danube.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177872,\n            \"They had, mind ye, taken the box on the deck ready to fling in, and as it was marked Galatz via Varna, I thocht I\\u2019d let it lie till we discharged in the port an\\u2019get rid o\\u2019t althegither.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178594,\n            \"As a preliminary step, I was released from my promise to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178642,\n            \"so I asked them all to lie down for half an hour whilst I should enter everything up to the moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178664,\n            \"I feel so grateful to the man who invented the \\u201cTraveller\\u2019s\\u201dtypewriter, and to Mr. Morris for getting this one for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178838,\n            \"Whilst they are resting, I shall go over all carefully, and perhaps I may arrive at some conclusion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178883,\n            \"I do believe that under God\\u2019s providence I have made a discovery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178922,\n            \"My new conclusion is ready, so I shall get our party together and read it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180019,\n            \"I read in the typescript that in my trance I heard cows low and water swirling level with my ears and the creaking of wood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180190,\n            \"The others kept shaking me by both hands, and Dr. Van Helsing said:-\\u201cOur dear Madam Mina is once more our teacher.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180627,\n            \"\\u201d He looked at Jonathan as he spoke, and Jonathan looked at me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181193,\n            \"\\u201d Here he turned to me, and as his eyes lit on my forehead he threw up his arms with a cry: \\u201cOh, my God, what have we done to have this terror upon us!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181363,\n            \"If the Count escape us this time-and he is strong and subtle and cunning-he may choose to sleep him for a century, and then in time our dear one \\\"-he took my hand-\\\" would come to him to keep him company, and would be as those others that you, Jonathan, saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181765,\n            \"Professor Van Helsing and I are to leave by the 11: 40 train to-night for Veresti, where we are to get a carriage to drive to the Borgo Pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181855,\n            \"We have all got arms, even for me a large-bore revolver;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181947,\n            \"- It took all my courage to say good-bye to my darling.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182214,\n            \"But I cannot sleep-how can I with the terrible danger hanging over my darling, and her going out into that awful place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182243,\n            \"My only comfort is that we are in the hands of God.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182851,\n            \"God bless him for all his goodness to poor dear Mina and me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182982,\n            \"I wonder where Mina is now, and Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183137,\n            \"I hope that before we get to Strasba we may see them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183703,\n            \"The Professor encourages her, and whispers to me that it may be a week before we can get any good food again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183806,\n            \"I am afraid to think what may happen to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184053,\n            \"In the first house where we stopped, when the woman who served us saw the scar on my forehead, she crossed herself and put out two fingers towards me, to keep off the evil eye.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184092,\n            \"I believe they went to the trouble of putting an extra amount of garlic into our food;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184118,\n            \"Ever since then I have taken care not to take off my hat or veil, and so have escaped their suspicions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184164,\n            \"but I daresay that fear of the evil eye will follow hard behind us all the way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184262,\n            \"I write this whilst we wait in a farmhouse for the horses to be got ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184335,\n            \"I shall tell him that we have days before us, and we must not break down when most of all his strength will be needed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184379,\n            \"- I was successful, and we took turns driving all night;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184422,\n            \"I mean that it oppresses us both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184474,\n            \"I do hope that my darling will not run any chance of danger-more than need be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184562,\n            \"I think we make an effort each to cheer the other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184671,\n            \"We are not worried with other travellers, and so even I can drive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184777,\n            \"As for me, I am not worthy in His sight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184791,\n            \"I am unclean to His eyes, and shall be until He may deign to let me stand forth in His sight as one of those who have not incurred His wrath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184866,\n            \"It is morning, and I write by a fire which all the night I have kept alive-Madam Mina aiding me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185041,\n            \"At sunset I try to hypnotise her, but alas!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185096,\n            \"Now to the historical, for as Madam Mina write not in her stenography, I must, in my cumbrous old fashion, that so each day of us may not go unrecorded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185174,\n            \"I made a couch with furs, and Madam Mina, lying down, yield herself as usual, but more slow and more short time than ever, to the hypnotic sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185465,\n            \"At the first, I tell Madam Mina to sleep;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185489,\n            \"till at the last, I feel myself to suspicious grow, and attempt to wake her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185507,\n            \"But she sleep on, and I may not wake her though I try.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185522,\n            \"I do not wish to try too hard lest I harm her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185535,\n            \"for I know that she have suffer much, and sleep at times be all-in-all to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185605,\n            \"I look down and find Madam Mina still sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185683,\n            \"Then I arouse Madam Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185689,\n            \"This time she wake with not much trouble, and then I try to put her to hypnotic sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185709,\n            \"But she sleep not, being as though I were not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185721,\n            \"Still I try and try, till all at once I find her and myself in dark;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185753,\n            \"Madam Mina laugh, and I turn and look at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185765,\n            \"She is now quite awake, and look so well as I never saw her since that night at Carfax when we first enter the Count\\u2019s house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185805,\n            \"but she is so bright and tender and thoughtful for me that I forget all fear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185822,\n            \"I light a fire, for we have brought supply of wood with us, and she prepare food while I undo the horses and set them, tethered in shelter, to feed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185857,\n            \"Then when I return to the fire she have my supper ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185870,\n            \"I go to help her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185876,\n            \"but she smile, and tell me that she have eat already-that she was so hungry that she would not wait.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185911,\n            \"but I fear to affright her, and so I am silent of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185926,\n            \"She help me and I eat alone;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185934,\n            \"and then we wrap in fur and lie beside the fire, and I tell her to sleep while I watch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185964,\n            \"and when I sudden remember that I watch, I find her lying quiet, but awake, and looking at me with so bright eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186008,\n            \"When I wake I try to hypnotise her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186061,\n            \"I have to lift her up, and place her sleeping in the carriage when I have harnessed the horses and made all ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186164,\n            \"- Let me be accurate in everything, for though you and I have seen some strange things together, you may at the first think that I, Van Helsing, am mad-that the many horrors and the so long strain on nerves has at the last turn my brain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186270,\n            \"and though I did have hunger and appeased it, I could not waken her-even for food.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186290,\n            \"I began to fear that the fatal spell of the place was upon her, tainted as she is with that Vampire baptism.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186314,\n            \"\\u201cWell,\\u201dsaid I to myself, \\u201cif it be that she sleep all the day, it shall also be that I do not sleep at night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186346,\n            \"\\u201d As we travel on the rough road, for a road of an ancient and imperfect kind there was, I held down my head and slept.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186375,\n            \"Again I waked with a sense of guilt and of time passed, and found Madam Mina still sleeping, and the sun low down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186463,\n            \"I woke Madam Mina, and again tried to hypnotise her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186483,\n            \"Then, ere the great dark came upon us-for even after down-sun the heavens reflected the gone sun on the snow, and all was for a time in a great twilight-I took out the horses and fed them in what shelter I could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186540,\n            \"and near it I make Madam Mina, now awake and more charming than ever, sit comfortable amid her rugs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186562,\n            \"I got ready food: but she would not eat, simply saying that she had not hunger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186581,\n            \"I did not press her, knowing her unavailingness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186606,\n            \"Then, with the fear on me of what might be, I drew a ring so big for her comfort, round where Madam Mina sat;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186691,\n            \"But when I drew near, she clung to me, and I could know that the poor soul shook her from head to feet with a tremor that was pain to feel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186725,\n            \"I said to her presently, when she had grown more quiet:-\\u201cWill you not come over to the fire?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186749,\n            \"\\u201d for I wished to make a test of what she could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186808,\n            \"Then, looking at me with open eyes, as of one waked from sleep, she said simply:-\\u201cI cannot!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186838,\n            \"I rejoiced, for I knew that what she could not, none of those that we dreaded could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187218,\n            \"I looked at her, but she sat calm, and smiled at me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187233,\n            \"when I would have stepped to the fire to replenish it, she caught me and held me back, and whispered, like a voice that one hears in a dream, so low it was:-\\u201cNo!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187287,\n            \"\\u201d I turned to her, and looking in her eyes, said:-\\u201cBut you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187306,\n            \"It is for you that I fear!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187340,\n            \"None safer in all the world from them than I am,\\u201dand as I wondered at the meaning of her words, a puff of wind made the flame leap up, and I see the red scar on her forehead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187420,\n            \"Then they began to materialise till-if God have not take away my reason, for I saw it through my eyes-there were before me in actual flesh the same three women that Jonathan saw in the room, when they would have kissed his throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187560,\n            \"\\u201d In fear I turned to my poor Madam Mina, and my heart with gladness leapt like flame;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187583,\n            \"the terror in her sweet eyes, the repulsion, the horror, told a story to my heart that was all of hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187669,\n            \"for I knew that we were safe within our protections.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187680,\n            \"They could not approach, me, whilst so armed, nor Madam Mina whilst she remained within the ring, which she could not leave no more than they could enter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187833,\n            \"Instinctively, with the dawn coming, I turned to Madam Mina, intending to hypnotise her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187851,\n            \"but she lay in a deep and sudden sleep, from which I could not wake her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187869,\n            \"I tried to hypnotise through her sleep, but she made no response, none at all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188048,\n            \"I fear to think of her, off on the wolds near that horrid place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188116,\n            \"If I write no more Good-bye, Mina!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188320,\n            \"When I left Madam Mina sleeping within the Holy circle, I took my way to the castle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188462,\n            \"Then I bethought me of my dear Madam Mina, and I was in terrible plight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188487,\n            \"Her, I had not dare to take into this place, but left safe from the Vampire in that Holy circle;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188519,\n            \"I resolve me that my work lay here, and that as to the wolves we must submit, if it were God\\u2019s will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188557,\n            \"So did I choose for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188636,\n            \"She lay in her Vampire sleep, so full of life and voluptuous beauty that I shudder as though I have come to do murder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188806,\n            \"There is some fascination, surely, when I am moved by the mere presence of such an one, even lying as she lay in a tomb fretted with age and heavy with the dust of centuries, though there be that horrid odour such as the lairs of the Count have had.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188998,\n            \"Then I braced myself again to my horrid task, and found by wrenching away tomb-tops one other of the sisters, the other dark one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189027,\n            \"I dared not pause to look on her as I had on her sister, lest once more I should begin to be enthrall;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189052,\n            \"but I go on searching until, presently, I find in a high great tomb as if made to one much beloved that other fair sister which, like Jonathan I had seen to gather herself out of the atoms of the mist.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189097,\n            \"She was so fair to look on, so radiantly beautiful, so exquisitely voluptuous, that the very instinct of man in me, which calls some of my sex to love and to protect one of hers, made my head whirl with new emotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189145,\n            \"But God be thanked, that soul-wail of my dear Madam Mina had not died out of my ears;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189208,\n            \"and as there had been only three of these Un-Dead phantoms around us in the night, I took it that there were no more of active Un-Dead existent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189484,\n            \"I tremble and tremble even yet, though till all was over, God be thanked, my nerve did stand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189593,\n            \"And the poor souls, I can pity them now and weep, as I think of them placid each in her full sleep of death for a short moment ere fading.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189706,\n            \"When I stepped into the circle where Madam Mina slept, she woke from her sleep, and, seeing, me, cried out in pain that I had endured too much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189792,\n            \"I was glad to see her paleness and her illness, for my mind was full of the fresh horror of that ruddy vampire sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189818,\n            \"And so with trust and hope, and yet full of fear, we go eastward to meet our friends-and him-whom Madam Mina tell me that she know are coming to meet us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189865,\n            \"- It was late in the afternoon when the Professor and I took our way towards the east whence I knew Jonathan was coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189973,\n            \"When we had gone about a mile, I was tired with the heavy walking and sat down to rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190120,\n            \"I knew from the way Dr. Van Helsing was searching about that he was trying to seek some strategic point, where we would be less exposed in case of attack.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190253,\n            \"\\u201d He brought in our furs, and made a snug nest for me, and got out some provisions and forced them upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190479,\n            \"Straight in front of us and not far off-in fact, so near that I wondered we had not noticed before-came a group of mounted men hurrying along.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190714,\n            \"\\u201d He took the glasses from me, and at the next lull of the snow swept the whole space below us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190898,\n            \"I knew at all events that neither of them was Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190923,\n            \"looking around I saw on the north side of the coming party two other men, riding at break-neck speed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190946,\n            \"One of them I knew was Jonathan, and the other I took, of course, to be Lord Godalming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190980,\n            \"When I told the Professor he shouted in glee like a schoolboy, and, after looking intently till a snow fall made sight impossible, he laid his Winchester rifle ready for use against the boulder at the opening of our shelter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191047,\n            \"\\u201d I got out my revolver ready to hand, for whilst we were speaking the howling of wolves came louder and closer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191118,\n            \"Sweeping the glass all around us I could see here and there dots moving singly and in twos and threes and larger numbers-the wolves were gathering for their prey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191402,\n            \"The Professor and I crouched down behind our rock, and held our weapons ready;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191418,\n            \"I could see that he was determined that they should not pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191601,\n            \"At the same moment Dr. Van Helsing and I rose behind the rock and pointed our weapons at them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191745,\n            \"I should have felt terrible fear at seeing Jonathan in such danger, but that the ardour of battle must have been upon me as well as the rest of them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192018,\n            \"All the time I had been breathlessly watching Jonathan I had, with the tail of my eye, seen him pressing desperately forward, and had seen the knives of the gypsies flash as he won a way through them, and they cut at him.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 7]\": [\n        [\n            97072,\n            \"Can you tell me how the Indian fakir can make himself to die and have been buried, and his grave sealed and corn sowed on it, and the corn reaped and be cut and sown and reaped and cut again, and then men come and take away the unbroken seal and that there lie the Indian fakir, not dead, but that rise up and walk amongst them as before?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109996,\n            \"But there remains a greater task: to find out the author of all this our sorrow and to stamp him out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113386,\n            \"I remember how much \\u201cThe Dailygraph\\u201dand \\u201cThe Whitby Gazette,\\u201dof which I had made cuttings, helped us to understand the terrible events at Whitby when Count Dracula landed, so I shall look through the evening papers since then, and perhaps I shall get some new light.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113695,\n            \"Strange that it never struck me that the very next house might be the Count\\u2019s hiding-place!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113800,\n            \"He thinks that in the meantime I should see Renfield, as hitherto he has been a sort of index to the coming and going of the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114226,\n            \"It was now my object to trace that horrid cargo of the Count\\u2019s to its place in London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114349,\n            \"It gave me almost a turn to see again one of the letters which I had seen on the Count\\u2019s table before I knew of his diabolical plans.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115465,\n            \"I suppose one ought to pity any thing so hunted as is the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118865,\n            \"\\u201d I agreed heartily with him, and then I told him what we had found in his absence: that the house which Dracula had bought was the very next one to my own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118924,\n            \"\\u201d he said, \\u201cfor then we might have reached him in time to save poor Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119539,\n            \"I shall then make known to you something of the history of this man, which has been ascertained for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119768,\n            \"This vampire which is amongst us is of himself so strong in person as twenty men;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119955,\n            \"How then are we to begin our strike to destroy him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119967,\n            \"How shall we find his where;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120011,\n            \"For if we fail in this our fight he must surely win;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120051,\n            \"It is that we become as him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120059,\n            \"that we henceforward become foul things of the night like him-without heart or conscience, preying on the bodies and the souls of those we love best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120857,\n            \"For, let me tell you, he is known everywhere that men have been.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120899,\n            \"and in China, so far from us in all ways, there even is he, and the peoples fear him at this day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120925,\n            \"He have follow the wake of the berserker Icelander, the devil-begotten Hun, the Slav, the Saxon, the Magyar.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121018,\n            \"Even more, we have seen amongst us that he can even grow younger;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121138,\n            \"He can transform himself to wolf, as we gather from the ship arrival in Whitby, when he tear open the dog;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121162,\n            \"he can be as bat, as Madam Mina saw him on the window at Whitby, and as friend John saw him fly from this so near house, and as my friend Quincey saw him at the window of Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121226,\n            \"but, from what we know, the distance he can make this mist is limited, and it can only be round himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121272,\n            \"He become so small-we ourselves saw Miss Lucy, ere she was at peace, slip through a hairbreadth space at the tomb door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121299,\n            \"He can, when once he find his way, come out from anything or into anything, no matter how close it be bound or even fused up with fire-solder you call it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121535,\n            \"Thus, whereas he can do as he will within his limit, when he have his earth-home, his coffin-home, his hell-home, the place unhallowed, as we saw when he went to the grave of the suicide at Whitby;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121621,\n            \"Then there are things which so afflict him that he has no power, as the garlic that we know of;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121643,\n            \"and as for things sacred, as this symbol, my crucifix, that was amongst us even now when we resolve, to them he is nothing, but in their presence he take his place far off and silent with respect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121742,\n            \"and as for the stake through him, we know already of its peace;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121775,\n            \"\\u201cThus when we find the habitation of this man-that-was, we can confine him to his coffin and destroy him, if we obey what we know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121813,\n            \"I have asked my friend Arminius, of Buda-Pesth University, to make his record;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121831,\n            \"and, from all the means that are, he tell me of what he has been.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121849,\n            \"He must, indeed, have been that Voivode Dracula who won his name against the Turk, over the great river on the very frontier of Turkey-land.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121880,\n            \"If it be so, then was he no common man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121930,\n            \"\\u2019 That mighty brain and that iron resolution went with him to his grave, and are even now arrayed against us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121987,\n            \"They learned his secrets in the Scholomance, amongst the mountains over Lake Hermanstadt, where the devil claims the tenth scholar as his due.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122039,\n            \"and in one manuscript this very Dracula is spoken of as \\u2018 wampyr,\\u2019which we all understand too well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122587,\n            \"and when we are ready, we must either capture or kill this monster in his lair;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122605,\n            \"or we must, so to speak, sterilise the earth, so that no more he can seek safety in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122628,\n            \"Thus in the end we may find him in his form of man between the hours of noon and sunset, and so engage with him when he is at his most weak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122831,\n            \"Mr. Morris resumed the discussion:-\\u201cAs there is no time to lose, I vote we have a look at his house right now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125863,\n            \"I can\\u2019t forget how he prayed with almost equal fervour for a cat, and then tried to tear my throat out with his teeth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125918,\n            \"That horrid thing has the wolves and the rats and his own kind to help him, so I suppose he isn\\u2019t above trying to use a respectable lunatic.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126214,\n            \"Remember that he has the strength of twenty men, and that, though our necks or our windpipes are of the common kind-and therefore breakable or crushable-his are not amenable to mere strength.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126276,\n            \"but they cannot hurt him as we can be hurt by him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126289,\n            \"We must, therefore, guard ourselves from his touch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127119,\n            \"None of the others had met the Count at all at close quarters, and when I had seen him he was either in the fasting stage of his existence in his rooms or, when he was gloated with fresh blood, in a ruined building open to the air;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127497,\n            \"Somewhere, looking out from the shadow, I seemed to see the high lights of the Count\\u2019s evil face, the ridge of the nose, the red eyes, the red lips, the awful pallor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128409,\n            \"One lesson, too, we have learned, if it be allowable to argue a particulari: that the brute beasts which are to the Count\\u2019s command are yet themselves not amenable to his spiritual power;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128449,\n            \"for look, these rats that would come to his call, just as from his castle top he summon the wolves to your going and to that poor mother\\u2019s cry, though they come to him, they run pell-mell from the so little dogs of my friend Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132388,\n            \"The systematic manner in which this was done made me think that he could not mean to confine himself to two sides of London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133058,\n            \"Indeed, it may not be a hard task, after all, for she herself has become reticent on the subject, and has not spoken of the Count or his doings ever since we told her of our decision.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134509,\n            \"beyond the Junior Constitutional I came across the house described, and was satisfied that this was the next of the lairs arranged by Dracula.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138749,\n            \"The purchaser is a foreign nobleman, Count de Ville, who effected the purchase himself paying the purchase money in notes \\u2018 over the counter,\\u2019if your Lordship will pardon us using so vulgar an expression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138789,\n            \"Beyond this we know nothing whatever of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142750,\n            \"We all hurried and took from our rooms the same things that we had when we entered the Count\\u2019s house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143176,\n            \"His face was turned from us, but the instant we saw we all recognised the Count-in every way, even to the scar on his forehead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143206,\n            \"With his left hand he held both Mrs. Harker\\u2019s hands, keeping them away with her arms at full tension;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143230,\n            \"his right hand gripped her by the back of the neck, forcing her face down on his bosom.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143250,\n            \"Her white nightdress was smeared with blood, and a thin stream trickled down the man\\u2019s bare breast which was shown by his torn-open dress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143309,\n            \"As we burst into the room, the Count turned his face, and the hellish look that I had heard described seemed to leap into it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143387,\n            \"With a wrench, which threw his victim back upon the bed as though hurled from a height, he turned and sprang at us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143437,\n            \"The Count suddenly stopped, just as poor Lucy had done outside the tomb, and cowered back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143456,\n            \"Further and further back he cowered, as we, lifting our crucifixes, advanced.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143645,\n            \"Then she put before her face her poor crushed hands, which bore on their whiteness the red mark of the Count\\u2019s terrible grip, and from behind them came a low desolate wail which made the terrible scream seem only the quick expression of an endless grief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143728,\n            \"Van Helsing whispered to me:-\\u201cJonathan is in a stupor such as we know the Vampire can produce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144224,\n            \"I have suffered enough to-night, God knows, without the dread of his harming you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144682,\n            \"but his nostrils twitched and his eyes blazed as I told how the ruthless hands of the Count had held his wife in that terrible and horrid position, with her mouth to the open wound in his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147960,\n            \"for if he is still with the quick Un-Dead, your death would make you even as he is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148004,\n            \"You must fight Death himself, though he come to you in pain or in joy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148331,\n            \"Had we done so, the Count must have guessed our purpose, and would doubtless have taken measures in advance to frustrate such an effort with regard to the others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148363,\n            \"but now he does not know our intentions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148372,\n            \"Nay, more, in all probability, he does not know that such a power exists to us as can sterilise his lairs, so that he cannot use them as of old.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148515,\n            \"If he go through a doorway, he must open the door like a mortal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148547,\n            \"So we shall, if we have not yet catch him and destroy him, drive him to bay in some place where the catching and the destroying shall be, in time, sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149152,\n            \"not if they knew the man was properly employed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149886,\n            \"but it made my blood run cold in my veins to think of what had occurred with poor Lucy when the Count had sucked her blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149967,\n            \"It was finally agreed that before starting for Piccadilly we should destroy the Count\\u2019s lair close at hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149988,\n            \"In case he should find it out too soon, we should thus be still ahead of him in our work of destruction;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150012,\n            \"and his presence in his purely material shape, and at his weakest, might give us some new clue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150090,\n            \"It was possible, if not likely, the Professor urged, that the Count might appear in Piccadilly during the day, and that if so we might be able to cope with him then and there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150129,\n            \"At any rate, we might be able to follow him in force.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150230,\n            \"and that, as it was, all the strength we could muster was required to cope with the Count\\u2019s extraordinary power.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150377,\n            \"The Count may come to Piccadilly earlier than we think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151285,\n            \"Till then we bear our Cross, as His Son did in obedience to His Will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151302,\n            \"It may be that we are chosen instruments of His good pleasure, and that we ascend to His bidding as that other through stripes and shame;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151704,\n            \"We must sterilise this earth, so sacred of holy memories, that he has brought from a far distant land for such fell use.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151741,\n            \"Thus we defeat him with his own weapon, for we make it more holy still.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152809,\n            \"It did indeed smell vilely-like the old chapel at Carfax-and with our previous experience it was plain to us that the Count had been using the place pretty freely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152858,\n            \"for we knew we had a strong and wily enemy to deal with, and as yet we did not know whether the Count might not be in the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153039,\n            \"It was evident to us that the Count was not at present in the house, and we proceeded to search for any of his effects.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153066,\n            \"After a cursory glance at the rest of the rooms, from basement to attic, we came to the conclusion that the dining-room contained any effects which might belong to the Count;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153284,\n            \"The rest of us are, with what patience we can, waiting their return-or the coming of the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153629,\n            \"As I learned from the researches of my friend Arminus of Buda-Pesth, he was in life a most wonderful man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153791,\n            \"and if it had not been that we have crossed his path he would be yet-he may be yet if we fail-the father or furtherer of a new order of beings, whose road must lead through Death, not Life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155057,\n            \"If, however, he doesn\\u2019t turn up by five o\\u2019clock, we must start off;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155162,\n            \"That he went south has a meaning for us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155195,\n            \"You must have been at Bermondsey only a short time before him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155429,\n            \"Van Helsing, Harker, and I were just behind the door, so that when it was opened the Professor could guard it whilst we two stepped between the incomer and the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155523,\n            \"Suddenly with a single bound he leaped into the room, winning a way past us before any of us could raise a hand to stay him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155610,\n            \"As the Count saw us, a horrible sort of snarl passed over his face, showing the eye-teeth long and pointed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155868,\n            \"and it was without surprise that I saw the monster cower back before a similar movement made spontaneously by each one of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156044,\n            \"We ran over and saw him spring unhurt from the ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156075,\n            \"There he turned and spoke to us:-\\u201cYou think to baffle me, you-with your pale faces all in a row, like sheep in a butcher\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156121,\n            \"You think you have left me without a place to rest;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156198,\n            \"\\u201d With a contemptuous sneer, he passed quickly through the door, and we heard the rusty bolt creak as he fastened it behind him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156232,\n            \"The first of us to speak was the Professor, as, realising the difficulty of following him through the stable, we moved toward the hall.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156268,\n            \"Notwithstanding his brave words, he fears us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156459,\n            \"but the mews was deserted and no one had seen him depart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156902,\n            \"When we came to the part where Harker had rushed at the Count so recklessly, she clung to her husband\\u2019s arm, and held it tight as though her clinging could protect him from any harm that might come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157323,\n            \"As she stopped speaking he leaped to his feet, almost tearing his hand from hers as he spoke:-\\u201cMay God give him into my hand just for long enough to destroy that earthly life of him which we are aiming at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157662,\n            \"Before they retired the Professor fixed up the room against any coming of the Vampire, and assured Mrs. Harker that she might rest in peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157921,\n            \"All we knew was that one earth-box remained, and that the Count alone knew where it was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157942,\n            \"If he chooses to lie hidden, he may baffle us for years;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158001,\n            \"I love her a thousand times more for her sweet pity of last night, a pity that made my own hate of the monster seem despicable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159736,\n            \"We can know now what was in the Count\\u2019s mind, when he seize that money, though Jonathan\\u2019s so fierce knife put him in the danger that even he dread.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159839,\n            \"we follow him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160362,\n            \"for this he hurry at the last, lest we catch him before the sun go down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160380,\n            \"It was his last hope, save that he might hide in the tomb that he think poor Miss Lucy, being as he thought like him, keep open to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160565,\n            \"and yet in one day, when we know of the disposal of him we drive him out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160584,\n            \"He is finite, though he is powerful to do much harm and suffers not as we do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160703,\n            \"Already the certainty that the Count is out of the country has given her comfort;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160726,\n            \"For my own part, now that his horrible danger is not face to face with us, it seems almost impossible to believe in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162228,\n            \"\\u201cAnd so, my dear Madam Mina, it is that we have to rest for a time, for our enemy is on the sea, with the fog at his command, on his way to the Danube mouth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162284,\n            \"and when we start we go on land more quick, and we meet him there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162301,\n            \"Our best hope is to come on him when in the box between sunrise and sunset;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162318,\n            \"for then he can make no struggle, and we may deal with him as we should.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162351,\n            \"We know all about where he go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162528,\n            \"\\u201d I asked him again if it were really necessary that they should pursue the Count, for oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162722,\n            \"I have told them how the measure of leaving his own barren land-barren of peoples-and coming to a new land where life of man teems till they are like the multitude of standing corn, was the work of centuries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162767,\n            \"Were another of the Un-Dead, like him, to try to do what he has done, perhaps not all the centuries of the world that have been, or that will be, could aid him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162936,\n            \"In a hard and warlike time he was celebrate that he have more iron nerve, more subtle brain, more braver heart, than any man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163025,\n            \"And now this is what he is to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163035,\n            \"He have infect you-oh, forgive me, my dear, that I must say such;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163065,\n            \"He infect you in such wise, that even if he do no more, you have only to live-to live in your own old, sweet way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163096,\n            \"and so in time, death, which is of man\\u2019s common lot and with God\\u2019s sanction, shall make you like to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163139,\n            \"Thus are we ministers of God\\u2019s own wish: that the world, and men for whom His Son die, will not be given over to monsters, whose very existence would defame Him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163177,\n            \"He have allowed us to redeem one soul already, and we go out as the old knights of the Cross to redeem more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164311,\n            \"The Count had his own purposes when he gave her what Van Helsing called \\u201cthe Vampire\\u2019s baptism of blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164641,\n            \"I can see the characteristics of the vampire coming in her face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164741,\n            \"If it be that she can, by our hypnotic trance, tell what the Count see and hear, is it not more true that he who have hypnotise her first, and who have drink of her very blood and make her drink of his, should, if he will, compel her mind to disclose to him that which she know?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165059,\n            \"Mrs. Harker had sent a message by her husband to say that she would not join us at present, as she thought it better that we should be free to discuss our movements without her presence to embarrass us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165248,\n            \"Now, if we allow for two days less for the ship\\u2019s voyage, owing to such weather influences as we know that the Count can bring to bear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166149,\n            \"She said:-\\u201cPromise me that you will not tell me anything of the plans formed for the campaign against the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166663,\n            \"I know that when the Count wills me I must go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166675,\n            \"I know that if he tells me to come in secret, I must come by wile;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170351,\n            \"If, then, we can come on board after sunrise, he is at our mercy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170369,\n            \"for we can open the box and make sure of him, as we did of poor Lucy, before he wakes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170392,\n            \"What mercy he shall get from us will not count for much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170768,\n            \"The Professor says that if we can so treat the Count\\u2019s body, it will soon after fall into dust.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171930,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing is terribly anxious, and told me just now that he fears the Count is escaping us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173145,\n            \"In the trance of three days ago the Count sent her his spirit to read her mind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173163,\n            \"or more like he took her to see him in his earth-box in the ship with water rushing, just as it go free at rise and set of sun.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173196,\n            \"He learn then that we are here;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173204,\n            \"for she have more to tell in her open life with eyes to see and ears to hear than he, shut, as he is, in his coffin-box.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173237,\n            \"Now he make his most effort to escape us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173247,\n            \"At present he want her not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173254,\n            \"\\u201cHe is sure with his so great knowledge that she will come at his call;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173271,\n            \"but he cut her off-take her, as he can do, out of his own power, that so she come not to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173301,\n            \"there I have hope that our man-brains that have been of man so long and that have not lost the grace of God, will come higher than his child-brain that lie in his tomb for centuries, that grow not yet to our stature, and that do only work selfish and therefore small.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173400,\n            \"when most we want all her great brain which is trained like man\\u2019s brain, but is of sweet woman and have a special power which the Count give her, and which he may not take away altogether-though he think not so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174178,\n            \"he, too, have child-brain, and it is of the child to do what he have done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174385,\n            \"His finger and thumb closed on her pulse, as I thought instinctively and unconsciously, as she spoke:-\\u201cThe Count is a criminal and of criminal type.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174417,\n            \"Nordau and Lombroso would so classify him, and qu\\u00e2 criminal he is of imperfectly formed mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174448,\n            \"His past is a clue, and the one page of it that we know-and that from his own lips-tells that once before, when in what Mr. Morris would call a \\u2018 tight place,\\u2019he went back to his own country from the land he had tried to invade, and thence, without losing purpose, prepared himself for a new effort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174788,\n            \"As he fled back over the Danube, leaving his forces to be cut to pieces, so now he is intent on being safe, careless of all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174910,\n            \"and by it he has left us here in Varna, whilst the ship that carried him rushed through enveloping fog up to Galatz, where, doubtless, he had made preparation for escaping from us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174958,\n            \"and it may be that, as ever is in God\\u2019s Providence, the very thing that the evil-doer most reckoned on for his selfish good, turns out to be his chiefest harm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175012,\n            \"For now that he think he is free from every trace of us all, and that he has escaped us with so many hours to him, then his selfish child-brain will whisper him to sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175052,\n            \"He think, too, that as he cut himself off from knowing your mind, there can be no knowledge of him to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175084,\n            \"That terrible baptism of blood which he give you makes you free to go to him in spirit, as you have as yet done in your times of freedom, when the sun rise and set.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175122,\n            \"At such times you go by my volition and not by his;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175135,\n            \"and this power to good of you and others, as you have won from your suffering at his hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175156,\n            \"This is now all the more precious that he know it not, and to guard himself have even cut himself off from his knowledge of our where.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175256,\n            \"You must be scribe and write him all down, so that when the others return from their work you can give it to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175864,\n            \"And if he be carried, then the customs men may discover what the box contain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175917,\n            \"for if he escape not at night we shall come on him in daytime, boxed up and at our mercy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176239,\n            \"I am in fear that her power of reading the Count\\u2019s sensations may die away, just when we want it most.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176304,\n            \"If I thought that the Count\\u2019s power over her would die away equally with her power of knowledge it would be a happy thought;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177724,\n            \"An\\u2019if he didn\\u2019t, well, we\\u2019d keep a sharp lookout anyhow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177820,\n            \"an\\u2019when the last o\\u2019them rose off the deck wi\\u2019his head in his hand, I had convinced them that, evil eye or no evil eye, the property and the trust of my owners were better in my hands than in the river Danube.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178989,\n            \"(a) He must be brought back by some one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179387,\n            \"We know from the record that he was on the water;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179425,\n            \"we may, then, get a light on what his later task is to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179444,\n            \"- We must differentiate between what he did in London as part of his general plan of action, when he was pressed for moments and had to arrange as best he could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179478,\n            \"Secondly we must see, as well as we can surmise it from the facts we know of, what he has done here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179503,\n            \"As to the first, he evidently intended to arrive at Galatz, and sent invoice to Varna to deceive us lest we should ascertain his means of exit from England;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179601,\n            \"That, so far, his plans were successful we know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179634,\n            \"but his superstition united with his canniness played the Count\\u2019s game for him, and he ran with his favouring wind through fogs and all till he brought up blindfold at Galatz.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179739,\n            \"Now we come to what the Count must have done after his arrival-on land, at Galatz.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179819,\n            \"and the man\\u2019s remark, that the murder was the work of a Slovak, showed the general feeling against his class.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179878,\n            \"He was brought from the castle by Szgany, and probably they delivered their cargo to Slovaks who took the boxes to Varna, for there they were shipped for London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179924,\n            \"When the box was on land, before sunrise or after sunset, he came out from his box, met Skinsky and instructed him what to do as to arranging the carriage of the box up some river.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179964,\n            \"When this was done, and he knew that all was in train, he blotted out his traces, as he thought, by murdering his agent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180251,\n            \"and if we can come on him by day, on the water, our task will be over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180298,\n            \"for them to suspect would be to prompt them to throw him in the stream where he perish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180473,\n            \"The Count, if you remember, took some other precautions;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180485,\n            \"he made some requisitions on others that Mrs. Harker could not quite hear or understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180600,\n            \"we shall not rest until the Count\\u2019s head and body have been separated, and we are sure that he cannot re-incarnate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180926,\n            \"Whilst the old fox is tied in his box, floating on the running stream whence he cannot escape to land-where he dares not raise the lid of his coffin-box lest his Slovak carriers should in fear leave him to perish-we shall go in the track where Jonathan went,-from Bistritz over the Borgo, and find our way to the Castle of Dracula.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181060,\n            \"\\u201d Here Jonathan interrupted him hotly:-\\u201cDo you mean to say, Professor Van Helsing, that you would bring Mina, in her sad case and tainted as she is with that devil\\u2019s illness, right into the jaws of his death-trap?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181363,\n            \"If the Count escape us this time-and he is strong and subtle and cunning-he may choose to sleep him for a century, and then in time our dear one \\\"-he took my hand-\\\" would come to him to keep him company, and would be as those others that you, Jonathan, saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182071,\n            \"Regarding our plans, we finally decided that Mina\\u2019s guess was correct, and that if any waterway was chosen for the Count\\u2019s escape back to his Castle, the Sereth and then the Bistritza at its junction, would be the one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183150,\n            \"for if by that time we have not overtaken the Count, it may be necessary to take counsel together what to do next.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185765,\n            \"She is now quite awake, and look so well as I never saw her since that night at Carfax when we first enter the Count\\u2019s house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188487,\n            \"Her, I had not dare to take into this place, but left safe from the Vampire in that Holy circle;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188806,\n            \"There is some fascination, surely, when I am moved by the mere presence of such an one, even lying as she lay in a tomb fretted with age and heavy with the dust of centuries, though there be that horrid odour such as the lairs of the Count have had.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189994,\n            \"Then we looked back and saw where the clear line of Dracula\\u2019s castle cut the sky;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 8]\": [\n        [\n            45488,\n            \"The clock was striking one as I was in the Crescent, and there was not a soul in sight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45529,\n            \"At the edge of the West Cliff above the pier I looked across the harbour to the East Cliff, in the hope or fear-I don\\u2019t know which-of seeing Lucy in our favourite seat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45676,\n            \"Whatever my expectation was, it was not disappointed, for there, on our favourite seat, the silver light of the moon struck a half-reclining figure, snowy white.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45757,\n            \"What it was, whether man or beast, I could not tell;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45811,\n            \"The town seemed as dead, for not a soul did I see;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46456,\n            \"when I told her to come at once with me home she rose without a word, with the obedience of a child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46480,\n            \"As we passed along, the gravel hurt my feet, and Lucy noticed me wince.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46514,\n            \"However, when we got to the pathway outside the churchyard, where there was a puddle of water, remaining from the storm, I daubed my feet with mud, using each foot in turn on the other, so that as we went home, no one, in case we should meet any one, should notice my bare feet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46698,\n            \"When we got in, and had washed our feet, and had said a prayer of thankfulness together, I tucked her into bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46724,\n            \"Before falling asleep she asked-even implored-me not to say a word to any one, even her mother, about her sleep-walking adventure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46761,\n            \"but on thinking of the state of her mother\\u2019s health, and how the knowledge of such a thing would fret her, and thinking, too, of how such a story might become distorted-nay, infallibly would-in case it should leak out, I thought it wiser to do so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47071,\n            \"We took our lunch to Mulgrave Woods, Mrs. Westenra driving by the road and Lucy and I walking by the cliff-path and joining her at the gate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47793,\n            \"I was a little startled myself, for it seemed for an instant as if the stranger had great eyes like burning flames;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47917,\n            \"so I said nothing, and we went home to dinner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47976,\n            \"When coming home-it was then bright moonlight, so bright that, though the front of our part of the Crescent was in shadow, everything could be well seen-I threw a glance up at our window, and saw Lucy\\u2019s head leaning out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48324,\n            \"Later on in the day she told me the cause.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48368,\n            \"She confided to me that she has got her death-warrant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48381,\n            \"She has not told Lucy, and made me promise secrecy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48576,\n            \"I keep the key of our door always fastened to my wrist at night, but she gets up and walks about the room, and sits at the open window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48754,\n            \"Unless they heal within a day or two, I shall insist on the doctor seeing about them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49636,\n            \"Then I had a vague memory of something long and dark with red eyes, just as we saw in the sunset, and something very sweet and very bitter all around me at once;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49672,\n            \"and then I seemed sinking into deep green water, and there was a singing in my ears, as I have heard there is to drowning men;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49800,\n            \"I did not quite like it, and thought it better not to keep her mind on the subject, so we drifted on to other subjects, and Lucy was like her old self again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49929,\n            \"Mr. Hawkins sent me on the letter, and wrote himself, oh, so kindly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50101,\n            \"The letter that he has seen and touched must comfort me till we meet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50144,\n            \"\\u201cDear Madam,-\\u201cI write by desire of Mr. Jonathan Harker, who is himself not strong enough to write, though progressing well, thanks to God and St.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50203,\n            \"He wishes me to convey his love, and to say that by this post I write for him to Mr. Peter Hawkins, Exeter, to say, with his dutiful respects, that he is sorry for his delay, and that all of his work is completed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50275,\n            \"He wishes me to say that he has not sufficient money with him, and that he would like to pay for his staying here, so that others who need shall not be wanting for help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50313,\n            \"\\u201cBelieve me, \\u201cYours, with sympathy and all blessings, \\u201cSister Agatha.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50335,\n            \"- My patient being asleep, I open this to let you know something more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50351,\n            \"He has told me all about you, and that you are shortly to be his wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50594,\n            \"There are, I pray God and St.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50660,\n            \"The attendant was struck by his manner, and knowing my interest in him, encouraged him to talk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50807,\n            \"His attitude to me was the same as that to the attendant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50820,\n            \"in his sublime self-feeling the difference between myself and attendant seemed to him as nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51307,\n            \"I had lain tossing about, and had heard the clock strike only twice, when the night-watchman came to me, sent up from the ward, to say that Renfield had escaped.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51378,\n            \"The attendant was waiting for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51429,\n            \"He ran back and saw his feet disappear through the window, and had at once sent up for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51516,\n            \"I am thin, so, with his aid, I got out, but feet foremost, and, as we were only a few feet above ground, landed unhurt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51549,\n            \"The attendant told me the patient had gone to the left, and had taken a straight line, so I ran as quickly as I could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51577,\n            \"As I got through the belt of trees I saw a white figure scale the high wall which separates our grounds from those of the deserted house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51605,\n            \"I ran back at once, told the watchman to get three or four men immediately and follow me into the grounds of Carfax, in case our friend might be dangerous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51700,\n            \"He was talking, apparently to some one, but I was afraid to go near enough to hear what he was saying, lest I might frighten him, and he should run off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51806,\n            \"I heard him say:-\\u201cI am here to do Your bidding, Master.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51944,\n            \"I never saw a lunatic in such a paroxysm of rage before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52150,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Lucy,-\\u201cI know you will be anxious to hear all that has happened since we parted at the railway station at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52361,\n            \"Sister Agatha, who is a good creature and a born nurse, tells me that he raved of dreadful things whilst he was off his head.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52443,\n            \"She is a sweet, good soul, and the next day, when she saw I was troubled, she opened up the subject again, and after saying that she could never mention what my poor dear raved about, added: \\u2018 I can tell you this much, my dear: that it was not about anything which he has done wrong himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52511,\n            \"and you, as his wife to be, have no cause to be concerned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52555,\n            \"\\u2019 I do believe the dear soul thought I might be jealous lest my poor dear should have fallen in love with any other girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52590,\n            \"And yet, my dear, let me whisper, I felt a thrill of joy through me when I knew that no other woman was a cause of trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52667,\n            \"I asked Sister Agatha, and she brought all his things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52750,\n            \"Then he called me back, and when I came he had his hand over the note-book, and he said to me very solemnly:-\\u201c\\u2018 Wilhelmina\\u2019- I knew then that he was in deadly earnest, for he has never called me by that name since he asked me to marry him-\\u2018 you know, dear, my ideas of the trust between husband and wife: there should be no secret, no concealment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52836,\n            \"I have had a great shock, and when I try to think of what it is I feel my head spin round, and I do not know if it was all real or the dreaming of a madman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52919,\n            \"\\u2019 For, my dear, we had decided to be married as soon as the formalities are complete.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53023,\n            \"I have asked Sister Agatha to beg the Superior to let our wedding be this afternoon, and am waiting her reply.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53049,\n            \"\\u201cShe has come and told me that the chaplain of the English mission church has been sent for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53172,\n            \"Please God, I shall never, never forget them, nor the grave and sweet responsibilities I have taken upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53204,\n            \"When the chaplain and the sisters had left me alone with my husband-oh, Lucy, it is the first time I have written the words \\u2018 my husband\\u2019- left me alone with my husband, I took the book from under his pillow, and wrapped it up in white paper, and tied it with a little bit of pale blue ribbon which was round my neck, and sealed it over the knot with sealing-wax, and for my seal I used my wedding ring.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53299,\n            \"Then I kissed it and showed it to my husband, and told him that I would keep it so, and then it would be an outward and visible sign for us all our lives that we trusted each other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53364,\n            \"Then he took my hand in his, and oh, Lucy, it was the first time he took his wife\\u2019s hand, and said that it was the dearest thing in all the wide world, and that he would go through all the past again to win it, if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53526,\n            \"And, my dear, when he kissed me, and drew me to him with his poor weak hands, it was like a very solemn pledge between us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53624,\n            \"I want you to see now, and with the eyes of a very happy wife, whither duty has led me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53818,\n            \"I wish you could be coming home soon enough to stay with us here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54128,\n            \"\\u201d The attendant came to tell me, so I ran down at once to have a look at him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54222,\n            \"It was a strange thing that the patient had humour enough to see their distrust, for, coming close to me, he said in a whisper, all the while looking furtively at them:-\\u201cThey think I could hurt you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54313,\n            \"Am I to take it that I have anything in common with him, so that we are, as it were, to stand together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54435,\n            \"The attendant tells me that he was quiet until just before dawn, and that then he began to get uneasy, and at length violent, until at last he fell into a paroxysm which exhausted him so that he swooned into a sort of coma.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54659,\n            \"I have given orders to the night attendant merely to shut him in the padded room, when once he is quiet, until an hour before sunrise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54791,\n            \"When he saw me he became furious, and had not the attendants seized him in time, he would have tried to kill me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54988,\n            \"- I must imitate Mina, and keep writing things down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55018,\n            \"I wish she were with me again, for I feel so unhappy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55119,\n            \"I wonder if I could sleep in mother\\u2019s room to-night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55150,\n            \"Mother did not seem to take to my proposal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55160,\n            \"She seems not too well herself, and doubtless she fears to worry me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55384,\n            \"I do not dare to ask her mother, for to disturb the poor lady\\u2019s mind about her daughter in her present state of health would be fatal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55415,\n            \"Mrs. Westenra has confided to me that her doom is spoken-disease of the heart-though poor Lucy does not know it yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55688,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear old fellow,-\\u201cWith regard to Miss Westenra\\u2019s health I hasten to let you know at once that in my opinion there is not any functional disturbance or any malady that I know of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55834,\n            \"\\u201cI found Miss Westenra in seemingly gay spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55844,\n            \"Her mother was present, and in a few seconds I made up my mind that she was trying all she knew to mislead her mother and prevent her from being anxious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55877,\n            \"I have no doubt she guesses, if she does not know, what need of caution there is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56049,\n            \"\\u2019 I reminded her that a doctor\\u2019s confidence was sacred, but that you were grievously anxious about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56402,\n            \"I have asked him to come over, and as you told me that all things were to be at your charge, I have mentioned to him who you are and your relations to Miss Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56440,\n            \"This, my dear fellow, is in obedience to your wishes, for I am only too proud and happy to do anything I can for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56469,\n            \"Van Helsing would, I know, do anything for me for a personal reason, so, no matter on what ground he comes, we must accept his wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56657,\n            \"I shall see Miss Westenra to-morrow again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56667,\n            \"She is to meet me at the Stores, so that I may not alarm her mother by too early a repetition of my call.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56758,\n            \"By good fortune I can leave just at once, without wrong to any of those who have trusted me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56779,\n            \"Were fortune other, then it were bad for those who have trusted, for I come to my friend when he call me to aid those he holds dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56810,\n            \"Tell your friend that when that time you suck from my wound so swiftly the poison of the gangrene from that knife that our other friend, too nervous, let slip, you did more for him when he wants my aids and you call for them than all his great fortune could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56887,\n            \"Have then rooms for me at the Great Eastern Hotel, so that I may be near to hand, and please it so arrange that we may see the young lady not too late on to-morrow, for it is likely that I may have to return here that night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57004,\n            \"He came on with me to Hillingham, and found that, by Lucy\\u2019s discretion, her mother was lunching out, so that we were alone with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57086,\n            \"When I told him of our friendship and how you trust to me in the matter, he said: \\u2018 You must tell him all you think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57239,\n            \"So I told him I would simply write an account of our visit, just as if I were doing a descriptive special article for The Daily Telegraph.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57433,\n            \"Then he began to chat of all things except ourselves and diseases and with such an infinite geniality that I could see poor Lucy\\u2019s pretense of animation merge into reality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57552,\n            \"\\u201d\\u2019And he snapped his fingers at me and went on: \\u2018 But you and I shall show them how wrong they are.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57578,\n            \"How can he\\u2019- and he pointed at me with the same look and gesture as that with which once he pointed me out to his class, on, or rather after, a particular occasion which he never fails to remind me of-\\u2018 know anything of a young ladies?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57826,\n            \"I have asked her to send me her maid, that I may ask just one or two question, that so I may not chance to miss nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57950,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cAs I tell you, he would not say a word more, even when we were alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57989,\n            \"I trust your poor father is rallying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58029,\n            \"I know your idea of duty to your father, and you are right to stick to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58208,\n            \"The attendant tells me that his screams whilst in the paroxysm were really appalling;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58730,\n            \"I had been to see Miss Westenra, whom I found much better, and had just returned, and was standing at our own gate looking at the sunset, when once more I heard him yelling.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58944,\n            \"I signalled to the attendants not to hold him, for I was anxious to see what he would do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59234,\n            \"I hold over telegram to Holmwood till have seen you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59245,\n            \"\\u201d CHAPTER X Letter, Dr. Seward to Hon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59303,\n            \"Mrs. Westenra was naturally anxious concerning Lucy, and has consulted me professionally about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsing, the great specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly with myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59479,\n            \"- The first thing Van Helsing said to me when we met at Liverpool Street was:-\\u201cHave you said anything to our young friend the lover of her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59535,\n            \"I wrote him a letter simply telling him that you were coming, as Miss Westenra was not so well, and that I should let him know if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59789,\n            \"\\u201d He stopped and looked at me, and said:-\\u201cMy friend John, when the corn is grown, even before it has ripened-while the milk of its mother-earth is in him, and the sunshine has not yet begun to paint him with his gold, the husbandman he pull the ear and rub him between his rough hands, and blow away the green chaff, and say to you: \\u2018 Look!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59903,\n            \"For reply he reached over and took my ear in his hand and pulled it playfully, as he used long ago to do at lectures, and said: \\u201cThe good husbandman tell you so then because he knows, but not till then.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60475,\n            \"I used my knowledge of this phase of spiritual pathology, and laid down a rule that she should not be present with Lucy or think of her illness more than was absolutely required.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60510,\n            \"She assented readily, so readily that I saw again the hand of Nature fighting for life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60646,\n            \"Then Van Helsing beckoned to me, and we went gently out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60787,\n            \"\\u201d I went downstairs with him, and as we were going there was a knock at the hall-door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61728,\n            \"Van Helsing turning to me, said: \\u201cHe is so young and strong and of blood so pure that we need not defibrinate it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62546,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShall I have a nurse?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62777,\n            \"When I told Mrs. Westenra that Dr. Van Helsing had directed that I should sit up with her she almost pooh-poohed the idea, pointing out her daughter\\u2019s renewed strength and excellent spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62831,\n            \"When her maid had prepared her for the night I came in, having in the meantime had supper, and took a seat by the bedside.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63243,\n            \"In the early morning her maid came, and I left her in her care and took myself back home, for I was anxious about many things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63272,\n            \"I sent a short wire to Van Helsing and to Arthur, telling them of the excellent result of the operation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63775,\n            \"I suppose it is that sickness and weakness are selfish things and turn our inner eyes and sympathy on ourselves, whilst health and strength give Love rein, and in thought and feeling he can wander where he wills.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63892,\n            \"Thank everybody for being so good to me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64652,\n            \"\\u201d When we stopped the operation, he attended to Lucy, whilst I applied digital pressure to my own incision.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65080,\n            \"When her mother came up to see her, she did not seem to notice any change whatever, but said to me gratefully:-\\u201cWe owe you so much, Dr. Seward, for all you have done, but you really must now take care not to overwork yourself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65229,\n            \"Van Helsing returned in a couple of hours, and presently said to me: \\u201cNow you go home, and eat much and drink enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65328,\n            \"\\u201d In the hall two of the maids came to me, and asked if they or either of them might not sit up with Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65356,\n            \"They implored me to let them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65363,\n            \"and when I said it was Dr. Van Helsing\\u2019s wish that either he or I should sit up, they asked me quite piteously to intercede with the \\u201cforeign gentleman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65398,\n            \"\\u201d I was much touched by their kindness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65407,\n            \"Perhaps it is because I am weak at present, and perhaps because it was on Lucy\\u2019s account, that their devotion was manifested;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65434,\n            \"for over and over again have I seen similar instances of woman\\u2019s kindness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66367,\n            \"\\u201d As we left the house in my fly, which was waiting, Van Helsing said:-\\u201cTo-night I can sleep in peace, and sleep I want-two nights of travel, much reading in the day between, and much anxiety on the day to follow, and a night to sit up, without to wink.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68357,\n            \"Thomas and his wife are hospitable folk, elderly, and without children, and if the specimen I enjoyed of their hospitality be of the average kind, their lives must be pretty comfortable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68804,\n            \"But, Lor\\u2019love yer\\u2019art, now that the old\\u2019ooman has stuck a chunk of her tea-cake in me, an\\u2019rinsed me out with her bloomin\\u2019old teapot, and I\\u2019ve lit hup, you may scratch my ears for all you\\u2019re worth, and won\\u2019t git even a growl out of me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68880,\n            \"I know what yer a-comin\\u2019at, that\\u2019ere escaped wolf.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68900,\n            \"I want you to give me your view of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68918,\n            \"and when I know the facts I\\u2019ll get you to say what you consider was the cause of it, and how you think the whole affair will end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69117,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, sir, it was about two hours after feedin\\u2019yesterday when I first hear my disturbance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69279,\n            \"He\\u2019ad white kid gloves on\\u2019is\\u2019 ands, and he pointed out the animiles to me and says: \\u2018 Keeper, these wolves seem upset at something.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69431,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cWell, it was a odd thing, but when the animiles see us a-talkin\\u2019they lay down, and when I went over to Bersicker he let me stroke his ears same as ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69543,\n            \"\\u2019 I says, tyking off my\\u2019at, for a man what trades in wolves, anceterer, is a good friend to keepers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69846,\n            \"At least, so he says, but I don\\u2019t give much for it myself, for if he did\\u2019e never said a word about it to his missis when\\u2019e got\\u2019ome, and it was only after the escape of the wolf was made known, and we had been up all night-a-huntin\\u2019of the Park for Bersicker, that he remembered seein\\u2019anything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70071,\n            \"\\u201d From the hearty way that both Thomas and his wife laughed at the joke I could see that it had done service before, and that the whole explanation was simply an elaborate sell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70107,\n            \"I couldn\\u2019t cope in badinage with the worthy Thomas, but I thought I knew a surer way to his heart, so I said:-\\u201cNow, Mr. Bilder, we\\u2019ll consider that first half-sovereign worked off, and this brother of his is waiting to be claimed when you\\u2019ve told me what you think will happen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70191,\n            \"\\u201cYe\\u2019ll excoose me, I know, for a-chaffin\\u2019of ye, but the old woman here winked at me, which was as much as telling me to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70486,\n            \"My eye, won\\u2019t some cook get a rum start when she sees his green eyes a-shining at her out of the dark!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70546,\n            \"If he doesn\\u2019t, and some nursemaid goes a-walkin\\u2019orf with a soldier, leavin\\u2019of the hinfant in the perambulator-well, then I shouldn\\u2019t be surprised if the census is one babby the less.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71239,\n            \"When the attendants rushed in, and we turned our attention to him, his employment positively sickened me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71285,\n            \"He was easily secured, and, to my surprise, went with the attendants quite placidly, simply repeating over and over again: \\u201cThe blood is the life!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71615,\n            \"- I write this and leave it to be seen, so that no one may by any chance get into trouble through me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71822,\n            \"so, as I feared to be alone, I opened my door and called out: \\u201cIs there anybody there?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72312,\n            \"I kept my eyes fixed on the window, but the wolf drew his head back, and a whole myriad of little specks seemed to come blowing in through the broken window, and wheeling and circling round like the pillar of dust that travellers describe when there is a simoon in the desert.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72501,\n            \"The sounds seemed to have awakened the maids, too, for I could hear their bare feet pattering outside my door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72524,\n            \"I called to them, and they came in, and when they saw what had happened, and what it was that lay over me on the bed, they screamed out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72573,\n            \"They lifted off the body of my dear mother, and laid her, covered up with a sheet, on the bed after I had got up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72602,\n            \"They were all so frightened and nervous that I directed them to go to the dining-room and have each a glass of wine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72670,\n            \"When they were there I remembered what Dr. Van Helsing had told me, but I didn\\u2019t like to remove them, and, besides, I would have some of the servants to sit up with me now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72713,\n            \"I was surprised that the maids did not come back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72724,\n            \"I called them, but got no answer, so I went to the dining-room to look for them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72939,\n            \"I shall hide this paper in my breast, where they shall find it when they come to lay me out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73085,\n            \"I cursed the laziness of the servants that they should lie abed at such an hour-for it was now ten o\\u2019clock-and so rang and knocked again, but more impatiently, but still without response.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73272,\n            \"They stopped at the gate, and a few seconds later I met Van Helsing running up the avenue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73328,\n            \"\\u201d I answered as quickly and coherently as I could that I had only got his telegram early in the morning, and had not lost a minute in coming here, and that I could not make any one in the house hear me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73617,\n            \"Van Helsing and I looked at each other, and as we moved away he said: \\u201cWe can attend to them later.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73693,\n            \"How shall I describe what we saw?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73996,\n            \"You go wake those maids.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74052,\n            \"\\u201d I went at once, and found little difficulty in waking three of the women.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74069,\n            \"The fourth was only a young girl, and the drug had evidently affected her more strongly, so I lifted her on the sofa and let her sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74122,\n            \"I was stern with them, however, and would not let them talk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74137,\n            \"I told them that one life was bad enough to lose, and that if they delayed they would sacrifice Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74277,\n            \"I bade her simply tell him that he must wait, for we could see no one now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74296,\n            \"She went away with the message, and, engrossed with our work, I clean forgot all about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74358,\n            \"He answered me in a way that I did not understand, but with the sternest look that his face could wear:-\\u201cIf that were all, I would stop here where we are now, and let her fade away into peace, for I see no light in life over her horizon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74473,\n            \"Van Helsing\\u2019s face almost beamed, and as we lifted her from the bath and rolled her in a hot sheet to dry her he said to me:-\\u201cThe first gain is ours!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74585,\n            \"Van Helsing called in one of the women, and told her to stay with her and not to take her eyes off her till we returned, and then beckoned me out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74734,\n            \"He was evidently torturing his mind about something, so I waited for an instant, and he spoke:-\\u201cWhat are we to do now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74930,\n            \"\\u201d I cried as our hands met.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75206,\n            \"The Professor watched whilst I went downstairs with Quincey Morris, and sent one of the maids to pay off one of the cabmen who were waiting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75234,\n            \"I left Quincey lying down after having a glass of wine, and told the cook to get ready a good breakfast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75340,\n            \"He handed me the paper saying only: \\u201cIt dropped from Lucy\\u2019s breast when we carried her to the bath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75539,\n            \"I am in hopes that we need have no inquest, for if we had it would surely kill poor Lucy, if nothing else did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75566,\n            \"I know, and you know, and the other doctor who attended her knows, that Mrs. Westenra had disease of the heart, and we can certify that she died of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75602,\n            \"Let us fill up the certificate at once, and I shall take it myself to the registrar and go on to the undertaker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75710,\n            \"\\u201d In the hall I met Quincey Morris, with a telegram for Arthur telling him that Mrs. Westenra was dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75757,\n            \"I told him where I was going, and he hurried me out, but as I was going said:-\\u201cWhen you come back, Jack, may I have two words with you all to ourselves?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75955,\n            \"When we were alone, he said to me:-\\u201cJack Seward, I don\\u2019t want to shove myself in anywhere where I\\u2019ve no right to be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76476,\n            \"Then I guess, Jack Seward, that that poor pretty creature that we all love has had put into her veins within that time the blood of four strong men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76975,\n            \"The Professor and I took it in turns to watch, and we never left her for a moment unattended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77375,\n            \"I fear that to-morrow will end our watching, for the shock has been too great;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77642,\n            \"\\u201cSo here we are, installed in this beautiful old house, and from both my bedroom and the drawing-room I can see the great elms of the cathedral close, with their great black stems standing out against the old yellow stone of the cathedral and I can hear the rooks overhead cawing and cawing and chattering and gossiping all day, after the manner of rooks-and humans.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78110,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear Sir,-\\u201cIn accordance with your wishes, I enclose report of the conditions of everything left in my charge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78237,\n            \"I was myself looking out of the study window, having a smoke after dinner, and saw one of them come up to the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78621,\n            \"I called to the attendants to follow me, and ran after him, for I feared he was intent on some mischief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78692,\n            \"Before I could get up to him the patient rushed at them, and pulling one of them off the cart, began to knock his head against the ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78805,\n            \"You know I am no light weight, and the others were both burly men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79079,\n            \"I quite understood their drift, and after a stiff glass of grog, or rather more of the same, and with each a sovereign in hand, they made light of the attack, and swore that they would encounter a worse madman any day for the pleasure of meeting so \\u2018 bloomin\\u2019good a bloke\\u2019as your correspondent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79569,\n            \"but, Lucy dear, I must tell some one, for the strain of keeping up a brave and cheerful appearance to Jonathan tries me, and I have no one here that I can confide in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79608,\n            \"I dread coming up to London, as we must do the day after to-morrow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79835,\n            \"It was only when I told him that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80847,\n            \"\\u201d When we came into Lucy\\u2019s room I could see that Van Helsing had, with his usual forethought, been putting matters straight and making everything look as pleasing as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81288,\n            \"I kept my eyes fixed on Lucy, as did Van Helsing, and we saw a spasm as of rage flit like a shadow over her face;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81759,\n            \"\\u201d When I asked him what he meant, he only shook his head and answered:-\\u201cWe can do nothing as yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81822,\n            \"I attended to all the ghastly formalities, and the urbane undertaker proved that his staff were afflicted-or blessed-with something of his own obsequious suavity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81989,\n            \"Under the circumstances, Van Helsing and I took it upon ourselves to examine papers, etc.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82018,\n            \"I asked him why, for I feared that he, being a foreigner, might not be quite aware of English legal requirements, and so might in ignorance make some unnecessary trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82065,\n            \"You forget that I am a lawyer as well as a doctor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82146,\n            \"\\u201cWhen you find anything of the solicitor who is for the late Mrs. Westenra, seal all her papers, and write him to-night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82219,\n            \"\\u201d I went on with my part of the work, and in another half hour had found the name and address of Mrs. Westenra\\u2019s solicitor and had written to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82421,\n            \"\\u201d When we had finished the work in hand, he said to me:-\\u201cAnd now, friend John, I think we may to bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82451,\n            \"We want sleep, both you and I, and rest to recuperate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82588,\n            \"All Lucy\\u2019s loveliness had come back to her in death, and the hours that had passed, instead of leaving traces of \\u201cdecay\\u2019s effacing fingers,\\u201dhad but restored the beauty of life, till positively I could not believe my eyes that I was looking at a corpse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82868,\n            \"you a surgeon, and so shocked!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83248,\n            \"Were you not amazed, nay horrified, when I would not let Arthur kiss his love-though she was dying-and snatched him away by all my strength?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83282,\n            \"And yet you saw how she thanked me, with her so beautiful dying eyes, her voice, too, so weak, and she kiss my rough old hand and bless me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83319,\n            \"And did you not hear me swear promise to her, that so she closed her eyes grateful?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84627,\n            \"The Professor noticed it, too, and motioned me to bring him upstairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84642,\n            \"I did so, and left him at the door of the room, as I felt he would like to be quite alone with her, but he took my arm and led me in, saying huskily:-\\u201cYou loved her too, old fellow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84692,\n            \"she told me all about it, and there was no friend had a closer place in her heart than you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84714,\n            \"I don\\u2019t know how to thank you for all you have done for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84856,\n            \"I stood still and silent till his sobs died away, and then I said softly to him:-\\u201cCome and look at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84883,\n            \"\\u201d Together we moved over to the bed, and I lifted the lawn from her face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84946,\n            \"At last, after a long pause, he said to me in a faint whisper:-\\u201cJack, is she really dead?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85181,\n            \"When he came out of the room again I told him of Arthur\\u2019s question, and he replied:-\\u201cI am not surprised.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85218,\n            \"\\u201d We all dined together, and I could see that poor Art was trying to make the best of things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85683,\n            \"\\u201d The Professor cleared his throat a couple of times, as though about to speak, and finally said:-\\u201cMay I ask you something now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86241,\n            \"I am rusty in my shorthand-see what unexpected prosperity does for us-so it may be as well to freshen it up again with an exercise anyhow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86323,\n            \"Jonathan and I stood hand in hand, and we felt that our best and dearest friend was gone from us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86364,\n            \"Jonathan thought it would interest me to go into the Row for a while, so we sat down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86449,\n            \"I felt it very improper, for you can\\u2019t go on for some years teaching etiquette and decorum to other girls without the pedantry of it biting into yourself a bit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86657,\n            \"He was looking at her so hard that he did not see either of us, and so I had a good view of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87342,\n            \"and now a telegram from Van Helsing, whoever he may be:-\\u201cYou will be grieved to hear that Mrs. Westenra died five days ago, and that Lucy died the day before yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87483,\n            \"I believe in my heart of hearts that he suffered as much about Lucy\\u2019s death as any of us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87816,\n            \"He laughed till he cried, and I had to draw down the blinds lest any one should see us and misjudge;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88005,\n            \"Keep it always with you that laughter who knock at your door and say, \\u2018 May I come in?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88124,\n            \"And yet I can laugh at her very grave-laugh when the clay from the spade of the sexton drop upon her coffin and say \\u2018 Thud!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88219,\n            \"And yet when he say things that touch my husband-heart to the quick, and make my father-heart yearn to him as to no other man-not even to you, friend John, for we are more level in experiences than father and son-yet even at such moment King Laugh he come to me and shout and bellow in my ear, \\u2018 Here I am!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88530,\n            \"As he answered me his face grew stern, and he said in quite a different tone:-\\u201cOh, it was the grim irony of it all-this so lovely lady garlanded with flowers, that looked so fair as life, till one by one we wondered if she were truly dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88695,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, for the life of me, Professor,\\u201dI said, \\u201cI can\\u2019t see anything to laugh at in all that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88937,\n            \"I showed not my feeling to others when it would wound, but only to you, my old friend, whom I can trust.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89141,\n            \"and God only knows if I shall ever begin another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90104,\n            \"I remember how on our wedding-day he said: \\u201cUnless some solemn duty come upon me to go back to the bitter hours, asleep or awake, mad or sane.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90365,\n            \"By the kindness of Lord Godalming, I am empowered to read her letters and papers, for I am deeply concerned about certain matters vitally important.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90393,\n            \"In them I find some letters from you, which show how great friends you were and how you love her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90477,\n            \"I am friend of Dr. John Seward and of Lord Godalming (that was Arthur of Miss Lucy).\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90844,\n            \"I hope I did right in not saying anything of it to Mrs. Westenra;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90920,\n            \"I suppose a cry does us all good at times-clears the air as other rain does.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90939,\n            \"Perhaps it was reading the journal yesterday that upset me, and then Jonathan went away this morning to stay away from me a whole day and night, the first time we have been parted since our marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91670,\n            \"He said to me:-\\u201cMrs. Harker, is it not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91736,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cSir,\\u201dI said, \\u201cyou could have no better claim on me than that you were a friend and helper of Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92051,\n            \"\\u201d I could not resist the temptation of mystifying him a bit-I suppose it is some of the taste of the original apple that remains still in our mouths-so I handed him the shorthand diary.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 9]\": [\n        [\n            129361,\n            \"He said to Madam Mina, as I see in your diary of yesterday, that he had once had such a belief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129843,\n            \"Friend John, it does rejoice me unspeakable that she is no more to be pained, no more to be worried with our terrible things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133114,\n            \"By the first post I got my directed envelope with a dirty scrap of paper enclosed, on which was written with a carpenter\\u2019s pencil in a sprawling hand:-\\u201cSam Bloxam, Korkrans, 4, Poters Cort, Bartel Street, Walworth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134999,\n            \"When I asked who had purchased it, he opened his eyes a thought wider, and paused a few seconds before replying:-\\u201cIt is sold, sir.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135732,\n            \"when I had finished Van Helsing said:-\\u201cThis has been a great day\\u2019s work, friend Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136340,\n            \"\\u201d He smiled on me in quite a superior sort of way-such a smile as would have become the face of Malvolio-as he answered me:-\\u201cThe fly, my dear sir, has one striking feature;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136526,\n            \"You must get a new patient, doctor, if you wish to study zo\\u00f6phagy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138048,\n            \"\\u201cTo hell with you and your souls!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138114,\n            \"The instant, however, that I did so he became calm, and said apologetically:-\\u201cForgive me, Doctor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138677,\n            \"\\u201cMy Lord, \\u201cWe are at all times only too happy to meet your wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138695,\n            \"We beg, with regard to the desire of your Lordship, expressed by Mr. Harker on your behalf, to supply the following information concerning the sale and purchase of No.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138798,\n            \"\\u201cWe are, my Lord, \\u201cYour Lordship\\u2019s humble servants, \\u201cMitchell, Sons & Candy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173591,\n            \"Then holding the pages between his finger and thumb he said:-\\u201cFriend John, to you with so much of experience already-and you, too, dear Madam Mina, that are young-here is a lesson: do not fear ever to think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175256,\n            \"You must be scribe and write him all down, so that when the others return from their work you can give it to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 10]\": [\n        [\n            15525,\n            \"When he had satisfied himself on these points of which he had spoken, and I had verified all as well as I could by the books available, he suddenly stood up and said:-\\u201cHave you written since your first letter to our friend Mr. Peter Hawkins, or to any other?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15615,\n            \"\\u201cThen write now, my young friend,\\u201dhe said, laying a heavy hand on my shoulder: \\u201cwrite to our friend and to any other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15755,\n            \"It was Mr. Hawkins\\u2019 s interest, not mine, and I had to think of him, not myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15990,\n            \"So I determined to write only formal notes now, but to write fully to Mr. Hawkins in secret, and also to Mina, for to her I could write in shorthand, which would puzzle the Count, if he did see it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20701,\n            \"Mina\\u2019s is in shorthand, and I simply ask Mr. Hawkins to communicate with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20920,\n            \"\\\"-he must have looked at it-\\\" one is from you, and to my friend Peter Hawkins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36801,\n            \"- Another week gone, and no news from Jonathan, not even to Mr. Hawkins, from whom I have heard.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 11]\": [\n        [\n            314,\n            \"it had struck me that some foreknowledge of the country could hardly fail to have some importance in dealing with a nobleman of that country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            340,\n            \"I find that the district he named is in the extreme east of the country, just on the borders of three states, Transylvania, Moldavia and Bukovina, in the midst of the Carpathian mountains;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            428,\n            \"but I found that Bistritz, the post town named by Count Dracula, is a fairly well-known place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            603,\n            \", I must ask the Count all about them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1283,\n            \"Count Dracula had directed me to go to the Golden Krone Hotel, which I found, to my great delight, to be thoroughly old-fashioned, for of course I wanted to see all I could of the ways of the country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1450,\n            \"I am anxiously expecting you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1483,\n            \"At the Borgo Pass my carriage will await you and will bring you to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1499,\n            \"I trust that your journey from London has been a happy one, and that you will enjoy your stay in my beautiful land.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1535,\n            \"- I found that my landlord had got a letter from the Count, directing him to secure the best place on the coach for me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1657,\n            \"When I asked him if he knew Count Dracula, and could tell me anything of his castle, both he and his wife crossed themselves, and, saying that they knew nothing at all, simply refused to speak further.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2668,\n            \", I must ask the Count about these superstitions) When we started, the crowd round the inn door, which had by this time swelled to a considerable size, all made the sign of the cross and pointed two fingers towards me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2759,\n            \"This was not very pleasant for me, just starting for an unknown place to meet an unknown man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4360,\n            \"I was now myself looking out for the conveyance which was to take me to the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4740,\n            \"\\u201d The man stammered in reply:-\\u201cThe English Herr was in a hurry,\\u201dto which the stranger replied:-\\u201cThat is why, I suppose, you wished him to go on to Bukovina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4907,\n            \"\\u201cGive me the Herr\\u2019s luggage,\\u201dsaid the driver;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5075,\n            \"but a cloak was thrown over my shoulders, and a rug across my knees, and the driver said in excellent German:-\\u201cThe night is chill, mein Herr, and my master the Count bade me take all care of you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7543,\n            \"so to make sure, I said interrogatively:-\\u201cCount Dracula?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7574,\n            \"and I bid you welcome, Mr. Harker, to my house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7606,\n            \"\\u201d As he was speaking, he put the lamp on a bracket on the wall, and stepping out, took my luggage;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7631,\n            \"he had carried it in before I could forestall him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7642,\n            \"I protested but he insisted:-\\u201cNay, sir, you are my guest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7670,\n            \"Let me see to your comfort myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7678,\n            \"\\u201d He insisted on carrying my traps along the passage, and then up a great winding stair, and along another great passage, on whose stone floor our steps rang heavily.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7712,\n            \"At the end of this he threw open a heavy door, and I rejoiced to see within a well-lit room in which a table was spread for supper, and on whose mighty hearth a great fire of logs, freshly replenished, flamed and flared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7762,\n            \"The Count halted, putting down my bags, closed the door, and crossing the room, opened another door, which led into a small octagonal room lit by a single lamp, and seemingly without a window of any sort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7866,\n            \"The Count himself left my luggage inside and withdrew, saying, before he closed the door:-\\u201cYou will need, after your journey, to refresh yourself by making your toilet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7902,\n            \"I trust you will find all you wish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7930,\n            \"\\u201d The light and warmth and the Count\\u2019s courteous welcome seemed to have dissipated all my doubts and fears.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7989,\n            \"My host, who stood on one side of the great fireplace, leaning against the stonework, made a graceful wave of his hand to the table, and said:-\\u201cI pray you, be seated and sup how you please.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8035,\n            \"You will, I trust, excuse me that I do not join you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8062,\n            \"\\u201d I handed to him the sealed letter which Mr. Hawkins had entrusted to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8087,\n            \"then, with a charming smile, he handed it to me to read.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8117,\n            \"\\u201cI must regret that an attack of gout, from which malady I am a constant sufferer, forbids absolutely any travelling on my part for some time to come;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8209,\n            \"He shall be ready to attend on you when you will during his stay, and shall take your instructions in all matters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8233,\n            \"\\u201d The Count himself came forward and took off the cover of a dish, and I fell to at once on an excellent roast chicken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8286,\n            \"During the time I was eating it the Count asked me many questions as to my journey, and I told him by degrees all I had experienced.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8315,\n            \"By this time I had finished my supper, and by my host\\u2019s desire had drawn up a chair by the fire and begun to smoke a cigar which he offered me, at the same time excusing himself that he did not smoke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8362,\n            \"I had now an opportunity of observing him, and found him of a very marked physiognomy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8532,\n            \"Hitherto I had noticed the backs of his hands as they lay on his knees in the firelight, and they had seemed rather white and fine;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8613,\n            \"As the Count leaned over me and his hands touched me, I could not repress a shudder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8632,\n            \"It may have been that his breath was rank, but a horrible feeling of nausea came over me, which, do what I would, I could not conceal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8788,\n            \"\\u201d Seeing, I suppose, some expression in my face strange to him, he added:-\\u201cAh, sir, you dwellers in the city cannot enter into the feelings of the hunter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8826,\n            \"\\u201d Then he rose and said:-\\u201cBut you must be tired.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8876,\n            \"\\u201d With a courteous bow, he opened for me himself the door to the octagonal room, and I entered my bedroom.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9269,\n            \"Some time after I had finished my meal-I do not know whether to call it breakfast or dinner, for it was between five and six o\\u2019clock when I had it-I looked about for something to read, for I did not like to go about the castle until I had asked the Count\\u2019s permission.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9516,\n            \"Whilst I was looking at the books, the door opened, and the Count entered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9533,\n            \"He saluted me in a hearty way, and hoped that I had had a good night\\u2019s rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9554,\n            \"Then he went on:-\\u201cI am glad you found your way in here, for I am sure there is much that will interest you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9583,\n            \"These companions \\\"-and he laid his hand on some of the books-\\\" have been good friends to me, and for some years past, ever since I had the idea of going to London, have given me many, many hours of pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9633,\n            \"Through them I have come to know your great England;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9702,\n            \"as yet I only know your tongue through books.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9712,\n            \"To you, my friend, I look that I know it to speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9727,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut, Count,\\u201dI said, \\u201cyou know and speak English thoroughly!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9750,\n            \"\\u201cI thank you, my friend, for your all too-flattering estimate, but yet I fear that I am but a little way on the road I would travel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9804,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed,\\u201dI said, \\u201cyou speak excellently.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9826,\n            \"\\u201cWell, I know that, did I move and speak in your London, none there are who would not know me for a stranger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9974,\n            \"You come to me not alone as agent of my friend Peter Hawkins, of Exeter, to tell me all about my new estate in London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10002,\n            \"You shall, I trust, rest here with me awhile, so that by our talking I may learn the English intonation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10062,\n            \"but you will, I know, forgive one who has so many important affairs in hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10105,\n            \"He answered: \\u201cYes, certainly,\\u201dand added:-\\u201cYou may go anywhere you wish in the castle, except where the doors are locked, where of course you will not wish to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10146,\n            \"There is reason that all things are as they are, and did you see with my eyes and know with my knowledge, you would perhaps better understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10221,\n            \"Nay, from what you have told me of your experiences already, you know something of what strange things there may be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10252,\n            \"and as it was evident that he wanted to talk, if only for talking\\u2019s sake, I asked him many questions regarding things that had already happened to me or come within my notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10307,\n            \"but generally he answered all I asked most frankly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10317,\n            \"Then as time went on, and I had got somewhat bolder, I asked him of some of the strange things of the preceding night, as, for instance, why the coachman went to the places where he had seen the blue flames.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10364,\n            \"He then explained to me that it was commonly believed that on a certain night of the year-last night, in fact, when all evil spirits are supposed to have unchecked sway-a blue flame is seen over any place where treasure has been concealed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10414,\n            \"\\u201cThat treasure has been hidden,\\u201dhe went on, \\u201cin the region through which you came last night, there can be but little doubt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10638,\n            \"he answered:-\\u201cBecause your peasant is at heart a coward and a fool!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10702,\n            \"Why, even the peasant that you tell me of who marked the place of the flame would not know where to look in daylight even for his own work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10733,\n            \"Even you would not, I dare be sworn, be able to find these places again?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10751,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere you are right,\\u201dI said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10785,\n            \"\\u201cCome,\\u201dhe said at last, \\u201ctell me of London and of the house which you have procured for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10881,\n            \"The lamps were also lit in the study or library, and I found the Count lying on the sofa, reading, of all things in the world, an English Bradshaw\\u2019s Guide.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10918,\n            \"When I came in he cleared the books and papers from the table;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10932,\n            \"and with him I went into plans and deeds and figures of all sorts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10947,\n            \"He was interested in everything, and asked me a myriad questions about the place and its surroundings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10966,\n            \"He clearly had studied beforehand all he could get on the subject of the neighbourhood, for he evidently at the end knew very much more than I did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10996,\n            \"When I remarked this, he answered:-\\u201cWell, but, my friend, is it not needful that I should?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11021,\n            \"When I go there I shall be all alone, and my friend Harker Jonathan-nay, pardon me, I fall into my country\\u2019s habit of putting your patronymic first-my friend Jonathan Harker will not be by my side to correct and aid me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11114,\n            \"When I had told him the facts and got his signature to the necessary papers, and had written a letter with them ready to post to Mr. Hawkins, he began to ask me how I had come across so suitable a place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11160,\n            \"I read to him the notes which I had made at the time, and which I inscribe here:-\\u201cAt Purfleet, on a by-road, I came across just such a place as seemed to be required, and where was displayed a dilapidated notice that the place was for sale.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11530,\n            \"\\u201d When I had finished, he said:-\\u201cI am glad that it is old and big.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11551,\n            \"I myself am of an old family, and to live in a new house would kill me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11749,\n            \"Presently, with an excuse, he left me, asking me to put all my papers together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11768,\n            \"He was some little time away, and I began to look at some of the books around me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11810,\n            \"On looking at it I found in certain places little rings marked, and on examining these I noticed that one was near London on the east side, manifestly where his new estate was situated;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11897,\n            \"I am informed that your supper is ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11906,\n            \"\\u201d He took my arm, and we went into the next room, where I found an excellent supper ready on the table.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11949,\n            \"But he sat as on the previous night, and chatted whilst I ate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11964,\n            \"After supper I smoked, as on the last evening, and the Count stayed with me, chatting and asking questions on every conceivable subject, hour after hour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11995,\n            \"I felt that it was getting very late indeed, but I did not say anything, for I felt under obligation to meet my host\\u2019s wishes in every way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12167,\n            \"How remiss I am to let you stay up so long.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12179,\n            \"You must make your conversation regarding my dear new country of England less interesting, so that I may not forget how time flies by us,\\u201dand, with a courtly bow, he quickly left me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12381,\n            \"I have only the Count to speak with, and he!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12497,\n            \"Suddenly I felt a hand on my shoulder, and heard the Count\\u2019s voice saying to me, \\u201cGood-morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12522,\n            \"\\u201d I started, for it amazed me that I had not seen him, since the reflection of the glass covered the whole room behind me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12567,\n            \"Having answered the Count\\u2019s salutation, I turned to the glass again to see how I had been mistaken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12589,\n            \"This time there could be no error, for the man was close to me, and I could see him over my shoulder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12647,\n            \"This was startling, and, coming on the top of so many strange things, was beginning to increase that vague feeling of uneasiness which I always have when the Count is near;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12725,\n            \"When the Count saw my face, his eyes blazed with a sort of demoniac fury, and he suddenly made a grab at my throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12752,\n            \"I drew away, and his hand touched the string of beads which held the crucifix.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12769,\n            \"It made an instant change in him, for the fury passed so quickly that I could hardly believe that it was ever there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12794,\n            \"\\u201cTake care,\\u201dhe said, \\u201ctake care how you cut yourself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12953,\n            \"but I could not find the Count anywhere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12967,\n            \"It is strange that as yet I have not seen the Count eat or drink.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13328,\n            \"that it is no use making my ideas known to the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13341,\n            \"He knows well that I am imprisoned;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13349,\n            \"and as he has done it himself, and has doubtless his own motives for it, he would only deceive me if I trusted him fully with the facts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13455,\n            \"I had hardly come to this conclusion when I heard the great door below shut, and knew that the Count had returned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13479,\n            \"He did not come at once into the library, so I went cautiously to my own room and found him making the bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13527,\n            \"When later I saw him through the chink of the hinges of the door laying the table in the dining-room, I was assured of it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13580,\n            \"This gave me a fright, for if there is no one else in the castle, it must have been the Count himself who was the driver of the coach that brought me here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13807,\n            \"In the meantime I must find out all I can about Count Dracula, as it may help me to understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13829,\n            \"To-night he may talk of himself, if I turn the conversation that way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13846,\n            \"I must be very careful, however, not to awake his suspicion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13862,\n            \"- I have had a long talk with the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13873,\n            \"I asked him a few questions on Transylvania history, and he warmed up to the subject wonderfully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13892,\n            \"In his speaking of things and people, and especially of battles, he spoke as if he had been present at them all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13917,\n            \"This he afterwards explained by saying that to a boyar the pride of his house and name is his own pride, that their glory is his glory, that their fate is his fate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13953,\n            \"Whenever he spoke of his house he always said \\u201cwe,\\u201dand spoke almost in the plural, like a king speaking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13978,\n            \"I wish I could put down all he said exactly as he said it, for to me it was most fascinating.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14050,\n            \"One thing he said which I shall put down as nearly as I can;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14065,\n            \"for it tells in its way the story of his race:-\\u201cWe Szekelys have a right to be proud, for in our veins flows the blood of many brave races who fought as the lion fights, for lordship.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14555,\n            \"who, when he was beaten back, came again, and again, and again, though he had to come alone from the bloody field where his troops were being slaughtered, since he knew that he alone could ultimately triumph!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14599,\n            \"They said that he thought only of himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14670,\n            \"Ah, young sir, the Szekelys-and the Dracula as their heart\\u2019s blood, their brains, and their swords-can boast a record that mushroom growths like the Hapsburgs and the Romanoffs can never reach.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14853,\n            \"Last evening when the Count came from his room he began by asking me questions on legal matters and on the doing of certain kinds of business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14915,\n            \"There was a certain method in the Count\\u2019s inquiries, so I shall try to put them down in sequence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14950,\n            \"First, he asked if a man in England might have two solicitors or more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14966,\n            \"I told him he might have a dozen if he wished, but that it would not be wise to have more than one solicitor engaged in one transaction, as only one could act at a time, and that to change would be certain to militate against his interest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15018,\n            \"He seemed thoroughly to understand, and went on to ask if there would be any practical difficulty in having one man to attend, say, to banking, and another to look after shipping, in case local help were needed in a place far from the home of the banking solicitor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15073,\n            \"I asked him to explain more fully, so that I might not by any chance mislead him, so he said:-\\u201cI shall illustrate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15102,\n            \"Your friend and mine, Mr. Peter Hawkins, from under the shadow of your beautiful cathedral at Exeter, which is far from London, buys for me through your good self my place at London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15143,\n            \"Now here let me say frankly, lest you should think it strange that I have sought the services of one so far off from London instead of some one resident there, that my motive was that no local interest might be served save my wish only;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15192,\n            \"and as one of London residence might, perhaps, have some purpose of himself or friend to serve, I went thus afield to seek my agent, whose labours should be only to my interest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15525,\n            \"When he had satisfied himself on these points of which he had spoken, and I had verified all as well as I could by the books available, he suddenly stood up and said:-\\u201cHave you written since your first letter to our friend Mr. Peter Hawkins, or to any other?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15615,\n            \"\\u201cThen write now, my young friend,\\u201dhe said, laying a heavy hand on my shoulder: \\u201cwrite to our friend and to any other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15646,\n            \"and say, if it will please you, that you shall stay with me until a month from now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15667,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo you wish me to stay so long?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15705,\n            \"When your master, employer, what you will, engaged that someone should come on his behalf, it was understood that my needs only were to be consulted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15778,\n            \"and besides, while Count Dracula was speaking, there was that in his eyes and in his bearing which made me remember that I was a prisoner, and that if I wished it I could have no choice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15819,\n            \"The Count saw his victory in my bow, and his mastery in the trouble of my face, for he began at once to use them, but in his own smooth, resistless way:-\\u201cI pray you, my good young friend, that you will not discourse of things other than business in your letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15910,\n            \"\\u201d As he spoke he handed me three sheets of note-paper and three envelopes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15927,\n            \"They were all of the thinnest foreign post, and looking at them, then at him, and noticing his quiet smile, with the sharp, canine teeth lying over the red underlip, I understood as well as if he had spoken that I should be careful what I wrote, for he would be able to read it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15990,\n            \"So I determined to write only formal notes now, but to write fully to Mr. Hawkins in secret, and also to Mina, for to her I could write in shorthand, which would puzzle the Count, if he did see it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16037,\n            \"When I had written my two letters I sat quiet, reading a book whilst the Count wrote several notes, referring as he wrote them to some books on his table.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16070,\n            \"Then he took up my two and placed them with his own, and put by his writing materials, after which, the instant the door had closed behind him, I leaned over and looked at the letters, which were face down on the table.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16222,\n            \"I sank back in my seat, having just had time to replace the letters as they had been and to resume my book before the Count, holding still another letter in his hand, entered the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16262,\n            \"He took up the letters on the table and stamped them carefully, and then turning to me, said:-\\u201cI trust you will forgive me, but I have much work to do in private this evening.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16304,\n            \"You will, I hope, find all things as you wish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16317,\n            \"\\u201d At the door he turned, and after a moment\\u2019s pause said:-\\u201cLet me advise you, my dear young friend-nay, let me warn you with all seriousness, that should you leave these rooms you will not by any chance go to sleep in any other part of the castle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16434,\n            \"But if you be not careful in this respect, then \\\"-He finished his speech in a gruesome way, for he motioned with his hands as if he were washing them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16522,\n            \"I shall not fear to sleep in any place where he is not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16565,\n            \"When he left me I went to my room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16777,\n            \"As I leaned from the window my eye was caught by something moving a storey below me, and somewhat to my left, where I imagined, from the order of the rooms, that the windows of the Count\\u2019s own room would look out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16875,\n            \"What I saw was the Count\\u2019s head coming out from the window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16890,\n            \"I did not see the face, but I knew the man by the neck and the movement of his back and arms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16962,\n            \"But my very feelings changed to repulsion and terror when I saw the whole man slowly emerge from the window and begin to crawl down the castle wall over that dreadful abyss, face down with his cloak spreading out around him like great wings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17159,\n            \"- Once more have I seen the Count go out in his lizard fashion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17203,\n            \"When his head had disappeared, I leaned out to try and see more, but without avail-the distance was too great to allow a proper angle of sight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17235,\n            \"I knew he had left the castle now, and thought to use the opportunity to explore more than I had dared to do as yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17351,\n            \"I must watch should his door be unlocked, so that I may get it and escape.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17824,\n            \"Still, it was better than living alone in the rooms which I had come to hate from the presence of the Count, and after trying a little to school my nerves, I found a soft quietude come over me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18027,\n            \"If I be sane, then surely it is maddening to think that of all the foul things that lurk in this hateful place the Count is the least dreadful to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18060,\n            \"that to him alone I can look for safety, even though this be only whilst I can serve his purpose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18199,\n            \"The Count\\u2019s mysterious warning frightened me at the time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18211,\n            \"it frightens me more now when I think of it, for in future he has a fearful hold upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18233,\n            \"I shall fear to doubt what he may say!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18265,\n            \"The Count\\u2019s warning came into my mind, but I took a pleasure in disobeying it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19198,\n            \"I was conscious of the presence of the Count, and of his being as if lapped in a storm of fury.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19221,\n            \"As my eyes opened involuntarily I saw his strong hand grasp the slender neck of the fair woman and with giant\\u2019s power draw it back, the blue eyes transformed with fury, the white teeth champing with rage, and the fair cheeks blazing red with passion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19356,\n            \"With a fierce sweep of his arm, he hurled the woman from him, and then motioned to the others, as though he were beating them back;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19401,\n            \"In a voice which, though low and almost in a whisper seemed to cut through the air and then ring round the room he said:-\\u201cHow dare you touch him, any of you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19440,\n            \"How dare you cast eyes on him when I had forbidden it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19453,\n            \"Back, I tell you all!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19466,\n            \"Beware how you meddle with him, or you\\u2019ll have to deal with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19549,\n            \"Then the Count turned, after looking at my face attentively, and said in a soft whisper:-\\u201cYes, I too can love;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19591,\n            \"Well, now I promise you that when I am done with him you shall kiss him at your will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19641,\n            \"\\u201d said one of them, with a low laugh, as she pointed to the bag which he had thrown upon the floor, and which moved as though there were some living thing within it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19829,\n            \"If it be that I had not dreamt, the Count must have carried me here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19962,\n            \"Of one thing I am glad: if it was that the Count carried me here and undressed me, he must have been hurried in his task, for my pockets are intact.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19997,\n            \"I am sure this diary would have been a mystery to him which he would not have brooked.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20179,\n            \"Last night the Count asked me in the suavest tones to write three letters, one saying that my work here was nearly done, and that I should start for home within a few days, another that I was starting on the next morning from the time of the letter, and the third that I had left the castle and arrived at Bistritz.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20246,\n            \"I would fain have rebelled, but felt that in the present state of things it would be madness to quarrel openly with the Count whilst I am so absolutely in his power;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20295,\n            \"He knows that I know too much, and that I must not live, lest I be dangerous to him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20338,\n            \"I saw in his eyes something of that gathering wrath which was manifest when he hurled that fair woman from him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20360,\n            \"He explained to me that posts were few and uncertain, and that my writing now would ensure ease of mind to my friends;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20385,\n            \"and he assured me with so much impressiveness that he would countermand the later letters, which would be held over at Bistritz until due time in case chance would admit of my prolonging my stay, that to oppose him would have been to create new suspicion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20434,\n            \"I therefore pretended to fall in with his views, and asked him what dates I should put on the letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20755,\n            \"Should the letters not carry, then the Count shall not yet know my secret or the extent of my knowledge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20850,\n            \"As the Count did not come in, I have written here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20871,\n            \"He sat down beside me, and said in his smoothest voice as he opened two letters:-\\u201cThe Szgany has given me these, of which, though I know not whence they come, I shall, of course, take care.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20920,\n            \"\\\"-he must have looked at it-\\\" one is from you, and to my friend Peter Hawkins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21050,\n            \"Your letters are sacred to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21057,\n            \"Your pardon, my friend, that unknowingly I did break the seal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21078,\n            \"\\u201d He held out the letter to me, and with a courteous bow handed me a clean envelope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21098,\n            \"I could only redirect it and hand it to him in silence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21111,\n            \"When he went out of the room I could hear the key turn softly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21142,\n            \"When, an hour or two after, the Count came quietly into the room, his coming awakened me, for I had gone to sleep on the sofa.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21173,\n            \"He was very courteous and very cheery in his manner, and seeing that I had been sleeping, he said:-\\u201cSo, my friend, you are tired?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21236,\n            \"but you will sleep, I pray.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21769,\n            \"- Last night the Count left me early, and locked himself into his own room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21809,\n            \"I thought I would watch for the Count, for there is something going on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21879,\n            \"I had been at the window somewhat less than half an hour, when I saw something coming out of the Count\\u2019s window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21905,\n            \"I drew back and watched carefully, and saw the whole man emerge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21919,\n            \"It was a new shock to me to find that he had on the suit of clothes which I had worn whilst travelling here, and slung over his shoulder the terrible bag which I had seen the women take away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21961,\n            \"There could be no doubt as to his quest, and in my garb, too!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21978,\n            \"This, then, is his new scheme of evil: that he will allow others to see me, as they think, so that he may both leave evidence that I have been seen in the towns or villages posting my own letters, and that any wickedness which he may do shall by the local people be attributed to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22084,\n            \"I thought I would watch for the Count\\u2019s return, and for a long time sat doggedly at the window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22398,\n            \"When a couple of hours had passed I heard something stirring in the Count\\u2019s room, something like a sharp wail quickly suppressed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22644,\n            \"Somewhere high overhead, probably on the tower, I heard the voice of the Count calling in his harsh, metallic whisper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22966,\n            \"I have not yet seen the Count in the daylight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22977,\n            \"Can it be that he sleeps when others wake, that he may be awake whilst they sleep?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22996,\n            \"If I could only get into his room!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23049,\n            \"I have seen him myself crawl from his window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23059,\n            \"Why should not I imitate him, and go in by his window?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23304,\n            \"I knew pretty well the direction and distance of the Count\\u2019s window, and made for it as well as I could, having regard to the opportunities available.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23394,\n            \"Then I looked around for the Count, but, with surprise and gladness, made a discovery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23906,\n            \"He was either dead or asleep, I could not say which-for the eyes were open and stony, but without the glassiness of death-and the cheeks had the warmth of life through all their pallor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24031,\n            \"I thought he might have the keys on him, but when I went to search I saw the dead eyes, and in them, dead though they were, such a look of hate, though unconscious of me or my presence, that I fled from the place, and leaving the Count\\u2019s room by the window, crawled again up the castle wall.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24123,\n            \"- To-day is the date of my last letter, and the Count has taken steps to prove that it was genuine, for again I saw him leave the castle by the same window, and in my clothes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24166,\n            \"As he went down the wall, lizard fashion, I wished I had a gun or some lethal weapon, that I might destroy him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24213,\n            \"I dared not wait to see him return, for I feared to see those weird sisters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24246,\n            \"I was awakened by the Count, who looked at me as grimly as a man can look as he said:-\\u201cTo-morrow, my friend, we must part.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24281,\n            \"You return to your beautiful England, I to some work which may have such an end that we may never meet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24311,\n            \"to-morrow I shall not be here, but all shall be ready for your journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24351,\n            \"When they have gone, my carriage shall come for you, and shall bear you to the Borgo Pass to meet the diligence from Bukovina to Bistritz.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24380,\n            \"But I am in hopes that I shall see more of you at Castle Dracula.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24396,\n            \"\\u201d I suspected him, and determined to test his sincerity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24410,\n            \"It seems like a profanation of the word to write it in connection with such a monster, so asked him point-blank:-\\u201cWhy may I not go to-night?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24480,\n            \"\\u201d He smiled, such a soft, smooth, diabolical smile that I knew there was some trick behind his smoothness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24503,\n            \"He said:-\\u201cAnd your baggage?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24530,\n            \"\\u201d The Count stood up, and said, with a sweet courtesy which made me rub my eyes, it seemed so real:-\\u201cYou English have a saying which is close to my heart, for its spirit is that which rules our boyars: \\u2018 Welcome the coming;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24589,\n            \"\\u2019 Come with me, my dear young friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24599,\n            \"Not an hour shall you wait in my house against your will, though sad am I at your going, and that you so suddenly desire it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24630,\n            \"\\u201d With a stately gravity, he, with the lamp, preceded me down the stairs and along the hall.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24670,\n            \"It was almost as if the sound sprang up at the rising of his hand, just as the music of a great orchestra seems to leap under the b\\u00e2ton of the conductor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24811,\n            \"I knew then that to struggle at the moment against the Count was useless.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24826,\n            \"With such allies as these at his command, I could do nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24892,\n            \"There was a diabolical wickedness in the idea great enough for the Count, and as a last chance I cried out:-\\u201cShut the door;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24997,\n            \"The last I saw of Count Dracula was his kissing his hand to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25012,\n            \"with a red light of triumph in his eyes, and with a smile that Judas in hell might be proud of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25065,\n            \"Unless my ears deceived me, I heard the voice of the Count:-\\u201cBack, back, to your own place!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25223,\n            \"I slept till just before the dawn, and when I woke threw myself on my knees, for I determined that if Death came he should find me ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25383,\n            \"It had been locked after I left the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25393,\n            \"Then a wild desire took me to obtain that key at any risk, and I determined then and there to scale the wall again and gain the Count\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25426,\n            \"He might kill me, but death now seemed the happier choice of evils.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25441,\n            \"Without a pause I rushed up to the east window, and scrambled down the wall, as before, into the Count\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25517,\n            \"I knew now well enough where to find the monster I sought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25732,\n            \"I shuddered as I bent over to touch him, and every sense in me revolted at the contact;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25799,\n            \"Then I stopped and looked at the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25824,\n            \"This was the being I was helping to transfer to London, where, perhaps, for centuries to come he might, amongst its teeming millions, satiate his lust for blood, and create a new and ever-widening circle of semi-demons to batten on the helpless.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26129,\n            \"the Szgany and the Slovaks of whom the Count had spoken were coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26143,\n            \"With a last look around and at the box which contained the vile body, I ran from the place and gained the Count\\u2019s room, determined to rush out at the moment the door should be opened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30850,\n            \"I have no hesitation in asking you, as I know a certain lady is engaged to a certain dinner-party, and that you are free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34398,\n            \"- The case of Renfield grows more interesting the more I get to understand the man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34444,\n            \"He seems to have some settled scheme of his own, but what it is I do not yet know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34465,\n            \"His redeeming quality is a love of animals, though, indeed, he has such curious turns in it that I sometimes imagine he is only abnormally cruel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34510,\n            \"He has at present such a quantity that I have had myself to expostulate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34525,\n            \"To my astonishment, he did not break out into a fury, as I expected, but took the matter in simple seriousness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34583,\n            \"I must watch him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34651,\n            \"- His spiders are now becoming as great a nuisance as his flies, and to-day I told him that he must get rid of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34680,\n            \"He looked very sad at this, so I said that he must clear out some of them, at all events.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34703,\n            \"He cheerfully acquiesced in this, and I gave him the same time as before for reduction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34721,\n            \"He disgusted me much while with him, for when a horrid blow-fly, bloated with some carrion food, buzzed into the room, he caught it, held it exultantly for a few moments between his finger and thumb, and, before I knew what he was going to do, put it in his mouth and ate it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34786,\n            \"I scolded him for it, but he argued quietly that it was very good and very wholesome;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34831,\n            \"I must watch how he gets rid of his spiders.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34869,\n            \"Whole pages of it are filled with masses of figures, generally single numbers added up in batches, and then the totals added in batches again, as though he were \\u201cfocussing\\u201dsome account, as the auditors put it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34916,\n            \"- There is a method in his madness, and the rudimentary idea in my mind is growing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34963,\n            \"I kept away from my friend for a few days, so that I might notice if there were any change.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35087,\n            \"When I came in he ran to me and said he wanted to ask me a great favour-a very, very great favour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35113,\n            \"and as he spoke he fawned on me like a dog.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35125,\n            \"I asked him what it was, and he said, with a sort of rapture in his voice and bearing:-\\u201cA kitten, a nice little, sleek playful kitten, that I can play with, and teach, and feed-and feed-and feed!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35178,\n            \"\\u201d I was not unprepared for this request, for I had noticed how his pets went on increasing in size and vivacity, but I did not care that his pretty family of tame sparrows should be wiped out in the same manner as the flies and the spiders;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35229,\n            \"so I said I would see about it, and asked him if he would not rather have a cat than a kitten.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35273,\n            \"I only asked for a kitten lest you should refuse me a cat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35287,\n            \"No one would refuse me a kitten, would they?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35325,\n            \"His face fell, and I could see a warning of danger in it, for there was a sudden fierce, sidelong look which meant killing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35353,\n            \"The man is an undeveloped homicidal maniac.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35361,\n            \"I shall test him with his present craving and see how it will work out;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35388,\n            \"- I have visited him again and found him sitting in a corner brooding.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35403,\n            \"When I came in he threw himself on his knees before me and implored me to let him have a cat;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35432,\n            \"I was firm, however, and told him that he could not have it, whereupon he went without a word, and sat down, gnawing his fingers, in the corner where I had found him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35472,\n            \"I shall see him in the morning early.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35541,\n            \"I looked around for his birds, and not seeing them, asked him where they were.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35590,\n            \"I said nothing, but went and told the keeper to report to me if there were anything odd about him during the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35620,\n            \"- The attendant has just been to me to say that Renfield has been very sick and has disgorged a whole lot of feathers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35645,\n            \"\\u201cMy belief is, doctor,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cthat he has eaten his birds, and that he just took and ate them raw!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35680,\n            \"- I gave Renfield a strong opiate to-night, enough to make even him sleep, and took away his pocket-book to look at it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35737,\n            \"I shall have to invent a new classification for him, and call him a zo\\u00f6phagous (life-eating) maniac;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35991,\n            \"I wonder at how many lives he values a man, or if at only one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95639,\n            \"so he had not been of any trouble to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113716,\n            \"Goodness knows that we had enough clues from the conduct of the patient Renfield!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113800,\n            \"He thinks that in the meantime I should see Renfield, as hitherto he has been a sort of index to the coming and going of the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113873,\n            \"I found Renfield sitting placidly in his room with his hands folded, smiling benignly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113889,\n            \"At the moment he seemed as sane as any one I ever saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113903,\n            \"I sat down and talked with him on a lot of subjects, all of which he treated naturally.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113923,\n            \"He then, of his own accord, spoke of going home, a subject he has never mentioned to my knowledge during his sojourn here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113964,\n            \"I believe that, had I not had the chat with Harker and read the letters and the dates of his outbursts, I should have been prepared to sign for him after a brief time of observation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114134,\n            \"I mistrust these quiet moods of his;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114142,\n            \"so I have given the attendant a hint to look closely after him, and to have a strait-waistcoat ready in case of need.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115244,\n            \"I shall try to see the carter who took away the boxes from Carfax when Renfield attacked them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117198,\n            \"What you have said of him in your diary interests me so much!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117244,\n            \"When I went into the room, I told the man that a lady would like to see him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117327,\n            \"\\u201d His method of tidying was peculiar: he simply swallowed all the flies and spiders in the boxes before I could stop him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117431,\n            \"I remembered how quiet he had been just before he attacked me in my own study, and I took care to stand where I could seize him at once if he attempted to make a spring at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117503,\n            \"She walked over to him, smiling pleasantly, and held out her hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117518,\n            \"\\u201cGood-evening, Mr. Renfield,\\u201dsaid she.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117531,\n            \"\\u201cYou see, I know you, for Dr. Seward has told me of you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117549,\n            \"\\u201d He made no immediate reply, but eyed her all over intently with a set frown on his face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117584,\n            \"then, to my intense astonishment, he said:-\\u201cYou\\u2019re not the girl the doctor wanted to marry, are you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117754,\n            \"\\u201d His reply was simply contemptuous, given in a pause in which he turned his eyes from Mrs. Harker to me, instantly turning them back again:-\\u201cWhat an asinine question!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117791,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI don\\u2019t see that at all, Mr. Renfield,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Harker, at once championing me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117817,\n            \"He replied to her with as much courtesy and respect as he had shown contempt to me:-\\u201cYou will, of course, understand, Mrs. Harker, that when a man is so loved and honoured as our host is, everything regarding him is of interest in our little community.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117960,\n            \"Here was my own pet lunatic-the most pronounced of his type that I had ever met with-talking elemental philosophy, and with the manner of a polished gentleman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118047,\n            \"and, seeing that he was seemingly quite reasonable, she ventured, looking at me questioningly as she began, to lead him to his favourite topic.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118076,\n            \"I was again astonished, for he addressed himself to the question with the impartiality of the completest sanity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118126,\n            \"Indeed, it was no wonder that my friends were alarmed, and insisted on my being put under control.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118203,\n            \"The doctor here will bear me out that on one occasion I tried to kill him for the purpose of strengthening my vital powers by the assimilation with my own body of his life through the medium of his blood-relying, of course, upon the Scriptural phrase, \\u2018 For the blood is the life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118313,\n            \"it was hard to imagine that I had seen him eat up his spiders and flies not five minutes before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118366,\n            \"She came at once, after saying pleasantly to Mr. Renfield: \\u201cGood-bye, and I hope I may see you often, under auspices pleasanter to yourself,\\u201dto which, to my astonishment, he replied:-\\u201cGood-bye, my dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123012,\n            \"- Just as we were about to leave the house, an urgent message was brought to me from Renfield to know if I would see him at once, as he had something of the utmost importance to say to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123055,\n            \"I told the messenger to say that I would attend to his wishes in the morning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123080,\n            \"The attendant added:-\\u201cHe seems very importunate, sir.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123093,\n            \"I have never seen him so eager.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123101,\n            \"I don\\u2019t know but what, if you don\\u2019t see him soon, he will have one of his violent fits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123156,\n            \"and I asked the others to wait a few minutes for me, as I had to go and see my \\u201cpatient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123195,\n            \"\\u201cHis case in your diary interest me much, and it had bearing, too, now and again on our case.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123277,\n            \"We found him in a state of considerable excitement, but far more rational in his speech and manner than I had ever seen him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123303,\n            \"There was an unusual understanding of himself, which was unlike anything I had ever met with in a lunatic;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123358,\n            \"His request was that I would at once release him from the asylum and send him home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123394,\n            \"\\u201cI appeal to your friends,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cthey will, perhaps, not mind sitting in judgment on my case.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123420,\n            \"By the way, you have not introduced me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123455,\n            \"and, besides, there was a certain dignity in the man\\u2019s manner, so much of the habit of equality, that I at once made the introduction: \\u201cLord Godalming;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123781,\n            \"And I am sure that you, Dr. Seward, humanitarian and medico-jurist as well as scientist, will deem it a moral duty to deal with me as one to be considered as under exceptional circumstances.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123849,\n            \"For my own part, I was under the conviction, despite my knowledge of the man\\u2019s character and history, that his reason had been restored;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123879,\n            \"and I felt under a strong impulse to tell him that I was satisfied as to his sanity, and would see about the necessary formalities for his release in the morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123912,\n            \"I thought it better to wait, however, before making so grave a statement, for of old I knew the sudden changes to which this particular patient was liable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123944,\n            \"So I contented myself with making a general statement that he appeared to be improving very rapidly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123962,\n            \"that I would have a longer chat with him in the morning, and would then see what I could do in the direction of meeting his wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123991,\n            \"This did not at all satisfy him, for he said quickly:-\\u201cBut I fear, Dr. Seward, that you hardly apprehend my wish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124323,\n            \"I had a growing conviction that this sudden change of his entire intellectual method was but yet another form or phase of his madness, and so determined to let him go on a little longer, knowing from experience that he would, like all lunatics, give himself away in the end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124404,\n            \"He said to Renfield in a tone which did not surprise me at the time, but only when I thought of it afterwards-for it was as of one addressing an equal:-\\u201cCan you not tell frankly your real reason for wishing to be free to-night?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124458,\n            \"I will undertake that if you will satisfy even me-a stranger, without prejudice, and with the habit of keeping an open mind-Dr. Seward will give you, at his own risk and on his own responsibility, the privilege you seek.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124756,\n            \"\\u201d As, however, I got near the door, a new change came over the patient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124775,\n            \"He moved towards me so quickly that for the moment I feared that he was about to make another homicidal attack.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124797,\n            \"My fears, however, were groundless, for he held up his two hands imploringly, and made his petition in a moving manner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124823,\n            \"As he saw that the very excess of his emotion was militating against him, by restoring us more to our old relations, he became still more demonstrative.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124868,\n            \"so I became a little more fixed in my manner, if not more stern, and motioned to him that his efforts were unavailing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124953,\n            \"My expectation was not realised, for, when he found that his appeal would not be successful, he got into quite a frantic condition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124980,\n            \"He threw himself on his knees, and held up his hands, wringing them in plaintive supplication, and poured forth a torrent of entreaty, with the tears rolling down his cheeks, and his whole face and form expressive of the deepest emotion:-\\u201cLet me entreat you, Dr. Seward, oh, let me implore you, to let me out of this house at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125590,\n            \"We were, I think, all a little upset by the scene with Mr. Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125608,\n            \"When we came away from his room we were silent till we got back to the study.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128643,\n            \"\\u201d The house was silent when we got back, save for some poor creature who was screaming away in one of the distant wards, and a low, moaning sound from Renfield\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130874,\n            \"The poor man was more loud than ever, and though I could not distinguish a word he said, I could in some way recognise in his tones some passionate entreaty on his part.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130910,\n            \"Then there was the sound of a struggle, and I knew that the attendants were dealing with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131781,\n            \"In the afternoon Mr. Renfield asked if he might see me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131794,\n            \"Poor man, he was very gentle, and when I came away he kissed my hand and bade God bless me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131824,\n            \"I am crying when I think of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136199,\n            \"- I am puzzled afresh about Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136207,\n            \"His moods change so rapidly that I find it difficult to keep touch of them, and as they always mean something more than his own well-being, they form a more than interesting study.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136245,\n            \"This morning, when I went to see him after his repulse of Van Helsing, his manner was that of a man commanding destiny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136296,\n            \"he was in the clouds and looked down on all the weaknesses and wants of us poor mortals.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136315,\n            \"I thought I would improve the occasion and learn something, so I asked him:-\\u201cWhat about the flies these times?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136340,\n            \"\\u201d He smiled on me in quite a superior sort of way-such a smile as would have become the face of Malvolio-as he answered me:-\\u201cThe fly, my dear sir, has one striking feature;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136940,\n            \"\\u201d I think that through the cloudiness of his insanity he saw some antagonism in me, for he at once fell back on the last refuge of such as he-a dogged silence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136976,\n            \"After a short time I saw that for the present it was useless to speak to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136994,\n            \"He was sulky, and so I came away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137004,\n            \"Later in the day he sent for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137013,\n            \"Ordinarily I would not have come without special reason, but just at present I am so interested in him that I would gladly make an effort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137119,\n            \"I would have taken him with me to see the patient, only I thought that after his last repulse he might not care to go again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137147,\n            \"There was also another reason: Renfield might not speak so freely before a third person as when he and I were alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137171,\n            \"I found him sitting out in the middle of the floor on his stool, a pose which is generally indicative of some mental energy on his part.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137200,\n            \"When I came in, he said at once, as though the question had been waiting on his lips:-\\u201cWhat about souls?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137318,\n            \"The matter seemed preying on his mind, and so I determined to use it-to \\u201cbe cruel only to be kind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137343,\n            \"\\u201d So I said:-\\u201cYou like life, and you want life?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137400,\n            \"\\u201d This seemed to puzzle him, so I followed it up:-\\u201cA nice time you\\u2019ll have some time when you\\u2019re flying out there, with the souls of thousands of flies and spiders and birds and cats buzzing and twittering and miauing all round you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137473,\n            \"\\u201d Something seemed to affect his imagination, for he put his fingers to his ears and shut his eyes, screwing them up tightly just as a small boy does when his face is being soaped.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137557,\n            \"It was evident that he was undergoing some process of mental disturbance, and, knowing how his past moods had interpreted things seemingly foreign to himself, I thought I would enter into his mind as well as I could and go with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137603,\n            \"The first step was to restore confidence, so I asked him, speaking pretty loud so that he would hear me through his closed ears:-\\u201cWould you like some sugar to get your flies round again?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137753,\n            \"\\u201d I thought to myself, \\u201cthis is the second time he has suddenly stopped at the word \\u2018 drink \\u2019;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137781,\n            \"\\u201d Renfield seemed himself aware of having made a lapse, for he hurried on, as though to distract my attention from it:-\\u201cI don\\u2019t take any stock at all in such matters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137859,\n            \"You might as well ask a man to eat molecules with a pair of chop-sticks, as to try to interest me about the lesser carnivora, when I know of what is before me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137938,\n            \"\\u201d He was getting too wide awake, so I thought I would press him hard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137974,\n            \"\\u201d The effect I desired was obtained, for he at once fell from his high-horse and became a child again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138092,\n            \"\\u201d He looked so hostile that I thought he was in for another homicidal fit, so I blew my whistle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138114,\n            \"The instant, however, that I did so he became calm, and said apologetically:-\\u201cForgive me, Doctor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138250,\n            \"Renfield watched them go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138295,\n            \"\\u201d I thought it well to leave him in this mood, and so I came away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138458,\n            \"the Count has been to him, and there is some new scheme of terror afoot!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138497,\n            \"and, after thinking the matter over for a while asked me to take him to Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138519,\n            \"As we came to the door we heard the lunatic within singing gaily, as he used to do in the time which now seems so long ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138548,\n            \"When we entered we saw with amazement that he had spread out his sugar as of old;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138582,\n            \"We tried to make him talk of the subject of our previous conversation, but he would not attend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138602,\n            \"He went on with his singing, just as though we had not been present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138654,\n            \"we must watch him to-night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138831,\n            \"- I placed a man in the corridor last night, and told him to make an accurate note of any sound he might hear from Renfield\\u2019s room, and gave him instructions that if there should be anything strange he was to call me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138937,\n            \"Before going to bed I went round to the patient\\u2019s room and looked in through the observation trap.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138973,\n            \"This morning the man on duty reported to me that a little after midnight he was restless and kept saying his prayers somewhat loudly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139359,\n            \"The attendant came bursting into my room and told me that Renfield had somehow met with some accident.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139378,\n            \"He had heard him yell;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139384,\n            \"and when he went to him found him lying on his face on the floor, all covered with blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139573,\n            \"The attendant who was kneeling beside the body said to me as we turned him over:-\\u201cI think, sir, his back is broken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139696,\n            \"And I suppose he might have broke his neck by falling out of bed, if he got in an awkward kink.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139968,\n            \"for, almost before he looked at the patient, he whispered to me:-\\u201cSend the attendant away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139990,\n            \"We must be alone with him when he becomes conscious, after the operation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140057,\n            \"\\u201d The man withdrew, and we went into a strict examination of the patient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140323,\n            \"When Quincey saw the attitude and state of the patient, and noted the horrible pool on the floor, he said softly:-\\u201cMy God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140363,\n            \"\\u201d I told him briefly, and added that we expected he would recover consciousness after the operation-for a short time, at all events.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140961,\n            \"Then Van Helsing said in a quiet grave tone:-\\u201cTell us your dream, Mr. Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141084,\n            \"We moistened the parched lips, and the patient quickly revived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142315,\n            \"Renfield went on without noticing:-\\u201cWhen Mrs. Harker came in to see me this afternoon she wasn\\u2019t the same;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142365,\n            \"he went on:-\\u201cI didn\\u2019t know that she was here till she spoke;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147094,\n            \"When Dr. Van Helsing and Dr. Seward had come back from seeing poor Renfield, we went gravely into what was to be done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147121,\n            \"First, Dr. Seward told us that when he and Dr. Van Helsing had gone down to the room below they had found Renfield lying on the floor, all in a heap.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147194,\n            \"He said that he had been sitting down-he confessed to half dozing-when he heard loud voices in the room, and then Renfield had called out loudly several times, \\u201cGod!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147235,\n            \"\\u201d after that there was a sound of falling, and when he entered the room he found him lying on the floor, face down, just as the doctors had seen him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147324,\n            \"He could swear to it, if required, that the word \\u201cGod\\u201dwas spoken by the patient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154043,\n            \"How he has been making use of the zo\\u00f6phagous patient to effect his entry into friend John\\u2019s home;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157542,\n            \"Oh, God, let these poor white hairs go in evidence of what he has suffered, who all his life has done no wrong, and on whom so many sorrows have come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192387,\n            \"but before our very eyes, and almost in the drawing of a breath, the whole body crumble into dust and passed from our sight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192483,\n            \"The gypsies, taking us as in some way the cause of the extraordinary disappearance of the dead man, turned, without a word, and rode away as if for their lives.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 12]\": [\n        [\n            75017,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing strode forward, and took his hand, looking him straight in the eyes as he said:-\\u201cA brave man\\u2019s blood is the best thing on this earth when a woman is in trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75060,\n            \"You\\u2019re a man and no mistake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75206,\n            \"The Professor watched whilst I went downstairs with Quincey Morris, and sent one of the maids to pay off one of the cabmen who were waiting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75234,\n            \"I left Quincey lying down after having a glass of wine, and told the cook to get ready a good breakfast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75710,\n            \"\\u201d In the hall I met Quincey Morris, with a telegram for Arthur telling him that Mrs. Westenra was dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75757,\n            \"I told him where I was going, and he hurried me out, but as I was going said:-\\u201cWhen you come back, Jack, may I have two words with you all to ourselves?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75955,\n            \"When we were alone, he said to me:-\\u201cJack Seward, I don\\u2019t want to shove myself in anywhere where I\\u2019ve no right to be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76476,\n            \"Then I guess, Jack Seward, that that poor pretty creature that we all love has had put into her veins within that time the blood of four strong men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84236,\n            \"and the inheritors, being remote, would not be likely to abandon their just rights, for sentimental reasons regarding an entire stranger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84320,\n            \"He did not remain long, but said he would look in later in the day and see Lord Godalming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85335,\n            \"I must not call you \\u2018 Mr.,\\u2019and I have grown to love you-yes, my dear boy, to love you-as Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87483,\n            \"I believe in my heart of hearts that he suffered as much about Lucy\\u2019s death as any of us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87505,\n            \"but he bore himself through it like a moral Viking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103145,\n            \"Quincey and I talked it over;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103434,\n            \"\\u201cI have done myself the honour of counting you one trusting friend, and such endorsement is dear to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105894,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey drew near also, as they too were curious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107245,\n            \"Quincey and I simultaneously moved towards him, and took his arms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107592,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur and Quincey came home with me, and we tried to cheer each other on the way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107641,\n            \"- A little before twelve o\\u2019clock we three-Arthur, Quincey Morris, and myself-called for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108214,\n            \"To me, a doctor\\u2019s preparations for work of any kind are stimulating and bracing, but the effect of these things on both Arthur and Quincey was to cause them a sort of consternation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109093,\n            \"Van Helsing opened his missal and began to read, and Quincey and I followed as well as we could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109817,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur bent and kissed her, and then we sent him and Quincey out of the tomb;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113174,\n            \"You tell me that Lord Godalming and Mr. Morris are coming too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"And Arthur and my friend Quincey, they are with you, too?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119444,\n            \"Opposite us were Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, and Mr. Morris-Lord Godalming being next the Professor, and Dr. Seward in the centre.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120430,\n            \"Jonathan held my right with his left and stretched across to Mr. Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122121,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst they were talking Mr. Morris was looking steadily at the window, and he now got up quietly, and went out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122367,\n            \"As he did so we heard Mr. Morris\\u2019 s voice without:-\\u201cSorry!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122385,\n            \"I fear I have alarmed you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122392,\n            \"I shall come in and tell you about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122437,\n            \"I fear I must have frightened you terribly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122513,\n            \"You used to laugh at me for it then, Art.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122558,\n            \"\\u201d Without saying any more he took his seat, and the Professor began to resume his statement:-\\u201cWe must trace each of these boxes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122831,\n            \"Mr. Morris resumed the discussion:-\\u201cAs there is no time to lose, I vote we have a look at his house right now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127644,\n            \"A few minutes later I saw Morris step suddenly back from a corner, which he was examining.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127663,\n            \"We all followed his movements with our eyes, for undoubtedly some nervousness was growing on us, and we saw a whole mass of phosphorescence, which twinkled like stars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135904,\n            \"I confess I don\\u2019t see how we are going to get in unless that agency duck can find us a key of some sort;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135931,\n            \"perhaps we shall know when you get his letter in the morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135962,\n            \"By-and-by he stopped and said, turning from one to another of us:-\\u201cQuincey\\u2019s head is level.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136003,\n            \"but we have now a rare job on hand-unless we can find the Count\\u2019s key basket.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139064,\n            \"To-day Harker is out following up his clue, and Art and Quincey are looking after horses.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140363,\n            \"\\u201d I told him briefly, and added that we expected he would recover consciousness after the operation-for a short time, at all events.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142874,\n            \"Art and Quincey held back, and the latter said:-\\u201cShould we disturb her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143487,\n            \"and when the gaslight sprang up under Quincey\\u2019s match, we saw nothing but a faint vapour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149770,\n            \"\\u201cHis head is what you call in plane with the horizon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150063,\n            \"that the two doctors and I should remain there, whilst Lord Godalming and Quincey found the lairs at Walworth and Mile End and destroyed them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152088,\n            \"- Just before we reached Fenchurch Street Lord Godalming said to me:-\\u201cQuincey and I will find a locksmith.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152793,\n            \"\\u201cThe place smells so vilely,\\u201dsaid the latter as we came in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153233,\n            \"When we had examined this last find, Lord Godalming and Quincey Morris taking accurate notes of the various addresses of the houses in the East and the South, took with them the keys in a great bunch, and set out to destroy the boxes in these places.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153318,\n            \"- The time seemed terrible long whilst we were waiting for the coming of Godalming and Quincey Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154347,\n            \"By my clock it is one hour and already, if all be well, friend Arthur and Quincey are on their way to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154810,\n            \"What we must hope for is that my Lord Arthur and Quincey arrive first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154945,\n            \"The gladness of our hearts must have shown upon our faces when on the step, close to the door, we saw Lord Godalming and Quincey Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155031,\n            \"\\u201d We were silent for a minute, and then Quincey said:-\\u201cThere\\u2019s nothing to do but to wait here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155343,\n            \"In all our hunting parties and adventures in different parts of the world, Quincey Morris had always been the one to arrange the plan of action, and Arthur and I had been accustomed to obey him implicitly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160986,\n            \"Present: Professor Van Helsing, Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, Mr. Quincey Morris, Jonathan Harker, Mina Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161302,\n            \"and when Quincey give him something from his pocket which crackle as he roll it up, and put it in a so small bag which he have hid deep in his clothing, he still better fellow and humble servant to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192748,\n            \"With one impulse the men sank on their knees and a deep and earnest \\u201cAmen\\u201dbroke from all as their eyes followed the pointing of his finger.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 13]\": [\n        [\n            188100,\n            \"Oh, if only Morris and Seward were with us.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 14]\": [\n        [\n            144838,\n            \"To which Lord Godalming answered:-\\u201cI could not see him anywhere in the passage, or in any of our rooms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147235,\n            \"\\u201d after that there was a sound of falling, and when he entered the room he found him lying on the floor, face down, just as the doctors had seen him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147324,\n            \"He could swear to it, if required, that the word \\u201cGod\\u201dwas spoken by the patient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152088,\n            \"- Just before we reached Fenchurch Street Lord Godalming said to me:-\\u201cQuincey and I will find a locksmith.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152166,\n            \"\\u201d I demurred as to my not sharing any danger even of odium, but he went on: \\u201cBesides, it will attract less attention if there are not too many of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152202,\n            \"My title will make it all right with the locksmith, and with any policeman that may come along.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153233,\n            \"When we had examined this last find, Lord Godalming and Quincey Morris taking accurate notes of the various addresses of the houses in the East and the South, took with them the keys in a great bunch, and set out to destroy the boxes in these places.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153318,\n            \"- The time seemed terrible long whilst we were waiting for the coming of Godalming and Quincey Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154945,\n            \"The gladness of our hearts must have shown upon our faces when on the step, close to the door, we saw Lord Godalming and Quincey Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157754,\n            \"When they had retired, Quincey, Godalming, and I arranged that we should sit up, dividing the night between us, and watch over the safety of the poor stricken lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158363,\n            \"\\u201d His look and gesture forbade discussion, so I came back and told Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158660,\n            \"In two or three minutes later Van Helsing was in the room in his dressing-gown, and Mr. Morris and Lord Godalming were with Dr. Seward at the door asking questions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159592,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Morris and Lord Godalming started for the door but the Professor\\u2019s calm voice called them back:-\\u201cStay, my friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160986,\n            \"Present: Professor Van Helsing, Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, Mr. Quincey Morris, Jonathan Harker, Mina Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161126,\n            \"These not so important as to go in your list of the shipping in the Times, and so we go, by suggestion of Lord Godalming, to your Lloyd\\u2019s, where are note of all ships that sail, however so small.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166925,\n            \"We went to his room, and within a minute Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, and Mr. Morris were with us also.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167278,\n            \"Quincey is all man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167283,\n            \"God bless him for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168879,\n            \"\\u201d said Lord Godalming, each of them in turn kneeling to her to take the oath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169838,\n            \"Lord Godalming went to the Consulate to see if any telegram had arrived for him, whilst the rest of us came on to this hotel-\\\" the Odessus.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170143,\n            \"He had four telegrams, one each day since we started, and all to the same effect: that the Czarina Catherine had not been reported to Lloyd\\u2019s from anywhere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170177,\n            \"He had arranged before leaving London that his agent should send him every day a telegram saying if the ship had been reported.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 15]\": [\n        [\n            19401,\n            \"In a voice which, though low and almost in a whisper seemed to cut through the air and then ring round the room he said:-\\u201cHow dare you touch him, any of you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19440,\n            \"How dare you cast eyes on him when I had forbidden it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19466,\n            \"Beware how you meddle with him, or you\\u2019ll have to deal with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19591,\n            \"Well, now I promise you that when I am done with him you shall kiss him at your will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22538,\n            \"When she saw my face at the window she threw herself forward, and shouted in a voice laden with menace:-\\u201cMonster, give me my child!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23975,\n            \"I bent over him, and tried to find any sign of life, but in vain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24031,\n            \"I thought he might have the keys on him, but when I went to search I saw the dead eyes, and in them, dead though they were, such a look of hate, though unconscious of me or my presence, that I fled from the place, and leaving the Count\\u2019s room by the window, crawled again up the castle wall.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26589,\n            \"away from this cursed spot, from this cursed land, where the devil and his children still walk with earthly feet!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26759,\n            \"When we are married I shall be able to be useful to Jonathan, and if I can stenograph well enough I can take down what he wants to say in this way and write it out for him on the typewriter, at which also I am practising very hard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26811,\n            \"He and I sometimes write letters in shorthand, and he is keeping a stenographic journal of his travels abroad.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26915,\n            \"I may show it to Jonathan some day if there is in it anything worth sharing, but it is really an exercise book.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27006,\n            \"I have just had a few hurried lines from Jonathan from Transylvania.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27032,\n            \"I am longing to hear all his news.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27051,\n            \"I wonder if we-I mean Jonathan and I-shall ever see them together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27295,\n            \"We met some time ago a man that would just do for you, if you were not already engaged to Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27318,\n            \"He is an excellent parti, being handsome, well off, and of good birth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27335,\n            \"He is a doctor and really clever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27368,\n            \"Mr. Holmwood introduced him to me, and he called here to see us, and often comes now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27389,\n            \"I think he is one of the most resolute men I ever saw, and yet the most calm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27414,\n            \"I can fancy what a wonderful power he must have over his patients.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27451,\n            \"He tries this on very much with me, but I flatter myself he has got a tough nut to crack.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27522,\n            \"He says that I afford him a curious psychological study, and I humbly think I do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27648,\n            \"I am blushing as I write, for although I think he loves me, he has not told me so in words.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28084,\n            \"Well, I must tell you about the three, but you must keep it a secret, dear, from every one, except, of course, Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28115,\n            \"You will tell him, because I would, if I were in your place, certainly tell Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28207,\n            \"I told you of him, Dr. John Seward, the lunatic-asylum man, with the strong jaw and the good forehead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28264,\n            \"but he almost managed to sit down on his silk hat, which men don\\u2019t generally do when they are cool, and then when he wanted to appear at ease he kept playing with a lancet in a way that made me nearly scream.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28312,\n            \"He spoke to me, Mina, very straightforwardly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28322,\n            \"He told me how dear I was to him, though he had known me so little, and what his life would be with me to help and cheer him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28354,\n            \"He was going to tell me how unhappy he would be if I did not care for him, but when he saw me cry he said that he was a brute and would not add to my present trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28395,\n            \"Then he broke off and asked if I could love him in time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28436,\n            \"He put it very nicely, saying that he did not want to wring my confidence from me, but only to know, because if a woman\\u2019s heart was free a man might have hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28475,\n            \"And then, Mina, I felt a sort of duty to tell him that there was some one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28495,\n            \"I only told him that much, and then he stood up, and he looked very strong and very grave as he took both my hands in his and said he hoped I would be happy, and that if I ever wanted a friend I must count him one of my best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28572,\n            \"Being proposed to is all very nice and all that sort of thing, but it isn\\u2019t at all a happy thing when you have to see a poor fellow, whom you know loves you honestly, going away and looking all broken-hearted, and to know that, no matter what he may say at the moment, you are passing quite out of his life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28669,\n            \"\\u201cArthur has just gone, and I feel in better spirits than when I left off, so I can go on telling you about the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28816,\n            \"No, I don\\u2019t, for there was Mr. Morris telling us his stories, and Arthur never told any, and yet-- My dear, I am somewhat previous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28874,\n            \"No, he doesn\\u2019t, for Arthur tried twice to make a chance, and I helping him all I could;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29031,\n            \"I do not know if Arthur likes it, as I have never heard him use any as yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30448,\n            \"He is so quaint that I am determined to understand him as well as I can.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30465,\n            \"To-day I seemed to get nearer than ever before to the heart of his mystery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30483,\n            \"I questioned him more fully than I had ever done, with a view to making myself master of the facts of his hallucination.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30525,\n            \"I seemed to wish to keep him to the point of his madness-a thing which I avoid with the patients as I would the mouth of hell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32200,\n            \"- I came up here an hour ago with Lucy, and we had a most interesting talk with my old friend and the two others who always come and join him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32233,\n            \"He is evidently the Sir Oracle of them, and I should think must have been in his time a most dictatorial person.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32257,\n            \"He will not admit anything, and downfaces everybody.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32267,\n            \"If he can\\u2019t out-argue them he bullies them, and then takes their silence for agreement with his views.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33102,\n            \"\\u201d When I came back Mr. Swales went on:-\\u201cWho brought him home, I wonder, to hap him here?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33135,\n            \"an\\u2019you consated his body lay under!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33635,\n            \"\\u2018 He was the only son of his mother, and she was a widow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40366,\n            \"Caffyn, of 33, East Elliot Place-who came immediately after me, declared, after making examination, that the man must have been dead for quite two days.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40428,\n            \"The coastguard said the man must have tied up his own hands, fastening the knots with his teeth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42412,\n            \"Mate says we must be past Straits of Dover, as in a moment of fog lifting he saw North Foreland, just as he heard the man cry out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43452,\n            \"The folk here hold almost universally that the captain is simply a hero, and he is to be given a public funeral.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44087,\n            \"There is an additional cause in that poor old Mr. Swales was found dead this morning on our seat, his neck being broken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44113,\n            \"He had evidently, as the doctor said, fallen back in the seat in some sort of fright, for there was a look of fear and horror on his face that the men said made them shudder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56469,\n            \"Van Helsing would, I know, do anything for me for a personal reason, so, no matter on what ground he comes, we must accept his wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56501,\n            \"He is a seemingly arbitrary man, but this is because he knows what he is talking about better than any one else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56779,\n            \"Were fortune other, then it were bad for those who have trusted, for I come to my friend when he call me to aid those he holds dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60809,\n            \"When we reached the hall the maid had just opened the door, and Arthur was stepping quickly in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60866,\n            \"The dad was better, so I ran down here to see for myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60978,\n            \"You are the lover of our dear miss.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61022,\n            \"\\u201cYou are to help her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61029,\n            \"You can do more than any that live, and your courage is your best help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61068,\n            \"My life is hers, and I would give the last drop of blood in my body for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61170,\n            \"\\u201cYou are a man, and it is a man we want.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61196,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur looked bewildered, and the Professor went on by explaining in a kindly way:-\\u201cYoung miss is bad, very bad.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61331,\n            \"Our nerves are not so calm and our blood not so bright than yours!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61728,\n            \"Van Helsing turning to me, said: \\u201cHe is so young and strong and of blood so pure that we need not defibrinate it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61914,\n            \"You attend him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62126,\n            \"He must then go home and rest, sleep much and eat much, that he may be recruited of what he has so given to his love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63272,\n            \"I sent a short wire to Van Helsing and to Arthur, telling them of the excellent result of the operation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63775,\n            \"I suppose it is that sickness and weakness are selfish things and turn our inner eyes and sympathy on ourselves, whilst health and strength give Love rein, and in thought and feeling he can wander where he wills.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68166,\n            \"Thank God for mother\\u2019s sake, and dear Arthur\\u2019s, and for all our friends who have been so kind!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72312,\n            \"I kept my eyes fixed on the window, but the wolf drew his head back, and a whole myriad of little specks seemed to come blowing in through the broken window, and wheeling and circling round like the pillar of dust that travellers describe when there is a simoon in the desert.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74277,\n            \"I bade her simply tell him that he must wait, for we could see no one now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74296,\n            \"She went away with the message, and, engrossed with our work, I clean forgot all about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75710,\n            \"\\u201d In the hall I met Quincey Morris, with a telegram for Arthur telling him that Mrs. Westenra was dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77147,\n            \"In the afternoon she asked for Arthur, and we telegraphed for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77209,\n            \"When he saw her, Arthur was simply choking with emotion, and none of us could speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77279,\n            \"she rallied a little, and spoke to him more brightly than she had done since we arrived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79771,\n            \"And he has been flapping those grim wings to some purpose of late-Lucy\\u2019s mother and Arthur\\u2019s father, and now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79820,\n            \"We wanted Arthur to go to rest also, but he refused at first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79835,\n            \"It was only when I told him that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79901,\n            \"You are sick and weak, and have had much sorrow and much mental pain, as well as that tax on your strength that we know of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79969,\n            \"You shall lie on one, and I on the other, and our sympathy will be comfort to each other, even though we do not speak, and even if we sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80685,\n            \"he trusts us, and we have promised him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80904,\n            \"When we came into the room she opened her eyes, and seeing him, whispered softly:-\\u201cArthur!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81957,\n            \"and as Arthur had to be back the next day to attend at his father\\u2019s funeral, we were unable to notify any one who should have been bidden.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82958,\n            \"he will be free after his father\\u2019s funeral to-morrow, and he will want to see her-to see it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83248,\n            \"Were you not amazed, nay horrified, when I would not let Arthur kiss his love-though she was dying-and snatched him away by all my strength?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83943,\n            \"he informed us that, with the exception of a certain entailed property of Lucy\\u2019s father\\u2019s which now, in default of direct issue, went back to a distant branch of the family, the whole estate, real and personal, was left absolutely to Arthur Holmwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84374,\n            \"Arthur was expected at five o\\u2019clock, so a little before that time we visited the death-chamber.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84490,\n            \"The undertaker seemed shocked at his own stupidity and exerted himself to restore things to the condition in which we left them the night before, so that when Arthur came such shocks to his feelings as we could avoid were saved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84627,\n            \"The Professor noticed it, too, and motioned me to bring him upstairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84642,\n            \"I did so, and left him at the door of the room, as I felt he would like to be quite alone with her, but he took my arm and led me in, saying huskily:-\\u201cYou loved her too, old fellow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84856,\n            \"I stood still and silent till his sobs died away, and then I said softly to him:-\\u201cCome and look at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84946,\n            \"At last, after a long pause, he said to me in a faint whisper:-\\u201cJack, is she really dead?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85181,\n            \"When he came out of the room again I told him of Arthur\\u2019s question, and he replied:-\\u201cI am not surprised.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85335,\n            \"I must not call you \\u2018 Mr.,\\u2019and I have grown to love you-yes, my dear boy, to love you-as Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85382,\n            \"\\u201cCall me what you will,\\u201dhe said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85429,\n            \"\\u201d He paused a moment, and went on: \\u201cI know that she understood your goodness even better than I do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85453,\n            \"and if I was rude or in any way wanting at that time you acted so-you remember \\\"-the Professor nodded-\\\" you must forgive me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85484,\n            \"\\u201d He answered with a grave kindness:-\\u201cI know it was hard for you to quite trust me then, for to trust such violence needs to understand;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85516,\n            \"and I take it that you do not-that you cannot-trust me now, for you do not yet understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85540,\n            \"And there may be more times when I shall want you to trust when you cannot-and may not-and must not yet understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85567,\n            \"But the time will come when your trust shall be whole and complete in me, and when you shall understand as though the sunlight himself shone through.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85596,\n            \"Then you shall bless me from first to last for your own sake, and for the sake of others and for her dear sake to whom I swore to protect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85628,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd, indeed, indeed, sir,\\u201dsaid Arthur warmly, \\u201cI shall in all ways trust you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85873,\n            \"and in the good time I shall give them back to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85886,\n            \"It\\u2019s a hard thing I ask, but you will do it, will you not, for Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85911,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur spoke out heartily, like his old self:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, you may do what you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86007,\n            \"We and you too-you most of all, my dear boy-will have to pass through the bitter water before we reach the sweet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86947,\n            \"Jonathan kept looking after him, and said, as if to himself:-\\u201cI believe it is the Count, but he has grown young.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87180,\n            \"\\u201d He had evidently forgotten all about the dark stranger, as in his illness he had forgotten all that this episode had reminded him of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87652,\n            \"When it was all over, we were standing beside Arthur, who, poor fellow, was speaking of his part in the operation where his blood had been transfused to his Lucy\\u2019s veins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90104,\n            \"I remember how on our wedding-day he said: \\u201cUnless some solemn duty come upon me to go back to the bitter hours, asleep or awake, mad or sane.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90939,\n            \"Perhaps it was reading the journal yesterday that upset me, and then Jonathan went away this morning to stay away from me a whole day and night, the first time we have been parted since our marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91147,\n            \"Please the good God, all this may not upset him again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91364,\n            \"Jonathan\\u2019s friend on \\u201cThe Exeter News\\u201dtold him that memory was everything in such work-that you must be able to put down exactly almost every word spoken, even if you had to refine some of it afterwards.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106399,\n            \"My own heart grew cold as ice, and I could hear the gasp of Arthur, as we recognised the features of Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106558,\n            \"Arthur was next to me, and if I had not seized his arm and held him up, he would have fallen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107245,\n            \"Quincey and I simultaneously moved towards him, and took his arms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107592,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur and Quincey came home with me, and we tried to cheer each other on the way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107641,\n            \"- A little before twelve o\\u2019clock we three-Arthur, Quincey Morris, and myself-called for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107682,\n            \"Of course, Arthur wore black, for he was in deep mourning, but the rest of us wore it by instinct.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107889,\n            \"When he again lifted the lid off Lucy\\u2019s coffin we all looked-Arthur trembling like an aspen-and saw that the body lay there in all its death-beauty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107952,\n            \"I could see even Arthur\\u2019s face grow hard as he looked.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108214,\n            \"To me, a doctor\\u2019s preparations for work of any kind are stimulating and bracing, but the effect of these things on both Arthur and Quincey was to cause them a sort of consternation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108267,\n            \"When all was ready, Van Helsing said:-\\u201cBefore we do anything, let me tell you this;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108415,\n            \"or again, last night when you open your arms to her, you would in time, when you had died, have become nosferatu, as they call it in Eastern Europe, and would all time make more of those Un-Deads that so have fill us with horror.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108751,\n            \"\\u201d We all looked at Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108758,\n            \"He saw, too, what we all did, the infinite kindness which suggested that his should be the hand which would restore Lucy to us as a holy, and not an unholy, memory;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108944,\n            \"Only think that we, your true friends, are round you, and that we pray for you all the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109114,\n            \"Arthur placed the point over the heart, and as I looked I could see its dint in the white flesh.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109204,\n            \"He looked like a figure of Thor as his untrembling arm rose and fell, driving deeper and deeper the mercy-bearing stake, whilst the blood from the pierced heart welled and spurted up around it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109321,\n            \"He reeled and would have fallen had we not caught him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109384,\n            \"For a few minutes we were so taken up with him that we did not look towards the coffin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109424,\n            \"We gazed so eagerly that Arthur rose, for he had been seated on the ground, and came and looked too;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109470,\n            \"There, in the coffin lay no longer the foul Thing that we had so dreaded and grown to hate that the work of her destruction was yielded as a privilege to the one best entitled to it, but Lucy as we had seen her in her life, with her face of unequalled sweetness and purity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109696,\n            \"\\u201d He put his hands on the Professor\\u2019s shoulder, and laying his head on his breast, cried for a while silently, whilst we stood unmoving.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109817,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur bent and kissed her, and then we sent him and Quincey out of the tomb;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"And Arthur and my friend Quincey, they are with you, too?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128449,\n            \"for look, these rats that would come to his call, just as from his castle top he summon the wolves to your going and to that poor mother\\u2019s cry, though they come to him, they run pell-mell from the so little dogs of my friend Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154810,\n            \"What we must hope for is that my Lord Arthur and Quincey arrive first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155343,\n            \"In all our hunting parties and adventures in different parts of the world, Quincey Morris had always been the one to arrange the plan of action, and Arthur and I had been accustomed to obey him implicitly.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 16]\": [\n        [\n            2091,\n            \"I did not know what to do, for, as an English Churchman, I have been taught to regard such things as in some measure idolatrous, and yet it seemed so ungracious to refuse an old lady meaning so well and in such a state of mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2142,\n            \"She saw, I suppose, the doubt in my face, for she put the rosary round my neck, and said, \\u201cFor your mother\\u2019s sake,\\u201dand went out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2216,\n            \"Whether it is the old lady\\u2019s fear, or the many ghostly traditions of this place, or the crucifix itself, I do not know, but I am not feeling nearly as easy in my mind as usual.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2479,\n            \"When I got on the coach the driver had not taken his seat, and I saw him talking with the landlady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18843,\n            \"You are first, and we shall follow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18896,\n            \"The fair girl advanced and bent over me till I could feel the movement of her breath upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18975,\n            \"The girl went on her knees, and bent over me, simply gloating.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18990,\n            \"There was a deliberate voluptuousness which was both thrilling and repulsive, and as she arched her neck she actually licked her lips like an animal, till I could see in the moonlight the moisture shining on the scarlet lips and on the red tongue as it lapped the white sharp teeth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19044,\n            \"Lower and lower went her head as the lips went below the range of my mouth and chin and seemed about to fasten on my throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19071,\n            \"Then she paused, and I could hear the churning sound of her tongue as it licked her teeth and lips, and could feel the hot breath on my neck.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19221,\n            \"As my eyes opened involuntarily I saw his strong hand grasp the slender neck of the fair woman and with giant\\u2019s power draw it back, the blue eyes transformed with fury, the white teeth champing with rage, and the fair cheeks blazing red with passion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19356,\n            \"With a fierce sweep of his arm, he hurled the woman from him, and then motioned to the others, as though he were beating them back;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19641,\n            \"\\u201d said one of them, with a low laugh, as she pointed to the bag which he had thrown upon the floor, and which moved as though there were some living thing within it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20338,\n            \"I saw in his eyes something of that gathering wrath which was manifest when he hurled that fair woman from him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20701,\n            \"Mina\\u2019s is in shorthand, and I simply ask Mr. Hawkins to communicate with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20720,\n            \"To her I have explained my situation, but without the horrors which I may only surmise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20738,\n            \"It would shock and frighten her to death were I to expose my heart to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22538,\n            \"When she saw my face at the window she threw herself forward, and shouted in a voice laden with menace:-\\u201cMonster, give me my child!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22569,\n            \"\\u201d She threw herself on her knees, and raising up her hands, cried the same words in tones which wrung my heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22615,\n            \"Finally, she threw herself forward, and, though I could not see her, I could hear the beating of her naked hands against the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22712,\n            \"There was no cry from the woman, and the howling of the wolves was but short.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22741,\n            \"I could not pity her, for I knew now what had become of her child, and she was better dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23131,\n            \"Good-bye, Mina, if I fail;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26507,\n            \"Mina is a woman, and there is nought in common.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26654,\n            \"CHAPTER V Letter from Miss Mina Murray to Miss Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27082,\n            \"\\u201cYour loving \\u201cMina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27088,\n            \"\\u201cTell me all the news when you write.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27098,\n            \"You have not told me anything for a long time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27146,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Mina,-\\u201cI must say you tax me very unfairly with being a bad correspondent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27167,\n            \"I wrote to you twice since we parted, and your last letter was only your second.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27185,\n            \"Besides, I have nothing to tell you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27295,\n            \"We met some time ago a man that would just do for you, if you were not already engaged to Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27589,\n            \"Mina, we have told all our secrets to each other since we were children;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27696,\n            \"I wish I were with you, dear, sitting by the fire undressing, as we used to sit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27792,\n            \"Mina, I must stop.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27802,\n            \"Bless me in your prayers;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27808,\n            \"and, Mina, pray for my happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27979,\n            \"Oh, Mina, I am so happy that I don\\u2019t know what to do with myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28084,\n            \"Well, I must tell you about the three, but you must keep it a secret, dear, from every one, except, of course, Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28115,\n            \"You will tell him, because I would, if I were in your place, certainly tell Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28135,\n            \"A woman ought to tell her husband everything-don\\u2019t you think so, dear?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28312,\n            \"He spoke to me, Mina, very straightforwardly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28475,\n            \"And then, Mina, I felt a sort of duty to tell him that there was some one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28550,\n            \"Oh, Mina dear, I can\\u2019t help crying: and you must excuse this letter being all blotted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28645,\n            \"My dear, I must stop here at present, I feel so miserable, though I am so happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28669,\n            \"\\u201cArthur has just gone, and I feel in better spirits than when I left off, so I can go on telling you about the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28816,\n            \"No, I don\\u2019t, for there was Mr. Morris telling us his stories, and Arthur never told any, and yet-- My dear, I am somewhat previous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28907,\n            \"I must tell you beforehand that Mr. Morris doesn\\u2019t always speak slang-that is to say, he never does so to strangers or before them, for he is really well educated and has exquisite manners-but he found out that it amused me to hear him talk American slang, and whenever I was present, and there was no one to be shocked, he said such funny things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28985,\n            \"I am afraid, my dear, he has to invent it all, for it fits exactly into whatever else he has to say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29083,\n            \"He took my hand in his, and said ever so sweetly:-\\u201c\\u2018 Miss Lucy, I know I ain\\u2019t good enough to regulate the fixin\\u2019s of your little shoes, but I guess if you wait till you find a man that is you will go join them seven young women with the lamps when you quit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29149,\n            \"Won\\u2019t you just hitch up alongside of me and let us go down the long road together, driving in double harness?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29282,\n            \"He really did look serious when he was saying it, and I couldn\\u2019t help feeling a bit serious too-I know, Mina, you will think me a horrid flirt-though I couldn\\u2019t help feeling a sort of exultation that he was number two in one day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29338,\n            \"And then, my dear, before I could say a word he began pouring out a perfect torrent of love-making, laying his very heart and soul at my feet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29403,\n            \"I suppose he saw something in my face which checked him, for he suddenly stopped, and said with a sort of manly fervour that I could have loved him for if I had been free:-\\u201c\\u2018 Lucy, you are an honest-hearted girl, I know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29457,\n            \"I should not be here speaking to you as I am now if I did not believe you clean grit, right through to the very depths of your soul.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29488,\n            \"Tell me, like one good fellow to another, is there any one else that you care for?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29508,\n            \"And if there is I\\u2019ll never trouble you a hair\\u2019s breadth again, but will be, if you will let me, a very faithful friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29540,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cMy dear Mina, why are men so noble when we women are so little worthy of them?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29576,\n            \"I burst into tears-I am afraid, my dear, you will think this a very sloppy letter in more ways than one-and I really felt very badly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29704,\n            \"\\u2019 I was right to speak to him so frankly, for quite a light came into his face, and he put out both his hands and took mine-I think I put them into his-and said in a hearty way:-\\u201c\\u2018 That\\u2019s my brave girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29760,\n            \"It\\u2019s better worth being late for a chance of winning you than being in time for any other girl in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29848,\n            \"Little girl, your honesty and pluck have made me a friend, and that\\u2019s rarer than a lover;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29877,\n            \"My dear, I\\u2019m going to have a pretty lonely walk between this and Kingdom Come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29896,\n            \"Won\\u2019t you give me one kiss?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29919,\n            \"You can, you know, if you like, for that other good fellow-he must be a good fellow, my dear, and a fine fellow, or you could not love him-hasn\\u2019t spoken yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29963,\n            \"\\u2019 That quite won me, Mina, for it was brave and sweet of him, and noble, too, to a rival-wasn\\u2019t it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30008,\n            \"He stood up with my two hands in his, and as he looked down into my face-I am afraid I was blushing very much-he said:-\\u201c\\u2018 Little girl, I hold your hand, and you\\u2019ve kissed me, and if these things don\\u2019t make us friends nothing ever will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30071,\n            \"Thank you for your sweet honesty to me, and good-bye.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30172,\n            \"My dear, this quite upset me, and I feel I cannot write of happiness just at once, after telling you of it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30229,\n            \"- Oh, about number Three-I needn\\u2019t tell you of number Three, need I?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30850,\n            \"I have no hesitation in asking you, as I know a certain lady is engaged to a certain dinner-party, and that you are free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30952,\n            \"We promise you a hearty welcome, and a loving greeting, and a health as true as your own right hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30975,\n            \"We shall both swear to leave you at home if you drink too deep to a certain pair of eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31061,\n            \"- Lucy met me at the station, looking sweeter and lovelier than ever, and we drove up to the house at the Crescent in which they have rooms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31218,\n            \"Right over the town is the ruin of Whitby Abbey, which was sacked by the Danes, and which is the scene of part of \\u201cMarmion,\\u201dwhere the girl was built up in the wall.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31778,\n            \"He is, I am afraid, a very sceptical person, for when I asked him about the bells at sea and the White Lady at the abbey he said very brusquely:-\\u201cI wouldn\\u2019t fash masel\\u2019about them, miss.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31981,\n            \"He was just settling himself to begin when the clock struck six, whereupon he laboured to get up, and said:-\\u201cI must gang ageeanwards home now, miss.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32054,\n            \"an \\u2019, miss, I lack belly-timber sairly by the clock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32169,\n            \"Lucy went out visiting with her mother, and as they were only duty calls, I did not go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32200,\n            \"- I came up here an hour ago with Lucy, and we had a most interesting talk with my old friend and the two others who always come and join him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33266,\n            \"Do ye think that all these men will have to make a rush to Whitby when the trumpet sounds?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33293,\n            \"I tell ye that when they got here they\\u2019d be jommlin\\u2019an\\u2019jostlin\\u2019one another that way that it\\u2019ud be like a fight up on the ice in the old days, when we\\u2019d be at one another from daylight to dark, an\\u2019tryin\\u2019to tie up our cuts by the light of the aurora borealis.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33450,\n            \"Answer me that, miss!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33466,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cTo please their relatives, you suppose!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33559,\n            \"The letters were upside down to me from where I sat, but Lucy was more opposite to them, so she leant over and read:-\\u201cSacred to the memory of George Canon, who died, in the hope of a glorious resurrection, on July, 29, 1873, falling from the rocks at Kettleness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33635,\n            \"\\u2018 He was the only son of his mother, and she was a widow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33926,\n            \"\\u201d I did not know what to say, but Lucy turned the conversation as she said, rising up:-\\u201cOh, why did you tell us of this?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34118,\n            \"My service to ye, ladies!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34131,\n            \"Lucy and I sat awhile, and it was all so beautiful before us that we took hands as we sat;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36089,\n            \"Oh, Lucy, Lucy, I cannot be angry with you, nor can I be angry with my friend whose happiness is yours;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36216,\n            \"I am unhappy about Lucy and about Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36412,\n            \"Poor dear, she is naturally anxious about Lucy, and she tells me that her husband, Lucy\\u2019s father, had the same habit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36487,\n            \"I sympathise with her, for I do the same, only Jonathan and I will start in life in a very simple way, and shall have to try to make both ends meet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36532,\n            \"Arthur Holmwood, only son of Lord Godalming-is coming up here very shortly-as soon as he can leave town, for his father is not very well, and I think dear Lucy is counting the moments till he comes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36577,\n            \"She wants to take him up to the seat on the churchyard cliff and show him the beauty of Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36598,\n            \"I daresay it is the waiting which disturbs her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36608,\n            \"she will be all right when he arrives.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36660,\n            \"Lucy walks more than ever, and each night I am awakened by her moving about the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36717,\n            \"Thank God, Lucy\\u2019s health keeps up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36748,\n            \"Lucy frets at the postponement of seeing him, but it does not touch her looks;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36879,\n            \"Lucy has not walked much in her sleep the last week, but there is an odd concentration about her which I do not understand;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37280,\n            \"When he sat down beside me, he said in a very gentle way:-\\u201cI want to say something to you, miss.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37334,\n            \"so he said, leaving his hand in mine:-\\u201cI\\u2019m afraid, my deary, that I must have shocked you by all the wicked things I\\u2019ve been sayin\\u2019about the dead, and such like, for weeks past;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37383,\n            \"but I didn\\u2019t mean them, and I want ye to remember that when I\\u2019m gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37473,\n            \"But, Lord love ye, miss, I ain\\u2019t afraid of dyin \\u2019, not a bit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37553,\n            \"Ye see, I can\\u2019t get out o\\u2019the habit of caffin\\u2019about it all at once;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43619,\n            \"- Lucy was very restless all night, and I, too, could not sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43952,\n            \"Lucy came with me, and we went early to our old seat, whilst the cort\\u00e8ge of boats went up the river to the Viaduct and came down again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44168,\n            \"Lucy is so sweet and sensitive that she feels influences more acutely than other people do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44185,\n            \"Just now she was quite upset by a little thing which I did not much heed, though I am myself very fond of animals.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44478,\n            \"I greatly fear that she is of too super-sensitive a nature to go through the world without trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44499,\n            \"She will be dreaming of this to-night, I am sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44564,\n            \"I think it will be best for her to go to bed tired out physically, so I shall take her for a long walk by the cliffs to Robin Hood\\u2019s Bay and back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44667,\n            \"Lucy, after a while, was in gay spirits, owing, I think, to some dear cows who came nosing towards us in a field close to the lighthouse, and frightened the wits out of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44826,\n            \"Lucy was really tired, and we intended to creep off to bed as soon as we could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44864,\n            \"Lucy and I had both a fight for it with the dusty miller;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45069,\n            \"I am so happy to-night, because dear Lucy seems better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45208,\n            \"The room was dark, so I could not see Lucy\\u2019s bed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45223,\n            \"I stole across and felt for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45265,\n            \"I feared to wake her mother, who has been more than usually ill lately, so threw on some clothes and got ready to look for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45340,\n            \"\\u201cThank God,\\u201dI said to myself, \\u201cshe cannot be far, as she is only in her nightdress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45430,\n            \"The people of the house are careful to lock the door every night, so I feared that Lucy must have gone out as she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46456,\n            \"when I told her to come at once with me home she rose without a word, with the obedience of a child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46480,\n            \"As we passed along, the gravel hurt my feet, and Lucy noticed me wince.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46698,\n            \"When we got in, and had washed our feet, and had said a prayer of thankfulness together, I tucked her into bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46724,\n            \"Before falling asleep she asked-even implored-me not to say a word to any one, even her mother, about her sleep-walking adventure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46761,\n            \"but on thinking of the state of her mother\\u2019s health, and how the knowledge of such a thing would fret her, and thinking, too, of how such a story might become distorted-nay, infallibly would-in case it should leak out, I thought it wiser to do so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47071,\n            \"We took our lunch to Mulgrave Woods, Mrs. Westenra driving by the road and Lucy and I walking by the cliff-path and joining her at the gate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47670,\n            \"We were silent for a while, and suddenly Lucy murmured as if to herself:-\\u201cHis red eyes again!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47774,\n            \"She appeared to be looking over at our own seat, whereon was a dark figure seated alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47976,\n            \"When coming home-it was then bright moonlight, so bright that, though the front of our part of the Crescent was in shadow, everything could be well seen-I threw a glance up at our window, and saw Lucy\\u2019s head leaning out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48268,\n            \"Lucy was languid and tired, and slept on after we had been called.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48307,\n            \"Lucy is full of quiet joy, and her mother is glad and sorry at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48335,\n            \"She is grieved to lose Lucy as her very own, but she is rejoiced that she is soon to have some one to protect her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48381,\n            \"She has not told Lucy, and made me promise secrecy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48393,\n            \"her doctor told her that within a few months, at most, she must die, for her heart is weakening.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48434,\n            \"Ah, we were wise to keep from her the affair of the dreadful night of Lucy\\u2019s sleep-walking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48490,\n            \"No news from Jonathan, and Lucy seems to be growing weaker, whilst her mother\\u2019s hours are numbering to a close.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48576,\n            \"I keep the key of our door always fastened to my wrist at night, but she gets up and walks about the room, and sits at the open window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49408,\n            \"I daresay poor old Mr. Swales would have told me that it was because I didn\\u2019t want to wake up Geordie.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49800,\n            \"I did not quite like it, and thought it better not to keep her mind on the subject, so we drifted on to other subjects, and Lucy was like her old self again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49837,\n            \"When we got home the fresh breeze had braced her up, and her pale cheeks were really more rosy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49858,\n            \"Her mother rejoiced when she saw her, and we all spent a very happy evening together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52150,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Lucy,-\\u201cI know you will be anxious to hear all that has happened since we parted at the railway station at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53204,\n            \"When the chaplain and the sisters had left me alone with my husband-oh, Lucy, it is the first time I have written the words \\u2018 my husband\\u2019- left me alone with my husband, I took the book from under his pillow, and wrapped it up in white paper, and tied it with a little bit of pale blue ribbon which was round my neck, and sealed it over the knot with sealing-wax, and for my seal I used my wedding ring.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53364,\n            \"Then he took my hand in his, and oh, Lucy, it was the first time he took his wife\\u2019s hand, and said that it was the dearest thing in all the wide world, and that he would go through all the past again to win it, if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53526,\n            \"And, my dear, when he kissed me, and drew me to him with his poor weak hands, it was like a very solemn pledge between us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53624,\n            \"I want you to see now, and with the eyes of a very happy wife, whither duty has led me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53664,\n            \"My dear, please Almighty God, your life may be all it promises: a long day of sunshine, with no harsh wind, no forgetting duty, no distrust.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53818,\n            \"I wish you could be coming home soon enough to stay with us here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54024,\n            \"She seems better, poor dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54222,\n            \"It was a strange thing that the patient had humour enough to see their distrust, for, coming close to me, he said in a whisper, all the while looking furtively at them:-\\u201cThey think I could hurt you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55384,\n            \"I do not dare to ask her mother, for to disturb the poor lady\\u2019s mind about her daughter in her present state of health would be fatal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55415,\n            \"Mrs. Westenra has confided to me that her doom is spoken-disease of the heart-though poor Lucy does not know it yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55541,\n            \"You are to come to lunch at Hillingham to-morrow, two o\\u2019clock, so as not to arouse any suspicion in Mrs. Westenra, and after lunch Lucy will take an opportunity of being alone with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55688,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear old fellow,-\\u201cWith regard to Miss Westenra\\u2019s health I hasten to let you know at once that in my opinion there is not any functional disturbance or any malady that I know of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56049,\n            \"\\u2019 I reminded her that a doctor\\u2019s confidence was sacred, but that you were grievously anxious about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56297,\n            \"She says that as a child she used to walk in her sleep, and that when in Whitby the habit came back, and that once she walked out in the night and went to East Cliff, where Miss Murray found her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56402,\n            \"I have asked him to come over, and as you told me that all things were to be at your charge, I have mentioned to him who you are and your relations to Miss Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56440,\n            \"This, my dear fellow, is in obedience to your wishes, for I am only too proud and happy to do anything I can for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56810,\n            \"Tell your friend that when that time you suck from my wound so swiftly the poison of the gangrene from that knife that our other friend, too nervous, let slip, you did more for him when he wants my aids and you call for them than all his great fortune could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57004,\n            \"He came on with me to Hillingham, and found that, by Lucy\\u2019s discretion, her mother was lunching out, so that we were alone with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57086,\n            \"When I told him of our friendship and how you trust to me in the matter, he said: \\u2018 You must tell him all you think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57433,\n            \"Then he began to chat of all things except ourselves and diseases and with such an infinite geniality that I could see poor Lucy\\u2019s pretense of animation merge into reality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57525,\n            \"They told me you were down in the spirit, and that you were of a ghastly pale.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57552,\n            \"\\u201d\\u2019And he snapped his fingers at me and went on: \\u2018 But you and I shall show them how wrong they are.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57722,\n            \"So, my dear, we will send him away to smoke the cigarette in the garden, whiles you and I have little talk all to ourselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57826,\n            \"I have asked her to send me her maid, that I may ask just one or two question, that so I may not chance to miss nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57950,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cAs I tell you, he would not say a word more, even when we were alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58029,\n            \"I know your idea of duty to your father, and you are right to stick to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59234,\n            \"I hold over telegram to Holmwood till have seen you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59303,\n            \"Mrs. Westenra was naturally anxious concerning Lucy, and has consulted me professionally about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsing, the great specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly with myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59362,\n            \"so now we can come and go without alarming her unduly, for a shock to her would mean sudden death, and this, in Lucy\\u2019s weak condition, might be disastrous to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59479,\n            \"- The first thing Van Helsing said to me when we met at Liverpool Street was:-\\u201cHave you said anything to our young friend the lover of her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59535,\n            \"I wrote him a letter simply telling him that you were coming, as Miss Westenra was not so well, and that I should let him know if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59623,\n            \"You deal with the madmen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59640,\n            \"and inasmuch as you deal discreetly with your madmen, so deal with God\\u2019s madmen, too-the rest of the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59713,\n            \"You and I shall keep as yet what we know here, and here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59789,\n            \"\\u201d He stopped and looked at me, and said:-\\u201cMy friend John, when the corn is grown, even before it has ripened-while the milk of its mother-earth is in him, and the sunshine has not yet begun to paint him with his gold, the husbandman he pull the ear and rub him between his rough hands, and blow away the green chaff, and say to you: \\u2018 Look!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60054,\n            \"Then he went on, and very gravely:-\\u201cYou were always a careful student, and your case-book was ever more full than the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60126,\n            \"Even if you have not kept the good practise, let me tell you that this case of our dear miss is one that may be-mind, I say may be-of such interest to us and others that all the rest may not make him kick the beam, as your peoples say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60355,\n            \"Here, in a case where any shock may prove fatal, matters are so ordered that, from some cause or other, the things not personal-even the terrible change in her daughter to whom she is so attached-do not seem to reach her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60475,\n            \"I used my knowledge of this phase of spiritual pathology, and laid down a rule that she should not be present with Lucy or think of her illness more than was absolutely required.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60623,\n            \"Lucy lay motionless, and did not seem to have strength to speak, so for a while we were all silent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61478,\n            \"\\u201d We all went up to Lucy\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61495,\n            \"Lucy turned her head and looked at us, but said nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61524,\n            \"Her eyes spoke to us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61716,\n            \"\\u201d So neither of us looked whilst he bent over her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62527,\n            \"You must remain here all the night, and you must not let your sight pass from her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62653,\n            \"He came back a moment later and put his head inside the door and said with warning finger held up:-\\u201cRemember, she is your charge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62683,\n            \"If you leave her, and harm befall, you shall not sleep easy hereafter!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62777,\n            \"When I told Mrs. Westenra that Dr. Van Helsing had directed that I should sit up with her she almost pooh-poohed the idea, pointing out her daughter\\u2019s renewed strength and excellent spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62831,\n            \"When her maid had prepared her for the night I came in, having in the meantime had supper, and took a seat by the bedside.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63602,\n            \"You can lie on the sofa for I know that nothing would induce any of you doctors to go to bed whilst there is a patient above the horizon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63632,\n            \"If I want anything I shall call out, and you can come to me at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64631,\n            \"You have work, much work, to do for her and for others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65080,\n            \"When her mother came up to see her, she did not seem to notice any change whatever, but said to me gratefully:-\\u201cWe owe you so much, Dr. Seward, for all you have done, but you really must now take care not to overwork yourself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65158,\n            \"\\u201d As she spoke, Lucy turned crimson, though it was only momentarily, for her poor wasted veins could not stand for long such an unwonted drain to the head.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65407,\n            \"Perhaps it is because I am weak at present, and perhaps because it was on Lucy\\u2019s account, that their devotion was manifested;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66260,\n            \"We then waited whilst Lucy made her toilet for the night, and when she was in bed he came and himself fixed the wreath of garlic round her neck.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66354,\n            \"Oh, what have I done to be blessed with such friends?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67545,\n            \"and together we went up to Lucy\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67761,\n            \"Presently he took an opportunity of telling Mrs. Westenra that she must not remove anything from Lucy\\u2019s room without consulting him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68166,\n            \"Thank God for mother\\u2019s sake, and dear Arthur\\u2019s, and for all our friends who have been so kind!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70191,\n            \"\\u201cYe\\u2019ll excoose me, I know, for a-chaffin\\u2019of ye, but the old woman here winked at me, which was as much as telling me to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72573,\n            \"They lifted off the body of my dear mother, and laid her, covered up with a sheet, on the bed after I had got up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73642,\n            \"\\u201d Then we ascended to Lucy\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73701,\n            \"On the bed lay two women, Lucy and her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73774,\n            \"The flowers which had been round her neck we found upon her mother\\u2019s bosom, and her throat was bare, showing the two little wounds which we had noticed before, but looking horribly white and mangled.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74473,\n            \"Van Helsing\\u2019s face almost beamed, and as we lifted her from the bath and rolled her in a hot sheet to dry her he said to me:-\\u201cThe first gain is ours!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74827,\n            \"What are we to do for some one who will open his veins for her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75340,\n            \"He handed me the paper saying only: \\u201cIt dropped from Lucy\\u2019s breast when we carried her to the bath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76768,\n            \"We both understood what that meant-that she had realised to the full her mother\\u2019s death;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76788,\n            \"so we tried what we could to comfort her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76824,\n            \"We told her that either or both of us would now remain with her all the time, and that seemed to comfort her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76975,\n            \"The Professor and I took it in turns to watch, and we never left her for a moment unattended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78181,\n            \"This afternoon a carrier\\u2019s cart with two men made a call at the empty house whose grounds abut on ours-the house to which, you will remember, the patient twice ran away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79079,\n            \"I quite understood their drift, and after a stiff glass of grog, or rather more of the same, and with each a sovereign in hand, they made light of the attack, and swore that they would encounter a worse madman any day for the pleasure of meeting so \\u2018 bloomin\\u2019good a bloke\\u2019as your correspondent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79281,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Lucy,-\\u201cSuch a sad blow has befallen us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79771,\n            \"And he has been flapping those grim wings to some purpose of late-Lucy\\u2019s mother and Arthur\\u2019s father, and now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81684,\n            \"\\u201cWe thought her dying whilst she slept, And sleeping when she died.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82204,\n            \"It is not well that her very thoughts go into the hands of strangers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82490,\n            \"\\u201d Before turning in we went to look at poor Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82588,\n            \"All Lucy\\u2019s loveliness had come back to her in death, and the hours that had passed, instead of leaving traces of \\u201cdecay\\u2019s effacing fingers,\\u201dhad but restored the beauty of life, till positively I could not believe my eyes that I was looking at a corpse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86657,\n            \"He was looking at her so hard that he did not see either of us, and so I had a good view of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87342,\n            \"and now a telegram from Van Helsing, whoever he may be:-\\u201cYou will be grieved to hear that Mrs. Westenra died five days ago, and that Lucy died the day before yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87483,\n            \"I believe in my heart of hearts that he suffered as much about Lucy\\u2019s death as any of us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87652,\n            \"When it was all over, we were standing beside Arthur, who, poor fellow, was speaking of his part in the operation where his blood had been transfused to his Lucy\\u2019s veins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88124,\n            \"And yet I can laugh at her very grave-laugh when the clay from the spade of the sexton drop upon her coffin and say \\u2018 Thud!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88530,\n            \"As he answered me his face grew stern, and he said in quite a different tone:-\\u201cOh, it was the grim irony of it all-this so lovely lady garlanded with flowers, that looked so fair as life, till one by one we wondered if she were truly dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88588,\n            \"she laid in that so fine marble house in that lonely churchyard, where rest so many of her kin, laid there with the mother who loved her, and whom she loved;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88829,\n            \"Then this so sweet maid is a polyandrist, and me, with my poor wife dead to me, but alive by Church\\u2019s law, though no wits, all gone-even I, who am faithful husband to this now-no-wife, am bigamist.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89086,\n            \"Lucy lies in the tomb of her kin, a lordly death-house in a lonely churchyard, away from teeming London;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90365,\n            \"By the kindness of Lord Godalming, I am empowered to read her letters and papers, for I am deeply concerned about certain matters vitally important.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90393,\n            \"In them I find some letters from you, which show how great friends you were and how you love her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90477,\n            \"I am friend of Dr. John Seward and of Lord Godalming (that was Arthur of Miss Lucy).\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91260,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing must be a good man as well as a clever one if he is Arthur\\u2019s friend and Dr. Seward\\u2019s, and if they brought him all the way from Holland to look after Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93367,\n            \"You have told me all about Lucy, and so now we shall not speak of it, lest it distress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94668,\n            \"Mina is dressing, and I shall call at the hotel in a few minutes and bring him over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94702,\n            \"When I came into the room where he was, and introduced myself, he took me by the shoulder, and turned my face round to the light, and said, after a sharp scrutiny:-\\u201cBut Madam Mina told me you were ill, that you had had a shock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94970,\n            \"and, oh, sir, you will pardon praise from an old man, but you are blessed in your wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94993,\n            \"\\u201d I would listen to him go on praising Mina for a day, so I simply nodded and stood silent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95015,\n            \"\\u201cShe is one of God\\u2019s women, fashioned by His own hand to show us men and other women that there is a heaven where we can enter, and that its light can be here on earth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95090,\n            \"And you, sir-I have read all the letters to poor Miss Lucy, and some of them speak of you, so I know you since some days from the knowing of others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95346,\n            \"When we were parting he said:-\\u201cPerhaps you will come to town if I send to you, and take Madam Mina too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95734,\n            \"As for myself, I was settling down to my work with the enthusiasm which I used to have for it, so that I might fairly have said that the wound which poor Lucy left on me was becoming cicatrised.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95996,\n            \"Whatever it was that injured her has injured them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96086,\n            \"Never, even in the midst of our despair about poor Lucy, had he looked more stern.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96140,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo you mean to tell me, friend John, that you have no suspicion as to what poor Lucy died of;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96681,\n            \"For, had she live one more day, we could have save her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96817,\n            \"how in some islands of the Western seas there are bats which hang on the trees all day, and those who have seen describe as like giant nuts or pods, and that when the sailors sleep on the deck, because that it is hot, flit down on them, and then-and then in the morning are found dead men, white as even Miss Lucy was?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96904,\n            \"\\u201cDo you mean to tell me that Lucy was bitten by such a bat;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97565,\n            \"You think then that those so small holes in the children\\u2019s throats were made by the same that made the hole in Miss Lucy?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97887,\n            \"He went on:-\\u201cMy friend, it was because I wished to be gentle in the breaking to you, for I know you have loved that so sweet lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98117,\n            \"Come, I tell you what I propose: first, that we go off now and see that child in the hospital.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98141,\n            \"Dr. Vincent, of the North Hospital, where the papers say the child is, is friend of mine, and I think of yours since you were in class at Amsterdam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98229,\n            \"\\u201cAnd then we spend the night, you and I, in the churchyard where Lucy lies.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98321,\n            \"We found the child awake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98612,\n            \"When she asked him why he wanted to go, he said he wanted to play with the \\u2018 bloofer lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99330,\n            \"It seemed to be as much an affront to the dead as it would have been to have stripped off her clothing in her sleep whilst living;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99432,\n            \"I had expected a rush of gas from the week-old corpse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99606,\n            \"I felt all the dogged argumentativeness of my nature awake within me as I answered him:-\\u201cI am satisfied that Lucy\\u2019s body is not in that coffin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100296,\n            \"\\u201cWe shall see,\\u201dsaid the Professor, and with one impulse we took our way out of the churchyard, he carrying the sleeping child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100325,\n            \"When we had got some little distance away, we went into a clump of trees, and struck a match, and looked at the child\\u2019s throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100390,\n            \"We had now to decide what we were to do with the child, and so consulted about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100435,\n            \"at least, we should have had to make some statement as to how we had come to find the child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100508,\n            \"At the edge of Hampstead Heath we heard a policeman\\u2019s heavy tramp, and laying the child on the pathway, we waited and watched until he saw it as he flashed his lantern to and fro.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100772,\n            \"Outrageous as it was to open a leaden coffin, to see if a woman dead nearly a week were really dead, it now seemed the height of folly to open the tomb again, when we knew, from the evidence of our own eyesight, that the coffin was empty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100896,\n            \"Van Helsing walked over to Lucy\\u2019s coffin, and I followed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100933,\n            \"There lay Lucy, seemingly just as we had seen her the night before her funeral.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100962,\n            \"and I could not believe that she was dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101122,\n            \"so, with an attempt to argue of which I was even at the moment ashamed, I said:-\\u201cShe may have been placed here since last night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101300,\n            \"She was bitten by the vampire when she was in a trance, sleep-walking-oh, you start;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101377,\n            \"Usually when the Un-Dead sleep at home \\\"-as he spoke he made a comprehensive sweep of his arm to designate what to a vampire was \\u201chome \\\"-\\\" their face show what they are, but this so sweet that was when she not Un-Dead she go back to the nothings of the common dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101589,\n            \"\\u201d It made me shudder to think of so mutilating the body of the woman whom I had loved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101816,\n            \"If you, who saw the wounds on Lucy\\u2019s throat, and saw the wounds so similar on the child\\u2019s at the hospital;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101844,\n            \"if you, who saw the coffin empty last night and full to-day with a woman who have not change only to be more rose and more beautiful in a whole week, after she die-if you know of this and know of the white figure last night that brought the child to the churchyard, and yet of your own senses you did not believe, how, then, can I expect Arthur, who know none of those things, to believe?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101934,\n            \"He doubted me when I took him from her kiss when she was dying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101991,\n            \"and that in most mistake of all we have killed her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102003,\n            \"He will then argue back that it is we, mistaken ones, that have killed her by our ideas;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102076,\n            \"and again, he will think that we may be right, and that his so beloved was, after all, an Un-Dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102389,\n            \"It pleases me that the Un-Dead, Miss Lucy, shall not leave to-night, that so on the morrow night she may be more eager.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102420,\n            \"Therefore I shall fix some things she like not-garlic and a crucifix-and so seal up the door of the tomb.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102531,\n            \"For Miss Lucy or from her, I have no fear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102570,\n            \"He is cunning, as I know from Mr. Jonathan and from the way that all along he have fooled us when he played with us for Miss Lucy\\u2019s life, and we lost;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102631,\n            \"even we four who gave our strength to Miss Lucy it also is all to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104071,\n            \"\\u201cI did not say she was alive, my child;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105318,\n            \"The next day we came here in day-time, and she lay there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106399,\n            \"My own heart grew cold as ice, and I could hear the gasp of Arthur, as we recognised the features of Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106492,\n            \"by the concentrated light that fell on Lucy\\u2019s face we could see that the lips were crimson with fresh blood, and that the stream had trickled over her chin and stained the purity of her lawn death-robe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106582,\n            \"When Lucy-I call the thing that was before us Lucy because it bore her shape-saw us she drew back with an angry snarl, such as a cat gives when taken unawares;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106619,\n            \"then her eyes ranged over us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106635,\n            \"but Lucy\\u2019s eyes unclean and full of hell-fire, instead of the pure, gentle orbs we knew.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106672,\n            \"had she then to be killed, I could have done it with savage delight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106868,\n            \"\\u201d There was something diabolically sweet in her tones-something of the tingling of glass when struck-which rang through the brains even of us who heard the words addressed to another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107298,\n            \"We all looked on in horrified amazement as we saw, when he stood back, the woman, with a corporeal body as real at that moment as our own, pass in through the interstice where scarce a knife-blade could have gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107889,\n            \"When he again lifted the lid off Lucy\\u2019s coffin we all looked-Arthur trembling like an aspen-and saw that the body lay there in all its death-beauty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107924,\n            \"But there was no love in my own heart, nothing but loathing for the foul Thing which had taken Lucy\\u2019s shape without her soul.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108003,\n            \"But wait a while, and you all see her as she was, and is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108415,\n            \"or again, last night when you open your arms to her, you would in time, when you had died, have become nosferatu, as they call it in Eastern Europe, and would all time make more of those Un-Deads that so have fill us with horror.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108497,\n            \"but if she live on, Un-Dead, more and more they lose their blood and by her power over them they come to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108525,\n            \"and so she draw their blood with that so wicked mouth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108758,\n            \"He saw, too, what we all did, the infinite kindness which suggested that his should be the hand which would restore Lucy to us as a holy, and not an unholy, memory;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109470,\n            \"There, in the coffin lay no longer the foul Thing that we had so dreaded and grown to hate that the work of her destruction was yielded as a privilege to the one best entitled to it, but Lucy as we had seen her in her life, with her face of unequalled sweetness and purity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109552,\n            \"but these were all dear to us, for they marked her truth to what we knew.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109678,\n            \"God bless you that you have given my dear one her soul again, and me peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109803,\n            \"She is God\\u2019s true dead, whose soul is with Him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109817,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur bent and kissed her, and then we sent him and Quincey out of the tomb;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110327,\n            \"\\u201cAh, that wonderful Madam Mina,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cpearl among women!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110395,\n            \"over it he told me of a diary kept by Jonathan Harker when abroad, and gave me a typewritten copy of it, as also of Mrs. Harker\\u2019s diary at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110743,\n            \"\\u201cI knew you from the description of poor dear Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110771,\n            \"The blush that rose to my own cheeks somehow set us both at ease, for it was a tacit answer to her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110796,\n            \"I got her luggage, which included a typewriter, and we took the Underground to Fenchurch Street, after I had sent a wire to my housekeeper to have a sitting-room and bedroom prepared at once for Mrs. Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110846,\n            \"She knew, of course, that the place was a lunatic asylum, but I could see that she was unable to repress a shudder when we entered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110876,\n            \"She told me that, if she might, she would come presently to my study, as she had much to say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110900,\n            \"So here I am finishing my entry in my phonograph diary whilst I await her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110943,\n            \"I must get her interested in something, so that I may have an opportunity of reading them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110962,\n            \"She does not know how precious time is, or what a task we have in hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110980,\n            \"I must be careful not to frighten her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111291,\n            \"and as it is entirely-almost entirely-about my cases, it may be awkward-that is, I mean--\\u201dHe stopped, and I tried to help him out of his embarrassment:-\\u201cYou helped to attend dear Lucy at the end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111343,\n            \"Let me hear how she died;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111350,\n            \"for all that I know of her, I shall be very grateful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111364,\n            \"She was very, very dear to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111373,\n            \"\\u201d To my surprise, he answered, with a horrorstruck look in his face:-\\u201cTell you of her death?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111918,\n            \"I know that Lucy told you of me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111927,\n            \"she told me of you too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112097,\n            \"Mrs. Harker was not down when the maid came to announce dinner, so I said: \\u201cShe is possibly tired;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112136,\n            \"I had just finished Mrs. Harker\\u2019s diary, when she came in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112216,\n            \"So I said as gently as I could:-\\u201cI greatly fear I have distressed you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112235,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cOh, no, not distressed me,\\u201dshe replied, \\u201cbut I have been more touched than I can say by your grief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112364,\n            \"She laid her hand on mine and said very gravely:-\\u201cAh, but they must!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112507,\n            \"and I see already, though your diary only took me to 7 September, how poor Lucy was beset, and how her terrible doom was being wrought out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112606,\n            \"\\u201d She looked at me so appealingly, and at the same time manifested such courage and resolution in her bearing, that I gave in at once to her wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112638,\n            \"\\u201cYou shall,\\u201dI said, \\u201cdo as you like in the matter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112672,\n            \"but if you have so far travelled on the road to poor Lucy\\u2019s death, you will not be content, I know, to remain in the dark.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112747,\n            \"When you have eaten you shall learn the rest, and I shall answer any questions you ask-if there be anything which you do not understand, though it was apparent to us who were present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112901,\n            \"When the terrible story of Lucy\\u2019s death, and-and all that followed, was done, I lay back in my chair powerless.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112977,\n            \"My brain was all in a whirl, and only that there came through all the multitude of horrors, the holy ray of light that my dear, dear Lucy was at last at peace, I do not think I could have borne it without making a scene.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113747,\n            \"Oh, if we had only had them earlier we might have saved poor Lucy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115277,\n            \"- Mina and I have worked all day, and we have put all the papers into order.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115495,\n            \"To read Dr. Seward\\u2019s account of poor Lucy\\u2019s death, and what followed, is enough to dry up the springs of pity in one\\u2019s heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115566,\n            \"It was to me a painful meeting, for it brought back all poor dear Lucy\\u2019s hopes of only a few months ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115592,\n            \"Of course they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has been quite \\u201cblowing my trumpet,\\u201das Mr. Morris expressed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115629,\n            \"Poor fellows, neither of them is aware that I know all about the proposals they made to Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115712,\n            \"I knew from Dr. Seward\\u2019s diary that they had been at Lucy\\u2019s death-her real death-and that I need not fear to betray any secret before the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115916,\n            \"Besides, I know you loved my poor Lucy-\\u201d Here he turned away and covered his face with his hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116093,\n            \"I said to him, for I could see that his heart was breaking:-\\u201cI loved dear Lucy, and I know what she was to you, and what you were to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116131,\n            \"She and I were like sisters;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116138,\n            \"and now she is gone, will you not let me be like a sister to you in your trouble?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116176,\n            \"If sympathy and pity can help in your affliction, won\\u2019t you let me be of some little service-for Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116562,\n            \"You will let me be like a brother, will you not, for all our lives-for dear Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116587,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cFor dear Lucy\\u2019s sake,\\u201dI said as we clasped hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117024,\n            \"\\\"-the very words he had used to Lucy, and oh, but he proved himself a friend!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118562,\n            \"Madam Mina is with you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118628,\n            \"at which the Professor interrupted me:-\\u201cAh, that wonderful Madam Mina!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118644,\n            \"She has man\\u2019s brain-a brain that a man should have were he much gifted-and a woman\\u2019s heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118690,\n            \"Friend John, up to now fortune has made that woman of help to us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118832,\n            \"You tell me she has wrote all, then she must consult with us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118847,\n            \"but to-morrow she say good-bye to this work, and we go alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118924,\n            \"\\u201d he said, \\u201cfor then we might have reached him in time to save poor Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119679,\n            \"Had I known at the first what now I know-nay, had I even guess at him-one so precious life had been spared to many of us who did love her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121162,\n            \"he can be as bat, as Madam Mina saw him on the window at Whitby, and as friend John saw him fly from this so near house, and as my friend Quincey saw him at the window of Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121272,\n            \"He become so small-we ourselves saw Miss Lucy, ere she was at peace, slip through a hairbreadth space at the tomb door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125470,\n            \"- I went with the party to the search with an easy mind, for I think I never saw Mina so absolutely strong and well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125497,\n            \"I am so glad that she consented to hold back and let us men do the work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125515,\n            \"Somehow, it was a dread to me that she was in this fearful business at all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125533,\n            \"but now that her work is done, and that it is due to her energy and brains and foresight that the whole story is put together in such a way that every point tells, she may well feel that her part is finished, and that she can henceforth leave the rest to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126448,\n            \"If so that we can open the door, we need not break house by the window, as before at Miss Lucy\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126541,\n            \"It was startlingly like the image conveyed to me in Dr. Seward\\u2019s diary of the opening of Miss Westenra\\u2019s tomb;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128702,\n            \"I came tiptoe into our own room, and found Mina asleep, breathing so softly that I had to put my ear down to hear it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128736,\n            \"I hope the meeting to-night has not upset her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128748,\n            \"I am truly thankful that she is to be left out of our future work, and even of our deliberations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128840,\n            \"Henceforth our work is to be a sealed book to her, till at least such time as we can tell her that all is finished, and the earth free from a monster of the nether world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128929,\n            \"I rest on the sofa, so as not to disturb her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128978,\n            \"Even Mina must have felt its exhaustion, for though I slept till the sun was high, I was awake before her, and had to call two or three times before she awoke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129014,\n            \"Indeed, she was so sound asleep that for a few seconds she did not recognize me, but looked at me with a sort of blank terror, as one looks who has been waked out of a bad dream.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129056,\n            \"She complained a little of being tired, and I let her rest till later in the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129361,\n            \"He said to Madam Mina, as I see in your diary of yesterday, that he had once had such a belief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129819,\n            \"so I shall go, if I may, and cheer myself with a few happy words with that sweet soul Madam Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129843,\n            \"Friend John, it does rejoice me unspeakable that she is no more to be pained, no more to be worried with our terrible things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129870,\n            \"Though we shall much miss her help, it is better so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130430,\n            \"If I hadn\\u2019t gone to Whitby, perhaps poor dear Lucy would be with us now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130449,\n            \"She hadn\\u2019t taken to visiting the churchyard till I came, and if she hadn\\u2019t come there in the day-time with me she wouldn\\u2019t have walked there in her sleep;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131458,\n            \"till, as I looked, the fire divided, and seemed to shine on me through the fog like two red eyes, such as Lucy told me of in her momentary mental wandering when, on the cliff, the dying sunlight struck the windows of St.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132952,\n            \"Poor dear, I\\u2019ve no doubt it frets her to be kept in the dark, and it may make her doubly anxious about me and the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133011,\n            \"The doctors were quite right to insist on her being kept out of this dreadful business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133044,\n            \"I shall not ever enter on the subject with her under any circumstances.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133058,\n            \"Indeed, it may not be a hard task, after all, for she herself has become reticent on the subject, and has not spoken of the Count or his doings ever since we told her of our decision.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133168,\n            \"\\u201d I got the letter in bed, and rose without waking Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133195,\n            \"I determined not to wake her, but that, when I should return from this new search, I would arrange for her going back to Exeter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133224,\n            \"I think she would be happier in our own home, with her daily tasks to interest her, than in being here amongst us and in ignorance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135440,\n            \"Mina was looking tired and pale, but she made a gallant effort to be bright and cheerful, it wrung my heart to think that I had had to keep anything from her and so caused her inquietude.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135480,\n            \"Thank God, this will be the last night of her looking on at our conferences, and feeling the sting of our not showing our confidence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135508,\n            \"It took all my courage to hold to the wise resolution of keeping her out of our grim task.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135558,\n            \"I am glad we made our resolution in time, as with such a feeling as this, our growing knowledge would be torture to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135602,\n            \"so after dinner-followed by a little music to save appearances even amongst ourselves-I took Mina to her room and left her to go to bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135632,\n            \"The dear girl was more affectionate with me than ever, and clung to me as though she would detain me;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 17]\": [\n        [\n            34153,\n            \"and she told me all over again about Arthur and their coming marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34167,\n            \"That made me just a little heart-sick, for I haven\\u2019t heard from Jonathan for a whole month.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34213,\n            \"I hope there cannot be anything the matter with Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34369,\n            \"I wonder where Jonathan is and if he is thinking of me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34382,\n            \"I wish he were here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36216,\n            \"I am unhappy about Lucy and about Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36225,\n            \"I had not heard from Jonathan for some time, and was very concerned;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36240,\n            \"but yesterday dear Mr. Hawkins, who is always so kind, sent me a letter from him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36626,\n            \"I am getting quite uneasy about him, though why I should I do not know;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36643,\n            \"but I do wish that he would write, if it were only a single line.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36801,\n            \"- Another week gone, and no news from Jonathan, not even to Mr. Hawkins, from whom I have heard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36825,\n            \"Oh, I do hope he is not ill.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36841,\n            \"I look at that last letter of his, but somehow it does not satisfy me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36972,\n            \"but no one has heard a word of Jonathan since that last letter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43847,\n            \"Somehow I felt glad that Jonathan was not on the sea last night, but on land.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43883,\n            \"I am getting fearfully anxious about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45102,\n            \"I should be quite happy if I only knew if Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45117,\n            \"God bless and keep him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50101,\n            \"The letter that he has seen and touched must comfort me till we meet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50185,\n            \"He has been under our care for nearly six weeks, suffering from a violent brain fever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50203,\n            \"He wishes me to convey his love, and to say that by this post I write for him to Mr. Peter Hawkins, Exeter, to say, with his dutiful respects, that he is sorry for his delay, and that all of his work is completed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50255,\n            \"He will require some few weeks\\u2019 rest in our sanatorium in the hills, but will then return.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50275,\n            \"He wishes me to say that he has not sufficient money with him, and that he would like to pay for his staying here, so that others who need shall not be wanting for help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50335,\n            \"- My patient being asleep, I open this to let you know something more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50351,\n            \"He has told me all about you, and that you are shortly to be his wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50375,\n            \"He has had some fearful shock-so says our doctor-and in his delirium his ravings have been dreadful;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50454,\n            \"We should have written long ago, but we knew nothing of his friends, and there was on him nothing that any one could understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50481,\n            \"He came in the train from Klausenburg, and the guard was told by the station-master there that he rushed into the station shouting for a ticket for home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50513,\n            \"Seeing from his violent demeanour that he was English, they gave him a ticket for the furthest station on the way thither that the train reached.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50660,\n            \"The attendant was struck by his manner, and knowing my interest in him, encouraged him to talk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50680,\n            \"He is usually respectful to the attendant and at times servile;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50717,\n            \"All he would say was:-\\u201cI don\\u2019t want to talk to you: you don\\u2019t count now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50748,\n            \"\\u201d The attendant thinks it is some sudden form of religious mania which has seized him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50807,\n            \"His attitude to me was the same as that to the attendant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50820,\n            \"in his sublime self-feeling the difference between myself and attendant seemed to him as nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50838,\n            \"It looks like religious mania, and he will soon think that he himself is God.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50945,\n            \"All at once that shifty look came into his eyes which we always see when a madman has seized an idea, and with it the shifty movement of the head and back which asylum attendants come to know so well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51127,\n            \") To this he answered enigmatically:-\\u201cThe bride-maidens rejoice the eyes that wait the coming of the bride;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51307,\n            \"I had lain tossing about, and had heard the clock strike only twice, when the night-watchman came to me, sent up from the ward, to say that Renfield had escaped.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51367,\n            \"Those ideas of his might work out dangerously with strangers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51385,\n            \"He said he had seen him not ten minutes before, seemingly asleep in his bed, when he had looked through the observation-trap in the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51429,\n            \"He ran back and saw his feet disappear through the window, and had at once sent up for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51465,\n            \"The attendant thought it would be more useful to watch where he should go than to follow him, as he might lose sight of him whilst getting out of the building by the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51549,\n            \"The attendant told me the patient had gone to the left, and had taken a straight line, so I ran as quickly as I could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51605,\n            \"I ran back at once, told the watchman to get three or four men immediately and follow me into the grounds of Carfax, in case our friend might be dangerous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51700,\n            \"He was talking, apparently to some one, but I was afraid to go near enough to hear what he was saying, lest I might frighten him, and he should run off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51806,\n            \"I heard him say:-\\u201cI am here to do Your bidding, Master.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51823,\n            \"I am Your slave, and You will reward me, for I shall be faithful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51840,\n            \"I have worshipped You long and afar off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51849,\n            \"Now that You are near, I await Your commands, and You will not pass me by, will You, dear Master, in Your distribution of good things?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51881,\n            \"\\u201d He is a selfish old beggar anyhow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51915,\n            \"When we closed in on him he fought like a tiger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51927,\n            \"He is immensely strong, for he was more like a wild beast than a man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51965,\n            \"It is a mercy that we have found out his strength and his danger in good time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52067,\n            \"Just now he spoke coherent words for the first time:-\\u201cI shall be patient, Master.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52361,\n            \"Sister Agatha, who is a good creature and a born nurse, tells me that he raved of dreadful things whilst he was off his head.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52443,\n            \"She is a sweet, good soul, and the next day, when she saw I was troubled, she opened up the subject again, and after saying that she could never mention what my poor dear raved about, added: \\u2018 I can tell you this much, my dear: that it was not about anything which he has done wrong himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52527,\n            \"He has not forgotten you or what he owes to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52667,\n            \"I asked Sister Agatha, and she brought all his things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52750,\n            \"Then he called me back, and when I came he had his hand over the note-book, and he said to me very solemnly:-\\u201c\\u2018 Wilhelmina\\u2019- I knew then that he was in deadly earnest, for he has never called me by that name since he asked me to marry him-\\u2018 you know, dear, my ideas of the trust between husband and wife: there should be no secret, no concealment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52836,\n            \"I have had a great shock, and when I try to think of what it is I feel my head spin round, and I do not know if it was all real or the dreaming of a madman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52906,\n            \"I want to take up my life here, with our marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53069,\n            \"We are to be married in an hour, or as soon after as Jonathan awakes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53204,\n            \"When the chaplain and the sisters had left me alone with my husband-oh, Lucy, it is the first time I have written the words \\u2018 my husband\\u2019- left me alone with my husband, I took the book from under his pillow, and wrapped it up in white paper, and tied it with a little bit of pale blue ribbon which was round my neck, and sealed it over the knot with sealing-wax, and for my seal I used my wedding ring.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53299,\n            \"Then I kissed it and showed it to my husband, and told him that I would keep it so, and then it would be an outward and visible sign for us all our lives that we trusted each other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53364,\n            \"Then he took my hand in his, and oh, Lucy, it was the first time he took his wife\\u2019s hand, and said that it was the dearest thing in all the wide world, and that he would go through all the past again to win it, if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53526,\n            \"And, my dear, when he kissed me, and drew me to him with his poor weak hands, it was like a very solemn pledge between us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54128,\n            \"\\u201d The attendant came to tell me, so I ran down at once to have a look at him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54222,\n            \"It was a strange thing that the patient had humour enough to see their distrust, for, coming close to me, he said in a whisper, all the while looking furtively at them:-\\u201cThey think I could hurt you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54313,\n            \"Am I to take it that I have anything in common with him, so that we are, as it were, to stand together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54435,\n            \"The attendant tells me that he was quiet until just before dawn, and that then he began to get uneasy, and at length violent, until at last he fell into a paroxysm which exhausted him so that he swooned into a sort of coma.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54545,\n            \"He escaped before without our help;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54561,\n            \"We shall give him a chance, and have the men ready to follow in case they are required.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54642,\n            \"We shall in future be able to ease his bonds for a few hours each day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54659,\n            \"I have given orders to the night attendant merely to shut him in the padded room, when once he is quiet, until an hour before sunrise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54730,\n            \"Renfield artfully waited until the attendant was entering the room to inspect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54743,\n            \"Then he dashed out past him and flew down the passage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54764,\n            \"Again he went into the grounds of the deserted house, and we found him in the same place, pressed against the old chapel door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54791,\n            \"When he saw me he became furious, and had not the attendants seized him in time, he would have tried to kill me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54817,\n            \"As we were holding him a strange thing happened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54923,\n            \"The patient grew calmer every instant, and presently said:-\\u201cYou needn\\u2019t tie me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56810,\n            \"Tell your friend that when that time you suck from my wound so swiftly the poison of the gangrene from that knife that our other friend, too nervous, let slip, you did more for him when he wants my aids and you call for them than all his great fortune could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58090,\n            \"- Zo\\u00f6phagous patient still keeps up our interest in him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58208,\n            \"The attendant tells me that his screams whilst in the paroxysm were really appalling;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58730,\n            \"I had been to see Miss Westenra, whom I found much better, and had just returned, and was standing at our own gate looking at the sunset, when once more I heard him yelling.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58916,\n            \"It is wonderful, however, what intellectual recuperative power lunatics have, for within a few minutes he stood up quite calmly and looked around him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58944,\n            \"I signalled to the attendants not to hold him, for I was anxious to see what he would do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59083,\n            \"there may be a clue after all, if we can find why to-day his paroxysms came on at high noon and at sunset.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64748,\n            \"If our young lover should turn up unexpected, as before, no word to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69056,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDon\\u2019t you mind him, sir!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69846,\n            \"At least, so he says, but I don\\u2019t give much for it myself, for if he did\\u2019e never said a word about it to his missis when\\u2019e got\\u2019ome, and it was only after the escape of the wolf was made known, and we had been up all night-a-huntin\\u2019of the Park for Bersicker, that he remembered seein\\u2019anything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70107,\n            \"I couldn\\u2019t cope in badinage with the worthy Thomas, but I thought I knew a surer way to his heart, so I said:-\\u201cNow, Mr. Bilder, we\\u2019ll consider that first half-sovereign worked off, and this brother of his is waiting to be claimed when you\\u2019ve told me what you think will happen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70286,\n            \"but I don\\u2019t believe him, for, yer see, sir, wolves don\\u2019t gallop no more nor dogs does, they not bein\\u2019built that way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70486,\n            \"My eye, won\\u2019t some cook get a rum start when she sees his green eyes a-shining at her out of the dark!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70546,\n            \"If he doesn\\u2019t, and some nursemaid goes a-walkin\\u2019orf with a soldier, leavin\\u2019of the hinfant in the perambulator-well, then I shouldn\\u2019t be surprised if the census is one babby the less.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71239,\n            \"When the attendants rushed in, and we turned our attention to him, his employment positively sickened me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71285,\n            \"He was easily secured, and, to my surprise, went with the attendants quite placidly, simply repeating over and over again: \\u201cThe blood is the life!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77478,\n            \"when we arrived at Exeter there was a carriage waiting for us, and in it, though he had an attack of gout, Mr. Hawkins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77742,\n            \"for, now that Jonathan is a partner, Mr. Hawkins wants to tell him all about the clients.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78181,\n            \"This afternoon a carrier\\u2019s cart with two men made a call at the empty house whose grounds abut on ours-the house to which, you will remember, the patient twice ran away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78264,\n            \"As he passed the window of Renfield\\u2019s room, the patient began to rate him from within, and called him all the foul names he could lay his tongue to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78298,\n            \"The man, who seemed a decent fellow enough, contented himself by telling him to \\u201cshut up for a foul-mouthed beggar,\\u201dwhereon our man accused him of robbing him and wanting to murder him and said that he would hinder him if he were to swing for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78621,\n            \"I called to the attendants to follow me, and ran after him, for I feared he was intent on some mischief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78692,\n            \"Before I could get up to him the patient rushed at them, and pulling one of them off the cart, began to knock his head against the ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78745,\n            \"The other fellow jumped down and struck him over the head with the butt-end of his heavy whip.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78772,\n            \"but he did not seem to mind it, but seized him also, and struggled with the three of us, pulling us to and fro as if we were kittens.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78830,\n            \"but as we began to master him, and the attendants were putting a strait-waistcoat on him, he began to shout: \\u2018 I\\u2019ll frustrate them!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78862,\n            \"They shan\\u2019t rob me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78869,\n            \"they shan\\u2019t murder me by inches!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78897,\n            \"It was with very considerable difficulty that they got him back to the house and put him in the padded room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78975,\n            \"Their threats were, however, mingled with some sort of indirect apology for the defeat of the two of them by a feeble madman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79001,\n            \"They said that if it had not been for the way their strength had been spent in carrying and raising the heavy boxes to the cart they would have made short work of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79304,\n            \"Some may not think it so sad for us, but we had both come to so love him that it really seems as though we had lost a father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79364,\n            \"It is not only that he feels sorrow, deep sorrow, for the dear, good man who has befriended him all his life, and now at the end has treated him like his own son and left him a fortune which to people of our modest bringing up is wealth beyond the dream of avarice, but Jonathan feels it on another account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79490,\n            \"Oh, it is too hard that a sweet, simple, noble, strong nature such as his-a nature which enabled him by our dear, good friend\\u2019s aid to rise from clerk to master in a few years-should be so injured that the very essence of its strength is gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79569,\n            \"but, Lucy dear, I must tell some one, for the strain of keeping up a brave and cheerful appearance to Jonathan tries me, and I have no one here that I can confide in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79648,\n            \"As there are no relations at all, Jonathan will have to be chief mourner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86284,\n            \"There were only ourselves and the servants there, one or two old friends of his from Exeter, his London agent, and a gentleman representing Sir John Paxton, the President of the Incorporated Law Society.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88219,\n            \"And yet when he say things that touch my husband-heart to the quick, and make my father-heart yearn to him as to no other man-not even to you, friend John, for we are more level in experiences than father and son-yet even at such moment King Laugh he come to me and shout and bellow in my ear, \\u2018 Here I am!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92155,\n            \"\\u201cI knew long that Mr. Jonathan was a man of much thankfulness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92802,\n            \"Your husband is noble nature, and you are noble too, for you trust, and trust cannot be where there is mean nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92855,\n            \"\\u201d I saw here an opening to ask him about Jonathan, so I said:-\\u201cHe was almost recovered, but he has been greatly upset by Mr. Hawkins\\u2019 s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92916,\n            \"\\u201d I went on:-\\u201cI suppose this upset him, for when we were in town on Thursday last he had a sort of shock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93005,\n            \"The pity for Jonathan, the horror which he experienced, the whole fearful mystery of his diary, and the fear that has been brooding over me ever since, all came in a tumult.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93042,\n            \"I suppose I was hysterical, for I threw myself on my knees and held up my hands to him, and implored him to make my husband well again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93286,\n            \"I promise you that I will gladly do all for him that I can-all to make his life strong and manly, and your life a happy one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93331,\n            \"Husband Jonathan would not like to see you so pale;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93357,\n            \"Therefore for his sake you must eat and smile.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93426,\n            \"And then, too, you will tell me of husband Jonathan\\u2019s trouble so far as you can, but not yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93463,\n            \"\\u201d After lunch, when we went back to the drawing-room, he said to me:-\\u201cAnd now tell me all about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93492,\n            \"\\u201d When it came to speaking to this great learned man, I began to fear that he would think me a weak fool, and Jonathan a madman-that journal is all so strange-and I hesitated to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93536,\n            \"But he was so sweet and kind, and he had promised to help, and I trusted him, so I said:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, what I have to tell you is so queer that you must not laugh at me or at my husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93782,\n            \"It will tell you my trouble and Jonathan\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93860,\n            \"\\u201cI shall in the morning, so soon as I can, come to see you and your husband, if I may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93885,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cJonathan will be here at half-past eleven, and you must come to lunch with us and see him then;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93929,\n            \"\\u201d He was surprised at my knowledge of the trains off-hand, but he does not know that I have made up all the trains to and from Exeter, so that I may help Jonathan in case he is in a hurry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94022,\n            \"\\u201cDear Madam Mina,-\\u201cI have read your husband\\u2019s so wonderful diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94072,\n            \"but for him and you there is no dread.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94082,\n            \"He is a noble fellow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94088,\n            \"and let me tell you from experience of men, that one who would do as he did in going down that wall and to that room-ay, and going a second time-is not one to be injured in permanence by a shock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98176,\n            \"He will let two scientists see his case, if he will not let two friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98193,\n            \"We shall tell him nothing, but only that we wish to learn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98612,\n            \"When she asked him why he wanted to go, he said he wanted to play with the \\u2018 bloofer lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98634,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201c\\u201cI hope,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing, \\u201cthat when you are sending the child home you will caution its parents to keep strict watch over it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98691,\n            \"But in any case I suppose you will not let it away for some days?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104620,\n            \"at the first to please my friend John, and then to help a sweet young lady, whom, too, I came to love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110112,\n            \"Then said the Professor as we moved off:-\\u201cTwo nights hence you shall meet with me and dine together at seven of the clock with friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110395,\n            \"over it he told me of a diary kept by Jonathan Harker when abroad, and gave me a typewritten copy of it, as also of Mrs. Harker\\u2019s diary at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111762,\n            \"\\u201cWhen you have read those papers-my own diary and my husband\\u2019s also, which I have typed-you will know me better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112538,\n            \"Jonathan and I have been working day and night since Professor Van Helsing saw us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113028,\n            \"It is all so wild, and mysterious, and strange that if I had not known Jonathan\\u2019s experience in Transylvania I could not have believed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113121,\n            \"I have sent a telegram to Jonathan to come on here when he arrives in London from Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113319,\n            \"Before I left him I remembered what Jonathan put in his diary of the Professor\\u2019s perturbation at reading something in an evening paper at the station at Exeter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115318,\n            \"It is, I suppose, the reaction from the haunting fear which I have had: that this terrible affair and the reopening of his old wound might act detrimentally on Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115352,\n            \"I saw him leave for Whitby with as brave a face as I could, but I was sick with apprehension.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115544,\n            \"Dr. Seward was out on business, and had taken Jonathan with him, so I had to see them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117681,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy husband and I are staying on a visit with Dr. Seward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118504,\n            \"He saw me at once, and rushed up to me, saying:-\\u201cAh, friend John, how goes all?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118690,\n            \"Friend John, up to now fortune has made that woman of help to us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118832,\n            \"You tell me she has wrote all, then she must consult with us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118865,\n            \"\\u201d I agreed heartily with him, and then I told him what we had found in his absence: that the house which Dracula had bought was the very next one to my own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118993,\n            \"Before we went to prepare for dinner he said to Mrs. Harker:-\\u201cI am told, Madam Mina, by my friend John that you and your husband have put up in exact order all things that have been, up to this moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119223,\n            \"It can but make your husband love you the more, and all us, your friends, more honour you-as well as more esteem and love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119438,\n            \"Jonathan sat next to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120222,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst he was speaking, Jonathan had taken my hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120234,\n            \"I feared, oh so much, that the appalling nature of our danger was overcoming him when I saw his hand stretch out;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120307,\n            \"When the Professor had done speaking my husband looked in my eyes, and I in his;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120430,\n            \"Jonathan held my right with his left and stretched across to Mr. Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121162,\n            \"he can be as bat, as Madam Mina saw him on the window at Whitby, and as friend John saw him fly from this so near house, and as my friend Quincey saw him at the window of Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122190,\n            \"We know from the inquiry of Jonathan that from the castle to Whitby came fifty boxes of earth, all of which were delivered at Carfax;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122977,\n            \"I shall lie down and pretend to sleep, lest Jonathan have added anxiety about me when he returns.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123180,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cTake me with you, friend John,\\u201dsaid the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125695,\n            \"\\u201d Lord Godalming and I were silent, but Dr. Van Helsing added:-\\u201cFriend John, you know more of lunatics than I do, and I\\u2019m glad of it, for I fear that if it had been to me to decide I would before that last hysterical outburst have given him free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130078,\n            \"This morning I slept late after the fatigues of yesterday, and though Jonathan was late too, he was the earlier.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130101,\n            \"He spoke to me before he went out, never more sweetly or tenderly, but he never mentioned a word of what had happened in the visit to the Count\\u2019s house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130136,\n            \"And yet he must have known how terribly anxious I was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130152,\n            \"I suppose it must have distressed him even more than it did me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130199,\n            \"And now I am crying like a silly fool, when I know it comes from my husband\\u2019s great love and from the good, good wishes of those other strong men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130366,\n            \"I kept thinking over everything that has been ever since Jonathan came to see me in London, and it all seems like a horrible tragedy, with fate pressing on relentlessly to some destined end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130540,\n            \"I must hide it from Jonathan, for if he knew that I had been crying twice in one morning-I, who never cried on my own account, and whom he has never caused to shed a tear-the dear fellow would fret his heart out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130591,\n            \"I shall put a bold face on, and if I do feel weepy, he shall never see it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130969,\n            \"but I must have fallen asleep, for, except dreams, I do not remember anything until the morning, when Jonathan woke me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130995,\n            \"I think that it took me an effort and a little time to realise where I was, and that it was Jonathan who was bending over me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131050,\n            \"I thought that I was asleep, and waiting for Jonathan to come back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131065,\n            \"I was very anxious about him, and I was powerless to act;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131151,\n            \"The gaslight which I had left lit for Jonathan, but turned down, came only like a tiny red spark through the fog, which had evidently grown thicker and poured into the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131513,\n            \"Suddenly the horror burst upon me that it was thus that Jonathan had seen those awful women growing into reality through the whirling mist in the moonlight, and in my dream I must have fainted, for all became black darkness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131732,\n            \"I must have slept soundly, for I was not waked by Jonathan coming to bed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131846,\n            \"Jonathan would be miserable if he knew I had been crying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131858,\n            \"He and the others were out till dinner-time, and they all came in tired.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131944,\n            \"I could see from Jonathan\\u2019s manner that he had something important to communicate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144216,\n            \"Jonathan, you must not leave me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144224,\n            \"I have suffered enough to-night, God knows, without the dread of his harming you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144243,\n            \"You must stay with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144268,\n            \"and, he yielding to her, she pulled him down sitting on the bed side, and clung to him fiercely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144360,\n            \"\\u201d She shuddered and was silent, holding down her head on her husband\\u2019s breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144378,\n            \"When she raised it, his white night-robe was stained with blood where her lips had touched, and where the thin open wound in her neck had sent forth drops.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144439,\n            \"I must touch him or kiss him no more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144449,\n            \"Oh, that it should be that it is I who am now his worst enemy, and whom he may have most cause to fear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144502,\n            \"I would not hear it of you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144519,\n            \"May God judge me by my deserts, and punish me with more bitter suffering than even this hour, if by any act or will of mine anything ever come between us!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144553,\n            \"\\u201d He put out his arms and folded her to his breast;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144575,\n            \"He looked at us over her bowed head, with eyes that blinked damply above his quivering nostrils;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144601,\n            \"After a while her sobs became less frequent and more faint, and then he said to me, speaking with a studied calmness which I felt tried his nervous power to the utmost:-\\u201cAnd now, Dr. Seward, tell me all about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144682,\n            \"but his nostrils twitched and his eyes blazed as I told how the ruthless hands of the Count had held his wife in that terrible and horrid position, with her mouth to the open wound in his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145454,\n            \"\\u201d The poor, dear lady shivered, and I could see the tension of her nerves as she clasped her husband closer to her and bent her head lower and lower still on his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145525,\n            \"The other hand was locked in that of her husband, who held his other arm thrown round her protectingly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145625,\n            \"\\u201d Her husband involuntarily groaned as she turned to him and said lovingly: \\u201cDo not fret, dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145928,\n            \"I knew him at once from the description of the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146231,\n            \"She clasped his hand harder, and looked at him pityingly, as if he were the injured one, and went on:-\\u201cI felt my strength fading away, and I was in a half swoon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146313,\n            \"\\u201d The remembrance seemed for a while to overpower her, and she drooped and would have sunk down but for her husband\\u2019s sustaining arm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148119,\n            \"so sorrowfully, as she held out her hand:-\\u201cI promise you, my dear friend, that if God will let me live, I shall strive to do so;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149299,\n            \"I have read of a gentleman who owned a so fine house in London, and when he went for months of summer to Switzerland and lock up his house, some burglar came and broke window at back and got in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149342,\n            \"Then he went and made open the shutters in front and walk out and in through the door, before the very eyes of the police.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149411,\n            \"Then he go to a builder, and he sell him that house, making an agreement that he pull it down and take all away within a certain time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157095,\n            \"\\u201cJonathan,\\u201dshe said, and the word sounded like music on her lips it was so full of love and tenderness, \\u201cJonathan dear, and you all my true, true friends, I want you to bear something in mind through all this dreadful time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157147,\n            \"I know that you must fight-that you must destroy even as you destroyed the false Lucy so that the true Lucy might live hereafter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157323,\n            \"As she stopped speaking he leaped to his feet, almost tearing his hand from hers as he spoke:-\\u201cMay God give him into my hand just for long enough to destroy that earthly life of him which we are aiming at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157407,\n            \"Don\\u2019t say such things, Jonathan, my husband;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157419,\n            \"or you will crush me with fear and horror.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157495,\n            \"my husband, indeed I would have spared you such a thought had there been another way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157513,\n            \"but I pray that God may not have treasured your wild words, except as the heart-broken wail of a very loving and sorely stricken man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157754,\n            \"When they had retired, Quincey, Godalming, and I arranged that we should sit up, dividing the night between us, and watch over the safety of the poor stricken lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157789,\n            \"The first watch falls to Quincey, so the rest of us shall be off to bed as soon as we can.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158738,\n            \"friend Jonathan, we have got our dear Madam Mina, as of old, back to us to-day!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159736,\n            \"We can know now what was in the Count\\u2019s mind, when he seize that money, though Jonathan\\u2019s so fierce knife put him in the danger that even he dread.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160206,\n            \"You are to stay with your dear Madam Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160245,\n            \"But do you stay and take care of her to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160515,\n            \"Then we will comfort you and poor dear Madam Mina with new hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161126,\n            \"These not so important as to go in your list of the shipping in the Times, and so we go, by suggestion of Lord Godalming, to your Lloyd\\u2019s, where are note of all ships that sail, however so small.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162697,\n            \"you, my dear Madam Mina, will learn it in the phonograph of my friend John, or in that of your husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167935,\n            \"then, motioning her husband to sit beside her on the sofa where she was half reclining, she made the rest of us bring chairs up close.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167964,\n            \"Taking her husband\\u2019s hand in hers began:-\\u201cWe are all here together in freedom, for perhaps the last time!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167995,\n            \"I know that you will always be with me to the end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168542,\n            \"\\u201d She looked again questioningly, but this time avoided her husband\\u2019s face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168563,\n            \"he nodded, and her face lit up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168597,\n            \"You must promise me, one and all-even you, my beloved husband-that, should the time come, you will kill me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168647,\n            \"\\u201cWhen you shall be convinced that I am so changed that it is better that I die than I may live.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168724,\n            \"He knelt down before her and taking her hand in his said solemnly:-\\u201cI\\u2019m only a rough fellow, who hasn\\u2019t, perhaps, lived as a man should to win such a distinction, but I swear to you by all that I hold sacred and dear that, should the time ever come, I shall not flinch from the duty that you have set us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168800,\n            \"And I promise you, too, that I shall make all certain, for if I am only doubtful I shall take it that the time has come!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168836,\n            \"\\u201d was all she could say amid her fast-falling tears, as, bending over, she kissed his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169151,\n            \"If that time shall come again, I look to you to make it a happy memory of my husband\\u2019s life that it was his loving hand which set me free from the awful thrall upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169368,\n            \"\\u201d She was interrupted by a deep groan from her husband;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169380,\n            \"taking his hand in hers, she held it over her heart, and continued: \\u201cYou must read it over me some day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169432,\n            \"You, my dearest, will I hope read it, for then it will be in your voice in my memory for ever-come what may!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169461,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut oh, my dear one,\\u201dhe pleaded, \\u201cdeath is afar off from you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169518,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cOh, my wife, must I read it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169538,\n            \"\\u201cIt would comfort me, my husband!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169553,\n            \"and he began to read when she had got the book ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171615,\n            \"When, however, her husband mentioned casually that she was sleeping so soundly that he could not wake her, we went to her room to see for ourselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172783,\n            \"John will stay with Madam Mina and me, and we shall consult.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175632,\n            \"Quincey raised his eyebrows slightly and looked at her intently, whilst Harker\\u2019s hand instinctively closed round the hilt of his Kukri.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178289,\n            \"When Skinsky had come to him, he had taken him to the ship and handed over the box, so as to save porterage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180510,\n            \"\\u201d Dr. Seward said:-\\u201cI think I had better go with Quincey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180627,\n            \"\\u201d He looked at Jonathan as he spoke, and Jonathan looked at me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180926,\n            \"Whilst the old fox is tied in his box, floating on the running stream whence he cannot escape to land-where he dares not raise the lid of his coffin-box lest his Slovak carriers should in fear leave him to perish-we shall go in the track where Jonathan went,-from Bistritz over the Borgo, and find our way to the Castle of Dracula.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181060,\n            \"\\u201d Here Jonathan interrupted him hotly:-\\u201cDo you mean to say, Professor Van Helsing, that you would bring Mina, in her sad case and tainted as she is with that devil\\u2019s illness, right into the jaws of his death-trap?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181193,\n            \"\\u201d Here he turned to me, and as his eyes lit on my forehead he threw up his arms with a cry: \\u201cOh, my God, what have we done to have this terror upon us!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181248,\n            \"The Professor\\u2019s voice, as he spoke in clear, sweet tones, which seemed to vibrate in the air, calmed us all:-\\u201cOh, my friend, it is because I would save Madam Mina from that awful place that I would go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181363,\n            \"If the Count escape us this time-and he is strong and subtle and cunning-he may choose to sleep him for a century, and then in time our dear one \\\"-he took my hand-\\\" would come to him to keep him company, and would be as those others that you, Jonathan, saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181427,\n            \"You have told us of their gloating lips;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181524,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo as you will,\\u201dsaid Jonathan, with a sob that shook him all over, \\u201cwe are in the hands of God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184279,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing is sleeping, Poor dear, he looks very tired and old and grey, but his mouth is set as firmly as a conqueror\\u2019s;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184743,\n            \"God grant that we may be guided aright, and that He will deign to watch over my husband and those dear to us both, and who are in such deadly peril.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185293,\n            \"\\u201cOf course I know it,\\u201dshe answer, and with a pause, add: \\u201cHave not my Jonathan travelled it and wrote of his travel?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185432,\n            \"By-and-by we find all the things which Jonathan have note in that wonderful diary of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186407,\n            \"the frowning mountains seemed further away, and we were near the top of a steep-rising hill, on summit of which was such a castle as Jonathan tell of in his diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187420,\n            \"Then they began to materialise till-if God have not take away my reason, for I saw it through my eyes-there were before me in actual flesh the same three women that Jonathan saw in the room, when they would have kissed his throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187503,\n            \"and as their laugh came through the silence of the night, they twined their arms and pointed to her, and said in those so sweet tingling tones that Jonathan said were of the intolerable sweetness of the water-glasses:-\\u201cCome, sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188705,\n            \"So he delay, and delay, and delay, till the mere beauty and the fascination of the wanton Un-Dead have hypnotise him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189052,\n            \"but I go on searching until, presently, I find in a high great tomb as if made to one much beloved that other fair sister which, like Jonathan I had seen to gather herself out of the atoms of the mist.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189865,\n            \"- It was late in the afternoon when the Professor and I took our way towards the east whence I knew Jonathan was coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190120,\n            \"I knew from the way Dr. Van Helsing was searching about that he was trying to seek some strategic point, where we would be less exposed in case of attack.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190253,\n            \"\\u201d He brought in our furs, and made a snug nest for me, and got out some provisions and forced them upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190670,\n            \"Round the rock he had drawn a circle, such as we had found shelter in last night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190714,\n            \"\\u201d He took the glasses from me, and at the next lull of the snow swept the whole space below us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190898,\n            \"I knew at all events that neither of them was Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190946,\n            \"One of them I knew was Jonathan, and the other I took, of course, to be Lord Godalming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190980,\n            \"When I told the Professor he shouted in glee like a schoolboy, and, after looking intently till a snow fall made sight impossible, he laid his Winchester rifle ready for use against the boulder at the opening of our shelter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191402,\n            \"The Professor and I crouched down behind our rock, and held our weapons ready;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191418,\n            \"I could see that he was determined that they should not pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191601,\n            \"At the same moment Dr. Van Helsing and I rose behind the rock and pointed our weapons at them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191636,\n            \"The leader turned to them and gave a word at which every man of the gypsy party drew what weapon he carried, knife or pistol, and held himself in readiness to attack.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191745,\n            \"I should have felt terrible fear at seeing Jonathan in such danger, but that the ardour of battle must have been upon me as well as the rest of them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191793,\n            \"Seeing the quick movement of our parties, the leader of the gypsies gave a command;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191951,\n            \"instinctively they cowered, aside and let him pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192018,\n            \"All the time I had been breathlessly watching Jonathan I had, with the tail of my eye, seen him pressing desperately forward, and had seen the knives of the gypsies flash as he won a way through them, and they cut at him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192204,\n            \"By this time the gypsies, seeing themselves covered by the Winchesters, and at the mercy of Lord Godalming and Dr. Seward, had given in and made no resistance.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 5]\": [\n        [\n            115592,\n            \"Of course they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has been quite \\u201cblowing my trumpet,\\u201das Mr. Morris expressed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115948,\n            \"Mr. Morris, with instinctive delicacy, just laid a hand for a moment on his shoulder, and then walked quietly out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117056,\n            \"- I got home at five o\\u2019clock, and found that Godalming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had made and arranged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170745,\n            \"Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181628,\n            \"I felt so thankful that Lord Godalming is rich, and that both he and Mr. Morris, who also has plenty of money, are willing to spend it so freely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183071,\n            \"I wonder how Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris are getting on.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 6]\": [\n        [\n            117056,\n            \"- I got home at five o\\u2019clock, and found that Godalming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had made and arranged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156395,\n            \"Godalming and Morris had rushed out into the yard, and Harker had lowered himself from the window to follow the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170745,\n            \"Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181628,\n            \"I felt so thankful that Lord Godalming is rich, and that both he and Mr. Morris, who also has plenty of money, are willing to spend it so freely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183071,\n            \"I wonder how Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris are getting on.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 7]\": [\n        [\n            145212,\n            \"I thought it well to know if possible where the Count would go when he left the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145231,\n            \"I did not see him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156395,\n            \"Godalming and Morris had rushed out into the yard, and Harker had lowered himself from the window to follow the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180367,\n            \"\\u201cAnd I, horses to follow on the bank lest by chance he land,\\u201dsaid Mr. Morris.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 9]\": [\n        [\n            134999,\n            \"When I asked who had purchased it, he opened his eyes a thought wider, and paused a few seconds before replying:-\\u201cIt is sold, sir.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135072,\n            \"\\u201cIt is sold, sir,\\u201dwas again his laconic reply.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 11]\": [\n        [\n            145237,\n            \"but I saw a bat rise from Renfield\\u2019s window, and flap westward.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 12]\": [\n        [\n            122121,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst they were talking Mr. Morris was looking steadily at the window, and he now got up quietly, and went out of the room.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 13]\": [\n        [\n            188100,\n            \"Oh, if only Morris and Seward were with us.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 14]\": [\n        [\n            152420,\n            \"Out of it, in leisurely fashion, got Lord Godalming and Morris;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156395,\n            \"Godalming and Morris had rushed out into the yard, and Harker had lowered himself from the window to follow the Count.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 16]\": [\n        [\n            115592,\n            \"Of course they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has been quite \\u201cblowing my trumpet,\\u201das Mr. Morris expressed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117024,\n            \"\\\"-the very words he had used to Lucy, and oh, but he proved himself a friend!\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 6]\": [\n        [\n            113478,\n            \"He had got his wife\\u2019s wire just before starting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113588,\n            \"- After lunch Harker and his wife went back to their own room, and as I passed a while ago I heard the click of the typewriter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113666,\n            \"He is now reading his wife\\u2019s typescript of my diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117056,\n            \"- I got home at five o\\u2019clock, and found that Godalming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had made and arranged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118334,\n            \"Looking at my watch, I saw that I should go to the station to meet Van Helsing, so I told Mrs. Harker that it was time to leave.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118592,\n            \"\\u201d As I drove to the house I told him of what had passed, and of how my own diary had come to be of some use through Mrs. Harker\\u2019s suggestion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118993,\n            \"Before we went to prepare for dinner he said to Mrs. Harker:-\\u201cI am told, Madam Mina, by my friend John that you and your husband have put up in exact order all things that have been, up to this moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119042,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNot up to this moment, Professor,\\u201dshe said impulsively, \\u201cbut up to this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119106,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Harker began to blush, and taking a paper from her pockets, she said:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, will you read this, and tell me if it must go in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119187,\n            \"\\u201d The Professor read it over gravely, and handed it back, saying:-\\u201cIt need not go in if you do not wish it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129976,\n            \"\\u201d So Van Helsing has gone to confer with Mrs. Harker and Harker;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138695,\n            \"We beg, with regard to the desire of your Lordship, expressed by Mr. Harker on your behalf, to supply the following information concerning the sale and purchase of No.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139796,\n            \"I want him without an instant\\u2019s delay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139829,\n            \"When he saw Renfield on the ground, he looked keenly at him a moment, and then turned to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139851,\n            \"I think he recognised my thought in my eyes, for he said very quietly, manifestly for the ears of the attendant:-\\u201cAh, a sad accident!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139968,\n            \"for, almost before he looked at the patient, he whispered to me:-\\u201cSend the attendant away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140184,\n            \"I went over and opened it and found in the corridor without, Arthur and Quincey in pajamas and slippers: the former spoke:-\\u201cI heard your man call up Dr. Van Helsing and tell him of an accident.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140473,\n            \"I had a horrible sinking in my heart, and from Van Helsing\\u2019s face I gathered that he felt some fear or apprehension as to what was to come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140716,\n            \"I looked up at the Professor and caught his eyes fixed on mine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141312,\n            \"It was that night after you left me, when I implored you to let me go away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141363,\n            \"I was in an agony of despair for a long time after you left me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141407,\n            \"I heard the dogs bark behind our house, but not where He was!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141422,\n            \"\\u201d As he spoke, Van Helsing\\u2019s eyes never blinked, but his hand came out and met mine and gripped it hard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141473,\n            \"Renfield proceeded:-\\u201cHe came up to the window in the mist, as I had seen him often before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141554,\n            \"I wouldn\\u2019t ask him to come in at first, though I knew he wanted to-just as he had wanted all along.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141581,\n            \"Then he began promising me things-not in words but by doing them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141663,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing nodded to him as he whispered to me unconsciously:-\\u201cThe Acherontia Aitetropos of the Sphinges-what you call the \\u2018 Death\\u2019s-head Moth \\u2019?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141764,\n            \"\\u2019 I laughed at him, for I wanted to see what he could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141794,\n            \"He beckoned me to the window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141801,\n            \"I got up and looked out, and He raised his hands, and seemed to call out without using any words.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141843,\n            \"and then He moved the mist to the right and left, and I could see that there were thousands of rats with their eyes blazing red-like His, only smaller.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141888,\n            \"and I thought he seemed to be saying: \\u2018 All these lives will I give you, ay, and many more and greater, through countless ages, if you will fall down and worship me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141947,\n            \"and before I knew what I was doing, I found myself opening the sash and saying to Him: \\u2018 Come in, Lord and Master!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141975,\n            \"\\u2019 The rats were all gone, but He slid into the room through the sash, though it was only open an inch wide-just as the Moon herself has often come in through the tiniest crack and has stood before me in all her size and splendour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142026,\n            \"\\u201d His voice was weaker, so I moistened his lips with the brandy again, and he continued;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142067,\n            \"I was about to call him back to the point, but Van Helsing whispered to me: \\u201cLet him go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142118,\n            \"\\u201d He proceeded:-\\u201cAll day I waited to hear from him, but he did not send me anything, not even a blow-fly, and when the moon got up I was pretty angry with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142161,\n            \"When he slid in through the window, though it was shut, and did not even knock, I got mad with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142186,\n            \"He sneered at me, and his white face looked out of the mist with his red eyes gleaming, and he went on as though he owned the whole place, and I was no one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142224,\n            \"He didn\\u2019t even smell the same as he went by me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142238,\n            \"I couldn\\u2019t hold him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142434,\n            \"but when she went away I began to think, and it made me mad to know that He had been taking the life out of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142481,\n            \"\\u201cSo when He came to-night I was ready for Him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142537,\n            \"Ay, and He felt it too, for He had to come out of the mist to struggle with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142563,\n            \"and I thought I was going to win, for I didn\\u2019t mean Him to take any more of her life, till I saw His eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142605,\n            \"He slipped through it, and when I tried to cling to Him, He raised me up and flung me down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142846,\n            \"his voice was breaking, and I do not know if rage or terror predominated in my own heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143052,\n            \"The Professor did actually fall, and I saw across him as he gathered himself up from hands and knees.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143535,\n            \"Van Helsing, Art, and I moved forward to Mrs. Harker, who by this time had drawn her breath and with it had given a scream so wild, so ear-piercing, so despairing that it seems to me now that it will ring in my ears till my dying day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143728,\n            \"Van Helsing whispered to me:-\\u201cJonathan is in a stupor such as we know the Vampire can produce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143872,\n            \"but at the instant I heard Harker\\u2019s quick exclamation as he woke to partial consciousness, and turned to the bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144139,\n            \"\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, you love Mina, I know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144291,\n            \"Van Helsing and I tried to calm them both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144782,\n            \"Van Helsing looked at me questioningly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148927,\n            \"but I knew that if he wished to delay he had a good reason for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148965,\n            \"you know, I am sure, what torture I am in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148978,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAh, my child, that I do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148989,\n            \"and indeed there is no wish of me to add to your anguish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149162,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThen,\\u201dhe looked at me as keenly as he spoke, \\u201call that is in doubt is the conscience of the employer, and the belief of your policemen as to whether or no that employer has a good conscience or a bad one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150411,\n            \"\\u201cDo you forget,\\u201dhe said, with actually a smile, \\u201cthat last night he banqueted heavily, and will sleep late?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151134,\n            \"so gravely that I could not help feeling that he was in some way inspired, and was stating things outside himself:-\\u201cIt may be that you may have to bear that mark till God himself see fit, as He most surely shall, on the Judgment Day, to redress all wrongs of the earth and of His children that He has placed thereon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151368,\n            \"Mina and I both felt so, and simultaneously we each took one of the old man\\u2019s hands and bent over and kissed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151674,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing said to us solemnly as we stood before them:-\\u201cAnd now, my friends, we have a duty here to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152657,\n            \"my own cigar burnt furiously, but Van Helsing\\u2019s went cold altogether.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154853,\n            \"It was just an ordinary knock, such as is given hourly by thousands of gentlemen, but it made the Professor\\u2019s heart and mine beat loudly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155429,\n            \"Van Helsing, Harker, and I were just behind the door, so that when it was opened the Professor could guard it whilst we two stepped between the incomer and the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156444,\n            \"Van Helsing and I tried to make inquiry at the back of the house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158501,\n            \"She said to me hurriedly:-\\u201cGo, call the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158877,\n            \"Mina gazed at him fixedly for a few minutes, during which my own heart beat like a trip hammer, for I felt that some crisis was at hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158936,\n            \"The Professor made a few more passes and then stopped, and I could see that his forehead was covered with great beads of perspiration.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159000,\n            \"Raising his hand to impose silence, the Professor motioned to me to bring the others in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159144,\n            \"without taking his eyes from Mina\\u2019s face, Dr. Van Helsing motioned me to pull up the blind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159283,\n            \"\\u201d I could detect the strain in the Professor\\u2019s patient voice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161540,\n            \"The captain come, when told that he will be pay well;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161639,\n            \"but the captain like it not and swear at him in many tongues, and tell him that if he like he can come and see where it shall be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161691,\n            \"Whereupon the captain tell him that he had better be quick-with blood-for that his ship will leave the place-of blood-before the turn of the tide-with blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161758,\n            \"The captain swear again, polyglot, and the thin man make him bow, and thank him, and say that he will so far intrude on his kindness as to come aboard before the sailing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161796,\n            \"Final the captain, more red than ever, and in more tongues tell him that he doesn\\u2019t want no Frenchmen-with bloom upon them and also with blood-in his ship-with blood on her also.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161984,\n            \"He was in no friendly mood, when just at full tide, the thin man came up the gang-plank again and asked to see where his box had been stowed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162018,\n            \"Then the captain replied that he wished that he and his box-old and with much bloom and blood-were in hell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162111,\n            \"My friends of the thirst and the language that was of bloom and blood laughed, as they told how the captain\\u2019s swears exceeded even his usual polyglot, and was more than ever full of picturesque, when on questioning other mariners who were on movement up and down on the river that hour, he found that few of them had seen any of fog at all, except where it lay round the wharf.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162477,\n            \"\\u201d When Dr. Van Helsing had done speaking, I asked him if he were certain that the Count had remained on board the ship.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162504,\n            \"He replied: \\u201cWe have the best proof of that: your own evidence, when in the hypnotic trance this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162528,\n            \"\\u201d I asked him again if it were really necessary that they should pursue the Count, for oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164270,\n            \"I have mentioned this to Van Helsing, and he and I are to talk it over when we are alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164435,\n            \"Van Helsing is coming to my study a little before the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164448,\n            \"I shall try to open the subject with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164475,\n            \"I could see that he had something on his mind which he wanted to say, but felt some hesitancy about broaching the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164500,\n            \"After beating about the bush a little, he said suddenly:-\\u201cFriend John, there is something that you and I must talk of alone, just at the first at any rate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164551,\n            \"then he stopped, so I waited;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164942,\n            \"I knew that it would be some sort of comfort to him if I told him that I also had come to the same conclusion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164981,\n            \"I told him, and the effect was as I expected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165023,\n            \"I really believe his purpose is to be able to pray alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165038,\n            \"- At the very outset of our meeting a great personal relief was experienced by both Van Helsing and myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165101,\n            \"The Professor and I looked at each other for an instant, and somehow we both seemed relieved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165654,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that now was the time for Van Helsing to warn him not to disclose our plans to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165682,\n            \"I looked at him significantly and coughed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166073,\n            \"You can ask Dr. Van Helsing if I am not right;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166086,\n            \"if he disagrees you may do as you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166381,\n            \"Mina woke me early, about the same time as yesterday, and asked me to bring Dr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166421,\n            \"He had evidently expected some such call, for I found him dressed in his room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166513,\n            \"\\u201d Dr. Van Helsing was as startled as I was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166539,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou must take me with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166548,\n            \"I am safer with you, and you shall be safer, too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166864,\n            \"\\u201d When he had spoken, Mina\\u2019s long spell of silence made me look at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166914,\n            \"Van Helsing motioned to me to come with him quietly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167693,\n            \"- Jonathan Harker has asked me to note this, as he says he is hardly equal to the task, and he wants an exact record kept.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168298,\n            \"Were death, or the fear of death, the only thing that stood in the way I would not shrink to die here, now, amidst the friends who love me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168975,\n            \"You are nearest and dearest and all the world to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169104,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing, I have not forgotten your mercy in poor Lucy\\u2019s case to him who loved \\\"-she stopped with a flying blush, and changed her phrase-\\\" to him who had best right to give her peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169151,\n            \"If that time shall come again, I look to you to make it a happy memory of my husband\\u2019s life that it was his loving hand which set me free from the awful thrall upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170745,\n            \"Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171020,\n            \"but Van Helsing says I must.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171157,\n            \"The lethargy grows upon her, and though she seems strong and well, and is getting back some of her colour, Van Helsing and I are not satisfied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171233,\n            \"Van Helsing examines, he tells me, her teeth very carefully, whilst she is in the hypnotic condition, for he says that so long as they do not begin to sharpen there is no active danger of a change in her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171483,\n            \"his hands are cold as ice, and an hour ago I found him whetting the edge of the great Ghoorka knife which he now always carries with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171545,\n            \"Van Helsing and I were a little alarmed about Mrs. Harker to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171930,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing is terribly anxious, and told me just now that he fears the Count is escaping us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171979,\n            \"\\u201d I was about to ask him more, but Harker just then came in, and he held up a warning hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172922,\n            \"but Van Helsing and I, turning to each other, met each a grave and troubled glance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172995,\n            \"when the door was shut upon her he said to me:-\\u201cWe mean the same!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173044,\n            \"Do you know why I asked her to get the manuscript?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173100,\n            \"And oh, my friend, I am taking a great-a terrible-risk;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174719,\n            \"but you will forgive me if I seem egotistical.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175621,\n            \"Van Helsing and I looked at each other with understanding.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176925,\n            \"- Mr. Morris took me to the hotel where our rooms had been ordered by telegraph, he being the one who could best be spared, since he does not speak any foreign language.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177083,\n            \"- At nine o\\u2019clock Dr. Van Helsing, Dr. Seward, and I called on Messrs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178812,\n            \"I have asked Dr. Van Helsing, and he has got me all the papers that I have not yet seen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178859,\n            \"I shall try to follow the Professor\\u2019s example, and think without prejudice on the facts before me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180190,\n            \"The others kept shaking me by both hands, and Dr. Van Helsing said:-\\u201cOur dear Madam Mina is once more our teacher.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181628,\n            \"I felt so thankful that Lord Godalming is rich, and that both he and Mr. Morris, who also has plenty of money, are willing to spend it so freely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181765,\n            \"Professor Van Helsing and I are to leave by the 11: 40 train to-night for Veresti, where we are to get a carriage to drive to the Borgo Pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181903,\n            \"Dear Dr. Van Helsing comforts me by telling me that I am fully armed as there may be wolves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182017,\n            \"- I am writing this in the light from the furnace door of the steam launch: Lord Godalming is firing up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182190,\n            \"Lord Godalming tells me to sleep for a while, as it is enough for the present for one to be on watch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182851,\n            \"God bless him for all his goodness to poor dear Mina and me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182876,\n            \"That good fellow would not wake me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182884,\n            \"He says it would have been a sin to, for I slept peacefully and was forgetting my trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182904,\n            \"It seems brutally selfish to me to have slept so long, and let him watch all night;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182937,\n            \"and, as I sit here and watch him sleeping, I can do all that is necessary both as to minding the engine, steering, and keeping watch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182982,\n            \"I wonder where Mina is now, and Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183071,\n            \"I wonder how Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris are getting on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183487,\n            \"The Professor tells me that this morning at dawn he could hardly hypnotise me at all, and that all I could say was: \\u201cdark and quiet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183703,\n            \"The Professor encourages her, and whispers to me that it may be a week before we can get any good food again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183826,\n            \"He alone knows what may be, and I pray Him, with all the strength of my sad and humble soul, that He will watch over my beloved husband;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184187,\n            \"all day he would not take any rest, though he made me sleep for a long spell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184206,\n            \"At sunset time he hypnotised me, and he says that I answered as usual \\u201cdarkness, lapping water and creaking wood \\\";\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184444,\n            \"At dawn Van Helsing hypnotised me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184451,\n            \"he says I answered \\u201cdarkness, creaking wood and roaring water,\\u201dso the river is changing as they ascend.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 7]\": [\n        [\n            97072,\n            \"Can you tell me how the Indian fakir can make himself to die and have been buried, and his grave sealed and corn sowed on it, and the corn reaped and be cut and sown and reaped and cut again, and then men come and take away the unbroken seal and that there lie the Indian fakir, not dead, but that rise up and walk amongst them as before?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113800,\n            \"He thinks that in the meantime I should see Renfield, as hitherto he has been a sort of index to the coming and going of the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119539,\n            \"I shall then make known to you something of the history of this man, which has been ascertained for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143728,\n            \"Van Helsing whispered to me:-\\u201cJonathan is in a stupor such as we know the Vampire can produce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150411,\n            \"\\u201cDo you forget,\\u201dhe said, with actually a smile, \\u201cthat last night he banqueted heavily, and will sleep late?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154609,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI care for nothing now,\\u201dhe answered hotly, \\u201cexcept to wipe out this brute from the face of creation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155093,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHe will be here before long now,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing, who had been consulting his pocket-book.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155429,\n            \"Van Helsing, Harker, and I were just behind the door, so that when it was opened the Professor could guard it whilst we two stepped between the incomer and the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157662,\n            \"Before they retired the Professor fixed up the room against any coming of the Vampire, and assured Mrs. Harker that she might rest in peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162477,\n            \"\\u201d When Dr. Van Helsing had done speaking, I asked him if he were certain that the Count had remained on board the ship.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162528,\n            \"\\u201d I asked him again if it were really necessary that they should pursue the Count, for oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162722,\n            \"I have told them how the measure of leaving his own barren land-barren of peoples-and coming to a new land where life of man teems till they are like the multitude of standing corn, was the work of centuries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164311,\n            \"The Count had his own purposes when he gave her what Van Helsing called \\u201cthe Vampire\\u2019s baptism of blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164641,\n            \"I can see the characteristics of the vampire coming in her face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165372,\n            \"\\u201d Here Quincey Morris added:-\\u201cI understand that the Count comes from a wolf country, and it may be that he shall get there before us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170720,\n            \"If the Count is there, Van Helsing and Seward will cut off his head at once and drive a stake through his heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171930,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing is terribly anxious, and told me just now that he fears the Count is escaping us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175122,\n            \"At such times you go by my volition and not by his;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177483,\n            \"\\u201d This mixture of simplicity and cunning, of superstition and commercial reasoning, aroused Van Helsing, who said:-\\u201cMine friend, that Devil is more clever than he is thought by some;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180350,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall get a steam launch and follow him,\\u201dsaid Lord Godalming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181060,\n            \"\\u201d Here Jonathan interrupted him hotly:-\\u201cDo you mean to say, Professor Van Helsing, that you would bring Mina, in her sad case and tainted as she is with that devil\\u2019s illness, right into the jaws of his death-trap?\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 8]\": [\n        [\n            57004,\n            \"He came on with me to Hillingham, and found that, by Lucy\\u2019s discretion, her mother was lunching out, so that we were alone with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57047,\n            \"He is to report to me, and I shall advise you, for of course I was not present all the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57071,\n            \"He is, I fear, much concerned, but says he must think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57086,\n            \"When I told him of our friendship and how you trust to me in the matter, he said: \\u2018 You must tell him all you think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57115,\n            \"Tell him what I think, if you can guess it, if you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57151,\n            \"\\u2019 I asked what he meant by that, for he was very serious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57192,\n            \"He would not give me any further clue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57201,\n            \"You must not be angry with me, Art, because his very reticence means that all his brains are working for her good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57239,\n            \"So I told him I would simply write an account of our visit, just as if I were doing a descriptive special article for The Daily Telegraph.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57298,\n            \"I am to get his report to-morrow if he can possibly make it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57408,\n            \"I believe Van Helsing saw it, too, for I saw the quick look under his bushy brows that I knew of old.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57433,\n            \"Then he began to chat of all things except ourselves and diseases and with such an infinite geniality that I could see poor Lucy\\u2019s pretense of animation merge into reality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57552,\n            \"\\u201d\\u2019And he snapped his fingers at me and went on: \\u2018 But you and I shall show them how wrong they are.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57578,\n            \"How can he\\u2019- and he pointed at me with the same look and gesture as that with which once he pointed me out to his class, on, or rather after, a particular occasion which he never fails to remind me of-\\u2018 know anything of a young ladies?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57751,\n            \"\\u2019 I took the hint, and strolled about, and presently the professor came to the window and called me in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57826,\n            \"I have asked her to send me her maid, that I may ask just one or two question, that so I may not chance to miss nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57950,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cAs I tell you, he would not say a word more, even when we were alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsing, the great specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly with myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59611,\n            \"And, my good friend John, let me caution you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59728,\n            \"\\u201d He touched me on the heart and on the forehead, and then touched himself the same way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59789,\n            \"\\u201d He stopped and looked at me, and said:-\\u201cMy friend John, when the corn is grown, even before it has ripened-while the milk of its mother-earth is in him, and the sunshine has not yet begun to paint him with his gold, the husbandman he pull the ear and rub him between his rough hands, and blow away the green chaff, and say to you: \\u2018 Look!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59889,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cI did not see the application, and told him so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59903,\n            \"For reply he reached over and took my ear in his hand and pulled it playfully, as he used long ago to do at lectures, and said: \\u201cThe good husbandman tell you so then because he knows, but not till then.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60041,\n            \"\\u201d He broke off, for he evidently saw that I understood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60528,\n            \"Van Helsing and I were shown up to Lucy\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60646,\n            \"Then Van Helsing beckoned to me, and we went gently out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60684,\n            \"Then he pulled me quickly in with him and closed the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60747,\n            \"Is it you or me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60753,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am younger and stronger, Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60787,\n            \"\\u201d I went downstairs with him, and as we were going there was a knock at the hall-door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61088,\n            \"\\u201d The Professor has a strongly humorous side, and I could from old knowledge detect a trace of its origin in his answer:-\\u201cMy young sir, I do not ask so much as that-not the last!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61728,\n            \"Van Helsing turning to me, said: \\u201cHe is so young and strong and of blood so pure that we need not defibrinate it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61938,\n            \"I dressed the wound and took his arm to bring him away, when Van Helsing spoke without turning round-the man seems to have eyes in the back of his head:-\\u201cThe brave lover, I think, deserve another kiss, which he shall have presently.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62059,\n            \"Arthur did not notice it, but I could hear the deep hiss of indrawn breath which is one of Van Helsing\\u2019s ways of betraying emotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62088,\n            \"He said nothing at the moment, but turned to me, saying: \\u201cNow take down our brave young lover, give him of the port wine, and let him lie down a while.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62301,\n            \"I asked the Professor in a whisper:-\\u201cWhat do you make of that mark on her throat?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62777,\n            \"When I told Mrs. Westenra that Dr. Van Helsing had directed that I should sit up with her she almost pooh-poohed the idea, pointing out her daughter\\u2019s renewed strength and excellent spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63272,\n            \"I sent a short wire to Van Helsing and to Arthur, telling them of the excellent result of the operation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63342,\n            \"A telegram came from Van Helsing at Amsterdam whilst I was at dinner, suggesting that I should be at Hillingham to-night, as it might be well to be at hand, and stating that he was leaving by the night mail and would join me early in the morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63920,\n            \"- I was conscious of the Professor\\u2019s hand on my head, and started awake all in a second.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64005,\n            \"The blind was down, and I went over to raise it gently, whilst Van Helsing stepped, with his soft, cat-like tread, over to the bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64038,\n            \"As I raised the blind, and the morning sunlight flooded the room, I heard the Professor\\u2019s low hiss of inspiration, and knowing its rarity, a deadly fear shot through my heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64076,\n            \"As I passed over he moved back, and his exclamation of horror, \\u201cGott in Himmel!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64575,\n            \"The Professor watched me critically.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64652,\n            \"\\u201d When we stopped the operation, he attended to Lucy, whilst I applied digital pressure to my own incision.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64674,\n            \"I laid down, whilst I waited his leisure to attend to me, for I felt faint and a little sick.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64697,\n            \"By-and-by he bound up my wound, and sent me downstairs to get a glass of wine for myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64721,\n            \"As I was leaving the room, he came after me, and half whispered:-\\u201cMind, nothing must be said of this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64784,\n            \"\\u201d When I came back he looked at me carefully, and then said:-\\u201cYou are not much the worse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64834,\n            \"\\u201d I followed out his orders, for I knew how right and wise they were.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65005,\n            \"When Van Helsing had seen her, he went out for a walk, leaving me in charge, with strict injunctions that I was not to leave her for a moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65038,\n            \"I could hear his voice in the hall, asking the way to the nearest telegraph office.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65229,\n            \"Van Helsing returned in a couple of hours, and presently said to me: \\u201cNow you go home, and eat much and drink enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65363,\n            \"and when I said it was Dr. Van Helsing\\u2019s wish that either he or I should sit up, they asked me quite piteously to intercede with the \\u201cforeign gentleman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65505,\n            \"Shortly after I had arrived, a big parcel from abroad came for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65808,\n            \"\\u201d To my surprise, Van Helsing rose up and said with all his sternness, his iron jaw set and his bushy eyebrows meeting:-\\u201cNo trifling with me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66069,\n            \"The Professor\\u2019s actions were certainly odd and not to be found in any pharmacop\\u0153ia that I ever heard of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66172,\n            \"It all seemed grotesque to me, and presently I said:-\\u201cWell, Professor, I know you always have a reason for what you do, but this certainly puzzles me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66367,\n            \"\\u201d As we left the house in my fly, which was waiting, Van Helsing said:-\\u201cTo-night I can sleep in peace, and sleep I want-two nights of travel, much reading in the day between, and much anxiety on the day to follow, and a night to sit up, without to wink.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66473,\n            \"\\u201d He seemed so confident that I, remembering my own confidence two nights before and with the baneful result, felt awe and vague terror.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66500,\n            \"It must have been my weakness that made me hesitate to tell it to my friend, but I felt it all the more, like unshed tears.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66549,\n            \"I quite love that dear Dr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66559,\n            \"I wonder why he was so anxious about these flowers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66570,\n            \"He positively frightened me, he was so fierce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66580,\n            \"And yet he must have been right, for I feel comfort from them already.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66820,\n            \"Van Helsing and I arrived at Hillingham at eight o\\u2019clock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67148,\n            \"You will be pleased with her, I am sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67173,\n            \"As she had spoken, I watched the Professor\\u2019s face, and saw it turn ashen grey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67242,\n            \"But the instant she had disappeared he pulled me, suddenly and forcibly, into the dining-room and closed the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67266,\n            \"Then, for the first time in my life, I saw Van Helsing break down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67556,\n            \"Once again I drew up the blind, whilst Van Helsing went towards the bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67657,\n            \"I had long ago recognised the necessity, and begun to take off my coat, but he stopped me with a warning hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67749,\n            \"This time I watched whilst Van Helsing recruited himself and rested.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67810,\n            \"Then he took over the care of the case himself, saying that he would watch this night and the next and would send me word when to come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68013,\n            \"Since, however, Dr. Van Helsing has been with me, all this bad dreaming seems to have passed away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68191,\n            \"I shall not even feel the change, for last night Dr. Van Helsing slept in his chair a lot of the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68216,\n            \"I found him asleep twice when I awoke;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68327,\n            \"Thomas Bilder lives in one of the cottages in the enclosure behind the elephant-house, and was just sitting down to his tea when I found him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68357,\n            \"Thomas and his wife are hospitable folk, elderly, and without children, and if the specimen I enjoyed of their hospitality be of the average kind, their lives must be pretty comfortable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68501,\n            \"\\u201d I queried, wishful to get him into a talkative humour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69242,\n            \"He had a\\u2019ard, cold look and red eyes, and I took a sort of mislike to him, for it seemed as if it was\\u2019 im as they was hirritated at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69279,\n            \"He\\u2019ad white kid gloves on\\u2019is\\u2019 ands, and he pointed out the animiles to me and says: \\u2018 Keeper, these wolves seem upset at something.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69312,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201c\\u2018 Maybe it\\u2019s you,\\u2019says I, for I did not like the airs as he give\\u2019isself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69338,\n            \"He didn\\u2019t git angry, as I\\u2019oped he would, but he smiled a kind of insolent smile, with a mouth full of white, sharp teeth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69387,\n            \"\\u201c\\u2018 Ow yes, they would,\\u2019says I, a-imitatin\\u2019of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69431,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cWell, it was a odd thing, but when the animiles see us a-talkin\\u2019they lay down, and when I went over to Bersicker he let me stroke his ears same as ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69741,\n            \"Just before twelve o\\u2019clock I just took a look round afore turnin\\u2019in, an \\u2019, bust me, but when I kem opposite to old Bersicker\\u2019s cage I see the rails broken and twisted about and the cage empty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69962,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, sir,\\u201dhe said, with a suspicious sort of modesty, \\u201cI think I can;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70107,\n            \"I couldn\\u2019t cope in badinage with the worthy Thomas, but I thought I knew a surer way to his heart, so I said:-\\u201cNow, Mr. Bilder, we\\u2019ll consider that first half-sovereign worked off, and this brother of his is waiting to be claimed when you\\u2019ve told me what you think will happen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70177,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cRight y\\u2019are, sir,\\u201dhe said briskly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70191,\n            \"\\u201cYe\\u2019ll excoose me, I know, for a-chaffin\\u2019of ye, but the old woman here winked at me, which was as much as telling me to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70597,\n            \"\\u201d I was handing him the half-sovereign, when something came bobbing up against the window, and Mr. Bilder\\u2019s face doubled its natural length with surprise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70706,\n            \"After all, however, there is nothing like custom, for neither Bilder nor his wife thought any more of the wolf than I should of a dog.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71069,\n            \"I was thunderstruck, for such a thing as a patient getting of his own accord into the Superintendent\\u2019s study is almost unknown.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71382,\n            \"Happily Van Helsing has not summoned me, so I need not forego my sleep;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71583,\n            \"I shall take this cylinder with me, and then I can complete my entry on Lucy\\u2019s phonograph.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71680,\n            \"I went to bed as usual, taking care that the flowers were placed as Dr. Van Helsing directed, and soon fell asleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71742,\n            \"I was not afraid, but I did wish that Dr. Seward was in the next room-as Dr. Van Helsing said he would be-so that I might have called him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72219,\n            \"Amongst other things, she clutched the wreath of flowers that Dr. Van Helsing insisted on my wearing round my neck, and tore it away from me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72670,\n            \"When they were there I remembered what Dr. Van Helsing had told me, but I didn\\u2019t like to remove them, and, besides, I would have some of the servants to sit up with me now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73272,\n            \"They stopped at the gate, and a few seconds later I met Van Helsing running up the avenue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73292,\n            \"When he saw me, he gasped out:-\\u201cThen it was you, and just arrived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73321,\n            \"Did you not get my telegram?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73328,\n            \"\\u201d I answered as quickly and coherently as I could that I had only got his telegram early in the morning, and had not lost a minute in coming here, and that I could not make any one in the house hear me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73458,\n            \"The Professor took a small surgical saw from his case, and handing it to me, pointed to the iron bars which guarded the window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73520,\n            \"I helped the Professor in, and followed him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73617,\n            \"Van Helsing and I looked at each other, and as we moved away he said: \\u201cWe can attend to them later.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73835,\n            \"then he gave a quick turn of his head, as of one who listens, and leaping to his feet, he cried out to me:-\\u201cIt is not yet too late!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73936,\n            \"I did not stay to make sure, but returned to Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73976,\n            \"He said to me:-\\u201cI can do this, all that can be at the present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74358,\n            \"He answered me in a way that I did not understand, but with the sternest look that his face could wear:-\\u201cIf that were all, I would stop here where we are now, and let her fade away into peace, for I see no light in life over her horizon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74473,\n            \"Van Helsing\\u2019s face almost beamed, and as we lifted her from the bath and rolled her in a hot sheet to dry her he said to me:-\\u201cThe first gain is ours!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74548,\n            \"I noticed that Van Helsing tied a soft silk handkerchief round her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74585,\n            \"Van Helsing called in one of the women, and told her to stay with her and not to take her eyes off her till we returned, and then beckoned me out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74734,\n            \"He was evidently torturing his mind about something, so I waited for an instant, and he spoke:-\\u201cWhat are we to do now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74885,\n            \"Van Helsing started angrily at the first sound, but his face softened and a glad look came into his eyes as I cried out: \\u201cQuincey Morris!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75005,\n            \"You know you have only to tell me what to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75206,\n            \"The Professor watched whilst I went downstairs with Quincey Morris, and sent one of the maids to pay off one of the cabmen who were waiting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75275,\n            \"When I came softly in, I found Van Helsing with a sheet or two of note-paper in his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75340,\n            \"He handed me the paper saying only: \\u201cIt dropped from Lucy\\u2019s breast when we carried her to the bath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75364,\n            \"\\u201d When I had read it, I stood looking at the Professor, and after a pause asked him: \\u201cIn God\\u2019s name, what does it all mean?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75476,\n            \"And now what is it that you came to me to say?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75566,\n            \"I know, and you know, and the other doctor who attended her knows, that Mrs. Westenra had disease of the heart, and we can certify that she died of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75747,\n            \"and that Van Helsing and I were with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75888,\n            \"From his putting his finger to his lips, I gathered that he expected her to wake before long and was afraid of forestalling nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76139,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat\\u2019s so,\\u201dI said, and he went on:-\\u201cI take it that both you and Van Helsing had done already what I did to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76302,\n            \"Jack, if you may tell me without betraying confidence, Arthur was the first, is not that so?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76397,\n            \"I paused before answering, for I felt that I must not betray anything which the Professor wished kept secret;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76561,\n            \"Van Helsing is simply frantic about it, and I am at my wits\\u2019 end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76662,\n            \"\\u201d When she woke late in the afternoon, Lucy\\u2019s first movement was to feel in her breast, and, to my surprise, produced the paper which Van Helsing had given me to read.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76721,\n            \"Her eye then lit on Van Helsing and on me too, and gladdened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77061,\n            \"At times she slept, and both Van Helsing and I noticed the difference in her, between sleeping and waking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77616,\n            \"\\u2019 I cried, Lucy dear, as Jonathan and the old man clasped hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79247,\n            \"\\u201cBelieve me, dear Sir, \\u201cYours faithfully, \\u201cPatrick Hennessey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79809,\n            \"I duly relieved Van Helsing in his watch over Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79835,\n            \"It was only when I told him that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80055,\n            \"I could see that the Professor had carried out in this room, as in the other, his purpose of using the garlic;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80319,\n            \"Presently she woke, and I gave her food, as Van Helsing had prescribed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80458,\n            \"At six o\\u2019clock Van Helsing came to relieve me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80486,\n            \"When he saw Lucy\\u2019s face I could hear the sissing indraw of his breath, and he said to me in a sharp whisper: \\u201cDraw up the blind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80557,\n            \"As he did so he started back, and I could hear his ejaculation, \\u201cMein Gott!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80631,\n            \"Then he turned to me and said calmly:-\\u201cShe is dying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80739,\n            \"I assured him that Lucy was still asleep, but told him as gently as I could that both Van Helsing and I feared that the end was near.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80809,\n            \"I took him by the hand and raised him up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80820,\n            \"\\u201cCome,\\u201dI said, \\u201cmy dear old fellow, summon all your fortitude: it will be best and easiest for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80847,\n            \"\\u201d When we came into Lucy\\u2019s room I could see that Van Helsing had, with his usual forethought, been putting matters straight and making everything look as pleasing as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81156,\n            \"but at that instant Van Helsing, who, like me, had been startled by her voice, swooped upon him, and catching him by the neck with both hands, dragged him back with a fury of strength which I never thought he could have possessed, and actually hurled him almost across the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81288,\n            \"I kept my eyes fixed on Lucy, as did Van Helsing, and we saw a spasm as of rage flit like a shadow over her face;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81589,\n            \"I went back to the room, and found Van Helsing looking at poor Lucy, and his face was sterner than ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81926,\n            \"\\u201d I noticed that Van Helsing never kept far away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81989,\n            \"Under the circumstances, Van Helsing and I took it upon ourselves to examine papers, etc.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82018,\n            \"I asked him why, for I feared that he, being a foreigner, might not be quite aware of English legal requirements, and so might in ignorance make some unnecessary trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82053,\n            \"He answered me:-\\u201cI know;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82065,\n            \"You forget that I am a lawyer as well as a doctor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82275,\n            \"I had hardly sealed the letter, when, to my surprise, Van Helsing walked into the room, saying:-\\u201cCan I help you, friend John?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82307,\n            \"I am free, and if I may, my service is to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82332,\n            \"\\u201d I asked, to which he replied:-\\u201cI did not look for any specific thing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82421,\n            \"\\u201d When we had finished the work in hand, he said to me:-\\u201cAnd now, friend John, I think we may to bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82451,\n            \"We want sleep, both you and I, and rest to recuperate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82829,\n            \"I want to operate, but not as you think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82840,\n            \"Let me tell you now, but not a word to another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82876,\n            \"You, whom I have seen with no tremble of hand or heart, do operations of life and death that make the rest shudder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82902,\n            \"Oh, but I must not forget, my dear friend John, that you loved her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82920,\n            \"and I have not forgotten it, for it is I that shall operate, and you must only help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82984,\n            \"Then, when she is coffined ready for the next day, you and I shall come when all sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83098,\n            \"\\u201d For answer he put his hand on my shoulder, and said, with infinite tenderness:-\\u201cFriend John, I pity your poor bleeding heart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83128,\n            \"and I love you the more because it does so bleed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83184,\n            \"John, my child, you have been my friend now many years, and yet did you ever know me to do any without good cause?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83229,\n            \"Was it not for these causes that you send for me when the great trouble came?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83248,\n            \"Were you not amazed, nay horrified, when I would not let Arthur kiss his love-though she was dying-and snatched him away by all my strength?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83282,\n            \"And yet you saw how she thanked me, with her so beautiful dying eyes, her voice, too, so weak, and she kiss my rough old hand and bless me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83319,\n            \"And did you not hear me swear promise to her, that so she closed her eyes grateful?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83355,\n            \"You have for many years trust me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83363,\n            \"you have believe me weeks past, when there be things so strange that you might have well doubt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83383,\n            \"Believe me yet a little, friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83392,\n            \"If you trust me not, then I must tell what I think;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83413,\n            \"And if I work-as work I shall, no matter trust or no trust-without my friend trust in me, I work with heavy heart and feel, oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83501,\n            \"Will you not have faith in me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83509,\n            \"\\u201d I took his hand, and promised him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83519,\n            \"I held my door open as he went away, and watched him go into his room and close the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84562,\n            \"He had, I knew, been very genuinely and devotedly attached to his father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84596,\n            \"With me he was warm as ever, and to Van Helsing he was sweetly courteous;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85134,\n            \"I left him in the drawing-room, and told Van Helsing that he had said good-bye;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87342,\n            \"and now a telegram from Van Helsing, whoever he may be:-\\u201cYou will be grieved to hear that Mrs. Westenra died five days ago, and that Lucy died the day before yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87583,\n            \"He is to stop with me then, if he can;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87615,\n            \"I fear that the strain of the past week has broken down even his iron strength.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87632,\n            \"All the time of the burial he was, I could see, putting some terrible restraint on himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87690,\n            \"I could see Van Helsing\\u2019s face grow white and purple by turns.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87751,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87788,\n            \"He has denied to me since that it was hysterics, and insisted that it was only his sense of humour asserting itself under very terrible conditions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87816,\n            \"He laughed till he cried, and I had to draw down the blinds lest any one should see us and misjudge;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87861,\n            \"I tried to be stern with him, as one is to a woman under the circumstances;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87899,\n            \"Then when his face grew grave and stern again I asked him why his mirth, and why at such a time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87941,\n            \"He said:-\\u201cAh, you don\\u2019t comprehend, friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88219,\n            \"And yet when he say things that touch my husband-heart to the quick, and make my father-heart yearn to him as to no other man-not even to you, friend John, for we are more level in experiences than father and son-yet even at such moment King Laugh he come to me and shout and bellow in my ear, \\u2018 Here I am!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88298,\n            \"\\u2019 till the blood come dance back and bring some of the sunshine that he carry with him to my cheek.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88398,\n            \"And believe me, friend John, that he is good to come, and kind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88496,\n            \"\\u201d I did not like to wound him by pretending not to see his idea;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88512,\n            \"but, as I did not yet understand the cause of his laughter, I asked him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88530,\n            \"As he answered me his face grew stern, and he said in quite a different tone:-\\u201cOh, it was the grim irony of it all-this so lovely lady garlanded with flowers, that looked so fair as life, till one by one we wondered if she were truly dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88915,\n            \"He laid his hand on my arm, and said:-\\u201cFriend John, forgive me if I pain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88937,\n            \"I showed not my feeling to others when it would wound, but only to you, my old friend, whom I can trust.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88963,\n            \"If you could have looked into my very heart then when I want to laugh;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88990,\n            \"if you could do so now, when King Laugh have pack up his crown, and all that is to him-for he go far, far away from me, and for a long, long time-maybe you would perhaps pity me the most of all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89042,\n            \"\\u201d I was touched by the tenderness of his tone, and asked why.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90646,\n            \"- I cannot help feeling terribly excited as the time draws near for the visit of Dr. Van Helsing, for somehow I expect that it will throw some light upon Jonathan\\u2019s sad experience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90684,\n            \"and as he attended poor dear Lucy in her last illness, he can tell me all about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91464,\n            \"\\u201d I rose and bowed, and he came towards me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91670,\n            \"He said to me:-\\u201cMrs. Harker, is it not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91736,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cSir,\\u201dI said, \\u201cyou could have no better claim on me than that you were a friend and helper of Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91773,\n            \"He took it and said tenderly:-\\u201cOh, Madam Mina, I knew that the friend of that poor lily girl must be good, but I had yet to learn--\\u201dHe finished his speech with a courtly bow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91819,\n            \"I asked him what it was that he wanted to see me about, so he at once began:-\\u201cI have read your letters to Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91869,\n            \"I know that you were with her at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91934,\n            \"In great perplexity then I come to you, and ask you out of your so much kindness to tell me all of it that you can remember.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91963,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI can tell you, I think, Dr. Van Helsing, all about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92006,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, doctor, but I wrote it all down at the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92022,\n            \"I can show it to you if you like.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92032,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cOh, Madam Mina, I will be grateful;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92044,\n            \"you will do me much favour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92051,\n            \"\\u201d I could not resist the temptation of mystifying him a bit-I suppose it is some of the taste of the original apple that remains still in our mouths-so I handed him the shorthand diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92109,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you wish,\\u201dI answered as demurely as I could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92181,\n            \"And will you not so much honour me and so help me as to read it for me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92224,\n            \"so I took the typewritten copy from my workbasket and handed it to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92254,\n            \"but I had been thinking that it was of dear Lucy that you wished to ask, and so that you might not have time to wait-not on my account, but because I know your time must be precious-I have written it out on the typewriter for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92317,\n            \"\\u201cYou are so good,\\u201dhe said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92335,\n            \"I may want to ask you some things when I have read.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 9]\": [\n        [\n            129361,\n            \"He said to Madam Mina, as I see in your diary of yesterday, that he had once had such a belief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129751,\n            \"I wish you would take yourself and your idiotic brain theories somewhere else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129843,\n            \"Friend John, it does rejoice me unspeakable that she is no more to be pained, no more to be worried with our terrible things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135303,\n            \"If you will let me have his lordship\\u2019s address I will consult the House on the subject, and will, in any case, communicate with his lordship by to-night\\u2019s post.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135732,\n            \"when I had finished Van Helsing said:-\\u201cThis has been a great day\\u2019s work, friend Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138695,\n            \"We beg, with regard to the desire of your Lordship, expressed by Mr. Harker on your behalf, to supply the following information concerning the sale and purchase of No.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173450,\n            \"let me speak, and you shall learn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174687,\n            \"John and I know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 11]\": [\n        [\n            113800,\n            \"He thinks that in the meantime I should see Renfield, as hitherto he has been a sort of index to the coming and going of the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123455,\n            \"and, besides, there was a certain dignity in the man\\u2019s manner, so much of the habit of equality, that I at once made the introduction: \\u201cLord Godalming;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123781,\n            \"And I am sure that you, Dr. Seward, humanitarian and medico-jurist as well as scientist, will deem it a moral duty to deal with me as one to be considered as under exceptional circumstances.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124378,\n            \"Van Helsing was gazing at him with a look of utmost intensity, his bushy eyebrows almost meeting with the fixed concentration of his look.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124404,\n            \"He said to Renfield in a tone which did not surprise me at the time, but only when I thought of it afterwards-for it was as of one addressing an equal:-\\u201cCan you not tell frankly your real reason for wishing to be free to-night?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124458,\n            \"I will undertake that if you will satisfy even me-a stranger, without prejudice, and with the habit of keeping an open mind-Dr. Seward will give you, at his own risk and on his own responsibility, the privilege you seek.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136245,\n            \"This morning, when I went to see him after his repulse of Van Helsing, his manner was that of a man commanding destiny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137119,\n            \"I would have taken him with me to see the patient, only I thought that after his last repulse he might not care to go again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139968,\n            \"for, almost before he looked at the patient, he whispered to me:-\\u201cSend the attendant away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140865,\n            \"He moved convulsively, and as he did so, said:-\\u201cI\\u2019ll be quiet, Doctor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140961,\n            \"Then Van Helsing said in a quiet grave tone:-\\u201cTell us your dream, Mr. Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140982,\n            \"\\u201d As he heard the voice his face brightened, through its mutilation, and he said:-\\u201cThat is Dr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141473,\n            \"Renfield proceeded:-\\u201cHe came up to the window in the mist, as I had seen him often before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141596,\n            \"\\u201d He was interrupted by a word from the Professor:-\\u201cHow?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147094,\n            \"When Dr. Van Helsing and Dr. Seward had come back from seeing poor Renfield, we went gravely into what was to be done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147121,\n            \"First, Dr. Seward told us that when he and Dr. Van Helsing had gone down to the room below they had found Renfield lying on the floor, all in a heap.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 12]\": [\n        [\n            74885,\n            \"Van Helsing started angrily at the first sound, but his face softened and a glad look came into his eyes as I cried out: \\u201cQuincey Morris!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75017,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing strode forward, and took his hand, looking him straight in the eyes as he said:-\\u201cA brave man\\u2019s blood is the best thing on this earth when a woman is in trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75206,\n            \"The Professor watched whilst I went downstairs with Quincey Morris, and sent one of the maids to pay off one of the cabmen who were waiting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79247,\n            \"\\u201cBelieve me, dear Sir, \\u201cYours faithfully, \\u201cPatrick Hennessey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87751,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95699,\n            \"Quincey wrote me a line too, and from him I hear that Arthur is beginning to recover something of his old buoyancy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102999,\n            \"Last night, at a little before ten o\\u2019clock, Arthur and Quincey came into Van Helsing\\u2019s room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103385,\n            \"\\u201cI\\u2019ll answer for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103394,\n            \"I don\\u2019t quite see his drift, but I swear he\\u2019s honest;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103420,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI thank you, sir,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing proudly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103456,\n            \"\\u201d He held out a hand, which Quincey took.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105175,\n            \"The silence was broken by Quincey Morris:-\\u201cProfessor, I answered for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105192,\n            \"Your word is all I want.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105199,\n            \"I wouldn\\u2019t ask such a thing ordinarily-I wouldn\\u2019t so dishonour you as to imply a doubt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105240,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI swear to you by all that I hold sacred that I have not removed nor touched her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105894,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey drew near also, as they too were curious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107641,\n            \"- A little before twelve o\\u2019clock we three-Arthur, Quincey Morris, and myself-called for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109093,\n            \"Van Helsing opened his missal and began to read, and Quincey and I followed as well as we could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113174,\n            \"You tell me that Lord Godalming and Mr. Morris are coming too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119444,\n            \"Opposite us were Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, and Mr. Morris-Lord Godalming being next the Professor, and Dr. Seward in the centre.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120346,\n            \"\\u201cCount me in, Professor,\\u201dsaid Mr. Quincey Morris, laconically as usual.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122367,\n            \"As he did so we heard Mr. Morris\\u2019 s voice without:-\\u201cSorry!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122558,\n            \"\\u201d Without saying any more he took his seat, and the Professor began to resume his statement:-\\u201cWe must trace each of these boxes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135962,\n            \"By-and-by he stopped and said, turning from one to another of us:-\\u201cQuincey\\u2019s head is level.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137064,\n            \"and so are Lord Godalming and Quincey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145165,\n            \"Van Helsing turned to Morris and asked:-\\u201cAnd you, friend Quincey, have you any to tell?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154347,\n            \"By my clock it is one hour and already, if all be well, friend Arthur and Quincey are on their way to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160986,\n            \"Present: Professor Van Helsing, Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, Mr. Quincey Morris, Jonathan Harker, Mina Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161302,\n            \"and when Quincey give him something from his pocket which crackle as he roll it up, and put it in a so small bag which he have hid deep in his clothing, he still better fellow and humble servant to us.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 13]\": [\n        [\n            71409,\n            \"Telegram, Van Helsing, Antwerp, to Seward, Carfax.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71512,\n            \"The arrival of Van Helsing\\u2019s telegram filled me with dismay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71742,\n            \"I was not afraid, but I did wish that Dr. Seward was in the next room-as Dr. Van Helsing said he would be-so that I might have called him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170720,\n            \"If the Count is there, Van Helsing and Seward will cut off his head at once and drive a stake through his heart.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 14]\": [\n        [\n            147270,\n            \"Van Helsing asked if he had heard \\u201cvoices\\u201dor \\u201ca voice,\\u201dand he said he could not say;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152711,\n            \"This he finally handed to Lord Godalming, who took out his purse and gave him something.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158660,\n            \"In two or three minutes later Van Helsing was in the room in his dressing-gown, and Mr. Morris and Lord Godalming were with Dr. Seward at the door asking questions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159592,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Morris and Lord Godalming started for the door but the Professor\\u2019s calm voice called them back:-\\u201cStay, my friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160986,\n            \"Present: Professor Van Helsing, Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, Mr. Quincey Morris, Jonathan Harker, Mina Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166925,\n            \"We went to his room, and within a minute Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, and Mr. Morris were with us also.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 15]\": [\n        [\n            60890,\n            \"I am so thankful to you, sir, for coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60902,\n            \"\\u201d When first the Professor\\u2019s eye had lit upon him he had been angry at his interruption at such a time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60926,\n            \"but now, as he took in his stalwart proportions and recognised the strong young manhood which seemed to emanate from him, his eyes gleamed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60953,\n            \"Without a pause he said to him gravely as he held out his hand:-\\u201cSir, you have come in time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61088,\n            \"\\u201d The Professor has a strongly humorous side, and I could from old knowledge detect a trace of its origin in his answer:-\\u201cMy young sir, I do not ask so much as that-not the last!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61155,\n            \"Van Helsing slapped him on the shoulder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61184,\n            \"You are better than me, better than my friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61196,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur looked bewildered, and the Professor went on by explaining in a kindly way:-\\u201cYoung miss is bad, very bad.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61440,\n            \"and you must leave at my sign.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61670,\n            \"When the Professor was satisfied he called Arthur into the room, and bade him strip off his coat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61728,\n            \"Van Helsing turning to me, said: \\u201cHe is so young and strong and of blood so pure that we need not defibrinate it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61858,\n            \"But the Professor\\u2019s face was set, and he stood watch in hand and with his eyes fixed now on the patient and now on Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61938,\n            \"I dressed the wound and took his arm to bring him away, when Van Helsing spoke without turning round-the man seems to have eyes in the back of his head:-\\u201cThe brave lover, I think, deserve another kiss, which he shall have presently.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62059,\n            \"Arthur did not notice it, but I could hear the deep hiss of indrawn breath which is one of Van Helsing\\u2019s ways of betraying emotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62088,\n            \"He said nothing at the moment, but turned to me, saying: \\u201cNow take down our brave young lover, give him of the port wine, and let him lie down a while.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63272,\n            \"I sent a short wire to Van Helsing and to Arthur, telling them of the excellent result of the operation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65593,\n            \"\\u201cNay, but they are not to take in a decoction or in nauseous form, so you need not snub that so charming nose, or I shall point out to my friend Arthur what woes he may have to endure in seeing so much beauty that he so loves so much distort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65676,\n            \"I put him in your window, I make pretty wreath, and hang him round your neck, so that you sleep well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76302,\n            \"Jack, if you may tell me without betraying confidence, Arthur was the first, is not that so?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77321,\n            \"It was now nearly one o\\u2019clock, and he and Van Helsing are sitting with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79835,\n            \"It was only when I told him that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79878,\n            \"Van Helsing was very kind to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79886,\n            \"\\u201cCome, my child,\\u201dhe said;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79969,\n            \"You shall lie on one, and I on the other, and our sympathy will be comfort to each other, even though we do not speak, and even if we sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80004,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur went off with him, casting back a longing look on Lucy\\u2019s face, which lay in her pillow, almost whiter than the lawn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80470,\n            \"Arthur had then fallen into a doze, and he mercifully let him sleep on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80739,\n            \"I assured him that Lucy was still asleep, but told him as gently as I could that both Van Helsing and I feared that the end was near.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80939,\n            \"\\u201d He was stooping to kiss her, when Van Helsing motioned him back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81156,\n            \"but at that instant Van Helsing, who, like me, had been startled by her voice, swooped upon him, and catching him by the neck with both hands, dragged him back with a fury of strength which I never thought he could have possessed, and actually hurled him almost across the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81438,\n            \"Then he turned to Arthur, and said to him: \\u201cCome, my child, take her hand in yours, and kiss her on the forehead, and only once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81492,\n            \"and Van Helsing, who had been watching closely, took Arthur\\u2019s arm, and drew him away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82941,\n            \"I would like to do it to-night, but for Arthur I must not;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83248,\n            \"Were you not amazed, nay horrified, when I would not let Arthur kiss his love-though she was dying-and snatched him away by all my strength?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84562,\n            \"He had, I knew, been very genuinely and devotedly attached to his father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84596,\n            \"With me he was warm as ever, and to Van Helsing he was sweetly courteous;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85134,\n            \"I left him in the drawing-room, and told Van Helsing that he had said good-bye;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87751,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90646,\n            \"- I cannot help feeling terribly excited as the time draws near for the visit of Dr. Van Helsing, for somehow I expect that it will throw some light upon Jonathan\\u2019s sad experience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107193,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur threw himself on his knees, and hid his face in his hands, as he answered:-\\u201cDo as you will, friend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107502,\n            \"\\u201d Coming close to Arthur, he said:-\\u201cMy friend Arthur, you have had a sore trial;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107641,\n            \"- A little before twelve o\\u2019clock we three-Arthur, Quincey Morris, and myself-called for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107889,\n            \"When he again lifted the lid off Lucy\\u2019s coffin we all looked-Arthur trembling like an aspen-and saw that the body lay there in all its death-beauty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107966,\n            \"Presently he said to Van Helsing:-\\u201cIs this really Lucy\\u2019s body, or only a demon in her shape?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108267,\n            \"When all was ready, Van Helsing said:-\\u201cBefore we do anything, let me tell you this;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108796,\n            \"he stepped forward and said bravely, though his hand trembled, and his face was as pale as snow:-\\u201cMy true friend, from the bottom of my broken heart I thank you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108848,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing laid a hand on his shoulder, and said:-\\u201cBrave lad!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109606,\n            \"Van Helsing came and laid his hand on Arthur\\u2019s shoulder, and said to him:-\\u201cAnd now, Arthur my friend, dear lad, am I not forgiven?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109641,\n            \"\\u201d The reaction of the terrible strain came as he took the old man\\u2019s hand in his, and raising it to his lips, pressed it, and said:-\\u201cForgiven!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109696,\n            \"\\u201d He put his hands on the Professor\\u2019s shoulder, and laying his head on his breast, cried for a while silently, whilst we stood unmoving.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109727,\n            \"When he raised his head Van Helsing said to him:-\\u201cAnd now, my child, you may kiss her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109892,\n            \"When the Professor locked the door he gave the key to Arthur.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 16]\": [\n        [\n            56990,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear Art,-\\u201cVan Helsing has come and gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57004,\n            \"He came on with me to Hillingham, and found that, by Lucy\\u2019s discretion, her mother was lunching out, so that we were alone with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57047,\n            \"He is to report to me, and I shall advise you, for of course I was not present all the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57086,\n            \"When I told him of our friendship and how you trust to me in the matter, he said: \\u2018 You must tell him all you think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57201,\n            \"You must not be angry with me, Art, because his very reticence means that all his brains are working for her good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57369,\n            \"She was very sweet to the professor (as she always is), and tried to make him feel at ease;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57433,\n            \"Then he began to chat of all things except ourselves and diseases and with such an infinite geniality that I could see poor Lucy\\u2019s pretense of animation merge into reality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57466,\n            \"Then, without any seeming change, he brought the conversation gently round to his visit, and suavely said:-\\u201c\\u2018 My dear young miss, I have the so great pleasure because you are so much beloved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57508,\n            \"That is much, my dear, ever were there that which I do not see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57525,\n            \"They told me you were down in the spirit, and that you were of a ghastly pale.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57552,\n            \"\\u201d\\u2019And he snapped his fingers at me and went on: \\u2018 But you and I shall show them how wrong they are.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57722,\n            \"So, my dear, we will send him away to smoke the cigarette in the garden, whiles you and I have little talk all to ourselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57795,\n            \"With you I agree that there has been much blood lost;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57826,\n            \"I have asked her to send me her maid, that I may ask just one or two question, that so I may not chance to miss nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57856,\n            \"I know well what she will say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57885,\n            \"You must send to me the telegram every day;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57905,\n            \"The disease-for not to be all well is a disease-interest me, and the sweet young dear, she interest me too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57932,\n            \"She charm me, and for her, if not for you or disease, I come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57950,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cAs I tell you, he would not say a word more, even when we were alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsing, the great specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly with myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59611,\n            \"And, my good friend John, let me caution you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59758,\n            \"Later I shall unfold to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59789,\n            \"\\u201d He stopped and looked at me, and said:-\\u201cMy friend John, when the corn is grown, even before it has ripened-while the milk of its mother-earth is in him, and the sunshine has not yet begun to paint him with his gold, the husbandman he pull the ear and rub him between his rough hands, and blow away the green chaff, and say to you: \\u2018 Look!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60054,\n            \"Then he went on, and very gravely:-\\u201cYou were always a careful student, and your case-book was ever more full than the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60091,\n            \"now you are master, and I trust that good habit have not fail.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60126,\n            \"Even if you have not kept the good practise, let me tell you that this case of our dear miss is one that may be-mind, I say may be-of such interest to us and others that all the rest may not make him kick the beam, as your peoples say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60528,\n            \"Van Helsing and I were shown up to Lucy\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61553,\n            \"Then he mixed a narcotic, and coming over to the bed, said cheerily:-\\u201cNow, little miss, here is your medicine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61590,\n            \"See, I lift you so that to swallow is easy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61716,\n            \"\\u201d So neither of us looked whilst he bent over her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61858,\n            \"But the Professor\\u2019s face was set, and he stood watch in hand and with his eyes fixed now on the patient and now on Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61918,\n            \"I will look to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61991,\n            \"\\u201d And as he had now finished his operation, he adjusted the pillow to the patient\\u2019s head.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62012,\n            \"As he did so the narrow black velvet band which she seems always to wear round her throat, buckled with an old diamond buckle which her lover had given her, was dragged a little up, and showed a red mark on her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62280,\n            \"By the bedside sat Van Helsing, looking at her intently.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62301,\n            \"I asked the Professor in a whisper:-\\u201cWhat do you make of that mark on her throat?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62653,\n            \"He came back a moment later and put his head inside the door and said with warning finger held up:-\\u201cRemember, she is your charge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62777,\n            \"When I told Mrs. Westenra that Dr. Van Helsing had directed that I should sit up with her she almost pooh-poohed the idea, pointing out her daughter\\u2019s renewed strength and excellent spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64267,\n            \"He felt her heart, and after a few moments of agonising suspense said:-\\u201cIt is not too late.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65005,\n            \"When Van Helsing had seen her, he went out for a walk, leaving me in charge, with strict injunctions that I was not to leave her for a moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65676,\n            \"I put him in your window, I make pretty wreath, and hang him round your neck, so that you sleep well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65879,\n            \"\\u201d Then seeing poor Lucy scared, as she might well be, he went on more gently: \\u201cOh, little miss, my dear, do not fear me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65932,\n            \"See, I place them myself in your room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65942,\n            \"I make myself the wreath that you are to wear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66240,\n            \"\\u201d he answered quietly as he began to make the wreath which Lucy was to wear round her neck.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66260,\n            \"We then waited whilst Lucy made her toilet for the night, and when she was in bed he came and himself fixed the wreath of garlic round her neck.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66291,\n            \"The last words he said to her were:-\\u201cTake care you do not disturb it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67058,\n            \"She was sleeping soundly-so soundly that even my coming did not wake her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67148,\n            \"You will be pleased with her, I am sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67173,\n            \"As she had spoken, I watched the Professor\\u2019s face, and saw it turn ashen grey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67193,\n            \"He had been able to retain his self-command whilst the poor lady was present, for he knew her state and how mischievous a shock would be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67223,\n            \"he actually smiled on her as he held open the door for her to pass into her room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67242,\n            \"But the instant she had disappeared he pulled me, suddenly and forcibly, into the dining-room and closed the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67761,\n            \"Presently he took an opportunity of telling Mrs. Westenra that she must not remove anything from Lucy\\u2019s room without consulting him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70191,\n            \"\\u201cYe\\u2019ll excoose me, I know, for a-chaffin\\u2019of ye, but the old woman here winked at me, which was as much as telling me to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70706,\n            \"After all, however, there is nothing like custom, for neither Bilder nor his wife thought any more of the wolf than I should of a dog.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71583,\n            \"I shall take this cylinder with me, and then I can complete my entry on Lucy\\u2019s phonograph.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72219,\n            \"Amongst other things, she clutched the wreath of flowers that Dr. Van Helsing insisted on my wearing round my neck, and tore it away from me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73815,\n            \"Without a word the Professor bent over the bed, his head almost touching poor Lucy\\u2019s breast;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74473,\n            \"Van Helsing\\u2019s face almost beamed, and as we lifted her from the bath and rolled her in a hot sheet to dry her he said to me:-\\u201cThe first gain is ours!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75340,\n            \"He handed me the paper saying only: \\u201cIt dropped from Lucy\\u2019s breast when we carried her to the bath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76247,\n            \"One of those big bats that they call vampires had got at her in the night, and what with his gorge and the vein left open, there wasn\\u2019t enough blood in her to let her stand up, and I had to put a bullet through her as she lay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76880,\n            \"Van Helsing stepped over and took the pieces from her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77560,\n            \"I know you both from children, and have, with love and pride, seen you grow up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77580,\n            \"Now I want you to make your home here with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77602,\n            \"all are gone, and in my will I have left you everything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80319,\n            \"Presently she woke, and I gave her food, as Van Helsing had prescribed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80882,\n            \"He had even brushed Lucy\\u2019s hair, so that it lay on the pillow in its usual sunny ripples.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81374,\n            \"\\u201cMy true friend,\\u201dshe said, in a faint voice, but with untellable pathos, \\u201cMy true friend, and his!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81401,\n            \"Oh, guard him, and give me peace!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81417,\n            \"\\u201d he said solemnly, kneeling beside her and holding up his hand, as one who registers an oath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82175,\n            \"For me, I watch here in the room and in Miss Lucy\\u2019s old room all night, and I myself search for what may be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87342,\n            \"and now a telegram from Van Helsing, whoever he may be:-\\u201cYou will be grieved to hear that Mrs. Westenra died five days ago, and that Lucy died the day before yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88530,\n            \"As he answered me his face grew stern, and he said in quite a different tone:-\\u201cOh, it was the grim irony of it all-this so lovely lady garlanded with flowers, that looked so fair as life, till one by one we wondered if she were truly dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90684,\n            \"and as he attended poor dear Lucy in her last illness, he can tell me all about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91773,\n            \"He took it and said tenderly:-\\u201cOh, Madam Mina, I knew that the friend of that poor lily girl must be good, but I had yet to learn--\\u201dHe finished his speech with a courtly bow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91819,\n            \"I asked him what it was that he wanted to see me about, so he at once began:-\\u201cI have read your letters to Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91869,\n            \"I know that you were with her at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92254,\n            \"but I had been thinking that it was of dear Lucy that you wished to ask, and so that you might not have time to wait-not on my account, but because I know your time must be precious-I have written it out on the typewriter for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93367,\n            \"You have told me all about Lucy, and so now we shall not speak of it, lest it distress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94668,\n            \"Mina is dressing, and I shall call at the hotel in a few minutes and bring him over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94702,\n            \"When I came into the room where he was, and introduced myself, he took me by the shoulder, and turned my face round to the light, and said, after a sharp scrutiny:-\\u201cBut Madam Mina told me you were ill, that you had had a shock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94758,\n            \"\\u201d It was so funny to hear my wife called \\u201cMadam Mina\\u201dby this kindly, strong-faced old man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94812,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBy your letter to Mina last night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94970,\n            \"and, oh, sir, you will pardon praise from an old man, but you are blessed in your wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94993,\n            \"\\u201d I would listen to him go on praising Mina for a day, so I simply nodded and stood silent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95090,\n            \"And you, sir-I have read all the letters to poor Miss Lucy, and some of them speak of you, so I know you since some days from the knowing of others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95346,\n            \"When we were parting he said:-\\u201cPerhaps you will come to town if I send to you, and take Madam Mina too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95503,\n            \"This recalled him to himself, and he leaned out of the window and waved his hand, calling out: \\u201cLove to Madam Mina;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96086,\n            \"Never, even in the midst of our despair about poor Lucy, had he looked more stern.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96140,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo you mean to tell me, friend John, that you have no suspicion as to what poor Lucy died of;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97655,\n            \"He threw himself with a despairing gesture into a chair, and placed his elbows on the table, covering his face with his hands as he spoke:-\\u201cThey were made by Miss Lucy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97713,\n            \"it was as if he had during her life struck Lucy on the face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97887,\n            \"He went on:-\\u201cMy friend, it was because I wished to be gentle in the breaking to you, for I know you have loved that so sweet lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98117,\n            \"Come, I tell you what I propose: first, that we go off now and see that child in the hospital.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98141,\n            \"Dr. Vincent, of the North Hospital, where the papers say the child is, is friend of mine, and I think of yours since you were in class at Amsterdam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98229,\n            \"\\u201cAnd then we spend the night, you and I, in the churchyard where Lucy lies.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99221,\n            \"Holding his candle so that he could read the coffin plates, and so holding it that the sperm dropped in white patches which congealed as they touched the metal, he made assurance of Lucy\\u2019s coffin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99606,\n            \"I felt all the dogged argumentativeness of my nature awake within me as I answered him:-\\u201cI am satisfied that Lucy\\u2019s body is not in that coffin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100264,\n            \"\\u201cDo you not see the child?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100296,\n            \"\\u201cWe shall see,\\u201dsaid the Professor, and with one impulse we took our way out of the churchyard, he carrying the sleeping child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100896,\n            \"Van Helsing walked over to Lucy\\u2019s coffin, and I followed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101233,\n            \"He was looking intently at the face of the dead woman, raising the eyelids and looking at the eyes, and once more opening the lips and examining the teeth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101300,\n            \"She was bitten by the vampire when she was in a trance, sleep-walking-oh, you start;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101377,\n            \"Usually when the Un-Dead sleep at home \\\"-as he spoke he made a comprehensive sweep of his arm to designate what to a vampire was \\u201chome \\\"-\\\" their face show what they are, but this so sweet that was when she not Un-Dead she go back to the nothings of the common dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101441,\n            \"There is no malign there, see, and so it make hard that I must kill her in her sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101564,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall cut off her head and fill her mouth with garlic, and I shall drive a stake through her body.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101975,\n            \"and he may think that in some more mistaken idea this woman was buried alive;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102003,\n            \"He will then argue back that it is we, mistaken ones, that have killed her by our ideas;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102048,\n            \"And he will sometimes think that she he loved was buried alive, and that will paint his dreams with horrors of what she must have suffered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102076,\n            \"and again, he will think that we may be right, and that his so beloved was, after all, an Un-Dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102570,\n            \"He is cunning, as I know from Mr. Jonathan and from the way that all along he have fooled us when he played with us for Miss Lucy\\u2019s life, and we lost;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102631,\n            \"even we four who gave our strength to Miss Lucy it also is all to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102708,\n            \"his hunting ground is more full of game than the churchyard where the Un-Dead woman sleep, and the one old man watch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103675,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur\\u2019s face fell as he said in an amazed sort of way:-\\u201cWhere poor Lucy is buried?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103982,\n            \"After a pause Van Helsing went on, evidently with an effort:-\\u201cMiss Lucy is dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104018,\n            \"But if she be not dead--\\u201dArthur jumped to his feet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104071,\n            \"\\u201cI did not say she was alive, my child;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104089,\n            \"I go no further than to say that she might be Un-Dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104198,\n            \"\\u201cNot for the wide world will I consent to any mutilation of her dead body.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104239,\n            \"What did that poor, sweet girl do that you should want to cast such dishonour on her grave?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104299,\n            \"I have a duty to do in protecting her grave from outrage;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105240,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI swear to you by all that I hold sacred that I have not removed nor touched her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106926,\n            \"She was leaping for them, when Van Helsing sprang forward and held between them his little golden crucifix.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106946,\n            \"She recoiled from it, and, with a suddenly distorted face, full of rage, dashed past him as if to enter the tomb.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106996,\n            \"Then she turned, and her face was shown in the clear burst of moonlight and by the lamp, which had now no quiver from Van Helsing\\u2019s iron nerves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107298,\n            \"We all looked on in horrified amazement as we saw, when he stood back, the woman, with a corporeal body as real at that moment as our own, pass in through the interstice where scarce a knife-blade could have gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107889,\n            \"When he again lifted the lid off Lucy\\u2019s coffin we all looked-Arthur trembling like an aspen-and saw that the body lay there in all its death-beauty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107966,\n            \"Presently he said to Van Helsing:-\\u201cIs this really Lucy\\u2019s body, or only a demon in her shape?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108677,\n            \"Will it be no joy to think of hereafter in the silence of the night when sleep is not: \\u2018 It was my hand that sent her to the stars;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109678,\n            \"God bless you that you have given my dear one her soul again, and me peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109727,\n            \"When he raised his head Van Helsing said to him:-\\u201cAnd now, my child, you may kiss her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110327,\n            \"\\u201cAh, that wonderful Madam Mina,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cpearl among women!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110344,\n            \"She arrive, but I cannot stay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111291,\n            \"and as it is entirely-almost entirely-about my cases, it may be awkward-that is, I mean--\\u201dHe stopped, and I tried to help him out of his embarrassment:-\\u201cYou helped to attend dear Lucy at the end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111373,\n            \"\\u201d To my surprise, he answered, with a horrorstruck look in his face:-\\u201cTell you of her death?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111842,\n            \"poor dear Lucy was right about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111918,\n            \"I know that Lucy told you of me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112507,\n            \"and I see already, though your diary only took me to 7 September, how poor Lucy was beset, and how her terrible doom was being wrought out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115592,\n            \"Of course they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has been quite \\u201cblowing my trumpet,\\u201das Mr. Morris expressed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115916,\n            \"Besides, I know you loved my poor Lucy-\\u201d Here he turned away and covered his face with his hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116093,\n            \"I said to him, for I could see that his heart was breaking:-\\u201cI loved dear Lucy, and I know what she was to you, and what you were to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116138,\n            \"and now she is gone, will you not let me be like a sister to you in your trouble?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116176,\n            \"If sympathy and pity can help in your affliction, won\\u2019t you let me be of some little service-for Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116562,\n            \"You will let me be like a brother, will you not, for all our lives-for dear Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118628,\n            \"at which the Professor interrupted me:-\\u201cAh, that wonderful Madam Mina!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120364,\n            \"\\u201cI am with you,\\u201dsaid Lord Godalming, \\u201cfor Lucy\\u2019s sake, if for no other reason.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126541,\n            \"It was startlingly like the image conveyed to me in Dr. Seward\\u2019s diary of the opening of Miss Westenra\\u2019s tomb;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129361,\n            \"He said to Madam Mina, as I see in your diary of yesterday, that he had once had such a belief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129843,\n            \"Friend John, it does rejoice me unspeakable that she is no more to be pained, no more to be worried with our terrible things.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 17]\": [\n        [\n            61235,\n            \"My friend John and I have consulted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61709,\n            \"Friend John, help to me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66000,\n            \"Come with me, friend John, and you shall help me deck the room with my garlic, which is all the way from Haarlem, where my friend Vanderpool raise herb in his glass-houses all the year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69472,\n            \"That there man kem over, and blessed but if he didn\\u2019t put in his hand and stroke the old wolf\\u2019s ears too!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70107,\n            \"I couldn\\u2019t cope in badinage with the worthy Thomas, but I thought I knew a surer way to his heart, so I said:-\\u201cNow, Mr. Bilder, we\\u2019ll consider that first half-sovereign worked off, and this brother of his is waiting to be claimed when you\\u2019ve told me what you think will happen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70828,\n            \"Old Bilder examined him all over with most tender solicitude, and when he had finished with his penitent said:-\\u201cThere, I knew the poor old chap would get into some kind of trouble;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70938,\n            \"\\u201d He took the wolf and locked him up in a cage, with a piece of meat that satisfied, in quantity at any rate, the elementary conditions of the fatted calf, and went off to report.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71069,\n            \"I was thunderstruck, for such a thing as a patient getting of his own accord into the Superintendent\\u2019s study is almost unknown.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75684,\n            \"Ah yes, I know, friend John;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75698,\n            \"I love you all the more for it!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76247,\n            \"One of those big bats that they call vampires had got at her in the night, and what with his gorge and the vein left open, there wasn\\u2019t enough blood in her to let her stand up, and I had to put a bullet through her as she lay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77616,\n            \"\\u2019 I cried, Lucy dear, as Jonathan and the old man clasped hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77732,\n            \"Jonathan and Mr. Hawkins are busy all day;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77742,\n            \"for, now that Jonathan is a partner, Mr. Hawkins wants to tell him all about the clients.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82399,\n            \"I shall see that poor lad to-morrow evening, and, with his sanction, I shall use some.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88219,\n            \"And yet when he say things that touch my husband-heart to the quick, and make my father-heart yearn to him as to no other man-not even to you, friend John, for we are more level in experiences than father and son-yet even at such moment King Laugh he come to me and shout and bellow in my ear, \\u2018 Here I am!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92155,\n            \"\\u201cI knew long that Mr. Jonathan was a man of much thankfulness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92855,\n            \"\\u201d I saw here an opening to ask him about Jonathan, so I said:-\\u201cHe was almost recovered, but he has been greatly upset by Mr. Hawkins\\u2019 s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93042,\n            \"I suppose I was hysterical, for I threw myself on my knees and held up my hands to him, and implored him to make my husband well again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93269,\n            \"for if your husband suffer, he suffer within the range of my study and experience.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93286,\n            \"I promise you that I will gladly do all for him that I can-all to make his life strong and manly, and your life a happy one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93426,\n            \"And then, too, you will tell me of husband Jonathan\\u2019s trouble so far as you can, but not yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93463,\n            \"\\u201d After lunch, when we went back to the drawing-room, he said to me:-\\u201cAnd now tell me all about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93492,\n            \"\\u201d When it came to speaking to this great learned man, I began to fear that he would think me a weak fool, and Jonathan a madman-that journal is all so strange-and I hesitated to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93536,\n            \"But he was so sweet and kind, and he had promised to help, and I trusted him, so I said:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, what I have to tell you is so queer that you must not laugh at me or at my husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93782,\n            \"It will tell you my trouble and Jonathan\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93860,\n            \"\\u201cI shall in the morning, so soon as I can, come to see you and your husband, if I may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93885,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cJonathan will be here at half-past eleven, and you must come to lunch with us and see him then;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93929,\n            \"\\u201d He was surprised at my knowledge of the trains off-hand, but he does not know that I have made up all the trains to and from Exeter, so that I may help Jonathan in case he is in a hurry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94022,\n            \"\\u201cDear Madam Mina,-\\u201cI have read your husband\\u2019s so wonderful diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94088,\n            \"and let me tell you from experience of men, that one who would do as he did in going down that wall and to that room-ay, and going a second time-is not one to be injured in permanence by a shock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94145,\n            \"this I swear, before I have even seen him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94161,\n            \"I shall have much to ask him of other things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94309,\n            \"I have this moment, whilst writing, had a wire from Jonathan, saying that he leaves by the 6: 25 to-night from Launceston and will be here at 10: 18, so that I shall have no fear to-night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98257,\n            \"I had it from the coffin-man to give to Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98634,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201c\\u201cI hope,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing, \\u201cthat when you are sending the child home you will caution its parents to keep strict watch over it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98691,\n            \"But in any case I suppose you will not let it away for some days?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110112,\n            \"Then said the Professor as we moved off:-\\u201cTwo nights hence you shall meet with me and dine together at seven of the clock with friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110172,\n            \"Friend John, you come with me home, for I have much to consult about, and you can help me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110218,\n            \"But first I shall have much to say, so that you may know what is to do and to dread.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111762,\n            \"\\u201cWhen you have read those papers-my own diary and my husband\\u2019s also, which I have typed-you will know me better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112538,\n            \"Jonathan and I have been working day and night since Professor Van Helsing saw us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113319,\n            \"Before I left him I remembered what Jonathan put in his diary of the Professor\\u2019s perturbation at reading something in an evening paper at the station at Exeter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118504,\n            \"He saw me at once, and rushed up to me, saying:-\\u201cAh, friend John, how goes all?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118993,\n            \"Before we went to prepare for dinner he said to Mrs. Harker:-\\u201cI am told, Madam Mina, by my friend John that you and your husband have put up in exact order all things that have been, up to this moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120222,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst he was speaking, Jonathan had taken my hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120307,\n            \"When the Professor had done speaking my husband looked in my eyes, and I in his;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123180,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cTake me with you, friend John,\\u201dsaid the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125695,\n            \"\\u201d Lord Godalming and I were silent, but Dr. Van Helsing added:-\\u201cFriend John, you know more of lunatics than I do, and I\\u2019m glad of it, for I fear that if it had been to me to decide I would before that last hysterical outburst have given him free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125988,\n            \"\\u201d The Professor stepped over, and laying his hand on his shoulder, said in his grave, kindly way:-\\u201cFriend John, have no fear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126431,\n            \"\\u201cNow,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cfriend John, where are the skeleton keys?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169151,\n            \"If that time shall come again, I look to you to make it a happy memory of my husband\\u2019s life that it was his loving hand which set me free from the awful thrall upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172705,\n            \"Do you, friend Jonathan, go to the agent of the ship and get from him letters to the agent in Galatz, with authority to make search the ship just as it was here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173762,\n            \"See I read here what Jonathan have written:-\\u201cThat other of his race who, in a later age, again and again, brought his forces over The Great River into Turkey Land;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180705,\n            \") He was silent awhile, and during his silence Dr. Van Helsing spoke:-\\u201cFriend Jonathan, this is to you for twice reasons.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181060,\n            \"\\u201d Here Jonathan interrupted him hotly:-\\u201cDo you mean to say, Professor Van Helsing, that you would bring Mina, in her sad case and tainted as she is with that devil\\u2019s illness, right into the jaws of his death-trap?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181248,\n            \"The Professor\\u2019s voice, as he spoke in clear, sweet tones, which seemed to vibrate in the air, calmed us all:-\\u201cOh, my friend, it is because I would save Madam Mina from that awful place that I would go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181463,\n            \"Forgive me that I make you so much pain, but it is necessary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181478,\n            \"My friend, is it not a dire need for the which I am giving, possibly my life?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181524,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo as you will,\\u201dsaid Jonathan, with a sob that shook him all over, \\u201cwe are in the hands of God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181708,\n            \"and now Lord Godalming and Jonathan have a lovely steam launch, with steam up ready to start at a moment\\u2019s notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184279,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing is sleeping, Poor dear, he looks very tired and old and grey, but his mouth is set as firmly as a conqueror\\u2019s;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 7]\": [\n        [\n            102745,\n            \"Take the papers that are with this, the diaries of Harker and the rest, and read them, and then find this great Un-Dead, and cut off his head and burn his heart or drive a stake through it, so that the world may rest from him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143728,\n            \"Van Helsing whispered to me:-\\u201cJonathan is in a stupor such as we know the Vampire can produce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144682,\n            \"but his nostrils twitched and his eyes blazed as I told how the ruthless hands of the Count had held his wife in that terrible and horrid position, with her mouth to the open wound in his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146216,\n            \"He placed his reeking lips upon my throat!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149094,\n            \"and think there was to you no conscience of the housebreaker, what would you do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149886,\n            \"but it made my blood run cold in my veins to think of what had occurred with poor Lucy when the Count had sucked her blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150090,\n            \"It was possible, if not likely, the Professor urged, that the Count might appear in Piccadilly during the day, and that if so we might be able to cope with him then and there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150208,\n            \"that amongst the Count\\u2019s papers might be some clue which I could understand out of my experience in Transylvania;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150411,\n            \"\\u201cDo you forget,\\u201dhe said, with actually a smile, \\u201cthat last night he banqueted heavily, and will sleep late?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153553,\n            \"So well as I can remember, here it is:-\\u201cI have studied, over and over again since they came into my hands, all the papers relating to this monster;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153629,\n            \"As I learned from the researches of my friend Arminus of Buda-Pesth, he was in life a most wonderful man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155429,\n            \"Van Helsing, Harker, and I were just behind the door, so that when it was opened the Professor could guard it whilst we two stepped between the incomer and the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155711,\n            \"Harker evidently meant to try the matter, for he had ready his great Kukri knife and made a fierce and sudden cut at him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155804,\n            \"The expression of the Count\\u2019s face was so hellish, that for a moment I feared for Harker, though I saw him throw the terrible knife aloft again for another stroke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155868,\n            \"and it was without surprise that I saw the monster cower back before a similar movement made spontaneously by each one of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155953,\n            \"The next instant, with a sinuous dive he swept under Harker\\u2019s arm, ere his blow could fall, and, grasping a handful of the money from the floor, dashed across the room, threw himself at the window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156361,\n            \"took the title-deeds in the bundle as Harker had left them, and swept the remaining things into the open fireplace, where he set fire to them with a match.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156395,\n            \"Godalming and Morris had rushed out into the yard, and Harker had lowered himself from the window to follow the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156902,\n            \"When we came to the part where Harker had rushed at the Count so recklessly, she clung to her husband\\u2019s arm, and held it tight as though her clinging could protect him from any harm that might come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158001,\n            \"I love her a thousand times more for her sweet pity of last night, a pity that made my own hate of the monster seem despicable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160420,\n            \"When that fail he make straight for his last resource-his last earth-work I might say did I wish double entente.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160726,\n            \"For my own part, now that his horrible danger is not face to face with us, it seems almost impossible to believe in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162228,\n            \"\\u201cAnd so, my dear Madam Mina, it is that we have to rest for a time, for our enemy is on the sea, with the fog at his command, on his way to the Danube mouth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162477,\n            \"\\u201d When Dr. Van Helsing had done speaking, I asked him if he were certain that the Count had remained on board the ship.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162528,\n            \"\\u201d I asked him again if it were really necessary that they should pursue the Count, for oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163035,\n            \"He have infect you-oh, forgive me, my dear, that I must say such;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163225,\n            \"\\u201d He paused and I said:-\\u201cBut will not the Count take his rebuff wisely?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166149,\n            \"She said:-\\u201cPromise me that you will not tell me anything of the plans formed for the campaign against the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170574,\n            \"- Everything is pretty well fixed now, I think, to welcome the Count on his return from his tour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171757,\n            \"To his doom, I trust!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171930,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing is terribly anxious, and told me just now that he fears the Count is escaping us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174385,\n            \"His finger and thumb closed on her pulse, as I thought instinctively and unconsciously, as she spoke:-\\u201cThe Count is a criminal and of criminal type.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174818,\n            \"So his own selfishness frees my soul somewhat from the terrible power which he acquired over me on that dreadful night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174871,\n            \"and all that haunts me is a fear lest in some trance or dream he may have used my knowledge for his ends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176239,\n            \"I am in fear that her power of reading the Count\\u2019s sensations may die away, just when we want it most.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176304,\n            \"If I thought that the Count\\u2019s power over her would die away equally with her power of knowledge it would be a happy thought;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177820,\n            \"an\\u2019when the last o\\u2019them rose off the deck wi\\u2019his head in his hand, I had convinced them that, evil eye or no evil eye, the property and the trust of my owners were better in my hands than in the river Danube.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            179849,\n            \"My surmise is, this: that in London the Count decided to get back to his castle by water, as the most safe and secret way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181363,\n            \"If the Count escape us this time-and he is strong and subtle and cunning-he may choose to sleep him for a century, and then in time our dear one \\\"-he took my hand-\\\" would come to him to keep him company, and would be as those others that you, Jonathan, saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185765,\n            \"She is now quite awake, and look so well as I never saw her since that night at Carfax when we first enter the Count\\u2019s house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188487,\n            \"Her, I had not dare to take into this place, but left safe from the Vampire in that Holy circle;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188564,\n            \"Had it but been for myself the choice had been easy, the maw of the wolf were better to rest in than the grave of the Vampire!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188806,\n            \"There is some fascination, surely, when I am moved by the mere presence of such an one, even lying as she lay in a tomb fretted with age and heavy with the dust of centuries, though there be that horrid odour such as the lairs of the Count have had.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189303,\n            \"Before I began to restore these women to their dead selves through my awful work, I laid in Dracula\\u2019s tomb some of the Wafer, and so banished him from it, Un-Dead, for ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189683,\n            \"\\u201d Before I left the castle I so fixed its entrances that never more can the Count enter there Un-Dead.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 9]\": [\n        [\n            138695,\n            \"We beg, with regard to the desire of your Lordship, expressed by Mr. Harker on your behalf, to supply the following information concerning the sale and purchase of No.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 11]\": [\n        [\n            113964,\n            \"I believe that, had I not had the chat with Harker and read the letters and the dates of his outbursts, I should have been prepared to sign for him after a brief time of observation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117181,\n            \"I want to see your patient, Mr. Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117192,\n            \"Do let me see him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117198,\n            \"What you have said of him in your diary interests me so much!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117754,\n            \"\\u201d His reply was simply contemptuous, given in a pause in which he turned his eyes from Mrs. Harker to me, instantly turning them back again:-\\u201cWhat an asinine question!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117791,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI don\\u2019t see that at all, Mr. Renfield,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Harker, at once championing me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117817,\n            \"He replied to her with as much courtesy and respect as he had shown contempt to me:-\\u201cYou will, of course, understand, Mrs. Harker, that when a man is so loved and honoured as our host is, everything regarding him is of interest in our little community.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118047,\n            \"and, seeing that he was seemingly quite reasonable, she ventured, looking at me questioningly as she began, to lead him to his favourite topic.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118366,\n            \"She came at once, after saying pleasantly to Mr. Renfield: \\u201cGood-bye, and I hope I may see you often, under auspices pleasanter to yourself,\\u201dto which, to my astonishment, he replied:-\\u201cGood-bye, my dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118419,\n            \"I pray God I may never see your sweet face again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139287,\n            \"If we could only get some hint as to what passed in his mind, between the time of my argument with him to-day and his resumption of fly-catching, it might afford us a valuable clue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139359,\n            \"The attendant came bursting into my room and told me that Renfield had somehow met with some accident.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139469,\n            \"When I came to Renfield\\u2019s room I found him lying on the floor on his left side in a glittering pool of blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139495,\n            \"When I went to move him, it became at once apparent that he had received some terrible injuries;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139573,\n            \"The attendant who was kneeling beside the body said to me as we turned him over:-\\u201cI think, sir, his back is broken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139829,\n            \"When he saw Renfield on the ground, he looked keenly at him a moment, and then turned to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139968,\n            \"for, almost before he looked at the patient, he whispered to me:-\\u201cSend the attendant away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140363,\n            \"\\u201d I told him briefly, and added that we expected he would recover consciousness after the operation-for a short time, at all events.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140505,\n            \"I dreaded the words that Renfield might speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140942,\n            \"but even with the effort his eyes seemed to grow glassy again so I gently put it back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141037,\n            \"I dreamed \\\"-he stopped and seemed fainting, I called quietly to Quincey-\\\" The brandy-it is in my study-quick!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141096,\n            \"It seemed, however, that his poor injured brain had been working in the interval, for, when he was quite conscious, he looked at me piercingly with an agonised confusion which I shall never forget, and said:-\\u201cI must not deceive myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141229,\n            \"when he opened them he said, hurriedly, and with more energy than he had yet displayed:-\\u201cQuick, Doctor, quick.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141473,\n            \"Renfield proceeded:-\\u201cHe came up to the window in the mist, as I had seen him often before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154043,\n            \"How he has been making use of the zo\\u00f6phagous patient to effect his entry into friend John\\u2019s home;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178768,\n            \"Poor fellow, maybe he is thinking, and I can see his face all wrinkled up with the concentration of his thoughts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192286,\n            \"He was deathly pale, just like a waxen image, and the red eyes glared with the horrible vindictive look which I knew too well.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 12]\": [\n        [\n            122402,\n            \"\\u201d A minute later he came in and said:-\\u201cIt was an idiotic thing of me to do, and I ask your pardon, Mrs. Harker, most sincerely;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141037,\n            \"I dreamed \\\"-he stopped and seemed fainting, I called quietly to Quincey-\\\" The brandy-it is in my study-quick!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143835,\n            \"and as I looked I could see Quincey Morris run across the lawn and hide himself in the shadow of a great yew-tree.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143861,\n            \"It puzzled me to think why he was doing this;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144760,\n            \"Just as I had finished, Quincey and Godalming knocked at the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150063,\n            \"that the two doctors and I should remain there, whilst Lord Godalming and Quincey found the lairs at Walworth and Mile End and destroyed them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152088,\n            \"- Just before we reached Fenchurch Street Lord Godalming said to me:-\\u201cQuincey and I will find a locksmith.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155343,\n            \"In all our hunting parties and adventures in different parts of the world, Quincey Morris had always been the one to arrange the plan of action, and Arthur and I had been accustomed to obey him implicitly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191840,\n            \"In the midst of this I could see that Jonathan on one side of the ring of men, and Quincey on the other, were forcing a way to the cart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192066,\n            \"He had parried with his great bowie knife, and at first I thought that he too had come through in safety;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192089,\n            \"but as he sprang beside Jonathan, who had by now jumped from the cart, I could see that with his left hand he was clutching at his side, and that the blood was spurting through his fingers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192590,\n            \"I flew to him, for the Holy circle did not now keep me back;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192628,\n            \"With a sigh he took, with a feeble effort, my hand in that of his own which was unstained.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192650,\n            \"He must have seen the anguish of my heart in my face, for he smiled at me and said:-\\u201cI am only too happy to have been of any service!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192689,\n            \"\\u201d he cried suddenly, struggling up to a sitting posture and pointing to me, \\u201cIt was worth for this to die!\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 14]\": [\n        [\n            144760,\n            \"Just as I had finished, Quincey and Godalming knocked at the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152088,\n            \"- Just before we reached Fenchurch Street Lord Godalming said to me:-\\u201cQuincey and I will find a locksmith.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152166,\n            \"\\u201d I demurred as to my not sharing any danger even of odium, but he went on: \\u201cBesides, it will attract less attention if there are not too many of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156395,\n            \"Godalming and Morris had rushed out into the yard, and Harker had lowered himself from the window to follow the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157754,\n            \"When they had retired, Quincey, Godalming, and I arranged that we should sit up, dividing the night between us, and watch over the safety of the poor stricken lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158317,\n            \"He raised a warning hand for silence as he whispered to me:-\\u201cHush!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158363,\n            \"\\u201d His look and gesture forbade discussion, so I came back and told Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167234,\n            \"\\u201d I grasped his hand instinctively and found it as firm as a piece of steel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167251,\n            \"I think he understood my look;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167258,\n            \"I hope he did.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 15]\": [\n        [\n            140184,\n            \"I went over and opened it and found in the corridor without, Arthur and Quincey in pajamas and slippers: the former spoke:-\\u201cI heard your man call up Dr. Van Helsing and tell him of an accident.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155343,\n            \"In all our hunting parties and adventures in different parts of the world, Quincey Morris had always been the one to arrange the plan of action, and Arthur and I had been accustomed to obey him implicitly.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 17]\": [\n        [\n            117681,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy husband and I are staying on a visit with Dr. Seward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118993,\n            \"Before we went to prepare for dinner he said to Mrs. Harker:-\\u201cI am told, Madam Mina, by my friend John that you and your husband have put up in exact order all things that have been, up to this moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119223,\n            \"It can but make your husband love you the more, and all us, your friends, more honour you-as well as more esteem and love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144666,\n            \"\\u201d I told him exactly what had happened, and he listened with seeming impassiveness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144682,\n            \"but his nostrils twitched and his eyes blazed as I told how the ruthless hands of the Count had held his wife in that terrible and horrid position, with her mouth to the open wound in his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145454,\n            \"\\u201d The poor, dear lady shivered, and I could see the tension of her nerves as she clasped her husband closer to her and bent her head lower and lower still on his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145742,\n            \"Jonathan coming in had not waked me, for he lay by my side when next I remember.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145821,\n            \"I turned to wake Jonathan, but found that he slept so soundly that it seemed as if it was he who had taken the sleeping draught, and not I.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145853,\n            \"I tried, but I could not wake him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145876,\n            \"Then indeed, my heart sank within me: beside the bed, as if he had stepped out of the mist-or rather as if the mist had turned into his figure, for it had entirely disappeared-stood a tall, thin man, all in black.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145928,\n            \"I knew him at once from the description of the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145999,\n            \"I knew, too, the red scar on his forehead where Jonathan had struck him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146096,\n            \"With a mocking smile, he placed one hand upon my shoulder and, holding me tight, bared my throat with the other, saying as he did so, \\u2018 First, a little refreshment to reward my exertions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146145,\n            \"it is not the first time, or the second, that your veins have appeased my thirst!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146164,\n            \"\\u2019 I was bewildered, and, strangely enough, I did not want to hinder him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146231,\n            \"She clasped his hand harder, and looked at him pityingly, as if he were the injured one, and went on:-\\u201cI felt my strength fading away, and I was in a half swoon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146467,\n            \"And you, their best beloved one, are now to me, flesh of my flesh;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146548,\n            \"You have aided in thwarting me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146613,\n            \"When the blood began to spurt out, he took my hands in one of his, holding them tight, and with the other seized my neck and pressed my mouth to the wound, so that I must either suffocate or swallow some of the-- Oh my God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148119,\n            \"so sorrowfully, as she held out her hand:-\\u201cI promise you, my dear friend, that if God will let me live, I shall strive to do so;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149299,\n            \"I have read of a gentleman who owned a so fine house in London, and when he went for months of summer to Switzerland and lock up his house, some burglar came and broke window at back and got in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157754,\n            \"When they had retired, Quincey, Godalming, and I arranged that we should sit up, dividing the night between us, and watch over the safety of the poor stricken lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160275,\n            \"Let me tell you that so you will know what we four know already, for I have tell them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162548,\n            \"I dread Jonathan leaving me, and I know that he would surely go if the others went.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162697,\n            \"you, my dear Madam Mina, will learn it in the phonograph of my friend John, or in that of your husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168597,\n            \"You must promise me, one and all-even you, my beloved husband-that, should the time come, you will kill me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168670,\n            \"When I am thus dead in the flesh, then you will, without a moment\\u2019s delay, drive a stake through me and cut off my head;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169151,\n            \"If that time shall come again, I look to you to make it a happy memory of my husband\\u2019s life that it was his loving hand which set me free from the awful thrall upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172783,\n            \"John will stay with Madam Mina and me, and we shall consult.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175632,\n            \"Quincey raised his eyebrows slightly and looked at her intently, whilst Harker\\u2019s hand instinctively closed round the hilt of his Kukri.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180174,\n            \"When I had done reading, Jonathan took me in his arms and kissed me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180627,\n            \"\\u201d He looked at Jonathan as he spoke, and Jonathan looked at me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180642,\n            \"I could see that the poor dear was torn about in his mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180656,\n            \"Of course he wanted to be with me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181193,\n            \"\\u201d Here he turned to me, and as his eyes lit on my forehead he threw up his arms with a cry: \\u201cOh, my God, what have we done to have this terror upon us!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181363,\n            \"If the Count escape us this time-and he is strong and subtle and cunning-he may choose to sleep him for a century, and then in time our dear one \\\"-he took my hand-\\\" would come to him to keep him company, and would be as those others that you, Jonathan, saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181870,\n            \"Jonathan would not be happy unless I was armed like the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183591,\n            \"If Jonathan and I were driving through it alone what a pleasure it would be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183858,\n            \"that whatever may happen, Jonathan may know that I loved him and honoured him more than I can say, and that my latest and truest thought will be always for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184240,\n            \"I am afraid to think of Jonathan, but somehow I have now no fear for him, or for myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187133,\n            \"for the snow flakes and the mist began to wheel and circle round, till I could get as though a shadowy glimpse of those women that would have kissed him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187420,\n            \"Then they began to materialise till-if God have not take away my reason, for I saw it through my eyes-there were before me in actual flesh the same three women that Jonathan saw in the room, when they would have kissed his throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188390,\n            \"Jonathan\\u2019s bitter experience served me here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188399,\n            \"By memory of his diary I found my way to the old chapel, for I knew that here my work lay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188662,\n            \"Ah, I doubt not that in old time, when such things were, many a man who set forth to do such a task as mine, found at the last his heart fail him, and then his nerve.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188861,\n            \"Yes, I was moved-I, Van Helsing, with all my purpose and with my motive for hate-I was moved to a yearning for delay which seemed to paralyse my faculties and to clog my very soul.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189052,\n            \"but I go on searching until, presently, I find in a high great tomb as if made to one much beloved that other fair sister which, like Jonathan I had seen to gather herself out of the atoms of the mist.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189626,\n            \"For, friend John, hardly had my knife severed the head of each, before the whole body began to melt away and crumble in to its native dust, as though the death that should have come centuries agone had at last assert himself and say at once and loud \\u201cI am here!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189865,\n            \"- It was late in the afternoon when the Professor and I took our way towards the east whence I knew Jonathan was coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190120,\n            \"I knew from the way Dr. Van Helsing was searching about that he was trying to seek some strategic point, where we would be less exposed in case of attack.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190169,\n            \"In a little while the Professor signalled to me, so I got up and joined him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190213,\n            \"He took me by the hand and drew me in: \\u201cSee!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190227,\n            \"\\u201d he said, \\u201chere you will be in shelter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190253,\n            \"\\u201d He brought in our furs, and made a snug nest for me, and got out some provisions and forced them upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190285,\n            \"to even try to do so was repulsive to me, and, much as I would have liked to please him, I could not bring myself to the attempt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190317,\n            \"He looked very sad, but did not reproach me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190369,\n            \"\\u201d I sprang up and stood beside him on the rock;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190381,\n            \"he handed me his glasses and pointed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190641,\n            \"In fear I turned to the Professor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190649,\n            \"to my consternation, however, he was not there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190660,\n            \"An instant later, I saw him below me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190689,\n            \"When he had completed it he stood beside me again, saying:-\\u201cAt least you shall be safe here from him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190714,\n            \"\\u201d He took the glasses from me, and at the next lull of the snow swept the whole space below us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190898,\n            \"I knew at all events that neither of them was Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190910,\n            \"At the same time I knew that Jonathan was not far off;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190946,\n            \"One of them I knew was Jonathan, and the other I took, of course, to be Lord Godalming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190980,\n            \"When I told the Professor he shouted in glee like a schoolboy, and, after looking intently till a snow fall made sight impossible, he laid his Winchester rifle ready for use against the boulder at the opening of our shelter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191402,\n            \"The Professor and I crouched down behind our rock, and held our weapons ready;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191418,\n            \"I could see that he was determined that they should not pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191601,\n            \"At the same moment Dr. Van Helsing and I rose behind the rock and pointed our weapons at them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191678,\n            \"The leader, with a quick movement of his rein, threw his horse out in front, and pointing first to the sun-now close down on the hill tops-and then to the castle, said something which I did not understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191745,\n            \"I should have felt terrible fear at seeing Jonathan in such danger, but that the ardour of battle must have been upon me as well as the rest of them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191840,\n            \"In the midst of this I could see that Jonathan on one side of the ring of men, and Quincey on the other, were forcing a way to the cart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192018,\n            \"All the time I had been breathlessly watching Jonathan I had, with the tail of my eye, seen him pressing desperately forward, and had seen the knives of the gypsies flash as he won a way through them, and they cut at him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192089,\n            \"but as he sprang beside Jonathan, who had by now jumped from the cart, I could see that with his left hand he was clutching at his side, and that the blood was spurting through his fingers.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 8]\": [\n        [\n            121162,\n            \"he can be as bat, as Madam Mina saw him on the window at Whitby, and as friend John saw him fly from this so near house, and as my friend Quincey saw him at the window of Miss Lucy.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 9]\": [\n        [\n            175256,\n            \"You must be scribe and write him all down, so that when the others return from their work you can give it to them;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 11]\": [\n        [\n            113800,\n            \"He thinks that in the meantime I should see Renfield, as hitherto he has been a sort of index to the coming and going of the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114035,\n            \"Can it be that his instinct is satisfied as to the vampire\\u2019s ultimate triumph?\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 12]\": [\n        [\n            122831,\n            \"Mr. Morris resumed the discussion:-\\u201cAs there is no time to lose, I vote we have a look at his house right now.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 13]\": [\n        [\n            170720,\n            \"If the Count is there, Van Helsing and Seward will cut off his head at once and drive a stake through his heart.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 14]\": [\n        [\n            144932,\n            \"\\u201d So Art went on:-\\u201cHe had been there, and though it could only have been for a few seconds, he made rare hay of the place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145020,\n            \"\\u201d His face lit for a moment, but fell again as he went on: \\u201cI ran downstairs then, but could see no sign of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156395,\n            \"Godalming and Morris had rushed out into the yard, and Harker had lowered himself from the window to follow the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167196,\n            \"\\u201cWhen I see the box I shall open it and destroy the monster, though there were a thousand men looking on, and if I am to be wiped out for it the next moment!\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 15]\": [\n        [\n            128449,\n            \"for look, these rats that would come to his call, just as from his castle top he summon the wolves to your going and to that poor mother\\u2019s cry, though they come to him, they run pell-mell from the so little dogs of my friend Arthur.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 16]\": [\n        [\n            118924,\n            \"\\u201d he said, \\u201cfor then we might have reached him in time to save poor Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121162,\n            \"he can be as bat, as Madam Mina saw him on the window at Whitby, and as friend John saw him fly from this so near house, and as my friend Quincey saw him at the window of Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121272,\n            \"He become so small-we ourselves saw Miss Lucy, ere she was at peace, slip through a hairbreadth space at the tomb door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130488,\n            \"and if she hadn\\u2019t gone there at night and asleep, that monster couldn\\u2019t have destroyed her as he did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133058,\n            \"Indeed, it may not be a hard task, after all, for she herself has become reticent on the subject, and has not spoken of the Count or his doings ever since we told her of our decision.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 17]\": [\n        [\n            118865,\n            \"\\u201d I agreed heartily with him, and then I told him what we had found in his absence: that the house which Dracula had bought was the very next one to my own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121093,\n            \"he make in the mirror no reflect, as again Jonathan observe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121106,\n            \"He has the strength of many of his hand-witness again Jonathan when he shut the door against the wolfs, and when he help him from the diligence too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121162,\n            \"he can be as bat, as Madam Mina saw him on the window at Whitby, and as friend John saw him fly from this so near house, and as my friend Quincey saw him at the window of Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121251,\n            \"He come on moonlight rays as elemental dust-as again Jonathan saw those sisters in the castle of Dracula.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144682,\n            \"but his nostrils twitched and his eyes blazed as I told how the ruthless hands of the Count had held his wife in that terrible and horrid position, with her mouth to the open wound in his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157226,\n            \"You must be pitiful to him, too, though it may not hold your hands from his destruction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157323,\n            \"As she stopped speaking he leaped to his feet, almost tearing his hand from hers as he spoke:-\\u201cMay God give him into my hand just for long enough to destroy that earthly life of him which we are aiming at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157369,\n            \"If beyond it I could send his soul for ever and ever to burning hell I would do it!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159736,\n            \"We can know now what was in the Count\\u2019s mind, when he seize that money, though Jonathan\\u2019s so fierce knife put him in the danger that even he dread.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180926,\n            \"Whilst the old fox is tied in his box, floating on the running stream whence he cannot escape to land-where he dares not raise the lid of his coffin-box lest his Slovak carriers should in fear leave him to perish-we shall go in the track where Jonathan went,-from Bistritz over the Borgo, and find our way to the Castle of Dracula.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181060,\n            \"\\u201d Here Jonathan interrupted him hotly:-\\u201cDo you mean to say, Professor Van Helsing, that you would bring Mina, in her sad case and tainted as she is with that devil\\u2019s illness, right into the jaws of his death-trap?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181181,\n            \"Have you felt the Vampire\\u2019s lips upon your throat?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181363,\n            \"If the Count escape us this time-and he is strong and subtle and cunning-he may choose to sleep him for a century, and then in time our dear one \\\"-he took my hand-\\\" would come to him to keep him company, and would be as those others that you, Jonathan, saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181436,\n            \"you heard their ribald laugh as they clutched the moving bag that the Count threw to them.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 12]\": [\n        [\n            74855,\n            \"\\u201d The voice came from the sofa across the room, and its tones brought relief and joy to my heart, for they were those of Quincey Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74885,\n            \"Van Helsing started angrily at the first sound, but his face softened and a glad look came into his eyes as I cried out: \\u201cQuincey Morris!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74946,\n            \"\\u201d He handed me a telegram:-\\u201cHave not heard from Seward for three days, and am terribly anxious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75206,\n            \"The Professor watched whilst I went downstairs with Quincey Morris, and sent one of the maids to pay off one of the cabmen who were waiting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75234,\n            \"I left Quincey lying down after having a glass of wine, and told the cook to get ready a good breakfast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75710,\n            \"\\u201d In the hall I met Quincey Morris, with a telegram for Arthur telling him that Mrs. Westenra was dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75757,\n            \"I told him where I was going, and he hurried me out, but as I was going said:-\\u201cWhen you come back, Jack, may I have two words with you all to ourselves?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75837,\n            \"When I got back Quincey was waiting for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75847,\n            \"I told him I would see him as soon as I knew about Lucy, and went up to her room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75914,\n            \"So I went down to Quincey and took him into the breakfast-room, where the blinds were not drawn down, and which was a little more cheerful, or rather less cheerless, than the other rooms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75955,\n            \"When we were alone, he said to me:-\\u201cJack Seward, I don\\u2019t want to shove myself in anywhere where I\\u2019ve no right to be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75996,\n            \"You know I loved that girl and wanted to marry her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76418,\n            \"but already he knew so much, and guessed so much, that there could be no reason for not answering, so I answered in the same phrase: \\u201cThat\\u2019s so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76476,\n            \"Then I guess, Jack Seward, that that poor pretty creature that we all love has had put into her veins within that time the blood of four strong men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76520,\n            \"\\u201d Then, coming close to me, he spoke in a fierce half-whisper: \\u201cWhat took it out?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76643,\n            \"\\u201cYou and the Dutchman will tell me what to do, and I\\u2019ll do it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76996,\n            \"Quincey Morris said nothing about his intention, but I knew that all night long he patrolled round and round the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79247,\n            \"\\u201cBelieve me, dear Sir, \\u201cYours faithfully, \\u201cPatrick Hennessey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87483,\n            \"I believe in my heart of hearts that he suffered as much about Lucy\\u2019s death as any of us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87751,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 13]\": [\n        [\n            71742,\n            \"I was not afraid, but I did wish that Dr. Seward was in the next room-as Dr. Van Helsing said he would be-so that I might have called him.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 15]\": [\n        [\n            53906,\n            \"Arthur says I am getting fat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53913,\n            \"By the way, I forgot to tell you that Arthur is here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53947,\n            \"and I love him more than ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53955,\n            \"He tells me that he loves me more, but I doubt that, for at first he told me that he couldn\\u2019t love me more than he did then.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53993,\n            \"There he is, calling to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55092,\n            \"When Arthur came to lunch he looked quite grieved when he saw me, and I hadn\\u2019t the spirit to try to be cheerful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55294,\n            \"I shall try to cheer up when Arthur comes, or else I know he will be miserable to see me so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56402,\n            \"I have asked him to come over, and as you told me that all things were to be at your charge, I have mentioned to him who you are and your relations to Miss Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56469,\n            \"Van Helsing would, I know, do anything for me for a personal reason, so, no matter on what ground he comes, we must accept his wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56544,\n            \"and he has, I believe, an absolutely open mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56631,\n            \"I tell you these facts that you may know why I have such confidence in him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56648,\n            \"I have asked him to come at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56779,\n            \"Were fortune other, then it were bad for those who have trusted, for I come to my friend when he call me to aid those he holds dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60829,\n            \"He rushed up to me, saying in an eager whisper:-\\u201cJack, I was so anxious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60850,\n            \"I read between the lines of your letter, and have been in an agony.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61088,\n            \"\\u201d The Professor has a strongly humorous side, and I could from old knowledge detect a trace of its origin in his answer:-\\u201cMy young sir, I do not ask so much as that-not the last!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61728,\n            \"Van Helsing turning to me, said: \\u201cHe is so young and strong and of blood so pure that we need not defibrinate it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61807,\n            \"After a bit I began to grow anxious, for the loss of blood was telling on Arthur, strong man as he was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61832,\n            \"It gave me an idea of what a terrible strain Lucy\\u2019s system must have undergone that what weakened Arthur only partially restored her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61924,\n            \"\\u201d When all was over I could see how much Arthur was weakened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61938,\n            \"I dressed the wound and took his arm to bring him away, when Van Helsing spoke without turning round-the man seems to have eyes in the back of his head:-\\u201cThe brave lover, I think, deserve another kiss, which he shall have presently.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62059,\n            \"Arthur did not notice it, but I could hear the deep hiss of indrawn breath which is one of Van Helsing\\u2019s ways of betraying emotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62088,\n            \"He said nothing at the moment, but turned to me, saying: \\u201cNow take down our brave young lover, give him of the port wine, and let him lie down a while.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62166,\n            \"I may take it, sir, that you are anxious of result.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62246,\n            \"\\u201d When Arthur had gone I went back to the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63272,\n            \"I sent a short wire to Van Helsing and to Arthur, telling them of the excellent result of the operation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63755,\n            \"Somehow Arthur feels very, very close to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63765,\n            \"I seem to feel his presence warm about me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63775,\n            \"I suppose it is that sickness and weakness are selfish things and turn our inner eyes and sympathy on ourselves, whilst health and strength give Love rein, and in thought and feeling he can wander where he wills.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63871,\n            \"And to-night I shall not fear to sleep, since he is close at hand and within call.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72312,\n            \"I kept my eyes fixed on the window, but the wolf drew his head back, and a whole myriad of little specks seemed to come blowing in through the broken window, and wheeling and circling round like the pillar of dust that travellers describe when there is a simoon in the desert.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72974,\n            \"Good-bye, dear Arthur, if I should not survive this night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72989,\n            \"God keep you, dear, and God help me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74277,\n            \"I bade her simply tell him that he must wait, for we could see no one now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74296,\n            \"She went away with the message, and, engrossed with our work, I clean forgot all about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75710,\n            \"\\u201d In the hall I met Quincey Morris, with a telegram for Arthur telling him that Mrs. Westenra was dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76302,\n            \"Jack, if you may tell me without betraying confidence, Arthur was the first, is not that so?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79835,\n            \"It was only when I told him that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80695,\n            \"\\u201d I went to the dining-room and waked him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80739,\n            \"I assured him that Lucy was still asleep, but told him as gently as I could that both Van Helsing and I feared that the end was near.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81082,\n            \"In a sort of sleep-waking, vague, unconscious way she opened her eyes, which were now dull and hard at once, and said in a soft, voluptuous voice, such as I had never heard from her lips:-\\u201cArthur!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81156,\n            \"but at that instant Van Helsing, who, like me, had been startled by her voice, swooped upon him, and catching him by the neck with both hands, dragged him back with a fury of strength which I never thought he could have possessed, and actually hurled him almost across the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81546,\n            \"\\u201d I took Arthur by the arm, and led him away to the drawing-room, where he sat down, and covered his face with his hands, sobbing in a way that nearly broke me down to see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83248,\n            \"Were you not amazed, nay horrified, when I would not let Arthur kiss his love-though she was dying-and snatched him away by all my strength?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84562,\n            \"He had, I knew, been very genuinely and devotedly attached to his father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84596,\n            \"With me he was warm as ever, and to Van Helsing he was sweetly courteous;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84613,\n            \"but I could not help seeing that there was some constraint with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84627,\n            \"The Professor noticed it, too, and motioned me to bring him upstairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84642,\n            \"I did so, and left him at the door of the room, as I felt he would like to be quite alone with her, but he took my arm and led me in, saying huskily:-\\u201cYou loved her too, old fellow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84741,\n            \"\\u201d Here he suddenly broke down, and threw his arms round my shoulders and laid his head on my breast, crying:-\\u201cOh, Jack!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84804,\n            \"\\u201d I comforted him as well as I could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84856,\n            \"I stood still and silent till his sobs died away, and then I said softly to him:-\\u201cCome and look at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84946,\n            \"At last, after a long pause, he said to me in a faint whisper:-\\u201cJack, is she really dead?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84972,\n            \"\\u201d I assured him sadly that it was so, and went on to suggest-for I felt that such a horrible doubt should not have life for a moment longer than I could help-that it often happened that after death faces became softened and even resolved into their youthful beauty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85076,\n            \"I told him that that must be good-bye, as the coffin had to be prepared;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85134,\n            \"I left him in the drawing-room, and told Van Helsing that he had said good-bye;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85181,\n            \"When he came out of the room again I told him of Arthur\\u2019s question, and he replied:-\\u201cI am not surprised.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86056,\n            \"\\u201d I slept on a sofa in Arthur\\u2019s room that night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86154,\n            \"It seems only yesterday that the last entry was made, and yet how much between then, in Whitby and all the world before me, Jonathan away and no news of him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86227,\n            \"Some day he may ask me about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86520,\n            \"I was looking at a very beautiful girl, in a big cart-wheel hat, sitting in a victoria outside Guiliano\\u2019s, when I felt Jonathan clutch my arm so tight that he hurt me, and he said under his breath: \\u201cMy God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86571,\n            \"\\u201d I am always anxious about Jonathan, for I fear that some nervous fit may upset him again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86591,\n            \"so I turned to him quickly, and asked him what it was that disturbed him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86727,\n            \"Jonathan kept staring at him, till I was afraid he would notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86741,\n            \"I feared he might take it ill, he looked so fierce and nasty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86756,\n            \"I asked Jonathan why he was disturbed, and he answered, evidently thinking that I knew as much about it as he did: \\u201cDo you see who it is?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86789,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, dear,\\u201dI said;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86811,\n            \"\\u201d His answer seemed to shock and thrill me, for it was said as if he did not know that it was to me, Mina, to whom he was speaking:-\\u201cIt is the man himself!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86867,\n            \"I do believe that if he had not had me to lean on and to support him he would have sunk down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87002,\n            \"\\u201d He was distressing himself so much that I feared to keep his mind on the subject by asking him any questions, so I remained silent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87030,\n            \"I drew him away quietly, and he, holding my arm, came easily.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87085,\n            \"After a few minutes\\u2019 staring at nothing, Jonathan\\u2019s eyes closed, and he went quietly into a sleep, with his head on my shoulder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87115,\n            \"I thought it was the best thing for him, so did not disturb him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87131,\n            \"In about twenty minutes he woke up, and said to me quite cheerfully:-\\u201cWhy, Mina, have I been asleep!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87228,\n            \"I must not ask him, for fear I shall do more harm than good;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87277,\n            \"Oh, Jonathan, you will, I know, forgive me if I do wrong, but it is for your own dear sake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87751,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89971,\n            \"that terrible record of Jonathan\\u2019s upset me so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90035,\n            \"I suppose I shall never know, for I dare not open the subject to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90076,\n            \"I suppose it was the funeral upset him and sent his mind back on some train of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90104,\n            \"I remember how on our wedding-day he said: \\u201cUnless some solemn duty come upon me to go back to the bitter hours, asleep or awake, mad or sane.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90240,\n            \"then, perhaps, if I am ready, poor Jonathan may not be upset, for I can speak for him and never let him be troubled or worried with it at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90275,\n            \"If ever Jonathan quite gets over the nervousness he may want to tell me of it all, and I can ask him questions and find out things, and see how I may comfort him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90646,\n            \"- I cannot help feeling terribly excited as the time draws near for the visit of Dr. Van Helsing, for somehow I expect that it will throw some light upon Jonathan\\u2019s sad experience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90939,\n            \"Perhaps it was reading the journal yesterday that upset me, and then Jonathan went away this morning to stay away from me a whole day and night, the first time we have been parted since our marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90979,\n            \"I do hope the dear fellow will take care of himself, and that nothing will occur to upset him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91016,\n            \"I shall say nothing of Jonathan\\u2019s journal unless he asks me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91114,\n            \"If I had not read Jonathan\\u2019s journal first, I should never have accepted even a possibility.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91160,\n            \"I shall try to save him from it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91322,\n            \"When he comes to-morrow I shall ask him about Jonathan;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 16]\": [\n        [\n            45529,\n            \"At the edge of the West Cliff above the pier I looked across the harbour to the East Cliff, in the hope or fear-I don\\u2019t know which-of seeing Lucy in our favourite seat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45733,\n            \"but it seemed to me as though something dark stood behind the seat where the white figure shone, and bent over it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45825,\n            \"I rejoiced that it was so, for I wanted no witness of poor Lucy\\u2019s condition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45903,\n            \"When I got almost to the top I could see the seat and the white figure, for I was now close enough to distinguish it even through the spells of shadow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45954,\n            \"I called in fright, \\u201cLucy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45988,\n            \"Lucy did not answer, and I ran on to the entrance of the churchyard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46004,\n            \"As I entered, the church was between me and the seat, and for a minute or so I lost sight of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46029,\n            \"When I came in view again the cloud had passed, and the moonlight struck so brilliantly that I could see Lucy half reclining with her head lying over the back of the seat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46081,\n            \"When I bent over her I could see that she was still asleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46131,\n            \"As I came close, she put up her hand in her sleep and pulled the collar of her nightdress close around her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46175,\n            \"I flung the warm shawl over her, and drew the edges tight round her neck, for I dreaded lest she should get some deadly chill from the night air, unclad as she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46212,\n            \"I feared to wake her all at once, so, in order to have my hands free that I might help her, I fastened the shawl at her throat with a big safety-pin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46250,\n            \"but I must have been clumsy in my anxiety and pinched or pricked her with it, for by-and-by, when her breathing became quieter, she put her hand to her throat again and moaned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46291,\n            \"When I had her carefully wrapped up I put my shoes on her feet and then began very gently to wake her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46338,\n            \"At last, as time was passing fast, and, for many other reasons, I wished to get her home at once, I shook her more forcibly, till finally she opened her eyes and awoke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46378,\n            \"She did not seem surprised to see me, as, of course, she did not realise all at once where she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46446,\n            \"She trembled a little, and clung to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46456,\n            \"when I told her to come at once with me home she rose without a word, with the obedience of a child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46480,\n            \"As we passed along, the gravel hurt my feet, and Lucy noticed me wince.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46497,\n            \"She stopped and wanted to insist upon my taking my shoes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46664,\n            \"I was filled with anxiety about Lucy, not only for her health, lest she should suffer from the exposure, but for her reputation in case the story should get wind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46698,\n            \"When we got in, and had washed our feet, and had said a prayer of thankfulness together, I tucked her into bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46724,\n            \"Before falling asleep she asked-even implored-me not to say a word to any one, even her mother, about her sleep-walking adventure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46761,\n            \"but on thinking of the state of her mother\\u2019s health, and how the knowledge of such a thing would fret her, and thinking, too, of how such a story might become distorted-nay, infallibly would-in case it should leak out, I thought it wiser to do so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46881,\n            \"Lucy slept till I woke her and seemed not to have even changed her side.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46932,\n            \"I was sorry to notice that my clumsiness with the safety-pin hurt her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46965,\n            \"I must have pinched up a piece of loose skin and have transfixed it, for there are two little red points like pin-pricks, and on the band of her nightdress was a drop of blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47005,\n            \"When I apologised and was concerned about it, she laughed and petted me, and said she did not even feel it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47071,\n            \"We took our lunch to Mulgrave Woods, Mrs. Westenra driving by the road and Lucy and I walking by the cliff-path and joining her at the gate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47210,\n            \"- My expectations were wrong, for twice during the night I was wakened by Lucy trying to get out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47277,\n            \"Lucy woke, too, and, I was glad to see, was even better than on the previous morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47299,\n            \"All her old gaiety of manner seemed to have come back, and she came and snuggled in beside me and told me all about Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47326,\n            \"I told her how anxious I was about Jonathan, and then she tried to comfort me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47389,\n            \"Again I awoke in the night, and found Lucy sitting up in bed, still asleep, pointing to the window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47505,\n            \"When I came back from the window Lucy had lain down again, and was sleeping peacefully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47546,\n            \"Lucy seems to have become as much in love with the spot as I am, and it is hard to get her away from it when it is time to come home for lunch or tea or dinner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47718,\n            \"I slewed round a little, so as to see Lucy well without seeming to stare at her, and saw that she was in a half-dreamy state, with an odd look on her face that I could not quite make out;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47764,\n            \"so I said nothing, but followed her eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47869,\n            \"I called Lucy\\u2019s attention to the peculiar effect, and she became herself with a start, but she looked sad all the same;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47939,\n            \"I saw her asleep, and went out for a little stroll myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47976,\n            \"When coming home-it was then bright moonlight, so bright that, though the front of our part of the Crescent was in shadow, everything could be well seen-I threw a glance up at our window, and saw Lucy\\u2019s head leaning out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48027,\n            \"I thought that perhaps she was looking out for me, so I opened my handkerchief and waved it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48127,\n            \"I was afraid she might get a chill, so I ran upstairs, but as I came into the room she was moving back to her bed, fast asleep, and breathing heavily;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48180,\n            \"I did not wake her, but tucked her up warmly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48215,\n            \"but she is paler than is her wont, and there is a drawn, haggard look under her eyes which I do not like.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48241,\n            \"I fear she is fretting about something.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48381,\n            \"She has not told Lucy, and made me promise secrecy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48515,\n            \"I do not understand Lucy\\u2019s fading away as she is doing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48565,\n            \"at night I hear her gasping as if for air.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48576,\n            \"I keep the key of our door always fastened to my wrist at night, but she gets up and walks about the room, and sits at the open window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48608,\n            \"Last night I found her leaning out when I woke up, and when I tried to wake her I could not;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48637,\n            \"When I managed to restore her she was as weak as water, and cried silently between long, painful struggles for breath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48661,\n            \"When I asked her how she came to be at the window she shook her head and turned away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48681,\n            \"I trust her feeling ill may not be from that unlucky prick of the safety-pin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48699,\n            \"I looked at her throat just now as she lay asleep, and the tiny wounds seem not to have healed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49264,\n            \"Last night she slept well all night, and did not disturb me once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49300,\n            \"If she were in any way an\\u00e6mic I could understand it, but she is not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49329,\n            \"All the morbid reticence seems to have passed from her, and she has just reminded me, as if I needed any reminding, of that night, and that it was here, on this very seat, I found her asleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49374,\n            \"As she told me she tapped playfully with the heel of her boot on the stone slab and said:-\\u201cMy poor little feet didn\\u2019t make much noise then!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49433,\n            \"\\u201d As she was in such a communicative humour, I asked her if she had dreamed at all that night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49455,\n            \"Before she answered, that sweet, puckered look came into her forehead, which Arthur-I call him Arthur from her habit-says he loves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49725,\n            \"I seem to remember that once the West Lighthouse was right under me, and then there was a sort of agonising feeling, as if I were in an earthquake, and I came back and found you shaking my body.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49768,\n            \"I saw you do it before I felt you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49785,\n            \"It seemed a little uncanny to me, and I listened to her breathlessly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49800,\n            \"I did not quite like it, and thought it better not to keep her mind on the subject, so we drifted on to other subjects, and Lucy was like her old self again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50059,\n            \"Lucy will bring my trunk to London and keep it till I send for it, for it may be that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51203,\n            \"I cannot but think of Lucy, and how different things might have been.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51260,\n            \"I have thought of Lucy, and I shall not dishonour her by mixing the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52132,\n            \"CHAPTER IX Letter, Mina Harker to Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52150,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Lucy,-\\u201cI know you will be anxious to hear all that has happened since we parted at the railway station at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52179,\n            \"Well, my dear, I got to Hull all right, and caught the boat to Hamburg, and then the train on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52269,\n            \"All the resolution has gone out of his dear eyes, and that quiet dignity which I told you was in his face has vanished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53195,\n            \"I must tell you of my wedding present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53204,\n            \"When the chaplain and the sisters had left me alone with my husband-oh, Lucy, it is the first time I have written the words \\u2018 my husband\\u2019- left me alone with my husband, I took the book from under his pillow, and wrapped it up in white paper, and tied it with a little bit of pale blue ribbon which was round my neck, and sealed it over the knot with sealing-wax, and for my seal I used my wedding ring.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53364,\n            \"Then he took my hand in his, and oh, Lucy, it was the first time he took his wife\\u2019s hand, and said that it was the dearest thing in all the wide world, and that he would go through all the past again to win it, if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53463,\n            \"\\u201cWell, my dear, what could I say?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53526,\n            \"And, my dear, when he kissed me, and drew me to him with his poor weak hands, it was like a very solemn pledge between us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53560,\n            \"\\u201cLucy dear, do you know why I tell you all this?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53574,\n            \"It is not only because it is all sweet to me, but because you have been, and are, very dear to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53600,\n            \"It was my privilege to be your friend and guide when you came from the schoolroom to prepare for the world of life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53624,\n            \"I want you to see now, and with the eyes of a very happy wife, whither duty has led me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53647,\n            \"so that in your own married life you too may be all happy as I am.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53697,\n            \"I must not wish you no pain, for that can never be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53711,\n            \"but I do hope you will be always as happy as I am now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53733,\n            \"I shall post this at once, and, perhaps, write you very soon again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53818,\n            \"I wish you could be coming home soon enough to stay with us here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53864,\n            \"You will be glad to know that I have quite given up walking in my sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53913,\n            \"By the way, I forgot to tell you that Arthur is here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54222,\n            \"It was a strange thing that the patient had humour enough to see their distrust, for, coming close to me, he said in a whisper, all the while looking furtively at them:-\\u201cThey think I could hurt you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55374,\n            \"I have asked her if there is any cause;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55384,\n            \"I do not dare to ask her mother, for to disturb the poor lady\\u2019s mind about her daughter in her present state of health would be fatal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55415,\n            \"Mrs. Westenra has confided to me that her doom is spoken-disease of the heart-though poor Lucy does not know it yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55442,\n            \"I am sure that there is something preying on my dear girl\\u2019s mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55458,\n            \"I am almost distracted when I think of her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55468,\n            \"to look at her gives me a pang.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55477,\n            \"I told her I should ask you to see her, and though she demurred at first-I know why, old fellow-she finally consented.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55506,\n            \"It will be a painful task for you, I know, old friend, but it is for her sake, and I must not hesitate to ask, or you to act.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55598,\n            \"I am filled with anxiety, and want to consult with you alone as soon as I can after you have seen her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55688,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear old fellow,-\\u201cWith regard to Miss Westenra\\u2019s health I hasten to let you know at once that in my opinion there is not any functional disturbance or any malady that I know of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55746,\n            \"she is woefully different from what she was when I saw her last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55760,\n            \"Of course you must bear in mind that I did not have full opportunity of examination such as I should wish;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55800,\n            \"I had better tell you exactly what happened, leaving you to draw, in a measure, your own conclusions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55929,\n            \"Then Mrs. Westenra went to lie down, and Lucy was left with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56005,\n            \"When I saw that her high spirits had failed, I at once took advantage of her reaction to make a diagnosis.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56028,\n            \"She said to me very sweetly:-\\u201c\\u2018 I cannot tell you how I loathe talking about myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56049,\n            \"\\u2019 I reminded her that a doctor\\u2019s confidence was sacred, but that you were grievously anxious about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56071,\n            \"She caught on to my meaning at once, and settled that matter in a word.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56114,\n            \"\\u201cI could easily see that she is somewhat bloodless, but I could not see the usual an\\u00e6mic signs, and by a chance I was actually able to test the quality of her blood, for in opening a window which was stiff a cord gave way, and she cut her hand slightly with broken glass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56342,\n            \"but she assures me that of late the habit has not returned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56402,\n            \"I have asked him to come over, and as you told me that all things were to be at your charge, I have mentioned to him who you are and your relations to Miss Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56440,\n            \"This, my dear fellow, is in obedience to your wishes, for I am only too proud and happy to do anything I can for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56631,\n            \"I tell you these facts that you may know why I have such confidence in him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56738,\n            \"\\u201cMy good Friend,-\\u201cWhen I have received your letter I am already coming to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56810,\n            \"Tell your friend that when that time you suck from my wound so swiftly the poison of the gangrene from that knife that our other friend, too nervous, let slip, you did more for him when he wants my aids and you call for them than all his great fortune could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56879,\n            \"it is to you that I come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57004,\n            \"He came on with me to Hillingham, and found that, by Lucy\\u2019s discretion, her mother was lunching out, so that we were alone with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57047,\n            \"He is to report to me, and I shall advise you, for of course I was not present all the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57086,\n            \"When I told him of our friendship and how you trust to me in the matter, he said: \\u2018 You must tell him all you think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57201,\n            \"You must not be angry with me, Art, because his very reticence means that all his brains are working for her good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57332,\n            \"Lucy was more cheerful than on the day I first saw her, and certainly looked better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57392,\n            \"though I could see that the poor girl was making a hard struggle for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57433,\n            \"Then he began to chat of all things except ourselves and diseases and with such an infinite geniality that I could see poor Lucy\\u2019s pretense of animation merge into reality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57552,\n            \"\\u201d\\u2019And he snapped his fingers at me and went on: \\u2018 But you and I shall show them how wrong they are.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57826,\n            \"I have asked her to send me her maid, that I may ask just one or two question, that so I may not chance to miss nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57950,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cAs I tell you, he would not say a word more, even when we were alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58029,\n            \"I know your idea of duty to your father, and you are right to stick to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58048,\n            \"but, if need be, I shall send you word to come at once to Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58066,\n            \"so do not be over-anxious unless you hear from me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59234,\n            \"I hold over telegram to Holmwood till have seen you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59303,\n            \"Mrs. Westenra was naturally anxious concerning Lucy, and has consulted me professionally about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsing, the great specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly with myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59429,\n            \"If any need I shall write, so that, if you do not hear from me, take it for granted that I am simply waiting for news.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59479,\n            \"- The first thing Van Helsing said to me when we met at Liverpool Street was:-\\u201cHave you said anything to our young friend the lover of her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59519,\n            \"\\u201cI waited till I had seen you, as I said in my telegram.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59535,\n            \"I wrote him a letter simply telling him that you were coming, as Miss Westenra was not so well, and that I should let him know if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59611,\n            \"And, my good friend John, let me caution you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59789,\n            \"\\u201d He stopped and looked at me, and said:-\\u201cMy friend John, when the corn is grown, even before it has ripened-while the milk of its mother-earth is in him, and the sunshine has not yet begun to paint him with his gold, the husbandman he pull the ear and rub him between his rough hands, and blow away the green chaff, and say to you: \\u2018 Look!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59994,\n            \"See you now, friend John?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60234,\n            \"\\u201d When I described Lucy\\u2019s symptoms-the same as before, but infinitely more marked-he looked very grave, but said nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60475,\n            \"I used my knowledge of this phase of spiritual pathology, and laid down a rule that she should not be present with Lucy or think of her illness more than was absolutely required.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60528,\n            \"Van Helsing and I were shown up to Lucy\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60541,\n            \"If I was shocked when I saw her yesterday, I was horrified when I saw her to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61832,\n            \"It gave me an idea of what a terrible strain Lucy\\u2019s system must have undergone that what weakened Arthur only partially restored her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62269,\n            \"I could see the counterpane move as her breast heaved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62301,\n            \"I asked the Professor in a whisper:-\\u201cWhat do you make of that mark on her throat?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62712,\n            \"- I sat up all night with Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62748,\n            \"Her spirits even were good, and she was full of a happy vivacity, but I could see evidences of the absolute prostration which she had undergone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62777,\n            \"When I told Mrs. Westenra that Dr. Van Helsing had directed that I should sit up with her she almost pooh-poohed the idea, pointing out her daughter\\u2019s renewed strength and excellent spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62831,\n            \"When her maid had prepared her for the night I came in, having in the meantime had supper, and took a seat by the bedside.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62859,\n            \"She did not in any way make objection, but looked at me gratefully whenever I caught her eye.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62923,\n            \"It was apparent that she did not want to sleep, so I tackled the subject at once:-\\u201cYou do not want to go to sleep?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62981,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAh, not if you were like me-if sleep was to you a presage of horror!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63095,\n            \"\\u201d I seized the opportunity, and said: \\u201cI promise you that if I see any evidence of bad dreams I will wake you at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63167,\n            \"All night long I watched by her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63447,\n            \"When she shook hands with me she looked sharply in my face and said:-\\u201cNo sitting up to-night for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63524,\n            \"Lucy came with me, and, enlivened by her charming presence, I made an excellent meal, and had a couple of glasses of the more than excellent port.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63556,\n            \"Then Lucy took me upstairs, and showed me a room next her own, where a cozy fire was burning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63676,\n            \"So, on her renewing her promise to call me if she should want anything, I lay on the sofa, and forgot all about everything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63828,\n            \"My dear, my dear, your ears must tingle as you sleep, as mine do waking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64888,\n            \"I fell asleep on the sofa, however, wondering over and over again how Lucy had made such a retrograde movement, and how she could have been drained of so much blood with no sign anywhere to show for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64931,\n            \"I think I must have continued my wonder in my dreams, for, sleeping and waking, my thoughts always came back to the little punctures in her throat and the ragged, exhausted appearance of their edges-tiny though they were.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65005,\n            \"When Van Helsing had seen her, he went out for a walk, leaving me in charge, with strict injunctions that I was not to leave her for a moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65056,\n            \"Lucy chatted with me freely, and seemed quite unconscious that anything had happened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65071,\n            \"I tried to keep her amused and interested.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65080,\n            \"When her mother came up to see her, she did not seem to notice any change whatever, but said to me gratefully:-\\u201cWe owe you so much, Dr. Seward, for all you have done, but you really must now take care not to overwork yourself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65191,\n            \"The reaction came in excessive pallor as she turned imploring eyes on me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65407,\n            \"Perhaps it is because I am weak at present, and perhaps because it was on Lucy\\u2019s account, that their devotion was manifested;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67108,\n            \"I feared that the heavy odour would be too much for the dear child in her weak state, so I took them all away and opened a bit of the window to let in a little fresh air.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67148,\n            \"You will be pleased with her, I am sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67173,\n            \"As she had spoken, I watched the Professor\\u2019s face, and saw it turn ashen grey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67242,\n            \"But the instant she had disappeared he pulled me, suddenly and forcibly, into the dining-room and closed the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70191,\n            \"\\u201cYe\\u2019ll excoose me, I know, for a-chaffin\\u2019of ye, but the old woman here winked at me, which was as much as telling me to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70706,\n            \"After all, however, there is nothing like custom, for neither Bilder nor his wife thought any more of the wolf than I should of a dog.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71015,\n            \"- I was engaged after dinner in my study posting up my books, which, through press of other work and the many visits to Lucy, had fallen sadly into arrear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71334,\n            \"I have lost too much of late for my physical good, and then the prolonged strain of Lucy\\u2019s illness and its horrible phases is telling on me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71583,\n            \"I shall take this cylinder with me, and then I can complete my entry on Lucy\\u2019s phonograph.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71706,\n            \"I was waked by the flapping at the window, which had begun after that sleep-walking on the cliff at Whitby when Mina saved me, and which now I know so well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71851,\n            \"I was afraid to wake mother, and so closed my door again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71962,\n            \"She said to me even more sweetly and softly than her wont:-\\u201cI was uneasy about you, darling, and came in to see that you were all right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71996,\n            \"\\u201d I feared she might catch cold sitting there, and asked her to come in and sleep with me, so she came into bed, and lay down beside me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72056,\n            \"As she lay there in my arms, and I in hers, the flapping and buffeting came to the window again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72096,\n            \"\\u201d I tried to pacify her, and at last succeeded, and she lay quiet;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72113,\n            \"but I could hear her poor dear heart still beating terribly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72219,\n            \"Amongst other things, she clutched the wreath of flowers that Dr. Van Helsing insisted on my wearing round my neck, and tore it away from me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72275,\n            \"then she fell over-as if struck with lightning, and her head hit my forehead and made me dizzy for a moment or two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72368,\n            \"I tried to stir, but there was some spell upon me, and dear mother\\u2019s poor body, which seemed to grow cold already-for her dear heart had ceased to beat-weighed me down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72469,\n            \"I was dazed and stupid with pain and terror and weakness, but the sound of the nightingale seemed like the voice of my dead mother come back to comfort me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72573,\n            \"They lifted off the body of my dear mother, and laid her, covered up with a sheet, on the bed after I had got up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72655,\n            \"and I laid what flowers I had on my dear mother\\u2019s breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72798,\n            \"It smelt of laudanum, and looking on the sideboard, I found that the bottle which mother\\u2019s doctor uses for her-oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72843,\n            \"I am back in the room with mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72852,\n            \"I cannot leave her, and I am alone, save for the sleeping servants, whom some one has drugged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73036,\n            \"I knocked gently and rang as quietly as possible, for I feared to disturb Lucy or her mother, and hoped to only bring a servant to the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73179,\n            \"I knew that minutes, even seconds of delay, might mean hours of danger to Lucy, if she had had again one of those frightful relapses;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74473,\n            \"Van Helsing\\u2019s face almost beamed, and as we lifted her from the bath and rolled her in a hot sheet to dry her he said to me:-\\u201cThe first gain is ours!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75340,\n            \"He handed me the paper saying only: \\u201cIt dropped from Lucy\\u2019s breast when we carried her to the bath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76975,\n            \"The Professor and I took it in turns to watch, and we never left her for a moment unattended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77340,\n            \"I am to relieve them in a quarter of an hour, and I am entering this on Lucy\\u2019s phonograph.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77423,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Lucy,-\\u201cIt seems an age since I heard from you, or indeed since I wrote.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77446,\n            \"You will pardon me, I know, for all my faults when you have read all my budget of news.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77717,\n            \"I am busy, I need not tell you, arranging things and housekeeping.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77772,\n            \"I wish I could run up to town for a day or two to see you, dear, but I dare not go yet, with so much on my shoulders;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77890,\n            \"And now I have told you my news, let me ask yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77941,\n            \"Tell me all about it, dear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77949,\n            \"tell me all about everything, for there is nothing which interests you which will not be dear to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78002,\n            \"and so, as you love me, and he loves me, and I love you with all the moods and tenses of the verb, I send you simply his \\u2018 love\\u2019instead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79079,\n            \"I quite understood their drift, and after a stiff glass of grog, or rather more of the same, and with each a sovereign in hand, they made light of the attack, and swore that they would encounter a worse madman any day for the pleasure of meeting so \\u2018 bloomin\\u2019good a bloke\\u2019as your correspondent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80319,\n            \"Presently she woke, and I gave her food, as Van Helsing had prescribed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80369,\n            \"It struck me as curious that the moment she became conscious she pressed the garlic flowers close to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81699,\n            \"\\u201d I stood beside Van Helsing, and said:-\\u201cAh, well, poor girl, there is peace for her at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82588,\n            \"All Lucy\\u2019s loveliness had come back to her in death, and the hours that had passed, instead of leaving traces of \\u201cdecay\\u2019s effacing fingers,\\u201dhad but restored the beauty of life, till positively I could not believe my eyes that I was looking at a corpse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82651,\n            \"He had not loved her as I had, and there was no need for tears in his eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83541,\n            \"As I stood without moving, I saw one of the maids pass silently along the passage-she had her back towards me, so did not see me-and go into the room where Lucy lay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86657,\n            \"He was looking at her so hard that he did not see either of us, and so I had a good view of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87342,\n            \"and now a telegram from Van Helsing, whoever he may be:-\\u201cYou will be grieved to hear that Mrs. Westenra died five days ago, and that Lucy died the day before yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87483,\n            \"I believe in my heart of hearts that he suffered as much about Lucy\\u2019s death as any of us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88069,\n            \"\\u2019 Behold, in example I grieve my heart out for that so sweet young girl;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88086,\n            \"I give my blood for her, though I am old and worn;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88111,\n            \"I let my other sufferers want that so she may have all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88124,\n            \"And yet I can laugh at her very grave-laugh when the clay from the spade of the sexton drop upon her coffin and say \\u2018 Thud!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88530,\n            \"As he answered me his face grew stern, and he said in quite a different tone:-\\u201cOh, it was the grim irony of it all-this so lovely lady garlanded with flowers, that looked so fair as life, till one by one we wondered if she were truly dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90325,\n            \"(Confidence) \\u201cDear Madam,-\\u201cI pray you to pardon my writing, in that I am so far friend as that I sent to you sad news of Miss Lucy Westenra\\u2019s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90365,\n            \"By the kindness of Lord Godalming, I am empowered to read her letters and papers, for I am deeply concerned about certain matters vitally important.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90393,\n            \"In them I find some letters from you, which show how great friends you were and how you love her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90415,\n            \"Oh, Madam Mina, by that love, I implore you, help me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90431,\n            \"It is for others\\u2019 good that I ask-to redress great wrong, and to lift much and terrible troubles-that may be more great than you can know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90464,\n            \"May it be that I see you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90472,\n            \"You can trust me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90477,\n            \"I am friend of Dr. John Seward and of Lord Godalming (that was Arthur of Miss Lucy).\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90509,\n            \"I should come to Exeter to see you at once if you tell me I am privilege to come, and where and when.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90534,\n            \"I implore your pardon, madam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90541,\n            \"I have read your letters to poor Lucy, and know how good you are and how your husband suffer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90562,\n            \"so I pray you, if it may be, enlighten him not, lest it may harm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90581,\n            \"Again your pardon, and forgive me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90684,\n            \"and as he attended poor dear Lucy in her last illness, he can tell me all about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90860,\n            \"I should never forgive myself if any act of mine, were it even a negative one, brought harm on poor dear Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91030,\n            \"I am so glad I have type-written out my own journal, so that, in case he asks about Lucy, I can hand it to him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91773,\n            \"He took it and said tenderly:-\\u201cOh, Madam Mina, I knew that the friend of that poor lily girl must be good, but I had yet to learn--\\u201dHe finished his speech with a courtly bow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91819,\n            \"I asked him what it was that he wanted to see me about, so he at once began:-\\u201cI have read your letters to Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91869,\n            \"I know that you were with her at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91879,\n            \"She sometimes kept a diary-you need not look surprised, Madam Mina;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91894,\n            \"it was begun after you had left, and was in imitation of you-and in that diary she traces by inference certain things to a sleep-walking in which she puts down that you saved her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92254,\n            \"but I had been thinking that it was of dear Lucy that you wished to ask, and so that you might not have time to wait-not on my account, but because I know your time must be precious-I have written it out on the typewriter for you.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 17]\": [\n        [\n            47103,\n            \"I felt a little sad myself, for I could not but feel how absolutely happy it would have been had Jonathan been with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47299,\n            \"All her old gaiety of manner seemed to have come back, and she came and snuggled in beside me and told me all about Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47326,\n            \"I told her how anxious I was about Jonathan, and then she tried to comfort me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47953,\n            \"I walked along the cliffs to the westward, and was full of sweet sadness, for I was thinking of Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49455,\n            \"Before she answered, that sweet, puckered look came into her forehead, which Arthur-I call him Arthur from her habit-says he loves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49484,\n            \"and, indeed, I don\\u2019t wonder that he does.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49947,\n            \"I am to leave in the morning and go over to Jonathan, and to help to nurse him if necessary, and to bring him home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50019,\n            \"It is of Jonathan, and must be next my heart, for he is in my heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50089,\n            \"I must keep it to say to Jonathan, my husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50101,\n            \"The letter that he has seen and touched must comfort me till we meet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50203,\n            \"He wishes me to convey his love, and to say that by this post I write for him to Mr. Peter Hawkins, Exeter, to say, with his dutiful respects, that he is sorry for his delay, and that all of his work is completed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50275,\n            \"He wishes me to say that he has not sufficient money with him, and that he would like to pay for his staying here, so that others who need shall not be wanting for help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50335,\n            \"- My patient being asleep, I open this to let you know something more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50351,\n            \"He has told me all about you, and that you are shortly to be his wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50562,\n            \"He is truly getting on well, and I have no doubt will in a few weeks be all himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50660,\n            \"The attendant was struck by his manner, and knowing my interest in him, encouraged him to talk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50692,\n            \"but to-night, the man tells me, he was quite haughty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50797,\n            \"At nine o\\u2019clock I visited him myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50807,\n            \"His attitude to me was the same as that to the attendant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50820,\n            \"in his sublime self-feeling the difference between myself and attendant seemed to him as nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50927,\n            \"I did not pretend to be watching him, but I kept strict observation all the same.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51014,\n            \"I thought I would find out if his apathy were real or only assumed, and tried to lead him to talk of his pets, a theme which had never failed to excite his attention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51088,\n            \"\\u201cYou don\\u2019t mean to tell me you don\\u2019t care about spiders?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51170,\n            \"\\u201d He would not explain himself, but remained obstinately seated on his bed all the time I remained with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51307,\n            \"I had lain tossing about, and had heard the clock strike only twice, when the night-watchman came to me, sent up from the ward, to say that Renfield had escaped.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51429,\n            \"He ran back and saw his feet disappear through the window, and had at once sent up for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51549,\n            \"The attendant told me the patient had gone to the left, and had taken a straight line, so I ran as quickly as I could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51605,\n            \"I ran back at once, told the watchman to get three or four men immediately and follow me into the grounds of Carfax, in case our friend might be dangerous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51656,\n            \"I could see Renfield\\u2019s figure just disappearing behind the angle of the house, so I ran after him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51678,\n            \"On the far side of the house I found him pressed close against the old ironbound oak door of the chapel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51700,\n            \"He was talking, apparently to some one, but I was afraid to go near enough to hear what he was saying, lest I might frighten him, and he should run off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51759,\n            \"After a few minutes, however, I could see that he did not take note of anything around him, and so ventured to draw nearer to him-the more so as my men had now crossed the wall and were closing him in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51806,\n            \"I heard him say:-\\u201cI am here to do Your bidding, Master.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52205,\n            \"I feel that I can hardly recall anything of the journey, except that I knew I was coming to Jonathan, and, that as I should have to do some nursing, I had better get all the sleep I could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52269,\n            \"All the resolution has gone out of his dear eyes, and that quiet dignity which I told you was in his face has vanished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52320,\n            \"At least, he wants me to believe so, and I shall never ask.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52336,\n            \"He has had some terrible shock, and I fear it might tax his poor brain if he were to try to recall it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52361,\n            \"Sister Agatha, who is a good creature and a born nurse, tells me that he raved of dreadful things whilst he was off his head.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52443,\n            \"She is a sweet, good soul, and the next day, when she saw I was troubled, she opened up the subject again, and after saying that she could never mention what my poor dear raved about, added: \\u2018 I can tell you this much, my dear: that it was not about anything which he has done wrong himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52581,\n            \"The idea of my being jealous about Jonathan!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52621,\n            \"I am now sitting by his bedside, where I can see his face while he sleeps.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52646,\n            \"\\u201cWhen he woke he asked me for his coat, as he wanted to get something from the pocket;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52667,\n            \"I asked Sister Agatha, and she brought all his things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52679,\n            \"I saw that amongst them was his note-book, and was going to ask him to let me look at it-for I knew then that I might find some clue to his trouble-but I suppose he must have seen my wish in my eyes, for he sent me over to the window, saying he wanted to be quite alone for a moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52750,\n            \"Then he called me back, and when I came he had his hand over the note-book, and he said to me very solemnly:-\\u201c\\u2018 Wilhelmina\\u2019- I knew then that he was in deadly earnest, for he has never called me by that name since he asked me to marry him-\\u2018 you know, dear, my ideas of the trust between husband and wife: there should be no secret, no concealment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52836,\n            \"I have had a great shock, and when I try to think of what it is I feel my head spin round, and I do not know if it was all real or the dreaming of a madman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52877,\n            \"You know I have had brain fever, and that is to be mad.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52939,\n            \"\\u2018 Are you willing, Wilhelmina, to share my ignorance?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53004,\n            \"\\u2019 He fell back exhausted, and I put the book under his pillow, and kissed him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53204,\n            \"When the chaplain and the sisters had left me alone with my husband-oh, Lucy, it is the first time I have written the words \\u2018 my husband\\u2019- left me alone with my husband, I took the book from under his pillow, and wrapped it up in white paper, and tied it with a little bit of pale blue ribbon which was round my neck, and sealed it over the knot with sealing-wax, and for my seal I used my wedding ring.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53299,\n            \"Then I kissed it and showed it to my husband, and told him that I would keep it so, and then it would be an outward and visible sign for us all our lives that we trusted each other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53341,\n            \"that I would never open it unless it were for his own dear sake or for the sake of some stern duty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53364,\n            \"Then he took my hand in his, and oh, Lucy, it was the first time he took his wife\\u2019s hand, and said that it was the dearest thing in all the wide world, and that he would go through all the past again to win it, if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53422,\n            \"The poor dear meant to have said a part of the past, but he cannot think of time yet, and I shall not wonder if at first he mixes up not only the month, but the year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53474,\n            \"I could only tell him that I was the happiest woman in all the wide world, and that I had nothing to give him except myself, my life, and my trust, and that with these went my love and duty for all the days of my life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53526,\n            \"And, my dear, when he kissed me, and drew me to him with his poor weak hands, it was like a very solemn pledge between us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53750,\n            \"I must stop, for Jonathan is waking-I must attend to my husband!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54128,\n            \"\\u201d The attendant came to tell me, so I ran down at once to have a look at him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54149,\n            \"He was still in the strait-waistcoat and in the padded room, but the suffused look had gone from his face, and his eyes had something of their old pleading-I might almost say, \\u201ccringing \\\"-softness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54194,\n            \"I was satisfied with his present condition, and directed him to be relieved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54222,\n            \"It was a strange thing that the patient had humour enough to see their distrust, for, coming close to me, he said in a whisper, all the while looking furtively at them:-\\u201cThey think I could hurt you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54276,\n            \"\\u201d It was soothing, somehow, to the feelings to find myself dissociated even in the mind of this poor madman from the others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54302,\n            \"but all the same I do not follow his thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54313,\n            \"Am I to take it that I have anything in common with him, so that we are, as it were, to stand together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54340,\n            \"or has he to gain from me some good so stupendous that my well-being is needful to him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54427,\n            \"\\u201d After a while I left him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54435,\n            \"The attendant tells me that he was quiet until just before dawn, and that then he began to get uneasy, and at length violent, until at last he fell into a paroxysm which exhausted him so that he swooned into a sort of coma.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54659,\n            \"I have given orders to the night attendant merely to shut him in the padded room, when once he is quiet, until an hour before sunrise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54791,\n            \"When he saw me he became furious, and had not the attendants seized him in time, he would have tried to kill me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54850,\n            \"Then I caught the patient\\u2019s eye and followed it, but could trace nothing as it looked into the moonlit sky except a big bat, which was flapping its silent and ghostly way to the west.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54958,\n            \"I feel there is something ominous in his calm, and shall not forget this night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56810,\n            \"Tell your friend that when that time you suck from my wound so swiftly the poison of the gangrene from that knife that our other friend, too nervous, let slip, you did more for him when he wants my aids and you call for them than all his great fortune could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58208,\n            \"The attendant tells me that his screams whilst in the paroxysm were really appalling;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58223,\n            \"I found my hands full when I got in, attending to some of the other patients who were frightened by him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58332,\n            \"At five o\\u2019clock I looked in on him, and found him seemingly as happy and contented as he used to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58389,\n            \"When he saw me, he came over and apologised for his bad conduct, and asked me in a very humble, cringing way to be led back to his own room and to have his note-book again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58431,\n            \"I thought it well to humour him: so he is back in his room with the window open.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58507,\n            \"I tried to get him to talk about the past few days, for any clue to his thoughts would be of immense help to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58540,\n            \"For a moment or two he looked very sad, and said in a sort of far-away voice, as though saying it rather to himself than to me:-\\u201cAll over!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58585,\n            \"No hope for me now unless I do it for myself!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58597,\n            \"\\u201d Then suddenly turning to me in a resolute way, he said: \\u201cDoctor, won\\u2019t you be very good to me and let me have a little more sugar?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58690,\n            \"I procured him a double supply, and left him as happy a man as, I suppose, any in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58714,\n            \"I wish I could fathom his mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58730,\n            \"I had been to see Miss Westenra, whom I found much better, and had just returned, and was standing at our own gate looking at the sunset, when once more I heard him yelling.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58769,\n            \"As his room is on this side of the house, I could hear it better than in the morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58863,\n            \"I reached him just as the sun was going down, and from his window saw the red disc sink.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58944,\n            \"I signalled to the attendants not to hold him, for I was anxious to see what he would do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59015,\n            \"All this surprised me, so I asked him: \\u201cAre you not going to keep flies any more?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59062,\n            \"I wish I could get some glimpse of his mind or of the cause of his sudden passion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69846,\n            \"At least, so he says, but I don\\u2019t give much for it myself, for if he did\\u2019e never said a word about it to his missis when\\u2019e got\\u2019ome, and it was only after the escape of the wolf was made known, and we had been up all night-a-huntin\\u2019of the Park for Bersicker, that he remembered seein\\u2019anything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69925,\n            \"My own belief was that the\\u2019armony\\u2019ad got into his\\u2019 ead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70107,\n            \"I couldn\\u2019t cope in badinage with the worthy Thomas, but I thought I knew a surer way to his heart, so I said:-\\u201cNow, Mr. Bilder, we\\u2019ll consider that first half-sovereign worked off, and this brother of his is waiting to be claimed when you\\u2019ve told me what you think will happen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70486,\n            \"My eye, won\\u2019t some cook get a rum start when she sees his green eyes a-shining at her out of the dark!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70546,\n            \"If he doesn\\u2019t, and some nursemaid goes a-walkin\\u2019orf with a soldier, leavin\\u2019of the hinfant in the perambulator-well, then I shouldn\\u2019t be surprised if the census is one babby the less.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71049,\n            \"Suddenly the door was burst open, and in rushed my patient, with his face distorted with passion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71069,\n            \"I was thunderstruck, for such a thing as a patient getting of his own accord into the Superintendent\\u2019s study is almost unknown.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71095,\n            \"Without an instant\\u2019s pause he made straight at me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71107,\n            \"He had a dinner-knife in his hand, and, as I saw he was dangerous, I tried to keep the table between us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71135,\n            \"He was too quick and too strong for me, however;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71147,\n            \"for before I could get my balance he had struck at me and cut my left wrist rather severely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71167,\n            \"Before he could strike again, however, I got in my right and he was sprawling on his back on the floor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71207,\n            \"I saw that my friend was not intent on further effort, and occupied myself binding up my wrist, keeping a wary eye on the prostrate figure all the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71239,\n            \"When the attendants rushed in, and we turned our attention to him, his employment positively sickened me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71259,\n            \"He was lying on his belly on the floor licking up, like a dog, the blood which had fallen from my wounded wrist.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71285,\n            \"He was easily secured, and, to my surprise, went with the attendants quite placidly, simply repeating over and over again: \\u201cThe blood is the life!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77616,\n            \"\\u2019 I cried, Lucy dear, as Jonathan and the old man clasped hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77834,\n            \"even now he sometimes starts out of his sleep in a sudden way and awakes all trembling until I can coax him back to his usual placidity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77970,\n            \"Jonathan asks me to send his \\u2018 respectful duty,\\u2019but I do not think that is good enough from the junior partner of the important firm Hawkins & Harker;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78002,\n            \"and so, as you love me, and he loves me, and I love you with all the moods and tenses of the verb, I send you simply his \\u2018 love\\u2019instead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78353,\n            \"I opened the window and signed to the man not to notice, so he contented himself after looking the place over and making up his mind as to what kind of a place he had got to by saying: \\u2018 Lor\\u2019bless yer, sir, I wouldn\\u2019t mind what was said to me in a bloomin\\u2019madhouse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78418,\n            \"I pity ye and the guv\\u2019nor for havin\\u2019to live in the house with a wild beast like that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78441,\n            \"\\u2019 Then he asked his way civilly enough, and I told him where the gate of the empty house was;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78478,\n            \"I went down to see if I could make out any cause for his anger, since he is usually such a well-behaved man, and except his violent fits nothing of the kind had ever occurred.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78518,\n            \"I found him, to my astonishment, quite composed and most genial in his manner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78535,\n            \"I tried to get him to talk of the incident, but he blandly asked me questions as to what I meant, and led me to believe that he was completely oblivious of the affair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78572,\n            \"It was, I am sorry to say, however, only another instance of his cunning, for within half an hour I heard of him again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78621,\n            \"I called to the attendants to follow me, and ran after him, for I feared he was intent on some mischief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78692,\n            \"Before I could get up to him the patient rushed at them, and pulling one of them off the cart, began to knock his head against the ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78723,\n            \"If I had not seized him just at the moment I believe he would have killed the man there and then.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79335,\n            \"I never knew either father or mother, so that the dear old man\\u2019s death is a real blow to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79452,\n            \"I try to cheer him up, and my belief in him helps him to have a belief in himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79569,\n            \"but, Lucy dear, I must tell some one, for the strain of keeping up a brave and cheerful appearance to Jonathan tries me, and I have no one here that I can confide in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88170,\n            \"My heart bleed for that poor boy-that dear boy, so of the age of mine own boy had I been so blessed that he live, and with his hair and eyes the same.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88208,\n            \"There, you know now why I love him so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88219,\n            \"And yet when he say things that touch my husband-heart to the quick, and make my father-heart yearn to him as to no other man-not even to you, friend John, for we are more level in experiences than father and son-yet even at such moment King Laugh he come to me and shout and bellow in my ear, \\u2018 Here I am!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90541,\n            \"I have read your letters to poor Lucy, and know how good you are and how your husband suffer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90562,\n            \"so I pray you, if it may be, enlighten him not, lest it may harm.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 11]\": [\n        [\n            136340,\n            \"\\u201d He smiled on me in quite a superior sort of way-such a smile as would have become the face of Malvolio-as he answered me:-\\u201cThe fly, my dear sir, has one striking feature;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138061,\n            \"\\u201cWhy do you plague me about souls?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138114,\n            \"The instant, however, that I did so he became calm, and said apologetically:-\\u201cForgive me, Doctor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138164,\n            \"If you only knew the problem I have to face, and that I am working out, you would pity, and tolerate, and pardon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138219,\n            \"I am sure you will understand!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138255,\n            \"when the door was closed he said, with considerable dignity and sweetness:-\\u201cDr. Seward, you have been very considerate towards me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138283,\n            \"Believe me that I am very, very grateful to you!\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 16]\": [\n        [\n            129361,\n            \"He said to Madam Mina, as I see in your diary of yesterday, that he had once had such a belief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129843,\n            \"Friend John, it does rejoice me unspeakable that she is no more to be pained, no more to be worried with our terrible things.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 17]\": [\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 11]\": [\n        [\n            15525,\n            \"When he had satisfied himself on these points of which he had spoken, and I had verified all as well as I could by the books available, he suddenly stood up and said:-\\u201cHave you written since your first letter to our friend Mr. Peter Hawkins, or to any other?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15615,\n            \"\\u201cThen write now, my young friend,\\u201dhe said, laying a heavy hand on my shoulder: \\u201cwrite to our friend and to any other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15990,\n            \"So I determined to write only formal notes now, but to write fully to Mr. Hawkins in secret, and also to Mina, for to her I could write in shorthand, which would puzzle the Count, if he did see it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20920,\n            \"\\\"-he must have looked at it-\\\" one is from you, and to my friend Peter Hawkins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21023,\n            \"Then he went on:-\\u201cThe letter to Hawkins-that I shall, of course, send on, since it is yours.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 16]\": [\n        [\n            20701,\n            \"Mina\\u2019s is in shorthand, and I simply ask Mr. Hawkins to communicate with her.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 17]\": [\n        [\n            36801,\n            \"- Another week gone, and no news from Jonathan, not even to Mr. Hawkins, from whom I have heard.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 12]\": [\n        [\n            125626,\n            \"Then Mr. Morris said to Dr. Seward:-\\u201cSay, Jack, if that man wasn\\u2019t attempting a bluff, he is about the sanest lunatic I ever saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125662,\n            \"I\\u2019m not sure, but I believe that he had some serious purpose, and if he had, it was pretty rough on him not to get a chance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140363,\n            \"\\u201d I told him briefly, and added that we expected he would recover consciousness after the operation-for a short time, at all events.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141037,\n            \"I dreamed \\\"-he stopped and seemed fainting, I called quietly to Quincey-\\\" The brandy-it is in my study-quick!\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 14]\": [\n        [\n            145050,\n            \"I looked into Renfield\\u2019s room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147235,\n            \"\\u201d after that there was a sound of falling, and when he entered the room he found him lying on the floor, face down, just as the doctors had seen him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147324,\n            \"He could swear to it, if required, that the word \\u201cGod\\u201dwas spoken by the patient.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 15]\": [\n        [\n            19401,\n            \"In a voice which, though low and almost in a whisper seemed to cut through the air and then ring round the room he said:-\\u201cHow dare you touch him, any of you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19440,\n            \"How dare you cast eyes on him when I had forbidden it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19460,\n            \"This man belongs to me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19466,\n            \"Beware how you meddle with him, or you\\u2019ll have to deal with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19591,\n            \"Well, now I promise you that when I am done with him you shall kiss him at your will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19617,\n            \"I must awaken him, for there is work to be done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24031,\n            \"I thought he might have the keys on him, but when I went to search I saw the dead eyes, and in them, dead though they were, such a look of hate, though unconscious of me or my presence, that I fled from the place, and leaving the Count\\u2019s room by the window, crawled again up the castle wall.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 16]\": [\n        [\n            19221,\n            \"As my eyes opened involuntarily I saw his strong hand grasp the slender neck of the fair woman and with giant\\u2019s power draw it back, the blue eyes transformed with fury, the white teeth champing with rage, and the fair cheeks blazing red with passion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19356,\n            \"With a fierce sweep of his arm, he hurled the woman from him, and then motioned to the others, as though he were beating them back;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19483,\n            \"\\u201d The fair girl, with a laugh of ribald coquetry, turned to answer him:-\\u201cYou yourself never loved;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19641,\n            \"\\u201d said one of them, with a low laugh, as she pointed to the bag which he had thrown upon the floor, and which moved as though there were some living thing within it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20338,\n            \"I saw in his eyes something of that gathering wrath which was manifest when he hurled that fair woman from him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30833,\n            \"Won\\u2019t you let this be at my camp-fire to-morrow night?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30850,\n            \"I have no hesitation in asking you, as I know a certain lady is engaged to a certain dinner-party, and that you are free.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 14]\": [\n        [\n            140391,\n            \"He went at once and sat down on the edge of the bed, with Godalming beside him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144760,\n            \"Just as I had finished, Quincey and Godalming knocked at the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152088,\n            \"- Just before we reached Fenchurch Street Lord Godalming said to me:-\\u201cQuincey and I will find a locksmith.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152298,\n            \"Godalming and Morris hurried off in a cab, we following in another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152776,\n            \"It was immediately opened by Quincey Morris, beside whom stood Lord Godalming lighting a cigar.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153233,\n            \"When we had examined this last find, Lord Godalming and Quincey Morris taking accurate notes of the various addresses of the houses in the East and the South, took with them the keys in a great bunch, and set out to destroy the boxes in these places.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153318,\n            \"- The time seemed terrible long whilst we were waiting for the coming of Godalming and Quincey Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154945,\n            \"The gladness of our hearts must have shown upon our faces when on the step, close to the door, we saw Lord Godalming and Quincey Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155464,\n            \"Godalming behind and Quincey in front stood just out of sight ready to move in front of the window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160986,\n            \"Present: Professor Van Helsing, Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, Mr. Quincey Morris, Jonathan Harker, Mina Harker.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 15]\": [\n        [\n            75710,\n            \"\\u201d In the hall I met Quincey Morris, with a telegram for Arthur telling him that Mrs. Westenra was dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77161,\n            \"Quincey went off to meet him at the station.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85335,\n            \"I must not call you \\u2018 Mr.,\\u2019and I have grown to love you-yes, my dear boy, to love you-as Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87461,\n            \"Arthur has gone back to Ring, and has taken Quincey Morris with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87751,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107592,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur and Quincey came home with me, and we tried to cheer each other on the way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107641,\n            \"- A little before twelve o\\u2019clock we three-Arthur, Quincey Morris, and myself-called for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108214,\n            \"To me, a doctor\\u2019s preparations for work of any kind are stimulating and bracing, but the effect of these things on both Arthur and Quincey was to cause them a sort of consternation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109817,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur bent and kissed her, and then we sent him and Quincey out of the tomb;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118456,\n            \"Poor Art seemed more cheerful than he has been since Lucy first took ill, and Quincey is more like his own bright self than he has been for many a long day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"And Arthur and my friend Quincey, they are with you, too?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155343,\n            \"In all our hunting parties and adventures in different parts of the world, Quincey Morris had always been the one to arrange the plan of action, and Arthur and I had been accustomed to obey him implicitly.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 16]\": [\n        [\n            79221,\n            \"\\u201cI shall report to you any matter of interest occurring here, and shall wire you at once if there is anything of importance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87483,\n            \"I believe in my heart of hearts that he suffered as much about Lucy\\u2019s death as any of us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109817,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur bent and kissed her, and then we sent him and Quincey out of the tomb;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118456,\n            \"Poor Art seemed more cheerful than he has been since Lucy first took ill, and Quincey is more like his own bright self than he has been for many a long day.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 17]\": [\n        [\n            120430,\n            \"Jonathan held my right with his left and stretched across to Mr. Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123675,\n            \"Sir, I make no apology for dropping all forms of conventional prefix.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191840,\n            \"In the midst of this I could see that Jonathan on one side of the ring of men, and Quincey on the other, were forcing a way to the cart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192089,\n            \"but as he sprang beside Jonathan, who had by now jumped from the cart, I could see that with his left hand he was clutching at his side, and that the blood was spurting through his fingers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192130,\n            \"He did not delay notwithstanding this, for as Jonathan, with desperate energy, attacked one end of the chest, attempting to prize off the lid with his great Kukri knife, he attacked the other frantically with his bowie.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192612,\n            \"Jonathan knelt behind him and the wounded man laid back his head on his shoulder.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[14, 17]\": [\n        [\n            157754,\n            \"When they had retired, Quincey, Godalming, and I arranged that we should sit up, dividing the night between us, and watch over the safety of the poor stricken lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161126,\n            \"These not so important as to go in your list of the shipping in the Times, and so we go, by suggestion of Lord Godalming, to your Lloyd\\u2019s, where are note of all ships that sail, however so small.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[15, 16]\": [\n        [\n            22538,\n            \"When she saw my face at the window she threw herself forward, and shouted in a voice laden with menace:-\\u201cMonster, give me my child!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27295,\n            \"We met some time ago a man that would just do for you, if you were not already engaged to Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27644,\n            \"I love him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27672,\n            \"But oh, Mina, I love him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27685,\n            \"I love him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28084,\n            \"Well, I must tell you about the three, but you must keep it a secret, dear, from every one, except, of course, Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28115,\n            \"You will tell him, because I would, if I were in your place, certainly tell Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28312,\n            \"He spoke to me, Mina, very straightforwardly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28475,\n            \"And then, Mina, I felt a sort of duty to tell him that there was some one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28669,\n            \"\\u201cArthur has just gone, and I feel in better spirits than when I left off, so I can go on telling you about the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28816,\n            \"No, I don\\u2019t, for there was Mr. Morris telling us his stories, and Arthur never told any, and yet-- My dear, I am somewhat previous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32200,\n            \"- I came up here an hour ago with Lucy, and we had a most interesting talk with my old friend and the two others who always come and join him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33635,\n            \"\\u2018 He was the only son of his mother, and she was a widow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33693,\n            \"But that\\u2019s because ye don\\u2019t gawm the sorrowin\\u2019mother was a hell-cat that hated him because he was acrewk\\u2019d-a regular lamiter he was-an\\u2019he hated her so that he committed suicide in order that she mightn\\u2019t get an insurance she put on his life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33807,\n            \"And, as to hopes of a glorious resurrection, I\\u2019ve often heard him say masel\\u2019that he hoped he\\u2019d go to hell, for his mother was so pious that she\\u2019d be sure to go to heaven, an\\u2019he didn\\u2019t want to addle where she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56095,\n            \"I do not care for myself, but all for him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56402,\n            \"I have asked him to come over, and as you told me that all things were to be at your charge, I have mentioned to him who you are and your relations to Miss Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56631,\n            \"I tell you these facts that you may know why I have such confidence in him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61771,\n            \"As the transfusion went on something like life seemed to come back to poor Lucy\\u2019s cheeks, and through Arthur\\u2019s growing pallor the joy of his face seemed absolutely to shine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61832,\n            \"It gave me an idea of what a terrible strain Lucy\\u2019s system must have undergone that what weakened Arthur only partially restored her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61858,\n            \"But the Professor\\u2019s face was set, and he stood watch in hand and with his eyes fixed now on the patient and now on Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65676,\n            \"I put him in your window, I make pretty wreath, and hang him round your neck, so that you sleep well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68166,\n            \"Thank God for mother\\u2019s sake, and dear Arthur\\u2019s, and for all our friends who have been so kind!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72249,\n            \"For a second or two she sat up, pointing at the wolf, and there was a strange and horrible gurgling in her throat;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79771,\n            \"And he has been flapping those grim wings to some purpose of late-Lucy\\u2019s mother and Arthur\\u2019s father, and now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80926,\n            \"Oh, my love, I am so glad you have come!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86608,\n            \"He was very pale, and his eyes seemed bulging out as, half in terror and half in amazement, he gazed at a tall, thin man, with a beaky nose and black moustache and pointed beard, who was also observing the pretty girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87652,\n            \"When it was all over, we were standing beside Arthur, who, poor fellow, was speaking of his part in the operation where his blood had been transfused to his Lucy\\u2019s veins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89825,\n            \"I am so glad that he has plenty of work to do, for that keeps his mind off the terrible things;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89848,\n            \"and oh, I am rejoiced that he is not now weighed down with the responsibility of his new position.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89869,\n            \"I knew he would be true to himself, and now how proud I am to see my Jonathan rising to the height of his advancement and keeping pace in all ways with the duties that come upon him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89928,\n            \"My household work is done, so I shall take his foreign journal, and lock myself up in my room and read it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90712,\n            \"it is concerning Lucy and her sleep-walking, and not about Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106791,\n            \"when she advanced to him with outstretched arms and a wanton smile he fell back and hid his face in his hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106814,\n            \"She still advanced, however, and with a languorous, voluptuous grace, said:-\\u201cCome to me, Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106846,\n            \"My arms are hungry for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107889,\n            \"When he again lifted the lid off Lucy\\u2019s coffin we all looked-Arthur trembling like an aspen-and saw that the body lay there in all its death-beauty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107966,\n            \"Presently he said to Van Helsing:-\\u201cIs this really Lucy\\u2019s body, or only a demon in her shape?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108397,\n            \"Friend Arthur, if you had met that kiss which you know of before poor Lucy die;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108415,\n            \"or again, last night when you open your arms to her, you would in time, when you had died, have become nosferatu, as they call it in Eastern Europe, and would all time make more of those Un-Deads that so have fill us with horror.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108635,\n            \"So that, my friend, it will be a blessed hand for her that shall strike the blow that sets her free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108758,\n            \"He saw, too, what we all did, the infinite kindness which suggested that his should be the hand which would restore Lucy to us as a holy, and not an unholy, memory;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109470,\n            \"There, in the coffin lay no longer the foul Thing that we had so dreaded and grown to hate that the work of her destruction was yielded as a privilege to the one best entitled to it, but Lucy as we had seen her in her life, with her face of unequalled sweetness and purity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109727,\n            \"When he raised his head Van Helsing said to him:-\\u201cAnd now, my child, you may kiss her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109751,\n            \"Kiss her dead lips if you will, as she would have you to, if for her to choose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109817,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur bent and kissed her, and then we sent him and Quincey out of the tomb;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118456,\n            \"Poor Art seemed more cheerful than he has been since Lucy first took ill, and Quincey is more like his own bright self than he has been for many a long day.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[15, 17]\": [\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[16, 17]\": [\n        [\n            36216,\n            \"I am unhappy about Lucy and about Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47326,\n            \"I told her how anxious I was about Jonathan, and then she tried to comfort me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48490,\n            \"No news from Jonathan, and Lucy seems to be growing weaker, whilst her mother\\u2019s hours are numbering to a close.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49455,\n            \"Before she answered, that sweet, puckered look came into her forehead, which Arthur-I call him Arthur from her habit-says he loves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52269,\n            \"All the resolution has gone out of his dear eyes, and that quiet dignity which I told you was in his face has vanished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53204,\n            \"When the chaplain and the sisters had left me alone with my husband-oh, Lucy, it is the first time I have written the words \\u2018 my husband\\u2019- left me alone with my husband, I took the book from under his pillow, and wrapped it up in white paper, and tied it with a little bit of pale blue ribbon which was round my neck, and sealed it over the knot with sealing-wax, and for my seal I used my wedding ring.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53364,\n            \"Then he took my hand in his, and oh, Lucy, it was the first time he took his wife\\u2019s hand, and said that it was the dearest thing in all the wide world, and that he would go through all the past again to win it, if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53526,\n            \"And, my dear, when he kissed me, and drew me to him with his poor weak hands, it was like a very solemn pledge between us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53790,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Mina,-\\u201cOceans of love and millions of kisses, and may you soon be in your own home with your husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54222,\n            \"It was a strange thing that the patient had humour enough to see their distrust, for, coming close to me, he said in a whisper, all the while looking furtively at them:-\\u201cThey think I could hurt you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54268,\n            \"Fancy me hurting you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56810,\n            \"Tell your friend that when that time you suck from my wound so swiftly the poison of the gangrene from that knife that our other friend, too nervous, let slip, you did more for him when he wants my aids and you call for them than all his great fortune could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56866,\n            \"But it is pleasure added to do for him, your friend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76247,\n            \"One of those big bats that they call vampires had got at her in the night, and what with his gorge and the vein left open, there wasn\\u2019t enough blood in her to let her stand up, and I had to put a bullet through her as she lay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78002,\n            \"and so, as you love me, and he loves me, and I love you with all the moods and tenses of the verb, I send you simply his \\u2018 love\\u2019instead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78181,\n            \"This afternoon a carrier\\u2019s cart with two men made a call at the empty house whose grounds abut on ours-the house to which, you will remember, the patient twice ran away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88767,\n            \"Said he not that the transfusion of his blood to her veins had made her truly his bride?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90541,\n            \"I have read your letters to poor Lucy, and know how good you are and how your husband suffer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90562,\n            \"so I pray you, if it may be, enlighten him not, lest it may harm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105334,\n            \"Did she not, friend John?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108709,\n            \"it was the hand of him that loved her best;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110352,\n            \"She must go to your house, friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110362,\n            \"You must meet her at the station.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110395,\n            \"over it he told me of a diary kept by Jonathan Harker when abroad, and gave me a typewritten copy of it, as also of Mrs. Harker\\u2019s diary at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118690,\n            \"Friend John, up to now fortune has made that woman of help to us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118832,\n            \"You tell me she has wrote all, then she must consult with us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120334,\n            \"\\u201cI answer for Mina and myself,\\u201dhe said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121162,\n            \"he can be as bat, as Madam Mina saw him on the window at Whitby, and as friend John saw him fly from this so near house, and as my friend Quincey saw him at the window of Miss Lucy.\"\n        ]\n    ]\n}"